"1","Anderson_Greg","Linda Berry-Brede Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 24, 2016 Dassel, Minnesota Linda Berry-Brede-LB Amy Sullivan-AS LB: I’m Linda LB and I do give Amy permission to record my conversation with her. 6, 12 AS: Thank you.  Could you start with you childhood? 9, 11 Where you grew up?  What your childhood was like? 10, 11 LB: I was born in Chicago, Illinois and my mother was a nursing student at the time. 9 Single, wasn’t sure who my father was, I was put up for adoption, she went off secretly and had me in Chicago. 5, 10, 15 Nobody knew about it. 6, 12 I was there for about a month and she decided she wanted to take me home after all. 6, 8, 12, 13, 19 She traveled to Chicago and brought me home to Minneapolis and kept me in her little apartment. 9, 18, 19, 20 Finally, my aunt and uncle found out about it because they came to visit her and it was a bar downstairs and she had me down there at the bar that she worked at. 5, 9, 12, 13, 19 They didn’t feel it was a fit environment for a child. 14, 16 Eventually, within a few weeks, she agreed for them to take me temporarily until she got her life together. 6, 11 AS: What year was this? 20 They took me home and took care of me and agreed that they would give me back eventually. 6, 7, 15, 19 That never really happened. 12, 13, 15 I just grew up with my aunt and uncle. 9, 12 It was my mother’s sister and her husband. 5, 9, 15 It was a great childhood, I can’t complain about it. 11 It was good.  I had a cousin that was three years younger than me. 5, 14, 20 He was born when I was five.  We are three years apart. 20 We grew up as brother and sister. 5, 9 AS: Did you see your mom much as a child? 15, 18 LB: Once in awhile.  She was my aunt.  I didn’t know she was my mom until I was in my thirties. 13, 14, 15 They told me I was adopted. 8, 20 Well, when I was in my thirties I decided I wanted to try and find my biological mother. 12, 13, 16 I asked them if I could get a copy of my birth certificate. 10 They said they had one and they would help me. 13 They said I was adopted through Lutheran Social Service. 7, 8 They didn’t have any record when I talked to them. 6, 10, 11 I said, “I don’t know what is going on.” 13, 14, 15 Eventually they came down and gave me my birth certificate and on that was the name of my aunt Georgina. 6, 10, 19 I was thinking, “Ok, so she is my mother.”  That kind of threw me for a loop. 15, 16, 17 It was kind of exciting in a way, and yet kind of puzzling. 16, 17 Anyway, eventually I wrote her a letter because I didn’t see her often. 12, 15, 16, 19 She was the aunt with the sports cars and she was just kind of a cool aunt. 7, 9, 12, 16, 17 I grew up with her kind of in my teens. 16, 17 I would stay with her sometimes. 5, 9, 18 She would let me smoke and have a drink when I was in my teens. 6, 14, 19 She was cool. 17 Very successful as a nurse.  She helped start a program that used to be HCMC now, the dialysis unit. 9, 11, 13, 14, 16 She worked with some real famous doctors.  She really did well in her life. 11 AS: Did she stay single? 9, 15 LB: No, I was a teenager when she married.  I went on to find out though that they didn’t stay married long. 9 She had two other children and gave them up for adoption. 14 One with him and one right after me. 14 Two boys. 8 She was an alcoholic. 5 She told me this when she was drinking one time. 6, 14, 20 I never knew for sure if that was the truth because I think she had a kind of personality disorder when I think back on it now. 6, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 Very kind, but she could turn around and be horrible. 8, 16, 17, 19 I found out she was my mom when I was in my thirties. 15 I did write her a letter and told her I knew. 6, 12, 19, 20 She took a while to connect with me after that.  I went down to her home, she lived in Brooklyn Center, went down to her home and talked to her about it. 10, 11, 19 I acted like I was really happy. 10, 17 Inside I was a little confused to be honest. 9 She admitted that yes, I’m your mom and talked about how things were back then. 10, 11, 14, 15, 16, 19 She had hoped to get me back but it just didn’t work out. 9, 10, 12, 19 As it turned out she didn’t visit that often. 12, 13, 15, 19 She just kind of let them have me. 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 She just didn’t seem to have the time or something. 9, 12, 19 She really wasn’t happy about being my mother even as an adult. 15, 17 AS: No motherly instinct. 9 LB: No motherly instinct really. 9 Really independent and a narcissist almost. 9, 12, 15 That is how my childhood started out. 9, 11 That’s how, as an adult, I found out she was my mother.  We didn’t have a close relationship really.  Cancer and she died of cancer, I don’t know, it has probably been ten years ago now or more. 13, 14, 15, 20 She had a living boyfriend that was my age. 6, 12 He somehow changed her will I think, unless she lied to me, but I got nothing from her. 16 She didn’t leave me anything. 6 She said she would.  I was the only child that had any contact with her. 10 He took everything and we always wondered if the will was changed somehow because she had said, “You’ll get…” 12, 16, 17 She was very bad before she died.  She didn’t know what was going on. 13, 14, 15 He took care of her. 7 He was a terrible alcoholic too. 5, 15 Very chronic.  Who knows. 13, 14, 15 AS: What a story. 9 Let’s see, where do I go from there.  I got married when I was very young. 14 Right out of high school. 8 I was pregnant my last month of high school I remember. 8, 9 We moved out of Minneapolis to Brainerd my last year of school. 8, 9, 20 I went to Brainerd high school, graduated in 1969 and my boyfriend at the time moved up there to go to college as well. 8, 12 I found out I was pregnant in May right before I graduated. 8, 14 We planned a wedding, told my parents, and went through this whole thing. 10, 16, 20 They didn’t care for the guy I was going with, Bob. 7 Not at all because he had long hair and my dad was a barber and she was a hairdresser [laughter]. 5, 12, 14 And he had very long hair and dad didn’t like it. 10, 12 We got married in September then.  I had my first son, Jason, the next February. 9 That was ok I guess, it went ok. 10 I was so young that I think it went ok because I was so young. 14 Both Bob and I partied a lot, drank a lot. 7, 14, 17 That was kind of our focus then was having fun and partying. 6, 15, 16, 17 Within a year I had another little boy [laughter]. 20 His name was Gabriel. 6 It was very hard because my husband by that time was really a full-blown alcoholic and was never home and going out with other women and girls in high school. 5, 8, 11, 15, 18, 19 We weren’t very old. 20 I was only 18 or 19 when I had Gabriel.  My aunt and uncle that raised me helped me a lot with that. 5, 13, 16, 17 We ended up going up there and staying a while because he was really abusive, my husband was abusive. 9, 11, 12, 15, 19 AS: Was he your age?  LB: A year older. 5, 20 Physically and mentally, you name it. 6, 7, 14 I tried to kind of still stick with that lifestyle of going out a lot, drinking, finding baby sitters. 5, 6, 9, 10, 11, 13, 14, 16, 17 We had his mom and dad living in town. 6, 15, 19 They were great and took them a lot, the kids. 11, 17 Things straightened out a little bit. 6, 9, 15 We lived in a little town west central Minnesota called Cosmos. 7, 9, 19 I was a big town girl. 8, 19 I wasn’t into small towns at all. 19 The only thing we had there was the Legion.  We would look forward to the Wednesday night steak fries. 9, 19 I wanted more for my life than that. 11, 12, 13 My family was more well-rounded and really encouraged me to do something. 8, 18 They wanted me to go to college, but I didn’t of course because I had kids. 8, 12, 13 It was ingrained in my mind that wasn’t enough living in a small town and going to the Legion on Wednesday nights. 6, 19, 20 I wanted more. 12, 13 I wanted to go to college and I wanted to do somethings in my life. 5, 8, 11, 12, 13, 16 In fact, we built a new house. 6, 9, 10 He worked with his dad they had a Ready Mix company and were doing fairly well with it.  We weren’t hard up for money at all. 11 We built a new house and back then of course it didn’t cost very much. 6, 9, 18, 19 I got into that and things settled down and straightened out. 6, 9, 15, 16, 17 We had a pretty good time for a while there. 18 It was still partying and then I got pregnant with my daughter. 5, 6, 9 She was born in ‘76.  That was really awesome to have a girl.  I really focused on the kids. 9, 15 Sewing and I made everything for them. 16 I was really into homemaking at that time. 19 Things seemed good for a while. 19 As time progressed, Bob was really an alcoholic and was very physically abusive. 5, 7, 9, 11 I started going out with other people thinking I would find somebody better. 9, 11 He was going out with other people and eventually I didn’t want to be with him anymore and I didn’t want to be in that town. 13, 15, 19 I went out with a guy that I thought could get me out of there. 11, 12 He was just totally not the right kind of person. 9, 12, 14, 16, 17 That didn’t work.  I moved to the Twin Cities for a while. 8 Left my boys behind and took my daughter with me. 5, 8 Got a job at Simer Pump Company.  I will never forget that. 15 It was just a no life job. 9, 11, 12 It was just to make some money to live. 9, 12, 16 I was so lonely down there.  I had friends, but it was just my daughter and I. 5, 9, 12, 18 One day my husband and his friend came down and took my daughter away from me and brought her back [with them]. 5, 9, 12, 15, 16, 18, 19 It was horrible. 17 AS: How did they manage that?  LB: I was staying with a friend, they came to the apartment, my friend let him in because my friend wasn’t really concerned. 9, 12, 19, 20 She knew him. 6, 12 They just took her. 9, 12 They grabbed her out of my arms and took her and brought her back to Cosmos. 9, 18, 19 Within a few weeks I moved back and went back to him because I couldn’t handle not having my kids. 8, 19 I felt so guilty about my boys and then not having her. 8, 17 He put her with a friend of his to take care of her every day. 6, 7, 10, 12, 19 I just couldn’t deal with that. 9, 12, 13 I went back. 19 I tried to make things work with him but I was over him. 10, 16 We even went on a vacation and took all kinds of things but it wasn’t… 10, 15, 16, 17 Eventually the abuse got so bad I ended up calling county social worker. 7, 9, 12 I didn’t know what to do. 13, 14, 15 My parents weren’t really standing behind me because they thought, they were kind of old fashioned. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 17, 20 I will never forget a statement my brother made: “Maybe if you stopped making frozen pizzas he would leave.” 5, 6, 9, 10, 15, 16, 20 I called the social worker, I told her I couldn’t live with him anymore, and she brought me to the women’s shelter in Willmar with my kids. 7, 9, 13, 18, 20 We were there for probably a couple of months. 8 I moved out of the house and petitioned for a divorce. 6, 8, 9 They helped me with a lot of things there. 13, 16, 17 We got an apartment and back then there was a lot of help. 13, 17, 19, 20 There was a lot of financial help available through the county that there isn’t now. 7, 13, 14, 17 They helped me pay for an apartment, they helped me get furniture, they helped pay my tuition while I went to the college in Willmar. 8, 13, 16, 20 My life was evolving. 11 I missed Bob in a way because I missed the companionship. 16 He could be nice sometimes, but overall it wasn’t good. 5, 18 The kids had also been somewhat…  the boys were physically abused and mentally abused. 7, 8, 9, 14 Kristin wasn’t. 9 She was only three and doesn’t remember it.  We lived in an apartment then and the life was kind of, I don’t know, it was ok. 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 20 I was trying to find another guy right away rather than be by myself. 13, 14, 16 I had a series of nothing really.  I would see some people a few times and then leave. 6, 18 I had kids and…  I was a lot of baggage with all that. 17 Then, I met my current husband, and that was in ‘78 when I met him at a bar. 5, 15, 16 He was into racing, star car racing and I really liked that. 7, 9, 10, 18 I don’t know why even. 13, 14, 15 My girlfriend and I would go to races. 12 They had a race track not too far.  I knew he raced but I thought he was married but I really didn’t care [laughter]. 6, 7, 11, 12 My morals weren’t too on spot back then. 19 I started seeing him out at the bars and eventually he left his wife and asked if he could move in with me. 5, 9, 10, 11, 15 This has been a matter of months. 8, 20 And, “Of course you can move in with me.”  He brought his suitcase and he kept seeing other women and I would let him use my car. 7, 9, 18, 19 I was totally desperate for this guy. 17 He had a really nice family that lived out on the farm out there. 18 They were super people. 12 Very Christian oriented, kind of like my family was. 8, 9, 16, 17, 18 I felt comfortable. 17 I joined their church and I became very involved in trying to find a family and … in their activities. 5, 10, 16, 18, 19 For the next two or three years he still continued to see other women that he knew. 6, 9, 12, 18, 20 I put up with it because I was so desperate. 10 He was very good with my kids and was like a real dad to them.  They would go visit their dad but he was so bad with his alcoholism that he would leave them with his parents and if he did bring them with him they would end up at some party or a bar. 5, 6, 10, 12, 13, 16 One time the county sheriff brought them home from their home visit. 7, 9, 12, 13, 18, 19 He had been put in jail because he had a bunch of trouble in a bar he was at and the kids were with him. 5, 9, 10 They came home and the boys didn’t seem phased a whole lot they just kind of dismissed it. 8, 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 My daughter was kind of scared. 5, 7, 11, 12, 16, 17 She was about five or six I think.  They were also diagnosed, the oldest boys, were diagnosed with borderline, back then, retardation. 5, 6, 8, 9, 19, 20 That’s what they called it back then. 7, 19 It wasn’t disability.  I kind of always assumed it was because I drank when I was pregnant. 7, 14, 16, 17 I thought it was fetal alcohol syndrome. 11, 12, 14 I don’t know if that was the cause. 9, 13, 14, 15 They didn’t look like that, but they had some of the issues that went along with that because I went to a lot of seminars later in life. 11, 14, 15, 17 We got divorced then, Bob and I were divorced finally. 5 Craig is his name, my husband’s name. 6, 15 He got divorced a couple of years later. 5, 20 He was really down and out, too, because he had lost a business and wasn’t really sure what he was doing. 9, 15 We were broke.  He was living with me and I got welfare. 6 That was what we lived on and I didn’t record that he was living with me. 6 He started working some jobs and was starting to make some money. 9, 11, 16 I was in college then. 8 I started college at the community college in human services. 8, 9, 11, 14 I did really well in college. 8 I was surprised I remember because I hated high school. 8, 12, 18 Things just evolved. 9, 12 We moved into another subsidized townhome and his brother was a very successful farmer. 5, 8, 19 He purchased some land and a house right outside of Willmar. 6, 8, 9, 14 He bought it for us and we took over the payments eventually, but he enabled us to get it. 7, 15, 16 We went into that together.  The kids loved it. 13 I felt like at peace out there. 17 It was a lot of work and the house was rickety but his dad helped us with a lot of the work on the house. 6, 9, 13, 16, 17 It was exciting.  The only thing was  Craig would not commit to me and I felt used. 9, 17 Eventually I left him for a while.  For a period of time I moved to Willmar. 8 I tried to go out with some other people. 10 I was like this is it he won’t commit to me.  He was still seeing other people I believe. 9 The guy I was dating was one of his friends and he decided to go back to his old girlfriend. 12, 18, 19, 20 He left me and then I had to go back to Craig I felt. 17, 19 I cared about him but I didn’t like his lifestyle. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12 I demanded that he married me if he was going to live with him.  I wasn’t just going to live with him anymore. 9, 12, 13 We had lived together for ten years. 20 AS: By this point it is like ‘88?  LB: It is about, yeah, It was actually ‘87 when we got married. 10 Right before our wedding, three months before, I found out I was pregnant. 8 I thought, “Oh my god. 10, 11, 12 This is not going to look good to his family at all.” 18 I considered an abortion. 12 I had had two before that, earlier.  Which makes me sick to this day, but anyway. 16, 19 Three days before the wedding I miscarried twins. 7, 14, 19 What happened was I lost one at home and still was in a lot of pain and went into the hospital and they were going to do a DNC and they did and there was another fetus they said. 9, 12, 13, 17, 19 They didn’t tell me right away. 14, 16 They aborted the second twin. 14, 20 They didn’t own up to it at the clinic.  The doctor didn’t.  They didn’t tell me they just said there was some fetal material. 9, 12 In the records, there was a gal at work there, and she saw in the records that it… 6, 7 AS: Why would they keep that from you? 12 LB: I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 I suppose they were worried about a lawsuit.  This woman, because she talked to me about it, she was going to lose her job. 10, 11 She was the girlfriend of the guy I had dated before and she hated me. 12 There was a lot of animosity there and I was scared of her because she had tried to come in my house while he was there and she pushed me down the steps. 5, 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 17, 19 She was going to kill me. 7 Threatening me all the time. 15 I was afraid of her and I told Craig, “I can’t deal with this. 13, 20 We are getting married in a few days.” 19 This went on for weeks after we were married.  I said, “I can’t do this anymore let’s just forget about it and not do anything.” 9, 12, 13, 19 I found out later the clinic was gearing up for a big lawsuit with this doctor because he didn’t do an ultrasound or something beforehand. 8, 10 That took a while to get through.  I was really depressed and we got married a few days later. 12, 19 That was nice, and we got through it.  Got married outside under our pine trees.  We still live there. 9 Marriage was fairly ok.  A year later I had Seth. 20 He is 27 now and that was in ‘89 I had Seth. 14 We were just delighted. 9, 12 It was his first child, he didn’t have any kids. 9 Seth was everything to us.  He couldn’t have been spoiled anymore than he was [laughter]. 13 Five years later we had Jordan. 20 Jordan is our youngest, he’s 22. 9, 14 We just did everything with those kids. 9, 12 Craig was one of them to raise.  We got them involved when they were really young into snocross racing. 14 They raced snowmobiles. 14 We spent a ton of money. 19 At that time Craig had started his own business again and was doing fairly well. 9, 11 Between that we had milked cows, we had taken over his dad’s farm. 6 We had done a lot of things together. 16, 17 We had quite a history at that point. 9 He was starting a new business and that was going fairly well. 6, 9, 11 We were financially doing a lot better. 17 Fixed up our house. 6, 9 Did a lot of things. 16, 17 Things seemed to be going well. 19 The kids loved snocross. 13 We took off every weekend and went to where the races were and traveled all over with them. 12, 19 Seth got to be very good.  He was with Arctic Cat with their team.  Jordan, he raced, but he was a real big kid. 8 He was really big for his age and that wasn’t good in snocross because you had to be lightweight like his brother was. 5, 8, 18 His anxiety would come out… 13, 19 his boots were this or that.  He would just go nuts every time. 9, 12 That was Jordan.  That was my first taste of his anxiety was when he was a little kid. 9 He was the one who eventually had the most problems. 15 We ended up having to quit that because my husband Craig wanted to get Seth into car racing. 7, 12, 13, 15 It was either that or snocross we couldn’t afford to do both.  We had a team of racecars that we had other people drive. 7, 14 Two dirt car models. 7, 15 We had some friends of Craigs’ drive them for us. 7, 12, 14, 18 It was time, he thought, to quit that and get our own kids involved. 11, 12 We got Seth involved and that was 2009.  It wasn’t all that long ago.  We got him involved and he took off.  He was just a gifted racer and just excelled at that. 7, 9, 12 I’m going to step back a little bit. 9, 12 When they were in school, because we traveled with the snocross and it was really hard to do school, I started homeschooling them. 8, 9, 11, 19 We were gone on weekends and every Friday and school didn’t like it. 8, 10, 12, 19 We homeschooled and that was not successful at all. 8, 19 Seth did it for a little bit and then he wouldn’t do it.  I just let it go and I started with Jordan. 9, 11, 12, 19 Jordan begged me, “Please, I hate school, I hate my teachers.” 8 And he didn’t get along with his teachers at all.  Both the boys were horrible in school. 8, 17 They were nice people but they just couldn’t stand authority. 9, 12 Neither one of them.  I don’t know if that came from us. 13, 14, 15, 19 I don’t know, I don’t think so. 13, 14, 15 They both had a real problem with authority.  I tried homeschooling and that didn’t work for either one of them. 8, 10, 19 Eventually I just gave up and they just quit school. 8, 9, 12 They just didn’t go to school. 8, 9, 12 I feel guilty about that to this day that I didn’t push it more. 16, 19 In the meantime we took in a foster son. 9, 16 Like I needed anything more, but we knew this little boy. 6, 12, 13 He was a friend of Seth’s, my older one. 5, 12, 20 We took him along with our family because I had a job I ended up as an independent living coordinator. 6, 12, 18 His parents were in my program. 10, 16 I knew them and they had two babies that were both mentally handicapped and it just wasn’t a good situation so we took him on. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14 At first it was so fine because he got to race and we got him a snowmobile. 9, 14 He was with us all the time.  Later on that turned out to be a disaster. 9, 19, 20 For a while it was good and we felt like we were doing something good. 17 AS: Was he the same age as your kids?  LB: He was Seth’s age, yes. 14 The 27 year old. 20 They were the same age.  It turned out they were horrible together. 17, 19 It didn’t go well.  AS: They didn’t get along?  LB: They were just wild together. 9, 12, 17 I think they both had ADHD.  I know he did but I think my son must have had it too. 13, 14, 15 We couldn’t go anywhere with them.  They would make a scene, wreck things in the hallways of hotels. 16, 17 We couldn’t take them out to eat for dinner anymore because the two of them together we would have to separate them or something. 6, 13 Anyway, I’m probably missing some things. 16 AS: I am wondering if we should go outside.  It is getting louder in here.  [pause] 9 AS: How old are your kids? 20 You have a foster son, John… 9 LB: That was when my second youngest, Seth, was probably 11 or 12. 9, 14, 20 I think they were in fifth grade. 20 AS: So they were big. 8 They could make some real trouble. 16 LB: Oh yes. 14 Together it didn’t work very well for those two.  My youngest son didn’t like him really. 9, 10, 14 They later became very close once, I don’t know, Seth kind of broke away from them and had his own friends. 5, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 My youngest son Jordan started getting closer to John. 9, 11, 14 Little did I know that was when the drug use started. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15 Jordan started drinking when he was like 15 because he went with Seth to a race and Seth called me and said, “Mom, you got to come and get this kid. 6, 7, 9, 11, 13, 14, 19 I’m not watching him.  He’s drunk, he’s running around the campground here causing trouble, fighting with people. 7, 8, 11, 14, 15 You have to come.” 13, 19 We got up in the middle of the night and drove up to Huron, South Dakota to pick him up. 7, 8, 14, 19 We were going to go the next day to watch Seth race. 19 Seth was racing.  We picked him up to the police station because they had brought him in and charged him with underage drinking. 6, 7, 9, 14, 17, 18 I was on the phone with the police the whole way down there. 7, 16 They were picking him up and bringing him in.  We were just sick. 9, 12 We had had some problems with Seth, too.  Not with drinking or drugs but some mental stuff where he would just go off. 6, 9, 12, 14 We kind of had our fill with that and now we thought, “Jordan! 11, 12, 14, 16, 17 Not Jordan.”  He seems like such a good kid, doesn’t seem to be influenced by that kind of stuff, you would hope. 9, 10, 16, 17, 19, 20 We went out, picked him up, and brought him home. 9, 18, 19 He was still drunk and it was just terrible seeing him like that. 9, 11, 12, 14, 15 I couldn’t handle it.  The next day we told him he couldn’t go back out but we took him back out the next day. 19, 20 That was the beginning that we knew he was using. 6, 12 We thought, oh, he is just experimenting like kids that age do and he just drank too much. 7, 9, 11, 12, 14, 18 “Oh I’m never going to do that again!” 15 Of course.  That was the beginning.  Him and John I think then started smoking some weed because I would kind of smell it when I would go out. 9, 11, 16, 17 We had a shop with a kind of office in it that was separate from our house. 6, 9, 16, 17 That is where they hung out a lot because they were working on different things and they would fix bikes out there and they were always doing things and I thought that was good. 11, 12, 16, 17 They were out of my hair a little bit, and yet they were doing good things. 12, 16 One time I remember thinking, “It smells like weed out here or something.”  I started suspecting things little by little. 9, 11, 16 Seth had kind of moved out. 8, 16, 17 When he got to be 18 he moved out and got his own place if I remember right. 8, 11, 14 I didn’t think he would do anything either because he wasn’t into drinking at that point really. 6, 14 He was obnoxious but he wasn’t into using I didn’t think.  That changed too in a short hurry. 16 We found out he had gotten an underage consumption [charge] and that is when it all started basically. 7, 9, 11, 15, 17 We went through that with Seth the older one and then the younger ones started picking it up more and more. 5, 9, 11, 14, 20 I think probably at about 18, when Jordan was 18, he’s 22 now, we noticed things started getting more out of hand. 9, 11, 14, 16 He started acting strange. 7, 9, 10, 11 All him and John did was play video games. 10 We had a house in New Ulm as well. 6, 9 My husband worked in a big piping project when the butter plant burned down. 8, 15 They rebuilt it.  My husband and his company. 15 We stayed there and rented a house there. 5, 6, 9, 16 Video games non-stop. 9, 10 I’m thinking, “This is too much, video games are going to ruin them for life.” 10, 11, 18 After that I think was when they started doing more and more weed. 9, 11 Jordan fell down and broke his leg. 15 He had many broken bones over the years. 5, 20 That is when he started on pain medication. 9, 10, 11 Percocet, they gave them out pretty readily then. 18 AS: This is how long ago??  LB: This was when he was about 18, yeah, 17 or 18. 10 He had a girlfriend then that he had had for a couple of years. 12, 20 She wasn’t really into using but she noticed too that he was just so awful. 9, 10, 12 Demanding, he started going downhill. 9, 11 We noticed his behavior changing. 16, 18 I thought it was the medication. 10, 11, 12 I said, “Maybe you need to get off this stuff and take some Tylenol.” 6, 9, 13 He has never been able to withstand pain. 9, 12, 15 Even when he was a little kid, everything was horrible if he was in pain. 17 Everybody had to cater to him. 10 He had to have this pain medication. 10 I thought, well, I suppose if he needs it. 11, 12, 13 The doctor kept refilling it.  He was on different ones. 16, 17 I’m sure he was hooked on it. 15 Then he broke his shoulder, or he had to have surgery on his shoulder.  That was about a year later and he was on more pain meds, of course, because he probably needed them at the time. 13, 20 I don’t think he ever got off of them.  Then he started finding more ways to get them. 9, 11, 16, 17 I am finding out now that he started snorting them. 9, 11, 14 Because I found a pill crusher out in the shop.  I started looking for things. 9, 11, 16 Sure enough there was stuff out there. 9, 20 That was a real red flag but when I questioned them they said, “We tried it once.” 6, 9, 10, 12 You know. 13, 14, 15 It just progressed and eventually I found out through the grapevine that John was selling drugs. 7, 9, 12, 14, 15 Our foster son. 9 He had gotten on probation for something else. 10, 15 An assault or something.  He was on probation because he assaulted someone and got in trouble. 10 He didn’t go see his PO and they had a warrant out for him. 7 I kept saying, “You need to turn yourself in I’m not going to let you stay here. 9, 11, 13, 19 I could get in trouble for this as well.  You need to go talk to your PO.” 10, 13 I called the sheriff and I said, “He is out here and I can’t have him here anymore. 7, 13 I understand he is possibly selling drugs.” 7, 9, 12, 14, 16 They said, “Yeah, we have been watching him and we pretty much know he is.” 13, 14, 15, 18 They picked him up, ransacked my shop and all my things up there. 7, 16 “Could we search?”  They totally wrecked half my possession up there looking for drugs. 14, 17 They didn’t find any.  I’m sure they were hidden well. 15 They did find a little bit of marijuana on him but they did find a gun and he had a felony against him, the assault.  That sent him to jail and eventually a prison sentence. 7, 15 LB: First 