 that?  LB: I think it is women in general. 18 I think we are raised that way. 5, 16 I think it is put into our mind from an early age that the mom is the feeling part of the family and the caring part of the family. 7, 10, 15, 16, 18 The dad is more the breadwinner.  They don’t talk as much. 10, 18 They aren’t quite as feel-y as the moms. 15, 16, 18 AS: But why wouldn’t they be the ones responsible for all the troubles?  Why isn’t there that sense of how “Oh I failed my son.” 17 LB: My husband does feel that way. 15, 16 He does a lot. 17 He knows that he probably spoiled him and gave him too much and didn’t tend to the issues as they arose and instead was just waiting. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18 He doesn’t like confrontation. 10 I think he does feel bad about some of that. 16 AS: Maybe they just might not want to speak about it very often. 9, 12, 13, 15 There is not the cultural expectation of caregiving. 7, 11 LB: Right.  I agree that is a big part of it. 8 AS: I wonder if that is going to change a little bit. 16 LB: I wonder.  AS: I see dads doing more.  LB: Oh, yes. 14 Much more than when I was a kid.  Dad would come home and mom would have the table set, mom would clean up. 13, 15, 17, 19 That is ok if that is what you want to do. 13 It’s not bad but things have changed. 16 In some ways I think it was good because I think the family dynamics were a little bit closer back then than they are now in some ways. 14, 16, 17, 18, 19 I don’t agree with everything.  But I think families are really not together like they used to be. 9 At least I have experienced that myself. 9 We are encouraging kids to be so independent and involved in this and involved in that and do this. 12 They’ve got to go to college. 8 I don’t agree with that either.  Kids have different interests. 9, 16, 17, 19 In that respect I think I did ok.  Even trying to homeschool. 8, 16, 19 Even if it failed.  Seth went on to get his GED and he is fine. 14 He went to college for a little bit and didn’t like it. 8, 10 They hate school. 8 They like to have hands on jobs. 10 That’s fine. 14 Whatever works. 14 I feel like I wish I had done a little more with myself. 16 I mean I got a degree in psychology and communication. 10, 16, 20 I worked in jobs and it helped but… 13, 16 I never really made any money doing anything with that. 15, 16 AS: What is it that you do exactly? 10 LB: Right now I work at… 14 I took this just as part time because I wasn’t working at all when our business was succeeding. 9, 12 It is called Chyrsalis in Willmar. 7 It is a friend of mine owns it. 12 It is mentally ill, mentally handicapped adults. 14 Right now I am just working with two women part time in their own apartment. 9, 12, 14, 18, 20 I go there a couple hours a day. 11, 19 It is some money.  It is a job.  At lesat I am doing something.  AS: And it is part time?  she would like me to do more. 10 AS: You have a lot on your plate. 17 LB: There is a lot going on. 17 Defintiely.  AS: At least for that kind of work. 9, 16, 17 IF you were to do other work maybe it shouldn’t be caretaking. 7, 9 LB: And I had a si… program.  I worked at the women’s shelter as an advocate. 10, 18 I went to court with a lot of women. 17, 18 I worked at a facility for teenage girls for 12 years. 8, 20 Just a lot. 9, 17 I worked at the crisis center. 9 I worked with a boys group. 8 Sexually abused boys. 8, 9 I had that group for a long time.  I guess that is what I felt comfortable doing. 10, 17 I loved doing that. 13 But it does take a toll after a while. 6 You know that I am sure. 13, 14, 15 You kinda just get where you lose yourself in it almost. 9, 12, 16, 17 I can do this sure. 15 I can help them yup. 13 I can help them yup. 13 What is your problem.  AS: Thank you. "
"2","Beck_Thilo","Janie Bining Colford Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 29, 2016  At the Narrator’s Home Chanhassen, Minnesota Janie Bining Colford-JC Amy Sullivan-AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan.  I’m with Janie Bining Colford at her home in Chanhassen. 19 It is June 29, I think.  JC: Yes.  AS: Janie would you state your name and say that you give me permission to record this interview? 6, 9 JC: Sure.  Janie Bining Colford and I give permission for you to record this. 6 AS: Thank you.  Can you just start by talking a little bit about your childhood and where you grew up and where you went to college? 8, 9, 10, 11, 12 Just to kind of give us a little life background. 6, 8, 9, 11, 16, 17, 19 JC: Sure.  I grew up in a suburb of, in the country outside of Cincinnati, Ohio on a farm. 11, 16 It was mostly a grain farm but we had cows and pigs and chickens. 9 I was one of three girls. 8 Although I do have a half-brother from an affair my father had. 5, 20 A pretty normal farm girl childhood. 11, 18 I went to Claremont Northeastern School, high school. 8, 9 I have a horticulture degree and worked in the horticulture field for a number of years. 20 Then moved to Minnesota and worked, I think I was twenty-one maybe, when I moved to Minnesota. 8, 9 I worked for a landscape, lawn care company in Roseville. 7, 8 Albrecht Landscaping, actually. 10 Just did that for the summer. 9 Decided that horticulture wasn’t really a good year round thing in Minnesota. 8, 20 So I started working for Prudential. 9, 11 I came here, actually this is maybe key to the story. 9, 10, 19 I came to be in Minnesota because a guy that I met while in college that I was sort of engaged to, although I think it was more kind of a fling. 5, 8, 16, 17, 19 He came here for chemical dependency training. 9, 12, 19 After he got out of treatment he stayed here. 5, 9, 16 I moved here and we lasted maybe a month. 8, 9 Another guy that he lived with, that also had been in treatment, he and I started dating. 9, 11, 16 We ended up getting married and having two kids. 12 My ex-husband, is the father of my two older boys. 5, 8, 15, 20 He was in recovery for a number of years, although now he drinks and smokes. 6, 14, 20 As far as I know that’s all. 13, 14, 15 I don’t know what else you want to know. 13, 14, 15 I was twenty five or twenty six when I had my oldest son. 5, 9, 20 Then two years later had Chance. 20 Now I have three other children with my second husband. 14, 15, 20 AS: So how long were you married to your older boy’s father? 5, 20 JC: I think I got married in 1989.  We got divorced in 1997. 5 We split up in 1983.  AS: ‘93 do you mean? 16 Yes, ’93, so not very long.  [Laughs].  AS: Were you single parenting the boys for a while? 8, 10, 15, 16 JC: No, I had for probably a year and a half, I had them during the week and every other weekend he had them. 12, 19, 20 Then we switched to I had them for a week and he had them for a week.  He moved to the same town that I was in. 8, 19 So we were able to make that work, same school district and everything. 8, 9, 16 [Side conversation]. 12 [Recording resumes after break] 18 So we did week to week for the boys which worked out well for the most part. 8 Although different parenting styles in each house I’m sure was one of our biggest challenges. 6, 8, 9, 10, 11, 15, 16, 17 The fact that the boys stepmother, who was very controlling and very much wanted to be their real mom, made it a little bit difficult. 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17, 18, 20 Anyways we did that pretty much up until they were out of high school. 8, 16, 17, 18 Probably at least until the older one was. 5, 9, 20 When Chance, he’s the one with substance abuse disorder, when he was in high school he started using. 8, 9, 11 Maybe even before then. 15 When we started to become aware of that that was when he was in high school. 8, 9, 11, 13, 19 I think it was his senior year that my husband, my current husband, did a fellowship at the Mayo Clinic in Jacksonville, Florida.