went straight to injecting. 6, 9, 13 We decided that he was such a good negotiator and such a good liar that if we just tried to talk to him without support we wouldn’t be successful. 9, 10, 12 We hired an interventionist from somewhere in Ohio. 9, 12 Her name was Jane Metts. 6 She came out and we did some planning. 19 We decided on Promises Rehab Center out in California. 12 We had this big thing worked out. 8 The morning of it my husband and I kind of made up some, “We’re going somewhere” you know and got Chance. 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 It was at his dad’s house. 6, 9 We had someone watching the little kids at my house. 6, 9 We got him over there.  I’d already had a bag packed assuming this would all go his way. 16 We do this intervention and then Jane said, “You’ve heard from your mom and dad. 15 We’ve got this treatment center.” 9, 16 The director the treatment center had flown out. 9, 14, 16 This cost us a lot of money. 9, 17 [Laughs].  “You’ve heard all this and we’ve got this treatment center, Promises is all picked out for you, they’re ready for you.” 9, 15, 16 I can’t remember her name now. 6, 14 “She’s going to fly back with you.” 19 Patricia.  Patricia Meyers. 16 “So what do you think?”  He goes, “Well what are my other options?” 7 Jane said to him, “You don’t have any other options.” 7 He said, “Okay, well then I guess I’ll go.” 10 So he went, did ninety days at Promises. 19 AS: Did you confront, is that the first time you talked to him about his heroin use? 9, 10, 11 Did he admit to it at that point?  JC: Yes.  He was always, and always has been, and still is very forthcoming once you confront him. 9, 16, 17, 19 Once you get him to start talking about it. 9, 10, 11 He’ll do the whole denial thing like, “What are you talking about?” 10 [Yelling kids].  [Resumes after break in recording] 6, 18 He’s always, once you kind of get past the bullshit, then pretty open about his use. 9, 16, 17, 18 Has generally, when push comes to shove and it’s time to go to treatme