om the hospital. 7 I could barely understand him. 5, 9, 12, 16 They hadn’t sedated him or anything but by now the adrenaline’s gone and the drugs are there. 6, 14, 19 I asked him, “What’s going on?” 10 “I don’t really know.” 13, 14, 15 “Well can I talk to a nurse?” 10 He’s like, “I don’t know how to get a nurse.” 10, 13, 14, 15 Finally I call back and I get the nurse’s station and they’re like, “Well I can’t tell you what’s going on.” 7, 9, 10, 19 “Can you go to his room and get his permission to tell me? 6, 7 He’ll give it.” 6 They did and they’re telling me, “Physically he’s probably okay. 7 We did a CT and everything looks okay.  We’ll probably be releasing him tonight.” 19 I said, “What’s the tox screen say?”  That’s how I knew alcohol, heroin, benzodiazepines, or opioids and benzodiazepines. 6, 10, 12 I said, “Can you have him talk to a social worker or something? 10 Don’t just like release him and call me before you release him.” 7, 9, 12 None of that happened. 12, 13 They released him.  He tells me, he calls me later after he had been out and one of his buddies picked him up. 7 He calls me to say, “It was just a slip, I hadn’t been using very long. 7, 9, 12 I’m kind of glad that this happened because I didn’t know what else to do. 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 I was going to kill myself.” 7 I’m like, “Oh my God.” 10 He tells me this over the phone. 7 I’m thinking, “Okay.  Well that’s really scary but you’ve only been using for like a week.” 7 He’s like, “I’m just going to stop. 9, 10, 12 I’m going to stay in school and I’m going to get back on track.” 8, 9, 19 Within the course of a couple days it became really obvious it wasn’t just a slip and it wasn’t just a couple weeks. 5, 9, 12, 19 He wasn’t managing to stay sober. 6, 9 This all happened on a Tuesday evening, Friday I flew out there. 7, 12, 13, 15, 19 I got him to my hotel room and the next morning went back to my apartment to get his friend who was also using. 7, 12, 19, 20 I tried to help manage those two. 10, 13 I convinced him to come back here. 13, 19 That was in November.  He came back here kind of under the pretense that he would detox for a week. 10, 15, 16, 17, 19 He was so concerned that he didn’t want to drop out of school. 8, 13, 14 I’m like, “Okay. 10 We’ll detox for a week and then you can fly back.” 10, 19 No intention of really helping that happen from me. 12, 13, 15 AS: No intention for you getting him back there to finish a semester? 9, 15, 19 JC: Right.  He was really pissed off at me.  He was like, “I’m just going to get a ticket and fly myself.” 9, 10, 12, 13 I said, “Good luck.  I don’t know how you’re going to do that. 13, 14, 15 I’ve got your ID; I’ve got your bank account card. 7 You don’t have a job.  Your dad’s not going to be helping.” 13 His trust fund was paying for his rent. 9, 11, 16 AS: Oh his dad, he has a trust fund? 9 JC: He has a trust fund he does not have access to unless he’s in school. 6, 8, 9 Then he still doesn’t have access to. 6, 9 The trust pays directly to school; the trust pays directly to his rent. 8, 9, 16 He stayed here, got on Suboxone. 5, 9 AS: Has that helped him? 13, 16 Have any of those medicines…  JC: The Suboxone, I think, helped keep him off heroin. 12, 13, 16 There needs to be more for him and probably everyone. 13 He wasn’t and hasn’t been willing to do 12-step meetings. 9, 12, 13 He’s not a 12 Stepper whether or not he’s really given it a chance. 6 I’ve got to think he has because I mean he’s been in treatment, pretty much every treatment place he had to spend some time in 12-steps. 9, 11, 12, 16, 18, 19 While he’s on it, if he’s taking it he’s not taking heroin.  AS: But he’s had trouble giving up other substances? 9, 11 JC: Yes.  Like weed and alcohol.  Again, I don’t care about the weed. 7 I really don’t but the alcohol.  AS: That’s a real problem for him.  JC: I think the weed really helps his anxiety. 13 Any other thing that he does he does to excess.  AS: And he’s twenty six now and he’s relapsed again recently? 14, 18 How long has he been living at home? 6, 19 JC: Since November.  AS: Oh so this was that, the November you were talking about or is that a different November? 10, 16, 17 JC: Yes, a couple weeks ago he relapsed again. 18 This time it was a very short period of time, he went through all of his money. 16 It didn’t last very long. 9 He is now back on Suboxone. 14, 19 AS: Does he want to stay sober? 6, 9, 13 JC: He says he does.  I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 His actions haven’t really supported that. 10, 16 When we met with Charlie yesterday he told Charlie, “I want to get off heroin but I don’t want to give up weed.” 5, 6, 9, 13, 14, 19, 20 Charlie’s like, “I don’t have a problem with that. 10 If you want to use weed, if you use Suboxone daily and you want to keep using weed and you don’t use alcohol and you don’t use benzos or any other substance besides weed and Suboxone I’ll support that.” 9, 12, 13 He asked me if I was in support of that. 10 I said, “Yes, I’ll support that but if other substances start being used then we need to revisit this.” 9, 11, 12, 13 We’ll see.  That was just yesterday. 9, 12, 14, 19 AS: Could you talk about how you got involved with Steve Rummler? 10 JC: Sure.  So my nephew in 2013, I believe it was, died of a heroin overdose. 15 My sister’s oldest son, Drew. 5, 9, 20 [Long pause]. 9 He died of a heroin overdose. 15 JC: That was in May, March or May.  I think it was May of 2013.  No, it was March of 2013.  He had been using, he and his wife.  He has a daughter that’s the same age as my twins. 5, 14 He had been in and out of trouble, with possession and intent to sell. 7, 15 Not that he really was selling but he had enough on him to qualify for that. 7, 20 He had been a drinker. 6, 14 He had some DUIs.  He and his wife were both using.  A few years prior to him dying my sister and Ashley, that was his wife’s mother, got physical and legal custody of the daughter and shared custody. 5, 9, 12, 19, 20 Rory, the granddaughter, had already been in my sister’s and the other grandma’s care. 5, 7, 9 Drew and Ashley, they lost their house that Drew had bought. 6, 7, 9 He lost his job. 9 They didn’t really have anywhere to live.  They were living with Jackie for a little while but things got crazy. 6, 16 So Jackie said, “Drew you can stay here. 9 Ashley you cannot.”  Ashley went to live with her mother.  Drew’s living with Jackie. 6 Jackie’s husband who really, they weren’t really together but he was still living there. 6, 9, 15 She couldn’t just get him to go. 9, 12 He is an alcoholic; he was an alcoholic he recently passed. 5 Drew was living with Jackie; Ashley was living with her mom. 6, 15 They would still see each other. 9 Drew was taking Suboxone or Subutex, whichever he could get.  He got a prescription for Suboxone but he was sharing it with Ashley because Ashley couldn’t get in to see a doctor or wouldn’t get in to see a doctor.  So he would inevitably run out every month towards the end of the month of his Suboxone because he was sharing it. 8, 11, 12 He would go buy Subutex because it was easier to buy Subutex than Suboxone. 7 One time, it was a Friday, he and Ashley went to buy Subutex and they also bought heroin. 7, 19 Nobody but he and Ashley knew that they each had heroin. 6, 12 They each went back to their respective parent’s house and they used that Friday night and Saturday. 6, 9, 10, 16, 19 Then it was on a Sunday when he was at home in the basement of his mom’s house. 6, 9, 15, 19 Jackie had just talked to him. 9, 10, 11, 12 He’d gone downstairs and she was doing some laundry. 9, 14 The laundry room is downstairs. 7, 9, 14 It’d been ten, fifteen minutes. 7, 15 She went down to switch out some laundry and she heard a noise, kind of a gurgling noise. 14, 15, 16, 17 She’s like, “Drew! 10 Drew!”  She found him on the floor, needle in his arm. 13 He was still warm. 9 They figured out between text messages that it couldn’t have been more than ten minutes because he had just texted Ashley and Ashley had texted him back. 7, 9, 12, 13, 19 Then by the time she got down there it had been about ten minutes. 7 She doesn’t know if he used right after the text message. 9, 13, 14, 15 Long story short they live in the country so it took the EMTs a long time to get there. 9, 11, 16 The sheriff got there fairly quickly. 9 Jackie in the meantime had been giving him CPR. 11, 16 He had aspirated or had vomited and had aspirated they think.  By the time the EMTs got there, they had naloxone because the sheriff didn’t.  He had been down at least twenty minutes. 7, 9 They weren’t getting a pulse.  They got him to a hospital.  By the time they got him to the hospital it’d been about forty five minutes after Jackie had found him. 7 They had been working on him.  They finally came out and said they had a pulse. 19 My niece said, “You have a pulse because he’s living or because of what you’re doing?” 6 They said, “Well we have a pulse.”  So he was on life support for a few days but no brain activity. 10, 11, 19 They pulled the plug on; I think it was Wednesday of that week. 19 What got me involved was that my sister was just kind of beating herself up that she didn’t have naloxone. 5, 9, 12, 16, 17 I had never heard of it at this point. 15 AS: She knew what it was? 6, 12 I hadn’t heard of it. 15 In Ohio you couldn’t get it.  AS: This was in Ohio?  JC: This was in Ohio.  I had flown out there that Sunday evening. 15, 19 I was like, “Well what is that?” 10 She told me and I’m like, “Oh yes. 10, 14, 20 I’ve seen something on Facebook about that.”  I’m like, “Jackie even if, you couldn’t have had it. 10, 15 You can’t get that as an average citizen in Ohio.”  When I got back to Minnesota I started thinking, “Why can’t they get it?” 9, 11, 19 I called the Drug Policy Alliance to find out. 7, 8 How can we get this in Ohio and how can we get it in Minnesota?  I found out that someone in Ohio was working on it and that someone in Minnesota was working on it.  They gave me Lexi’s and Judy’s, I think I had called Cathy King Willis, I don’t know if you know who she is. 7, 13, 14, 15 She’s in Illinois and she works for Roosevelt University. 13, 14 She works for the Illinois Drug Consortium as well as Roosevelt University. 13, 14, 17 I had called her because I’d seen stuff from her on Facebook about naloxone laws in other states. 7, 9, 19 She put me in touch with the Drug Policy Alliance in New York who then put me in touch with Lexi and Judy. 8, 10, 15 AS: Right, here.  JC: I called to say, “I heard you guys are working on this. 7, 15 I want to help.” 13 I started meeting with her, at the time it was Lexi, Sarah Gordon, Julia Pownell, Julie Hooker. 9, 11, 13 AS: Was that the opioid…  JC: No, this was just working on the Good Samaritan Law. 9, 12 They had already worked with Senator Eaton to get it drafted and were just starting to find a co-author. 9, 11, 12, 14 They were starting to get in touch with Dan Schoen. 9, 11, 15 He co-authored it. 12 When I got involved the bill had already been drafted. 14 They were trying to work on how it was going to get introduced in the next session for 2014, getting public awareness prior to that. 16, 19 That’s when I got involved.  We would meet weekly at the Recovery Church in St. Paul which is where MRC was housed at the time. 6, 9, 13 That’s really how I became involved. 5, 19 Then I started, by then my son had been Hazelden earlier in 2013. 9, 11 He went right from Hazelden to New Roads down in Utah. 14 It was kind of a door to door thing. 16, 17 Hazelden was recommending long-term programs. 12 Chance found this place in Utah which looked more appealing to him I guess. 10, 11 They had outdoor activities and stuff. 9, 10 Then I started thinking, “Is Utah doing anything?” 9, 11 They were as well.  I kind of kept up with what Utah was doing and what Ohio was doing, really more actively working on what we were doing here in Minnesota. 10, 16, 17 The Utah thing, it got passed right around the same time ours did. 14 By this time Jerrica and Chance were living together. 6 I kept keeping them informed. 11, 12, 17 “It passed so if something happens don’t be afraid to call.” 7, 12 Which when it did happen she wasn’t. 12 She did call. 7 That was good.  AS: When he relapsed? 18 JC: When he overdosed in Utah. 15 He says he’s been revived with Narcan three times. 18 I was only aware of the one time.  Apparently there have been a couple other ones. 10, 16 AS: Yes, it’s a familiar story. 9 What do you do now with…? 14 JC: So now I’m on the board of directors. 5, 14 I’m also the vice chair of the board which really doesn’t mean anything unless the chair leaves. 5, 6, 12, 16 I’m a volunteer.  Right now I’m more involved in the overdose prevention program which was one of the three programs of the foundation. 14, 15 The other ones being prescriber education, and advocacy. 10 I’m mostly doing community training. 9 Most of my training has been one on one with other parents, training and distributing naloxone. 9, 10, 16 Right now though we’re at kind of a stand still because we have very few vials of naloxone left in our source for getting naloxone has dried up. 9, 12, 14, 16, 17 We were getting free product, the auto injector product from Kaleo.  They’ve stopped our last application to get some they denied and said that they would be reconsidering applications. 9, 10, 20 It wasn’t just ours that they denied, they didn’t approve any. 9, 12 They’re not doing their charitable piece right now which is a whole different story. 9, 14, 16, 17 This is the company that raised the price from $750 to $3,500. 5 AS: For two doses?  JC: Now it’s $3,500 for two doses.  AS: They just did this because the demand rose. 9, 12 JC: The cynical part of me says that they give all these free doses away because who would want an auto injector instead of a vial and needle? 6, 9, 13, 16 AS: Have those gone up too, the price of those?  JC: Yes, those have gone up as well.  AS: What’s the name of the company again? 6 JC: Kaleo.  How do you spell that?  Is it with a “C?”  This is the auto injector.  They were giving all this away. 11, 16 Now they’re not.  I’m sure hoping that the organizations they were giving it to will say, “Well we can’t afford that.” 11, 15 AS: No, how could anybody afford that?  JC: Right.  If you get a prescription of it your insurance will cover it. 7 AS: But you have to be given a prescription. 6 JC: Right.  You can go to any doctor and they’ll more than likely write you a prescription but most people aren’t going to do that. 10 AS: Not those users of heroin. 9 JC: A lot of moms who have shame aren’t going to do that either. 15, 17, 18 They’re not going to go and get it.  When we give it out we do training. 6 We give you a kit, not just the medication. 6, 9, 10, 12 We give the training that has the instruction card. 6, 7, 9 It has stuff in it. 9 Then we were also getting IM from the Harm Reduction Coalition.  JC: The needle, vial. 13 So we’ve had that as well.  We were getting that for sixty nine cents a vial.  Through the Harm Reduction Coalition which was getting it from Hospera which is the manufacturer, who’s now been bought by Pfizer. 7, 10, 14 They had a program where they were giving it to Harm Reduction Coalitions and other charitable people who their requirement was that whoever they’re selling it to for sixty nine cents a vial, now it’s like $18 a vial, but that’s the charitable price. 7, 11, 14 AS: The eighteen is now their charitable price? 14 JC: The retail price is $45 for one.  So sixty nine cents for one was totally reasonable and that’s what we were paying. 11, 16, 17 We were getting it through the Harm Reduction group which had this arrangement with Hospera. 7 Now the Harm Reduction group doesn’t think we’re grassroots enough. 20 There’s a perception that our program with the hospitals is that we’re giving this to the hospitals. 11 We’re supplying it to the hospitals to give to the people who have ODed, who come in to get revived. 6, 13, 19 AS: When they leave, because they’re just letting them back out. 6, 9, 12, 19 They’re not like taking them to treatment. 9, 16 JC: Right.  The hospitals weren’t going to do this.  The hospitals weren’t going to pay for this. 16 So we’re having it stored at the hospitals so the hospitals can get it to people. 5, 9, 12 AS: Just for distribution, that point of contact. 9, 10 JC: Right.  We have it at Methadone clinics for the same exact reason. 10 We have it at sober living houses so that when someone decides to fly out the door because they’ve had enough they can throw a kit at them. 6, 9, 20 When they’re leaving as overdose prevention they can give them a kit. 6, 15, 19 AS: Because so many people are dying after they leave sober houses. 6, 9 JC: Or even while they’re in sober houses. 6, 9, 15 Now all the sober houses that are a member of MASH, we’ve trained all the staff. 6, 9 AS: What is MASH?  JC: MASH is the Minnesota Association of Sober Houses. 9 If you’re a member of MASH they require that all their houses have our kit, not necessarily our kit, but have naloxone and that the house managers all know how to administer it. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15 They’ve all moved to a second tier now which is that when a person leaves their sober living, whether they leave because they’ve progressed far enough to where they’re ready to be on their own or they just leave, that they give them a kit when they leave. 6, 8, 9, 12, 14, 20 That’s because we’ve been able to supply that.  We’re getting it to the people on the street but the Harm Reduction Coalition thinks because we’re not a needle exchange that we’re not getting it to the people who need it. 9, 13, 16 We’ve got that perception to change. 16 So right now we have like a hundred… 14 AS: Which is again a stigma that comes from the Harm Reduction people about who the users are. 9, 13, 19 About who the addicts are.  Even when all the evidence shows us a whole new group of users. 6, 9 JC: Yes, yes. 14 Very true.  We have about a hundred vials left right now. 14 We’ve got so many requests for training. 9 AS: That’s so upsetting. 17, 19 JC: It’s crazy and we have no money because we’re such a small organization. 16 We don’t have any expertise in fundraising. 14 We’ve got some hurdles that we’re trying to… 16 AS: The kind of sick thing, in my opinion, is your having to fundraise to pay this huge markup on a product that actually saves a life immediately. 10, 11, 14, 16, 17 JC: I’ll tell you what.  Even if we had enough money to buy this now I wouldn’t because why the heck would they charge $3,500. 7, 14, 17, 20 AS: Right.  That’s just obscene. 9, 12 JC: The needle and the vial is just fine. 9, 12, 13, 14 Their markup was not anywhere near.  AS: Right and most heroin users are not going to be afraid of a needle and a vial to save a friend. 9, 12, 13 JC: And a parent that finds their kid, they’re not going to hesitate either. 10, 13, 16 I get why law enforcement wants to have the nasal. 11, 13 Those are like $75 through the charitable program.  You can get the nasal.  AS: This is just on the arm. 9, 12 JC: Or the thigh. 8 This is the auto.  Like an epi pen kind of application thing. 10, 16, 17 That’s just my bias. 9, 12 That’s what I do for the foundation.  Right now we’re trying to figure out how to get naloxone, what source we have. 13, 14, 16 We’ve tapped into a few resources but aren’t having any luck.  Now we’ve got to focus on how to get more money. 15 Even the $18 a vial is out of reach. 13 We ask for a $25 donation for our kits.  If we had to put two doses, which is what we put in a kit, that’s $36 right there. 10, 14 If someone doesn’t have the $25 to donate we give them a kit anyway. 6, 16 I’ve given a ton away. 6, 16 It’s crazy. 16 It’s crazy. 16 AS: What would you say, just changing the topic a little bit, did you have a two thirty? 9, 12, 16, 18 JC: I thought my daughter’s friend was coming around that time but I guess she’s not here. 5, 10, 11, 12 AS: Are you okay to keep going for a minute then? 12 I’m wondering what the most shocking or alarming thing, or out of character thing you’ve done as the mother of an addict? 10 That you would have never, ever done in another circumstance. 9, 15 JC: Giving my son money knowing full well he was going to buy heroin because he was in such pain that I couldn’t watch him. 7, 11, 13, 14, 15 AS: Because he was in withdrawal? 14 Yes, basically buying heroin for him. 7, 11 And not being truthful with my spouse just because I didn’t want to deal with that right then. 9, 12, 13, 14 It was more important for me to focus on getting Chance stable. 9, 15, 18 And worry about this other stuff later. 9, 11 I never thought I would be as deceitful as I have been. 11, 12, 15 AS: In what way? 16 Just with your spouse? 9 JC: Yes, keeping secrets mostly with my spouse. 9, 11, 12 Keeping secrets to protect my son, in theory, whether it really was protecting him or not.  Who knows? 13, 14, 15 AS: You don’t have to answer this if you don’t want to. 13 How has your marriage been through this?  Has he been a support?  Have been you been able to parent Chance together at all? 10, 16 JC: Oh not much, no. 18 Really that was never even when he wasn’t using. 15 When he was young John would participate in things but he was never felt like it was his job to be the dad. 14, 15, 16, 17 AS: So most of this, would it be fair to say, most of Chance’s addiction has been yours to deal with? 13 JC: To some extent his dad and his stepmother have been involved but it’s always been, when it’s convenient for them or when I pull them in. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 It’s not generally, they don’t generally make it a point to call him and talk to him and find out how he’s doing and really listen. 7, 9, 10, 15, 16, 17 That always comes back on me. 13, 16, 17, 19 Why didn’t I tell them?  Why didn’t you ask?  When this stuff happened in November, I never give my husband enough credit because when this was happening in November. 6, 9, 12, 13, 15, 20 AS: Remind m