6, 17 JC: When this all happened, like you said, trying to affect the outcome. 12, 13, 16, 19 Trying to figure out when do I tell? 13 What do I tell?  I went out there on a Friday; I got in back here on a Sunday. 19 Sunday, night I sent a big long email to his dad and stepmom. 7, 8, 9, 12, 15, 19 The next morning I got reamed by the stepmom for not having told them last Wednesday when Chance called me. 7, 9, 12, 15, 19, 20 I’m like, “Okay. 10 Here’s the deal.” 13 AS: He’s twenty six years old first of all. 9, 20 JC: Right.  There’s many things but the one thing that kept popping into my mind that I just kept throwing back was one of the times when I helped get him back from another state, to get him into detox, when I called his dad to tell his dad. 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 16, 18, 19 “I’ve got Chance on a flight this morning from California to here.  He’s going right from here to detox and right from detox to treatment.” 9, 10, 14, 16 His dad response was, “Good luck with that.”  I said, “If you don’t want updates from me on your son then just let me know because I won’t waste my time giving them to you.” 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 He said, “The next update I want is when he’s sixty days sober and has a job or he’s in a box.” 6, 13, 19 I said, “The next update you get on your son will be from your son not me.”  I got over that anger and of course have given him updates since then. 6 I said to Linda, the stepmom, I’m like, “You guys want to be involved, and you want to hear all this.” 9, 10, 12, 13, 15 She’s like, “He’s telling me that you’re drug testing him and you’re telling me you’re not.” 9, 10, 14 I said, “If he’s telling you that I’m drug testing him and he’s telling me that you’re drug testing him shame on me for not following up with you and asking you if you were and shame on you for not following up with me. 9, 12, 13, 14 If we don’t believe and the history has been that this continues to happen. 9, 12 It’s not just me not asking the questions. 6, 9, 12, 13 It’s you guys too.”  AS: At some point, Chance has to live with what he’s doing.  JC: Right, right. 14 AS: And how he talks to his family. 10, 14, 18 JC: Right.  AS: His parents. 10, 16 JC: I don’t know why I brought that up. 9, 13, 14, 15, 18 AS: I think it’s related to how we try to navigate what are already complex, blended family situations with an addict child. 12, 13, 16, 18 From your ex-husband’s perspective it’s either he’s sober or he’s dead, don’t tell me about it. 6, 15 That’s such a common response among some parents. 10, 16 They get to their threshold, they get to their point where they just can’t. 9, 12, 20 If you’ve always been there doing what you’re doing then you’re an easy target. 16, 17 JC: I know you had asked me also what the thing that I did that I never ever thought I would do. 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 I’ve not just done that once. 9, 12 It’s that whole, when you know he’s in lots of pain and you’re not going to be able to get into detox for a couple days. 5, 10, 13, 14, 15, 17, 19 AS: That was the situation? 13 It wasn’t just… 9, 12 JC: It wasn’t just he’s out of money and I know he needs to use. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 It’s always your waiting for a detox. 10, 16, 17 JC: Or you’re waiting to get on Suboxone.  AS: Access to care is a huge barrier and makes you do things that you would never, ever consider doing. 5, 7, 15, 16 JC: We’re one of the lucky ones because I hear from other parents that are on wait lists for weeks. 9, 10, 16 We’ve really never had to be on a waitlist for more than a couple days for a treatment center. 9, 15, 16, 19 I don’t know if it’s because we have private insurance, I don’t know if it’s because it’s the type of insurance that we have, I don’t know if it’s because I’m so aggressive, making so many different calls. 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 We’ve had; fortunately, the opportunity to send him out of state if that’s what’s needed. 9, 12, 13 Or send him out of state if that’s the only place that’s available. 9, 11, 12 AS: He’s really, in some ways, alive potentially because of your ability to do what you do. 15, 16, 17 JC: Probably.  That and his willingness to finally say, “Yes, I’ll take help.” 6, 13 AS: When he slips up.  JC: The fact that he’s not stuck with state insurance. 7, 9, 10 Not that they’re bad because they work for other people, but you hear more horror stories and people that can’t get in because their on state and so there’s a big long waitlist. 8, 9, 18 I think people who have private insurance get better treatment which is not fair. 7, 9, 14, 16 I’m glad he’s been in that position. 13 Sometimes I feel guilty. 5, 16, 18 AS: It’s the system. 8, 9 It’s a bigger issue. 8, 15 JC: Our insurance has always been so good that… 7, 16, 17 you hear those stories where they get fourteen days and their insurance stops paying, that’s never been our case. 7, 9, 10, 11, 15, 16, 18, 19 I mean even with Hazelden, they were going to approve him to stay in the long term plan there. 9, 15, 16 That was probably the facility we waited the longest to get in. 9 It was three days. 19 That wasn’t very long but that was the longest he ever had to wait, when he was ready. 9 AS: He’d be detoxing at home or? 10, 19 JC: That time I think he was at Fairview.  He detoxed at Fairview and then went to, no he didn’t. 10 He didn’t detox at all. 10 He went right there using to Hazelden. 14 When I found out he had relapsed, I thought he was in recovery, when I found out he had relapsed I was in Hawaii. 11, 12, 18 His friend, who actually has since died of an overdose in January of this year out on Park Avenue Treatment Center, he had called me and said, “Don’t tell Chance I’m telling you this but he is using with my brother.” 5, 7, 10, 12, 15, 20 I called Chance right after that and said, “Do you have anything you need to tell me.” 7, 13, 14 He’s like, “No.” 10 I said, “Think about that.  I probably won’t be asking if I didn’t know something.” 13, 14, 15 He said, “I’m using.”  I said, “Here’s the deal. 13 You need to come up with a plan. 13, 19 Why don’t you call me back when you have one?” 7, 19 About five hours later he called me and said he had talked to Hazelden and he had initiated an assessment. 7, 10, 11 By the time I got back, this was towards the end of our trip there, by the time I got back here I had to do a couple things with insurance and the next day I think I took him in. 7, 12, 16, 19 He was, I’m sure, high when I got him there. 8, 15 AS: This is good.  Thank you so much. 18 JC: You’re welcome, a lot of stuff. 9, 13, 17, 19 AS: Yes, it’s a crazy road we’re on. 9, 16 JC: Yes it is. "
"3","Berry-Brede_Linda","Bill Cole Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer April 2, 2017  At the Home of Amy Sullivan Minneapolis, Minnesota Bill Cole -BC Amy Sullivan -AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan.  I’m at my home in Minneapolis with William Cole. 19 Bill Cole.  It is April 2, 2017.  Bill do you give me permission to record this interview? 6 AS: Thank you.  Let’s go back to what you were going to say about birds and childhood. 11, 19 BC: We were just talking about; Amy has a stack of bird books here. 9, 10, 12 I like birds, nature. 10 We were talking about pets. 10 Growing up I had all kinds of pets but never had a single dog which is kind of funny. 10, 15, 16, 17 I grew up in East Africa where my parents were missionaries. 9, 10, 15, 16 The mission forbade missionaries to have dogs because they were afraid of rabies. 10, 12, 15 We had everything else under the sun.  Different kinds of monkeys and baboons and antelopes and wild pigs and birds. 16, 17 AS: Where in East Africa did you grow up? 9, 17 BC: I was born in Ethiopia.  I live there until I was fourteen.  Then I moved to Southern Sudan. 8 I was going to a boarding school in Kenya when my parents worked in Sudan. 5, 8, 10, 16 Different way of growing up. 16, 17 AS: Do you want to talk about that a little more? 10, 13 When were you born?  How old are you? 20 BC: I was born in 1962.  That makes me fifty five. 16 I was born in the capital of Ethiopia, Addis Ababa.  My parents worked in many cases in very remote areas. 10, 16 We never owned a vehicle in Ethiopia. 15 There weren’t roads; the only way in and out was by airplane or by foot or mule. 9, 13, 16 No electricity, no running water. 6, 7, 11, 20 A very full life. 11 A lot of adventure. 17 I went to boarding school in the capital. 5, 8 AS: At what age?  BC: I started when I was seven. 9, 11 My brothers started when they were six or maybe even five. 5, 9, 11, 15 We would spend four or five years in Africa and then come back to the states for a year or to Ireland. 8, 9, 12, 13, 19, 20 My dad is from Ireland. 8 Then we’d come back and be on furlough. 13, 19 We’d go back and forth. 19 Boarding school was an interesting experience. 8, 9, 19 Not all bad, not all good.  AS: You were in boarding school in Kenya or in Ethiopia? 5, 8 BC: When we lived in Ethiopia I went to boarding school in Ethiopia in the capital. 5, 8 We would travel back and forth on vacations to see my folks. 10, 19 AS: But your parents would be kind of out in the bush? 9, 10, 16, 17 BC: Yes.  AS: Did you have a home? 19 BC: In the bush, yes. 9, 14 My dad was a builder.  He would go into a place and he’d build a clinic. 11 My mom was a nurse and she ran the clinic. 7, 15 My dad would build school buildings and houses. 6, 8, 9 He would hire Ethiopian teachers to teach and he’d administer the school and they’d move on to another place. 8, 9, 11 AS: What was the church affiliation?  BC: It’s an interdenominational Protestant organization. 9 We had all denominations.  AS: What was it called? 7 BC: It was called Sudan Interior Mission. 7 At the time now it’s called Serving in Mission. 7, 14 AS: So it’s still going? 9 BC: It’s a pretty large organization, well known. 10, 13, 14, 15, 18 They do a lot of development work as well as evangelical work. 16, 17 AS: Where are your parents now? 10, 14, 16 BC: They’ve both passed.  AS: Did they continue to do this even into your adulthood? 15 BC: Oh yes. 14 I lost my mom when I was sixteen. 9, 15 Then my dad remarried another missionary out there. 15 The only reason why they came back was because of his health issues. 14, 15, 19 He loved being there. 13 That was his life. 11 He loved wild places and wild people that lived in them. 11, 13, 17 AS: People kind of untouched by… 15, 16, 17 BC: He never really felt that comfortable. 15, 17 I don’t know how to put it. 10, 13, 14, 15 In formal urban settings. 17 He’d freak out if he got into an elevator.  He just didn’t like it. 9, 10, 12 AS: He was from Ireland? 8 Tell me about him a little bit and your mom? 15 BC: He grew up in Northern Ireland. 8 Went to school until about eighth grade equivalent. 8, 20 He did an apprenticeship under my grandfather. 5, 7, 16 Then had a conversion experience and decided that he wanted to be a missionary in Africa. 12, 13, 15 His father, my grandfather, said, “You’re out of here. 5, 7 I don’t want to see you again.” 13 That stayed. 5, 9 My grandfather died a very bitter man unfortunately. 5, 7 AS: Was it because of the religion that your dad professed?  Was it all Protestant? 9 BC: It was Protestant. 9 But my dad’s taking it seriously. 15 I think my grandfather was upset that my dad wasn’t carrying on the family business. 5, 7, 9, 17, 18, 19 He was a joiner or carpenter. 7 That was upsetting to him. 17, 19 My mom came from New England, from Boston. 8, 9, 15, 19 Her family was really from Nova Scotia. 18 They moved down and she went out unmarried. 8 AS: She went into missionary work unmarried? 15 BC: Yes.  They met later? 5 BC: Yes.  So for my dad he was very adventurous and I could see him doing that.  For a single young woman from a proper Boston upbringing to go and do this thing was just amazing to me. 9, 12, 14, 15 They met and married out there and had four kids. 5 I’m the youngest of four boys. 8, 9, 14 The things that my mom put up with. 10, 15, 16 Before they were married my dad would take off. 6 The mission would want to learn about places in Ethiopia, remote places. 11, 12, 13, 17 They said, his name was also Bill, “We’ll send Bill out and find out what’s going on out there.” 6, 12 My dad, he’d have a schedule.  He’d say, “I’ll be back in January.” 19 March would come around and he still wouldn’t be back. 8, 9, 13, 19 There’s no contact at all. 10 You’re out there.  Crazy, crazy experiences. 16 Once they got married that settled down. 17 BC: Yes and they were established in one place. 9, 11 She would run a clinic. 11 I have a lot of admiration for my mom. 15, 17 She was an amazing person. 15 Some of the things that she would do is just crazy. 9, 12, 16 Sometimes there’d be tribal warfare going on. 5, 18 She would have to take care of people sometimes with no anesthetics. 5, 6, 7, 9, 18 AS: She’d basically be the only medical person. 7, 11, 14 BC: Right.  My dad would help out where he could. 13 The level of commitment that they had was amazing. 15, 20 Just incredible. 9, 12 The love they had for each other and this common purpose is just astounding. 9, 12, 13 There’s one time where there was a tribal skirmish going on.  Our station was neutral. 9 No fighting at the station because all the wounded would be coming in. 9 The fighting would flare up and the women and children would all come to our station. 9, 13, 14, 18, 19 They would stay there and then the wounded would start coming in. 9, 11 And the tension. 15 AS: Because it would be women from both sides? 18 BC: Both sides, right. 14 The wounded from both sides.  Anytime that my dad wanted to leave the station, the home tribe, they were one of the warring tribes. 6, 9, 12, 13, 19 They really respected and appreciated my parents being there but if we wanted to leave the station the chief said, “You can’t leave unless you have seven or eight young men around you, armed men, to make sure that you’re protected.” 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 It was really touch and go sometimes. 5, 15, 18 AS: You said you moved to Sudan? 8 BC: We went from the kettle to the frying pan or something.  That was a dangerous place too. 11, 18 It’s an interesting upbringing. 9, 19 In a lot ways I sensed a lot of freedom, being able to move around. 8, 16, 17 But there’s also a lot of danger too. 17 There’s a certain element of danger.  I kind of like that. 16, 17 Everything’s an adventure there.  AS: You don’t have to go find out.  BC: Exactly. 10 AS: They exist simultaneously. 9 What about high school? 8 Your brothers, did you all go? 5 How long were you educated in Africa? 10 BC: Almost all of us through high school. 8, 9 Then we all came back to the states for college. 8, 9, 19 AS: Is there a big range in your ages? 7, 8 BC: Ten years. 20 I came back when I was eighteen. 19 I took a year off in high school and spent part of the time in Sudan with my dad. 8, 19, 20 Then I came back and spent the rest of the time working to get enough money for college. 8, 9, 19, 20 When I was in eighth grade I was in the states and I had a paper route. 9, 19, 20 I saved up five hundred dollars in eighth grade. 20 That was a lot of money. 17 I put it in a bank account in New York because I knew that I would need it someday. 6, 10, 12, 13, 19 I came back to New York and picked up my five hundred bucks and I was on my way. 16, 19 I grabbed my Greyhound ticket and I was going. 13 AS: Back up and tell me how did your mom pass? 15 BC: It was a car accident in Sudan. 7 We were both in the same car accident. 7 It was a pretty rough experience but a pretty amazing experience too. 15, 18 We were in the back of a heavy pickup and it flipped over. 19 My mom and I were in the back. 15, 19 She got thrown out.  We both got thrown up.  It landed on top of me. 8 AS: The truck?  BC: Yes.  They tried to lift it off of me and they couldn’t. 10 I was conscious the whole time which was even worse. 15 I was in shock.  There happened to be a bulldozer down the way. 12, 13, 16 This was in a part of Sudan where there are no paved roads within hundreds of miles and maybe ten working bulldozers. 9, 12, 14, 15 It was just amazing this thing was there. 9, 12, 15 It was able to lift it off of me.  This is kind of an awful story. 9, 10, 16, 17 They pulled me out and they took me to this nearest village where there was a medical, what they called a dresser, a paraprofessional who happened to be drunk at the time. 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19, 20 I didn’t know. 13, 14, 15 My mom seemed to be doing okay at the time. 15, 19 She’s hurting and her side was injured. 12 From my waist down I had been crushed. 9 He had grabbed my legs and was moving my legs around. 8 Just then these two Europeans came into this hut. 9, 19 Big, kind of balding but young European guy grabbed the dresser and just decked him. 9, 12, 14, 16, 17 Just knocked him on his butt. 9 He saw what he was doing.  This guy was a doctor.  He was working on a startup sugar cane plantation down there. 9, 11 He grabbed us and hauled us out to his facility.  I had injured my hands and he was stitching it up and stitching up my head and stuff. 9, 12 Then the next day we flew up to Khartoum. 7, 19 AS: Were your legs broken? 5 BC: My pelvis was crushed in four places. 11, 17 That’s what we knew at the time. 6, 12 We were in this place in Khartoum that wasn’t very good. 11 That’s where my mom, I think she had a blood clot or something. 11, 15, 17 It really was kind of awful. 10, 16, 17 We’re both in the same room. 7 I can’t move.  I’m paralyzed essentially from the waist down. 7, 9 She expired right there. 12, 14 It was kind of brutal. 16, 17 It was tough. 18 They flew me back to the states after that. 7, 9, 19 My mom was buried in Khartoum. 15 They flew me back to the states and they found out one of my vertebrae was cracked too. 7, 9, 19 At that point I was able to start moving my legs around a little more. 9, 11 I didn’t have very much feeling in my left leg. 16, 18 The doctor was saying, “You’ll be very fortunate to walk unaided again. 11 You’ll be here for at least a year.” 9, 20 BC: I was able to leave in a couple of months. 6, 8 I was fortunate.  I had a killer physical therapist, Patty. 6, 7, 9 She was great. 11 Then we moved back. 8, 19 AS: I was just interested. 9, 11, 12, 19 Thanks for sharing that.  That must have been hard though on everybody. 11 BC: It was hard. 11 It was really hard for my dad. 11 AS: They were a team.  BC: It was hard on his and my relationship. 11 I was coming home from school, from boarding school, and it would just be he and I. 5, 8, 9, 12, 19 Maybe sometimes some other people. 5, 18 You’re dealing with those teenager years to begin with and there is all this tension. 13, 15, 20 It was hard. 11 AS: Where did you go to college? 8 BC: I went to a small Christian school in Arkansas called the John Brown University. 7, 8, 9, 13 Have you heard of John Brown? 15 AS: I grew up in Tulsa.  We’re close to Tulsa.  AS: John Brown University is in what town? 13, 19 BC: Siloam Springs.  AS: I was going to guess somewhere around there. 8, 10 BC: I chose that school because I knew people that I grew up with there. 6, 8, 12 I had one cousin in the U.S. and all the rest of them were in Ireland. 5, 8, 9, 19 I had no connections here.  It was a great experience. 11 That’s where I met Laurie, my wife. 5 BC: She’s from Minnesota.  AS: Wow, and she ended up down in Arkansas. 12 BC: She wanted to head south and get warm. 7, 12, 13 AS: You guys met and then tell me about that and how you ended up here. 5, 12 I was smitten I guess. 10, 15 We met; we were friends for a long time. 5, 12, 18 We did a lot of fun stuff together. 9, 17 We used to run together a lot. 9, 11, 17 We’d go out and just have fun. 9, 12 Then we started dating. 9, 11 That was a great way to go about doing things. 11, 16 We got married on graduation day. 19 AS: You’re like twenty two, twenty three?  BC: Yes.  All of our friends were there. 12, 18 Why go someplace else? 11 We knew we wanted to get married. 6, 12, 13 Why get married and have everybody come to us? 13, 19 We planned everything and it was so low-key.  It was so fun.  It was a really simple thing.  Our families were all coming anyways. 16, 17 It was such a small school too. 8 At graduation they call your name and you walk across the aisle. 6, 7 “Bill Cole is getting married this afternoon.”  It was a great school experience. 8, 11 AS: What did you major in? 18 BC: Biology.  I love nature. 13 AS: When did you guys get married?  BC: We got married in ‘86.  From there we went to Florida, Fort Meyers, and lived there for a year. 16, 20 I did an internship for a non-profit called the Educational Concerns for Hunger organization. 7, 10, 14 They provide technical assistance to agriculture workers overseas. 9 They have a seed bank.  They redistribute seeds and collect information. 9, 12, 17 We lived in a small trailer in Fort Meyers, it was great. 11, 16 From there we moved to the Bahamas and lived in the Bahamas for a year, a small island. 8, 20 There were like twelve people on the entire island, it was a research facility. 8 From there we moved back up to Minnesota for the summer and then down to Alabama for graduate school. 8, 19 I did my graduate work in fisheries and aquaculture.  Laurie did hers in library and information sciences. 17 I went to school at Auburn. 8 She did her coursework at the University of Alabama. 13 If you know anything about those two schools people could not believe that we were married because there’s such a focus on football. 8, 13, 14, 15 AS: As if that dictates all relationships.  It’s crazy. 16 We finished up graduate school. 8 We got to California for a year. 20 I worked on a commercial fish farm out there, a tilapia farm.  Then from there we moved to the Virgin Islands for seven years. 8, 20 Will, our son, our one and only son was born down there.  He’s actually born here but then we moved. 8, 10 Then we left there when he was one and a half maybe. 9, 20 At that point we totally enjoyed living down there. 6, 17 It was a great place to be at that time. 11 We wanted Will to have some roots someplace. 11, 12, 13 We thought that was important. 11, 12 We moved back to the States, back to Alabama for a year. 8, 19, 20 I was working for Auburn in the fisheries program.  We moved up to Minnesota when Will was like two and a half. 8, 20 Then we’ve been here for nineteen years. 20 Hopefully the math adds up. 11 AS: How does that feel after moving around? 8, 16 You moved a lot as a kid too. 8, 17 BC: I have a hard time being in one place for too long. 11 I’ve gotten more used to it. 9, 15 That said, we’ve always told Will that once he’s out of college that all bets are off. 8, 16, 17, 20 Once he’s out of high school all bets are off. 8 We’ll go wherever we want to go. 13 I’ve no qualms about picking up and moving at all.  I love experiencing other places and other cultures and other people. 11, 13, 17 That’s the spice of life for me. 11 AS: Talk about Will.  Was his childhood pretty steady, pretty stable? 9, 11, 18 BC: Yes, I would think it pretty typical. 18 AS: I’m just guessing, I don’t mean to put words in your mouth. 9, 10, 12, 16 BC: I think you’re right. 14 A pretty typical suburban, middle class upbringing. 8, 18, 20 Both parents working. 10, 16 He went to a daycare fairly early on. 7, 18, 19 Developed friends from that daycare at an early school experience that he still has today. 7, 8, 9, 12, 18, 19 Really good friends. 12, 18 It’s really good that he still stays in touch with them. 9, 15 They really have a very close bond.  That’s a really fun thing.  That’s good.  He went through the Minnetonka school system? 8, 9 He was very social, very active, and athletic. 10, 19 He loved sports; he loved running around and games. 7, 8, 10, 11, 13 He was an avid reader.  I remember him reading the Harry Potter books, he was really young. 11, 14 I remember reading to him when he was at a certain age. 11 I remember him reading to me and me falling asleep. 7, 11 It was great. 11 It was a lot of fun. 17 BC: Yes.  We did a lot of stuff together. 9, 17 We did martial arts together which was fun.  It was a great father-son activity. 5, 10, 11 We’d both get into it.  We got our black belts.  He continued on and I ended up teaching for quite awhile. 12, 18 He dropped out after his black belt. 14 I don’t blame him. 17 He achieved something that was really good.  He said, “I just want to try other things.” 9, 12, 13, 16 “Fine, that’s great.” 11 It was a great experience. 11 He played football, basketball. 8 He got into lacrosse.  He was a very good lacrosse player up into high school. 8 When he started using then he totally dropped out. 9, 11, 14, 17 It was sad. 12 One of those things you give up. 6, 16 AS: Do you want to talk about that? 10, 13 When you first started noticing stuff? 9, 11 BC: I think Will being as social as he was and always wanting to be around people and be doing the “in” kind of thing. 13, 16, 17 I think he started smoking weed when he was around fourteen. 8, 9, 11 I think it started out occasional. 9, 11 It just fully progressed. 9, 11, 12 It got to the point where in high school I think he was smoking almost daily, at least numerous times a week. 8, 9, 18 He started using other drugs, opioids at around seventeen. 9, 10, 11, 14 From what he tells me the first time he ever tried them was one of his friends gave him some pills. 9, 10, 12, 18 His friends had this sports injury and had some extra pills that he gave to Will. 12, 18 Will took some and Will knew right then that was his drug of choice. 6, 12, 14, 17 That was what he was looking for.  Other drugs, primarily benzos and Xanax. 14 Those kinds of things. 16, 17 He started out with Vicodin and oxycodone and then I learned this a little bit later but he got into fentanyl. 9, 11, 12, 17 He was doing IV fentanyl a couple times in high school and then much more later on. 8, 9, 18 It was kind of a downhill slide through high school. 8, 16, 17 We tried to get him into outpatient up at Hazelden. 9, 10 I think at the time we just thought it was pot but it was heavy use. 9, 11, 12 How old was he? 20 BC: He was a junior. 8 He continued to use and he got kicked out of the program. 9, 18 He tried some other counseling. 10 He does have a history of anxiety issues. 9, 14, 15 I will back up a little bit. 19 When he was fourteen he was inpatient for anxiety at Riverview. 9 AS: Fairview?  BC: Fairview Riverside for a week.  I don’t know if that was the best experience for him. 9, 13, 14, 15 I think he was introduced to the drug culture there. 14 I think it was kind of traumatic on him too. 16, 17 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 AS: The institutional part? 9 BC: Yes, the institutional part and being away from home and being stuck in this place where he couldn’t leave. 6, 9, 11, 16, 19 I think that’s definitely influenced his story. 9, 20 Fast forwarding into high school, he entered his senior year using pot. 8, 9, 12, 20 I think that’s what we knew what he was doing at that time. 6, 12 His grades were always pretty good. 16, 17, 18, 20 He was always a good student. 9, 16, 17 Then his behavior was starting to change more and more. 9, 11, 16 I didn’t know I really didn’t know what was going on. 13, 14, 15 The signs of opioid use, the nodding, the pinpoint pupils. 9 I didn’t know at first. 9, 13, 14, 15 I knew he was doing something, some kind of drug. 6, 12, 14, 16, 17 It was so insane to me.  I remember telling him this, “Will, if I knew that you weren’t doing drugs I would take you to the hospital right now because of the way you’re acting. 6, 10, 12, 14, 16 I know you’re doing drugs, I know the reason.” 13, 14, 15 It’s so irrational, why don’t I take him to the hospital right now? 6, 14 It’s insane.  It doesn’t make any sense. 16, 17 Somehow I justified it in my mind. 9, 12 We definitely sought treatment for him. 9, 16 Once we understood what it was then we sought care. 7, 9 AS: You’re saying that the fact that you knew he was using drugs didn’t prompt you to take him to the hospital. 6, 10, 11, 12, 14 BC: To rush him to the hospital.  AS: Because you knew it was drugs. 6, 12, 14 If it had been anything else you would have seen how crazy, what bad shape he was in. 16 BC: Yes, somehow it made it not okay but I thought I understood what was going on. 9, 11, 12, 16 It’s at that point, I didn’t rush him to the hospital but we said we’ve got to get really serious about it.  AS: Did he ever admit what he was using?  At that point if you had said, “What are you doing?”  BC: I don’t recall when I first found out that he was doing opioids. 7, 9, 10 It was sometimes later in his seni