arted using pretty heavy. 9, 11, 18, 19 Then I found him again in his bathroom passed out. 7 That’s when I realized that he was IV fentanyl. 9, 14 I grabbed him and had my Narcan kit with me.  I didn’t administer it at the time. 9 I took him up to the emergency room. 7 The put him right on a Narcan drip. 10, 14 What they said was for heroin users they give them one shot. 6, 9, 15 They had him on a drip for four hours or something. 11, 14 Just to keep him awake. 9, 12 He was not happy about this situation at all. 13, 17 Then he went into treatment again. 9, 16 I had a hard time getting him into treatment even after overdosing in January. 9, 11, 15, 16 He went to Beauterre to treatment there. 9, 16 He came back, relapsed and now he’s in Hazelden. 14, 18, 19 AS: Where’s Beauterre?  BC: It’s in Owatonna.  It’s a good place. 11 He’d been there twice.  How I’m feeling, right now it’s just now that I’ve come to the really true realization that I can’t do anything for Will. 9, 12, 13, 14, 16, 19 As much as I try to get him into treatment that’s not helping him. 9, 13, 16, 18 It’s great that he’s there, don’t get me wrong. 11 He’s there and he’s not using.  Any day that he’s not using is a victory. 19 I don’t think he can live at home. 19 That’s a sad thing. 12 It’s not my choice. 17 AS: You haven’t had really a break since he got home in December from the chaos of addiction? 18, 19 BC: Right.  He was in Beauterre for thirty days. 19 You’re still not away from it. 9, 16 AS: You’re on because you’re visiting and you’re checking in. 12, 13 This is his sixth time in inpatient? 9 BC: Yes.  AS: Did he go willingly?  Do you want to talk about what you said early when you first got here about what you had to say? 9, 10, 13 BC: A few times, probably three out of the sixth times, we’ve told him, “It’s either treatment or you’re out on your own.” 9, 16, 18, 20 That’s what it came down to this time too. 19 AS: Has he ever left?  BC: I think he maybe spent one night out. 9, 19 “I don’t 