 is your boundary. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 16 You better understand it.” 9, 12, 16 With one kid it’s a little bit softer.  If that makes sense. 16, 17 AS: I think that’s a good way to put it. 10, 16 You don’t have to be as strict. 9 You can do more negotiating and coming to terms and dealing with each other. 13 BC: I think that’s right. 14 I think my own upbringing kind of influences my approach as a father. 5, 16, 17, 20 Growing up in boarding school, very restrictive, especially the first boarding school I went to. 5, 8, 9, 19, 20 Not only physically restrictive, there was a fence all the way around with barbed wire on top. 5, 7, 8, 9, 16, 19 Mostly for our protection. 9 We’d sneak out and stuff. 9 Also, all your time was occupied.  There’s very little freedom.  We were up early in the morning for Bible study, breakfast, school and we had rest hour right after lunch. 6, 8, 9, 14, 18, 19 We had to be in the dorm and lying on the bed and be quiet.  Back to school and then sports and then supper and then study hall and then to bed. 8, 9 Saturday was glorious. 19 Saturday was your day. 19 One of the punishments was they’d take away your Saturday and make you stay in the dorm room on your bed and you had to be quiet all day. 6, 7, 9, 16, 19 Besides they whipped you too.  AS: Did you get in trouble?  BC: Yes, I got into trouble a lot. 17 There was this real restriction and control. 9, 17, 19 I resent to this day. 7, 19 Critical thinking was not encouraged.  Being able to explore things was not encouraged. 16 This is the way you think and that’s it. 16 Now as a parent I push away from that. 10, 16 Maybe I give Will more freedom than he really needed. 6, 13 I’m not judging myself this is just what I’m perceiving. 9, 12 I want Will to know why he believes what he believes. 13, 14, 15 I want him to be his own person and be able to think critically. 7, 13 Maybe I drove him way too far the other way. 7, 14, 16 We had boundaries.  We were relatively strict with things. 9, 16 The thin