e and bring the dog. 10, 12, 13, 19 I told him not to get the dog because I said, “I am not taking care of that dog when you decide you’re tired of it and can’t handle it on the street anymore.” 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 20 And blah blah blah.  Well he did it anyway. 16 So guess who ended up with the dog eventually? 10, 12, 15 That’s kind of my amends many years later when he couldn’t take care of the dog. 6, 7, 10, 12, 16, 17, 20 That’s one of the first chapters in the book. 9 It was about how you learn that the hard and fast rules don’t make any sense. 9, 11, 12, 16, 17 Or the black and white rules don’t make any sense. 12, 16, 17 I had a chance to have Aaron come back home when he was fourteen or fifteen if I would have let him bring his dog home. 10, 13, 19 I told him he couldn’t because of the dog. 10, 20 AS: Oh he was fourteen or fifteen?  Oh wow. 14 GE: That’s what you’re supposed to do, the hard and fast line. 6, 9, 11 AS: Right.  Be tough, be in charge. 17, 18 GE: In charge of what? 17 AS: Right.  Well that’s what you’re told or we’re told. 20 GE: Many years later he called me from Portland, Oregon and the dog had fleas. 7, 8, 10, 20 I think he was into heroin addiction then, I didn’t know it. 13, 14, 15 He said, “Mom I can’t get rid of the fleas.”  We have become, there are many times when he would come over to the house and bring the dog. 6, 9, 10, 13, 18, 19 We all got attached to the dog, it was a Rottweiler. 10 A beautiful Rottweiler that he had trained magnificently. 6 He fed her, took her to a holistic vet. 9 He wouldn’t feed himself or take care of himself but he took care of the dog. 6, 7, 10 He called me and said. 7 You know it isn’t cold enough for fleas to die in Portland. 8, 13, 14, 15, 20 He said, “I can’t get rid of the fleas.  Maeve is really sick, she’s lost weight. 9, 18 If I pay money to send her home and give you money for the vet can I send her home to you? 6, 12, 16, 19 Will you take care of her and get her back on her feet? 6, 7, 19 I’ll be home in the spring and I’ll take her.” 6, 19 He paid for everything, he always paid. 16, 17 He sent the crates and paid for it. 7 He gave me money for the vet.  I got the dog well but when he came home that spring he was never able to take her back on a full time basis. 6, 10, 11, 15, 19 That was kind of my amends. 12, 16, 17 AS: How old was he at that point? 20 GE: I’d have to go in the book and look.  That was hard. 11 AS: I didn’t realize your book was his story. 9, 14 GE: Yes.  The book is a lot of his story and not just my story but what I saw him going through trying to recover. 9, 12, 16, 17 AS: That’ll be useful. 9 I’ll have to buy a copy from you. 7 GE: I think it would be very useful. 9 Early twenties.  Let’s see.  He was twenty five when he went to Wilmer and that happened after he came back here. 12, 13, 19 I can’t remember.  I’ll have to look in the book.  AS: That’s alright. 14 GE: That felt like the next best thing to do, to take that dog back. 6, 9, 10, 17, 19 AS: Was this the same dog? 10 GE: The same dog, yes. 10, 14 There was a part of me that it was like if I had her I knew he’d stay in touch with me. 6, 9, 12, 15 All this went on with him before there were cell phones. 7 So Aaron would be gone for weeks at a time.  One time months at a time and I wouldn’t hear from him. 8 I wouldn’t know if he was alive or dead. 13, 14, 15 There’d be many times, weeks when I wouldn’t hear from him. 18 He did carry a pager because he dealt drugs to support his habit. 7, 13, 14, 20 Not like the drugs that are available now. 10, 14 Oh my God.  I think he did cook meth for a short period of time. 5, 16 Mostly it was mushrooms and pot and I suppose he was dealing heroin too. 7, 9, 13 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 There’s a part of me that knew if I had the dog he’d stay in touch with me. 6, 9, 10, 12, 15 So I had kind of an ulterior motive. 16, 17 It felt kind of like I had a part of him with me when I had the dog. 10, 16, 17 It all sounds kind of stupid. 9, 10, 16, 17 AS: No it makes perfect sense. 16, 17 GE: Maeve was just such a wonderful dog. 9, 10, 12 We all loved her. 13 I ended up with his cat too. 10, 12 The cat, the dog. 10 The cat died, I had to put the cat down a couple of days after Aaron died. 10, 19 I came home after doing funeral pre-preps and the cat was laying here on the couch, a different couch, in her own urine. 10, 16, 17, 19 Just laying there. 9 I thought I’m getting ready to bury my son; I’m going to have a houseful. 6, 9, 11, 12 The only room where I could contain this cat was the utility room next to the downstairs bedroom, where my youngest brother was going to stay. 5, 7, 9, 10, 14 The cat would be going “Meow, meow, meow, meow.” 10 So I packed her up, took her to the vet.  She was seventeen years old. 20 She’d been missing the litterbox and those kinds of things anyways. 16, 17 I said, “I’ve got to put this cat down.” 10 They said, “It sounds like she could have kidney problems.” 10, 16 I said, “Listen. 9, 15 This cat is seventeen years old. 10, 20 She’s been missing, pooping outside the litterbox. 16 Sometimes she has poop dragging behind her because she doesn’t know.” 5, 13, 14, 15, 18 I said, “My son just died. 9, 12 I want to put this cat down. 10, 13 I can’t deal with a sick cat right now.” 10, 13, 14 “Well, this is not the time to make a decision.” 16 “Well are you going to put my cat down or am I going to have to go someplace else?” 10, 11 It was horrible. 17 She finally euthanized the cat. 10 I never regretted it. 15 The cat was ready to go. 10 It was laying in its own urine. 19 Right?  When you just said my son just died and I can’t deal with this. 9, 12, 13 GE: Well then she said, “Well this isn’t the time.”  Well really it makes logical sense. 16, 17 AS: It makes sense in a textbook kind of way. 16, 17 GE: I said, “I’m going to have a houseful of company. 6, 9 I’m going to put the cat down anyways. 10, 16, 17 I’m going to tell you that.  Why do I want to listen to a cat whine for five days? 9, 10, 13, 15, 17, 19 And worry about it.” 11 Yet, I digress.  AS: Let’s backup. 19 So Aaron.  When does he finally move out?  Tell me more about his teenage years. 20 Does he never live at home after age fourteen? 15, 19 GE: When Bob and I got married.  AS: Does he finish high school? 8 GE: He got a GED finally at a Bethlehem Alternative School.  Great experience for him.  He met a girl, a very bright woman who was six years older than he was. 5, 14, 20 They fell desperately in love. 13, 15 She wanted to go to acupuncture school and I think she already had one college degree. 8, 12, 13, 20 I can’t remember.  She wanted to go to New Mexico. 12, 13 Aaron was going too, they were going to move to New Mexico.  I finally had some pictures taken of Aaron when he was eighteen, I didn’t have any high school graduation pictures. 6, 8 When he went to New Mexico with her we had this kind of ceremony, a family ceremony where we all said goodbye to him. 16, 17, 18 I bought one of these big round candles that had five wicks and then a wick in the middle. 7, 8 We each said something.  He cried through the whole thing.  We all said something we loved about him and we were going to miss him, that he’d always take the candle so he’d know he’d always be part of us. 6, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 We each had a candle that we saved then.  I was afraid I was going to be really emotional. 13 It was really fun because it was nice to see him be emotional instead of me. 9, 13 I often wondered if he got emotional because I didn’t. 12, 13, 15 He did do some Junior College.  His father bought him another car. 5, 7 He totaled one car, never got a driver’s license until he was twenty. 7, 14, 15 His father bought him a little pickup truck. 5, 7 Which of course was great because he could do drug running with it. 7, 11, 14 But he was under our insurance until he totaled it. 7 Then my insurance was cancelled because he was under twenty five. 7 I said, “If you ever buy him another car, you’re going to have to figure out the insurance. 7, 13 I’m done.  I’m done giving him money. 11 I’m done giving him anything. 11 I think you’re enabling him.  You gave him a car. 7 At least don’t give him another car.” 6, 7, 9 That’s how Aaron got to New Mexico.  He took some Junior College classes down there. 8, 20 I’d hear from his girlfriend, “Aaron just won’t get a job.” 9, 12 Well he was smoking a lot of pot. 17 It’s kind of hard to work and smoke pot daily right? 11, 14, 16, 17 Then she wanted to finish acupuncture school in Portland. 8, 12, 13 That’s when I think he got into the heroin.  AS: Around what year is this? 8, 20 The early 2000s?  AS: Oh okay.  GE: I got married in ‘91.  So this all happened early 90s. 12, 13 Twenty years ago. 20 Twenty five years ago. 20 It was one of those times when we were in Portland when he sent the dog home, after they got up there. 7, 8, 10, 18, 19 She’d call and complain, “Aaron won’t get a job.” 7 She knew he was using heroin. 6, 12 She never told me. 15, 20 Here’s the power of Aaron and relationships. 15 They ended up, long story short; they ended up hating each other’s guts, he and this first woman. 9, 12, 16 When Aaron died she took planes, trains, and automobiles to get back for his service. 13, 19 The woman that found Sophie was his last girlfriend. 9, 12 He had three really long term relationships.  They loved him desperately. 13 Of course they were all co-dependent relationships. 12 There was something about him that you just couldn’t resist. 9, 12 The picture of him is very handsome, charming, witty.  He was very caring. 7 He could be very emotionally present for women. 7, 13, 18 Which is always a big draw right? 8, 14, 16, 17 AS: What year was Aaron born? 20 He would be forty three this October.  Finally, he came back and he and Marla broke up. 19 Or did he come back with her? 13, 19 Oh I shouldn’t have said her name. 6 AS: It’s okay.  We can take it out. 6 GE: I can’t remember.  How can I forget this?  He finally said he was coming back. 19 She was staying out there and finishing. 9, 19 I guess he wanted to come back or something. 10, 12, 13, 19 Or they broke up.  I can’t remember.  He came back. 19 He said, “I found somebody.  I’ve got a roommate but they won’t let me have the dog.” 7, 10, 19 It was all very mysterious. 9 Finally one day he showed up with another woman that he said was his roommate. 7, 19 I think they were just friends for a while. 9, 12, 18 He just looked like hell. 9, 12 He’d always come to visit me. 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 So he’s back in Minneapolis but I didn’t see very much of him. 18, 19 He’d always come to visit me during the day. 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 The kids were at school. 8 You know, I was still doing this business out of my home. 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 He just looked like hell. 9, 12 Finally this kind of went on I think for about six months, for a while. 8, 16, 17 He’d come to see the dog and talk with me and then he’d vanish for days. 10, 13, 19 I get this call. 7 We’re doing this big seminar for my business and Bob’s father had just died. 5, 8, 9, 12, 15 I get this call from him. 7 He says, “Mom I’m really sick and I’ve got to get to the clinic.  Can you give me a ride? 6 I’m up in Northeast.” 9 I just, it’s seven thirty in the morning, and I’ve just gotten out of the shower. 9, 12, 15 I’m putting on this big thing; Bob’s brothers are in town because his father just died. 5, 8, 9, 10, 12, 19 I’m saying, “Honey if you’re really sick but I just got out of the shower.” 9, 11, 12 “The clinic closes at nine o’clock.  I’ve got to get to the clinic to get my medicine before.”  I don’t know nothing about Methadone. 13, 14, 15 I don’t even know he’s a heroin addict. 13, 14, 15 AS: At this point.  GE: So this is before GPS or anything.  I say, “Give me the address.” 14 I put it into MapQuest, I print my directions. 9, 10 “You be standing out there on the corner, out in front of the house so I can get you.” 6, 9, 12 It’s up in Northeast. 9 I get in the car, I go pick him up and he gets in the car. 7 He looks like somebody who’s had the flu.  He’s in withdrawal right. 14 He’s got on somebody else’s holey sweater.  I said, “When is the last time you bathed?” 9 He said, “Mom just don’t talk to me. 9, 10, 12 Can you just get me there?” 9, 12 I said, “Where’s the clinic?”  He says, “Burnsville.”  I said, “What are you doing going to a health clinic in Burnsville?” 14 “Just get me to the clinic.” 9 So your kids sick, you haven’t seen him for days. 19 The last time you saw him he looks like death warmed over. 9 Now he looks like three deaths warmed over. 10 So are you going to take him to where he wants to go? 6, 11, 13 Sure.  I get him out there and there’s this non-descript clinic.  There’s no name on it or nothing. 6 He said, “I need five dollars for the co-pay. 13, 16 Can I borrow five bucks from you?”  I said, “Sure.  Don’t worry about paying me back.” 11, 16, 19 So I get out of the car he says, “No, no, no. 7 You don’t need to come in.” 13, 19 So he goes in, he comes back. 13, 19 He gets in the car and about twenty minutes later and it’s like he’s in a stupor. 7, 9 He gets in the car and kind of slumps down in the edge of the corner and I said, “What is going on?” 7, 16, 17 He said, “Just drive. 7, 9, 14 Can I come home and cleanup? 13, 19 Can I just come back to the house and just cleanup? 6, 9, 12, 13, 19 Just drive.” 7, 9, 14 So I start driving down Cliff Road from this. 9, 11, 14 It’s clear he’s nodding off and on.  I’m thinking I took him somewhere to get high, right? 8, 14 I don’t know what’s going on. 13, 14, 15 I stop at this park, I pull over and I said, “Tell me what the hell is going on. 9, 10 You’re high!” 8 He said, “I went to a Methadone clinic.”  I said, “Meth-o-what?”  He said, “Methadone.  It’s something they give people when they’re trying to get off of heroin.” 6, 16 That was the first time I knew he was a heroin addict. 6, 9, 12 I just went nuts. 9, 12 AS: Do you remember what year this is? 20 GE: It’s in my book.  AS: Is it long before he dies?  GE: Oh yes, yes. 14 Long time before he dies.  This is ten years before he dies. 20 AS: Oh okay.  That helps. 13 GE: I just start pommeling him with questions. 6, 9, 11, 12 He said, “I’ll tell you everything.  I know I’ve got to get off of heroin. 13, 14, 15 I’ve been trying. 16 I’m hoping this is going to help. 13 Can we talk later?” 10 It was always can we talk later. 10, 16, 17 I drove home. 7, 14, 19 He said, “Can I just go to bed? 9, 12 I haven’t slept for days.” 19 I tucked him into his bed upstairs and just held him, hoping. 9, 12 You know how you hold your kid and you think it’s going to make it all better? 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 That was the beginning of my journey with heroin and opiates and watching him go through treatment time and time again. 9, 16 And try to make Methadone work and abuse Methadone and sell Methadone and not be on Methadone and use pot when he was on Methadone. 7, 9, 16 Until his last gallant effort with Dr. French. 9 Tell me that.  GE: He went to Wilmer and went through treatment. 9, 16 Back then it was all, complete abstinence when you were in treatment. 9, 16, 19 When he went to Wilmer, he was court ordered to Wilmer. 12 He went into a pizza place high and they found opiates on him. 8, 11 AS: There were like cops in there or something? 10 GE: Yes.  He was probably visibly high and the cops happened to drive by and they caught him. 7, 8, 12, 13, 14 There were a lot of times he would be thrown in jail. 17, 18 He wouldn’t have any on him but because he was publicly intoxicated. 10 He’d call us for bail and I would bail him out. 7 One time afterwards, he told me this years afterwards, he was thrown in jail for public intoxication and he was on opiates so he was in withdrawal by that time. 10, 14, 20 He had, at times he had large amounts of cash because he was dealing. 13, 18 He hired this feisty lawyer to bail him out. 7, 9, 12 He had no car and his girlfriend didn’t have a car. 7, 12 It took him five hours to crawl home because he was in withdrawal. 11, 14, 19 AS: Oh my Gosh.  GE: Because I wouldn’t come pick him up. 13, 19 AS: Had you picked him up before?  What was your process like as a mother with this?  GE: I never when he was jailed. 15 I was all wrapped up in it being about…it was not declared a brain illness until 2011. 12, 14 Aaron died in 2007.  All of my training as a psychotherapist was this is a behavior or a personality disorder. 6, 9, 16 Although the American Medical Association declared it an illness in 1956 so you could get reimbursed for it as a disease. 12, 14 Treatment centers still treated it as a behavior disorder or personality disorder. 9, 16 They didn’t treat it as a brain illness. 14, 16 AS: It was a personality flaw. 16 GE: It was all cognitive behavior therapy.  We’ve got to learn to change your behavior, there’s something wrong with your behavior. 12, 16 You’re broken. 5 AS: So would you say that when he’s called to get out of jail you’ve already been dealing with him since he was thirteen, fourteen. 7, 13, 20 You’re still in your kind of tough love thing? 9, 13, 16, 17, 18 GE: He broke the law I figured he needed to… 12, 13 AS: Right.  Live with the consequences of what he was doing.  Right.  He was using illegal drugs. 14 GE: Right.  So I went to Wilmer.  AS: What is Wilmer?  GE: Wilmer Regional Treatment Center.  He was court ordered there. 12 He spent a month there and then he went to Prodigal House which had a pretty good reputation for repeat opiate offenders of being the right place to be. 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 18, 19 Unfortunately, Aaron teamed up with four guys in treatment and they all went to Prodigal House together. 9, 16 They were the band of brothers. 5, 15 He got out of Prodigal House and got a job driving cab but started using. 9, 11, 14 As long as he was working I said he could live at home. 19 So he did come back home. 13, 19 He lived in our basement.  I had other kids at home but he was driving cab. 14, 19 Well then I found vodka in there, I found vodka in his room. 7 He smashed up cars and couldn’t drive cab anymore because he was using. 7, 13, 14 Where are we in the story? 9 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 Then he hooked up with this last girlfriend, the one that found Sophie. 9, 12 She supported him for a long, long time. 16 So he didn’t live at home. 19 She would constantly call me, “Aaron this, Aaron that.” 7, 9 AS: How many years were they together? 20 GE: A long time.  I’d have to call her and ask her. 7 AS: That’s okay.  Ten years? 20 GE: Maybe not that long.  She finally broke up with him before he made this last gallant effort. 9, 16 She couldn’t take it anymore. 6, 13 They were maybe together five or six years. 9, 20 She was not around the last three years of his life. 9, 11, 20 He wrote her letters to let her know that he was really trying. 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 Not to try to get her back but, “I just want to let you know… 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 Mom’s even let me drive the car. 7, 14, 15, 19 I’m starting to get my parents trust back.” 9, 10, 11, 16, 19 When he died she just hated it that she never got in touch with him. 9, 12, 15 It’s her biggest regret. 8, 9, 11 She still loved him. 9, 13 She was in another relationship but nobody ever loved her the way that Aaron did. 13, 16 When I finally grasped…after he died, I didn’t really grasp this whole idea of addiction as a brain illness until after he died. 11, 14 AS: Yes, that’s what I’m thinking.  GE: It was through my continued training through MRC as a recovery coach and all my continued investigation. 9, 18 There were just so many things about Aaron that didn’t add up. 9, 12, 16 There wasn’t anything that kid couldn’t do when he set his mind to it. 17 When he wanted to recover and couldn’t. 12, 13 I’d see him try treatment after treatment after treatment after treatment and be so self-deprecating and not get it. 9, 10, 16 Why can’t you get this?  Then when I started reading it’s a brain illness characterized by compulsive drug seeking despite harmful consequences. 9, 10, 11, 14 I thought that’s what’s wrong with him, it’s his brain. 11, 12 It’s not Aaron.  It’s not his personality, it’s not his character. 10, 16 I’m telling you there was not a more loyal.  Yet he’d lie to me, he was deceptive in his illness and all that. 14 I’m talking about loyal to the core to his family, to his siblings, to me. 5, 10, 18 He had an incredible relationship with his stepdaughter. 5, 9, 12 He just idolized Bob. 9, 12 He finally saw what a marriage was supposed to be. 6 He saw somebody that loved his mother the way that he wanted his mother to be loved and respected. 12, 13, 16 That’s what really made me really want to write the book and tell other parents. 10, 13, 16 There was somewhere along the line before he died. 6 Like about five years before when I got the lightbulb that I’m not going to fix this. 16, 20 AS: Five years before. 20 GE: About five years before. 20 AS: What was that moment? 13, 15 GE: I don’t remember what did that.  [Long Pause]. 9 It was this realization that I wanted a relationship with him no matter what, whether he was sober, whether he was using. 6, 12, 13, 20 I couldn’t stand it when we were at odds. 9, 12 How could I take care of myself in the relationship and still maintain a relationship with him? 6, 7, 9 But make the boundaries about what I needed in the relationship not about trying to control his use. 9, 13, 16, 17 That wasn’t going to work.  When Bob and I made that whole switch about, no you can’t be in the house when you’re using we’ll still see you, we want to stay in touch with you, blah blah blah. 6, 9, 13, 15, 16 When you’re in recovery and you come to any family event but you come high I’m going to take you home. 6, 8, 13, 15, 18, 19 All these things. 16 What I needed to feel safe. 13, 16 You can’t stay in the house when you’re using because I don’t know who’s going to show up at the door. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15 I don’t sleep when you’re using in the house. 6, 7, 9 It’s not a good thing for me.  It’s not about trying to control you, this isn’t good for me. 16, 17 AS: How did you come to that? 13, 19 Did you go to any meetings? 13 GE: No, it was like Einstein’s Theory of Relativity. 9 It was like God finding.  My higher power finally sent me a message: you are not going to change him. 7, 8, 15, 16 What do you want to do if he dies, how do you want to remember your relationship with him? 13 It really Amy, it was like… 10 I write about this in the book.  It was the reading. 11 It was the July 5th reading in the Al-Anon Blue Book. 11 AS: The Nar-Anon Blue Book?  GE: No the Al-Anon Book.  I never went to Nar-Anon meetings. 13, 15 AS: Oh okay.  There probably wasn’t one.  GE: One day at a time. 19 Oh yes, there was Nar-Anon. 14 GE: It said, here it is this was the turning point for me. 19 I’d read this a million times right. 14, 18 “The non-alcoholic in the family doesn’t seem to realize that the alcoholic is in a terribly vulnerable position, he must be constantly be on guard because he knows, deep down inside how much trouble he’s bringing to the family. 5, 9, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 He knows he’s wide open to criticism but did it ever occur to you that your tantrums and harsh words are like whipping a sick dog. 10, 13, 14, 15, 17 Remember he’s lashing himself all the time.  If you apply more lashes you’re inviting him to transfer some of his guilt to you. 7 This can keep him from reaching his bottom and realizing how much he needs help to find sobriety. 12, 13, 18 Today’s reminder: 19 I will try to understand how desperately the alcoholic suffers from guilt. 5, 9, 12, 16 I will not yield to impulse to kick him when he’s down.  We both suffer in different ways from the alcoholism. 12, 16, 17 I who have God’s gift of sobriety must be the one to realize his dissatisfaction with himself no matter how defiant and defensive he may appear. 8, 10, 14, 20 If I were unfortunate enough to be an alcoholic how would I hope to be treated by the person I live with? 5, 10, 16, 20 The golden rule is a useful tool in all our personal relationships.” 9, 12, 16, 20 I realized I would treat a street person better than I was treating my own son. 9, 14, 16 I just said, “I don’t know what’s going to happen here but I’m going to start having a little compassion for the fact that he is sick.” 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 The whole illness concept hadn’t even come into being yet. 13, 14, 15, 19 But you saw it as a mom? 15 GE: I was picking it up on some kind of collective unconscious self. 16, 17 AS: Well you’re also just watching it. 9, 12 GE: Yes over and over.  Right.  AS: You saw him trying and failing and trying. 16 GE: He never tried and failed at anything else in his life. 10, 11, 15 He was a very resourceful drug dealer. 13, 14 He honestly never carried a gun Amy. 7, 9, 15, 16 I want you to know that my son was an honest drug dealer. 9, 13, 14, 15 AS: That’s great. 11 [Laughs].  GE: You’ll have to read the book.  AS: Oh I’m going to, tonight. 19 GE: Bob and I just started changing. 9, 11, 12, 16, 18 We started being compassionate and it was all about where we were and what we needed, when we can help support your recovery. 9, 11, 13 Aaron would call and ask me for help and the question was: is this going to support his recovery or is it going to enable his using? 6, 7, 9, 13 Those were my questions. 6, 9 That’s all in the book.  “Oh God Mom I missed a doctor’s appointment.  It’s too late to catch the bus; can you give me a ride?” 6, 9, 10 Well, doctor’s appointment, I’ve got to get him to the doctor.  “Well what’s this appointment for?”  Was it going to interfere with my work schedule and destruct the rest of the family? 9, 18, 19 I had to decide was helping him going to be as good for all of us as it was for him? 13 Now if it was a matter of life and death with him that’s a different matter. 11, 16, 17, 20 I also started basing every circumstance on what was going on now not all the shit that went before. 9, 11, 14 That’s where a lot of parents, well I’m not going to trust him now because… 9, 10, 14, 16, 17 GE: You know what? 13, 14, 15 If he was going to make me untrustworthy I would know and then I couldn’t trust him again. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16 Nobody was going to lose a life or if my property wasn’t going to be damaged. 11 You know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 You’ve got to start building trust again somewhere. 9, 11 Start it and see what happens. 12 The more we trusted him the more trustworthy he became. 5, 9, 19 AS: Even in his addiction.  GE: Even in his addiction, yes. 14 Then he started talking about, “You know Mom I’d read about these ultra-rapid detox.” 9, 10, 11, 13, 14, 15 That sounded a horrible, horrible, horrible experience. 10, 17 Except for the fact that I didn’t go with him, his father, his birth father stepped up and went with him and paid for it. 5, 9, 10, 12 It was the only time Ed was ever completely responsibly for Aaron’s emotional and physical well-being. 13, 14, 19 He told me it was the best time he’d ever had with Aaron, it was the best $10,000 he ever spent in his life. 9, 11, 19, 20 They finally connected emotionally before Aaron died. 13, 18 I said to Aaron, I said, “If you want to do this you can come over to the house, you can use the computer to look at websites, use the phone to make long-distance phone calls. 6, 7, 9, 10, 13, 16, 19 I watched him withdraw from heroin, opiates so many times. 14, 17, 18 I heard the vomiting and the constant dry heaving. 9, 14, 15 I was in Post-Traumatic Stress watching him withdraw from heroin so many times, and opiates, trying to go down on his Methadone. 9, 14, 16, 18 I said, “I can’t do it Aaron.  So then Jeff thinks that he’s going to go.  You’ve got to drive to Chicago, you spend a night in the hospital, and they do a physical. 7, 12, 14, 19 This was a reputable place. 10, 11 Then the procedure is this, the Naloxone I think it’s now Naloxone, but it’s an opiate antagonist that is intravenously run through your body while you’re sedated, intubated. 9, 11, 14 AS: Oh I’ve heard of this. 15 GE: It’s supposed to make the withdrawal shorter. 6, 14, 16 Then you get in the hospital the day afterwards and supposedly stabilize and then you get in the car and then you drive home from Chicago. 6, 7, 9, 14, 19 So Jeff thinks,  Aaron’s brother, thinks he’ll do it. 5 I said, “So when Aaron is vomiting and having diarrhea all the way home from Chicago what are you going to do?” 16, 19 “Well I’ll pull off at a rest stop.” 9, 10, 19 “How long are you going to be able to stay there? 9 How many days you going to take off work?” 6, 19 I said, “Jeffery he’s going to be violently ill.”  “Well this is supposed to not…” 6 “Trust me.” 9 So finally Ed stepped up to the plate and said, he was retired, and said, “I’ll take him.” 6, 9, 12, 19 I just had to ask Jeff all kinds of… 9, 12, 16, 17 I said this is really valiant of you to do this but I don’t think you have any idea. 8, 11 You’ve never seen anybody in opiate withdrawal. 14, 15 You have no idea what you’re getting yourself into. 11 AS: So what was going on with Jeff this whole time?  GE: That’s a whole chapter in the book.  AS: That’s another story. 9 [Laughs].  GE: Jeff and I finally have made amends. 12, 16 It took a long time, and he still doesn’t trust me when I say I’m going to show up for him. 9 It’s just that the sibling fallout. 9, 12 You’ve got to understand Aaron abandoned Jeff. 9, 12, 15, 16 AS: Oh yes, at the divorce. 14 GE: So there was such a love-hate relationship and all the addiction. 13 Jeff had his own issues. 14, 15 Aaron was never there for him. 15 It just took a long, long time for us to heal. 9, 12 I just kept saying to him because of that last five years with Aaron and the positive experience I had, instead of trying to fix him I just kept saying, “Jeff I know that you’re not yourself.” 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 He was just angry after Aaron died. 9, 12 You couldn’t even talk to him. 10, 15 Oh my God just angry, angry. 9, 12 I don’t know if you’re using drugs. 13, 14, 15 I don’t know what it is. 13, 14, 15 I love you, I care about you. 7, 13 I can’t help you. 13 You need help. 13 When you’re ready to get help I’ll support you. 13 I’m not going anywhere in between.  I can’t help you with this issue. 13, 15 When you are screaming and yelling you’re going to have to leave the house or I’m going to call the police. 6, 7, 9 I’m not going to take that kind of behavior in my home.” 6, 16, 17, 19 AS: Was he screaming and yelling at you?  GE: Oh yes, everything. 14 He just totally… 9, 12, 17 Jeff was the most easy-going, lovable, teddy-bear.  Everybody loved Jeff. 13 Man it totally changed. 16, 17 AS: What were the circumstances of Aaron’s death? 9 GE: Well he got back from that ultra-rapid detox process and my former husband was supposed to leave him at his apartment. 6, 10, 15, 17, 19, 20 He was still violently ill but he had medical marijuana stashed. 9, 14 He thought he was going to smoke his way out of the after effects of the thing. 11, 12, 16 Ed left him off at about seven o’clock and Aaron called me at nine thirty or ten and said, “Mom I can’t stop vomiting. 7, 9, 10 I’m really worried.  I don’t think I should be alone.  I think I need to go to the hospital.” 13 I picked him up and took him to Fairview South and so there I am watching him in opiate withdrawal anyway. 14, 16 I got him admitted to the hospital and he proceeded, and this is all in the book, he proceeded to continue to vomit for ten days. 19 Even rectal suppositories, he was on the IVs, he had this terrible taste in his mouth from the Naloxone or whatever that antagonist was they did intravenously. 9, 13, 15 He couldn’t keep anything down. 12 He was continually swishing his mouth with sodas.  The hospital complained so I had to bring in soda.  AS: Oh because he was drinking too much of their soda. 6, 14, 18 GE: Yes, right. 14 Get this.  He called an AA and asked for a sponsor, asked for somebody to come to the hospital to talk to him. 7, 10, 13, 19 They said, “Do you have a sponsor.”  He said, “No.”  “Well we can’t help you unless you have a sponsor.” 13 He reached out. 13 He was so sick and I had a lot of friends in the program. 12, 17, 18 I don’t know why I didn’t think about just calling. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 It’s like well they said that no one can talk to him unless he has a sponsor, must be true. 10 Finally the doctor up at Fairview, at the hospital, said, “I’m going to put him…” 10 You know he was just aghast that we ever did this ultra-rapid detox thing. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 He said, “The only way we’re going to get any homeostasis is to put him back on a small amount of Methadone.” 9, 10, 16, 18, 19 Ed was supposed to fly back home. 6, 19 When Aaron was so ill and I put him back in the hospital I called him and said, “I don’t think you should go home.” 7, 10, 19 So Ed and I and Bob took turns being up in the hospital with him.  Finally the doctor had a meeting with all three of us and said, “I’m going to put him back on Methadone.” 10, 13, 19 We just like jumped out of the chair because in order to get him to detox they had to switch him from Methadone to Dilaudid. 9, 10, 12 The ultra-rapid detox center said, “Well we can’t detox him directly off of Methadone. 9, 10 He’ll have to be on Dilaudid for ten days.” 19 Aaron knew it would work. 6, 12 He was wondering if it would work.  He’d used Dilaudid on the street enough. 9, 20 So it kept him stable, kept him in withdrawal enough. 9, 14, 18, 20 He just wanted to be off of Methadone. 9, 12, 13 He just couldn’t stand going to the clinic. 9, 12 He was becoming very black and white, again no education. 10 “You know what Aaron? 13, 14, 15 It would be ok to be on a small amount of Methadone for the rest of your life.” 9, 11, 18, 19 AS: Right, nobody said that?  GE: He knew some guys that were but I had my own stigma about it Amy. 6, 9, 12 The only thing I got was this pamphlet and I write about this in the book, called “About Methadone.” 7, 19 It explained.  He said, “Mom I want you to read this.” 13 He was trying his best to get me. 9, 16 All I saw was how he abused Methadone not how useful it was. 9 I’d see him kind of get stable and then they’d take him down. 6, 9, 16, 17, 18 Then he’d start using pot or heroin along with it. 9, 11 AS: He needed to stay stable. 9, 13, 18 GE: For a long, long, long time.  Right?  He could never get his life in order. 11, 15 He was always either in withdrawal or using on the street. 9, 14, 16, 17 You know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 There was never a period of stability on Methadone. 9, 15 AS: That was allowed to happen. 12 GE: There were a few times but every time he’d get there, he’d want to start tapering again. 9, 11, 13, 18 He’d say, “I can’t be on this anymore.” 13 AS: There’s jitteriness and an anxiety.  All the stigma and lack of education about medication, treatment is. 9, 10, 16 Now I know that Aaron’s disease had progressed to the point where he could not recover. 13, 14, 15 It wasn’t available to him in the way that it should have been. 16 I kept trying to make it about he was dishonest, I write about this all in the book. 9, 16 I stigmatized him for even years after he died. 9, 15, 20 Big book says he can recover if you keep him being honest. 9, 12 Aaron was always a little liar as a kid. 16, 17 AS: Wow, Gloria that’s tough. 18 GE: I’ve got a whole chapter in there.  I mean when somebody dies there’s got to be a reason. 16 he just couldn’t work a recovery program. 9, 12 He just wasn’t honest enough to work a recovery program. 9, 12, 20 When in fact his disease had progressed to the point where he couldn’t recover with what was being offered him. 10, 12 It was somebody; I went to speak at St. Joe’s, which was the last treatment center he was in. 9, 16 Anyways, I digress. 16, 17 So he goes to ultra-rapid detox. 10 They put him back, finally we agreed, puts him on five milligrams or twenty milligrams of Methadone and “Bam” he is well. 10, 19 He hasn’t eaten or kept anything down for two weeks. 15 The guy says, “I got a bed for you at Fairview Riverside, now. 14 Do you want to go?” 13 Aaron said, “How can I possibly go through treatment? 9, 16 I haven’t eaten for days.” 15, 19 He wasn’t hardly stable. 9, 11, 18 He said, “Hey Mom could I just come home and just get some good nutrition in my body and get stable? 9, 12, 13, 18, 19 I truly believed this was the truth.  I said, “Fine you’ve got two weeks.”  Then I knew he would be put on the proverbial waiting list. 6, 9, 10, 12 He didn’t take the bed then. 6 He came home and I kind of nursed him back. 16, 17, 19 The longer he was on Methadone the craving, you know he went to recovery meetings to begin with and then the cravings would increase. 13, 14, 15 He didn’t get into treatment in two weeks. 9, 16 I said, “You’ve got to go back to your apartment.” 19, 20 I’d given him the two weeks. 6 He went back to his apartment. 19, 20 He finally got into Fairview Riverside.  They started taking him off the Methadone and the step down was too fast. 9, 11, 12 He got sick all over again.  Riverside was abstinence based no Naloxone. 9 So he couldn’t go from Methadone to Naloxone.  That’s usually what they do now. 10, 14 If you’re trying to get off Methadone you get on to fifty milligrams of Methadone and then you go on Naloxone. 16 They tried to step him down too quick and he got sick and couldn’t finish treatment. 9, 10, 12, 16 So he went back to his apartment and started doing research. 9, 11, 19, 20 He found David French at St. Joe’s.  He was one of the first doctors to use Clonidine. 9 Which helps with, it’s a blood pressure medication that helps with. 10, 11, 13, 15 My daughter used that. 5, 9 He read about French and didn’t really like the program at St. Joe’s because he’d been through one before but he liked French. 10, 18 His insurance was so short. 7, 16 You left treatment there’s no way you’re going to get back in treatment again. 9, 16, 19 AS: Even though he was sick?  GE: If I go score some heroin, shoot up, go into the emergency room, and say I’m suicidal and that I’m drug addict they’ll have to admit me. 7, 14 So he got back into treatment at a hospital. 9, 16, 19 It’s in the book.  That’s how desperate he was.  So he gets into St. Joe’s.  AS: He totally understood the system by this point. 8, 9, 17 GE: Oh yes. 14 He gets into St. Joe’s.  He loves Dr. French. 13 He is only supposed to get three weeks of treatment. 6, 9, 16 He gets a social worker to petition.  He gets another week of treatment but he is told, “You will not get any more money. 9, 16, 20 You won’t be able to go to treatment for another two years if this doesn’t work.” 9, 16, 20 This has got to work.  He tells them when he goes in, “I do not want to be on any medication at all. 10, 13 When I leave here, Mom I can’t be a controlled addict. 6, 17 I want to be off of all medications. 10, 13 I don’t want to be on any anti-anxiety medications. 10, 13 I don’t want to be on any antidepressants. 13 I want to be off of everything when I leave here. 6, 13 I said, “Aaron let’s just deal with the Methadone. 9, 12, 13, 19 Let’s just go through treatment.” 9, 12, 16 He’s an adult, right? 14 So they do what he wants. 11, 13 By the end of the third week he is going nuts. 12, 20 He can’t sleep. 7 So all these emotions that have been suppressed for all these years by the anti-anxiety medications and the heroin and the pot are coming to the surface. 10, 20 We’ve got the angry addict back again. 19 He said, “If I don’t get out of this place I’m going to kill myself or somebody else.” 7, 11 I said, “Aaron this is the time you need to stay. 9, 13 I really implore you do not go off all your medications. 10 Just worry about the Methadone.” 9, 11 We used the term opiates then. 9 “Let’s just worry about treatment of opiates.” 9, 11, 12, 16 “I’ve got to get out of here.  I’m going to see how soon I can get out.”  I called the nurse and said, “He is threatening himself or other people. 7, 15 He threatened that he was going to kill himself or other people. 7, 15 You cannot let him out.” 19 “Well he hasn’t said that to us.”  Right?  See he knows. 13, 14, 15 He’s agreed to an out-patient day program. 19 “Since he’s been in treatment so long, so many days we feel that.” 9, 16, 19 I said, “He needs to be up on the psych ward. 13 Put him on a seventy two hour hold.” 20 “We have no basis to do that.  You can commit him.  I’ll give you the paperwork. 6 You can commit him to the psych ward for five days.” 19 AS: As his mom. 15 GE: The one thing that Aaron has always said to me, he signed release after release. 16, 17 I was always privy to any information. 16, 17 He said with one caveat, “Never ever commit me.  I don’t know if I could ever forgive you.” 6, 13, 14, 15 My codependency bought into that. 7, 12 I saw him committed by another doctor one other time.  I saw him on a seventy two hour hold in the psych ward. 20 He talked his way to the social worker, the psychiatrist, and the psychologist. 9, 10, 11, 16 I knew that if Aaron didn’t want the help he wasn’t going to get it. 6, 12, 13 Was it worth damaging my relationship, our relationship?  In the end, when he went through this last effort I promised him I would support him in whatever he wanted to do treatment his way. 9, 12, 13, 16 I was going to let him do it. 19 I was the support person not the mastermind. 9, 20 I had always been the mastermind. 9, 16, 17, 20 It was the one regret I have, that I didn’t commit him.  Maybe something could have been different for him. 16, 17 AS: So he gets out?  GE: He gets out.  I pick him up on Tuesday and I take him back to his apartment. 6, 19, 20 He’s really agitated.  I say, “Can I get you some groceries?”  I know he wants to go back to his apartment because he’s going to smoke pot. 11, 13, 14, 15, 19, 20 Do you need food?” 13 He said, “No, get me home.” 19 I said, “Okay.”  I had a meeting at the Woman’s Club the next day which is right down the street. 9, 13, 14, 19 His father