going over minutes. 7 I understand my phone’s going to be turned off.” 7, 9, 12, 16, 19 Never did he ever abuse it. 9 People say, “You’re giving a drug addict a phone?” 7, 11, 14 I said, “He’s going to make drug deals anyways. 13, 14, 16, 17 I have access to him this way.” 6, 16 The other deal was that he call me every morning at seven thirty and let me know he was okay. 7, 13, 14, 15, 19 Every day, seldom if he was late, and he always ended it with, “Goodbye Mom. 12, 16, 17, 19 I love you.” 13 He called me Thursday morning to check in after this great experience on Wednesday. 7, 11, 19 “I’m not doing well.  But I don’t want to focus on me. 13, 15 Let’s talk about Matt’s birthday party. 6, 10, 19 Should I ride the bus out to your house and go out there? 6, 9 Or should Bob pick me up?”  I said, “How about we figure that out on Friday. 13, 19 I’ve got this big thing.” 8 I was very preoccupied with this event. 15 I said, “Are you sure there isn’t anything you want to talk about?” 10, 13, 15 The day I picked him up from the hospital on Tuesday, I called to make arrangements to pick him up. 7, 16, 19 He said, “I had this dream, the strangest dream. 7, 9, 14 I dreamed I was a Tibetan monk and I was coming out of a cave. 14 I said in a language that I don’t know but I understood what I said to the guy next to me. 9, 13, 14, 15 ‘It’s been twenty years and it’s time for me to go home.’ 19, 20 Don’t you think that’s odd?”  I said, “Wow Aaron.  Maybe its twenty years it’s time for you to recover. 20 Maybe that’s what it’s all about.”  I think he had a premonition of his own death.  I said, “Let’s be in touch on Friday.” 15, 19 I kept trying to call him on Friday. 7, 16, 19 He didn’t call Matt and say he wasn’t coming to the birthday party. 6, 7, 19 His sister-in-law had had surgery. 5, 9 Very close to his aunt, very close to Bob’s sister-in-law. 5, 9 Didn’t call and check with her. 7 There were times when Aaron decided at the last minute, “I can’t do a family event.” 9, 12, 15, 18 So he just wouldn’t communicate with me. 9, 10, 12 I didn’t think that much about it. 18 We got to the birthday party. 6, 19 “Where’s Aaron?”  “Well he must have decided not to come. 12, 13, 19 Matt did you talk to him? 10 Did he call you?” 7 Another really weird thing.  On the way home Bob and I are having this silent thing. 16, 19 I just had this odd feeling, this premonition. 9, 12, 16 We were both just exhausted because we’d gone to this big business thing and I just kept trying to call Aaron. 7, 8, 9, 12, 16 No answer, no answer.  I woke up at one o’clock.  Came home, went to bed. 19 I said, “We’re going to go down there Saturday morning if I can’t get ahold of him.” 19, 20 I woke up at one o’clock in the morning and couldn’t go back to sleep. 7, 19 For some reason when we had rented the apartment I kept the super’s, the caretaker’s card. 6, 7, 12, 16, 20 I threw it in my desk somewhere. 15 I spent a couple hours finding that card. 7, 11, 19 It was in a secure building.  I started calling her at seven AM. 7, 9, 11 I finally got ahold of her. 20 She was showing apartments other places. 11, 17, 20 I said, “I’ve got to go check on my son.  I’m afraid something’s happened to him.” 12, 13 We found him at one o’clock.  It was clear that he was dead; I think he overdosed on Thursday night sometime. 5, 15, 19 That was the last time anybody had contacted him. 9, 10 Now they confiscate cell phones and all that trying to find out who they got the drugs from. 7, 10, 14, 16 Bob and I took his phone and started calling people. 7, 9, 11 We couldn’t find out.  Nobody cared that he died of a heroin overdose, in 2007. 7, 11, 12, 15 He was a junkie.  AS: I’m sorry. 10 GE: I know you are. 13, 14, 15 I know you understand. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 GE: We did have a great relationship the last five years. 9, 11, 20 He came over here. 19 He was on Methadone take-outs once a week. 6 He got his Methadone on Tuesday morning and he’d come over here and spend Monday night. 12, 13, 19 He’d take my car to the clinic. 6, 7 He was gone with the car just for exactly the right amount of time. 7, 9, 10, 12, 14, 18, 19 He was supposed to come back and then he made me breakfast on Tuesday mornings. 6, 9, 13, 16, 18, 19 That was our time together.  AS: At what point did you start on the journey that Aaron, you said that for a while you stigmatized him, you did things to try to explain it to yourself. 9, 11, 16 Then what was your turning point? 19 GE: I needed a reason for him to die so I could go on I think. 13 I needed to blame something. 13, 17 I’ve been a writer all my life. 11 I just have tons and tons of journal stuff. 9, 12 He died in May; I went to grief groups in the fall.  They were just horrendous experiences. 9, 12 There weren’t very many people that were dying of opiates back then. 19 It was just starting to come about. 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 Nobody understood, like the majority of people now, that addiction is an illness. 9, 14, 18 The underlying thing was, number one: my son was a drug addict but what did I expect? 14 Of course he’s going to die.  His life doesn’t have the value of my son who was a college athlete. 8, 11, 19 That died of something else or you know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 Almost seventy five percent of the parents I was in with, whose children died of accidental deaths were drug or alcohol related. 7, 9, 10, 14, 16 Right?  One girl stepped off a platform and went through to the tracks because she was drunk, on a platform in New York City, and got hit by the subway. 9, 11, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17 It was because she was drunk, she was high. 8, 11, 14, 15 It was because that platform was not made correctly and he sued the city of New York. 16, 17, 20 Which is probably, anybody probably could have stepped off. 9, 12 I just found myself educating them about addiction and trying to defend my son. 9, 10, 12, 16 I thought I am here for support. 11, 12 AS: This is not working.  GE: This is not working.  I went back to my Al-Anon group and got support there. 19 They understood addiction at least. 9 They could understand the double loss, the ambiguous loss. 8, 9, 12, 16 They got that.  That was just killing me. 7, 9, 12 You’ve got to understand, I was a person who did motivational seminars. 9, 12, 15, 16 I was the person that taught people you can do or be anything you want. 13 I was the symbol of hope eternal. 10 When he died it died.  I didn’t know, I had no idea who I really was. 11, 13, 14, 15 I felt like I lost my own identity. 9, 17 I couldn’t practice what I preached. 10, 13 That you can do anything you really want. 13 AS: You must be a fake then.  GE: Right.  That shit doesn’t work.  A friend gave me a book. 12 I can’t remember exactly. 10 It was about a kid that committed suicide.  Her son committed suicide because he had mental illness. 14 He purposely drove, created an accident. 7, 14 She was a person like me.  She’s in a coffee shop and she’s hearing two people talk about, “You know, I drove around the block and I just envisioned that a parking place was going to appear and it did.” 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 What her experience was after losing her son and listening to a conversation like that. 9, 12, 15, 17 Boy could I relate to that.  I wrote a poem about it.  I just started all this journaling about grief. 9, 11, 12 I just have reams and reams. 9, 12 What this was like for the last twenty years. 9, 20 I got out of the car one day. 7, 19 In network marketing you can continue to earn income, I mean if it’s a real buyable company, without continuing to build. 7, 13, 16, 19 I was just living off of residual income. 6, 9, 12, 13, 19 I just couldn’t do anything after he died. 9, 12 I just didn’t have that. 9, 12 My soul was gone. 19 I got out of the car at Zumba one day. 7, 19 I was praying, “God show me where I’m supposed to go and what I’m supposed to do now.” 6, 14 I get out of the car one day and God said, “You need to write. 7, 13, 19 You need to write a grief book about this. 13 You need to put all this stuff into a book.” 9, 10, 13 So I started that whole process and kind of got this huge conglomeration of stuff together. 9, 11, 16, 17 Part of it was sort of like; the first part was sort of like the first part of the book that you’re going to see. 9, 10, 17 The rest of it, the middle was about a different kind of grief about the addiction. 8, 9, 16, 17, 19 The rest was these meditations that were connected to quotes that I found. 9, 18, 19 My editor, God bless her, said, “You know there’s two different books here, two different audiences.” 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 By now the opiate epidemic is in full swing. 11, 14 She said, “People need to know what you learned in twenty years. 12, 13, 14, 15, 17, 20 So they don’t make the same mistakes.” 6, 9, 16 I’d had an editor, who worked also for Hazelton as a freelancer, do a lot of editing of my books. 17 So I could get the languaging down and all the medical terminology. 14 She helped me with some of the medical research. 13, 14, 16 I have a lot of research in my book to back up my own personal theories. 16, 17, 19 So then I had this editor look at my book once the one editor said, “You have two books.”  The opiate epidemic is going on, people need this. 13 I chopped off this other part about grief and put this together and then this other editor, my final editor looks at it. 10 She said, “I can’t keep track of this stuff. 9, 12 Are you going to just market this in the recovery community or do you want the general public to be able to understand this?” 9, 12, 13, 16 I said, “I want everybody to read this.” 13 “You’ve got to have a glossary.  You’ve got to do pull outs with lessons.  I can’t remember all this important stuff. 9 You’ve got to do little pull outs.  You’ve got to list them on the back. 9, 19 You’ve got to have a glossary of terms.  You’ve got to have resources.  This is what people need now. 13, 14 Do it this way.” 16 God bless her.  My book ended up being much more. 12, 18 It’s not a memoir.  It’s kind of a handbook of resources. 16, 17 Don’t do what I did, do what I learned. 12, 17 The grief book is waiting.  The first support groups I did were the grief groups. 9 Once I went through Minnesota Recovery Connection and got a website up. 13 I did that before I started really working seriously on this book. 9, 11, 15 Then I just got really involved in advocacy. 9, 12 I work with Minnesota Recovery Connection and still toy with the idea of becoming a non-profit. 9, 11, 14 I don’t know if I want to do that. 13, 14, 15 Probably would look better.  That involves a board, all this other stuff. 5, 9 I think I just want to focus on my speaking and my advocacy and another book. 9, 12, 13, 15, 16 Maybe.  I’m doing a lot of partnering with Rose McKinney. 13, 17 God bless Rummler Foundation.  They gave me a little seed money to get my groups off the ground. 8 I got a little bit of a grant. 7 I got a thousand dollars and managed to start that. 9, 11 Other people said, “Well do you have groups for people that are still in active addictions?” 9, 10 So I started my Courageous Caregivers group. 6, 9, 11 AS: You mean for families of people who are still? 9, 16 GE: Or significant others.  I had my Courageous Caregivers group. 6 Did you ever hear of the Opiate Coalition that started? 9, 11 She helped me do a pilot. 13, 16, 17 She and I piloted the first Courageous Caregivers group to see if people would show up. 6, 9, 17 They showed up. 7 She didn’t want to have any more to do with it. 13 What was her name? 6 GE: Mary Kay Forstrum. 9 She and I piloted that. 17 Once there was an interest she said, “You just take them and run them out of your house.” 6, 9, 11, 12, 19 I did that so I can keep the cost down. 9, 12 I had my first few groups at my church. 9 But then I had to charge more. 17 I moved them back here. 8, 19 People like coming to a home, more relaxing. 19 This is in the book; I kind of became a follower of Chuck Hilger. 5, 12, 16, 17, 19 He would come and say, “You need to write a book.” 13, 19 AS: He told me that too. 20 AS: There’s a thing about how you feel… 16 Sometimes I think that isn’t there enough out there. 5, 18, 20 I said that to Chuck Hilger who I met through the Steve’s Law lobbying day. 5, 19 I told him about this project. 20 He was really excited.  Two years later when I’m finally able to get to it. 20 I was like, “Chuck do you really think I should go forward with this?” 9, 10 He was like, “Are you kidding? 10 We need this. 13 Please keep going.” 12 GE: I think you ought to get ahold of the Minnesota Historical Society. 9, 20 AS: I talked to them. 10, 11 GE: They’re not interested? 9, 11, 19 AS: When I’m all finished they might look at it and they might decide to house it. 6, 9 I couldn’t believe it.  GE: There’s stigma for you right there. 9, 14 This is a major health crisis. 14, 18 This is a health epidemic. 14 AS: Of historic proportions. 9 The way I think about it is like AIDS. 16 History of medicine is one of my fields. 9 That’s how I’m starting to realize it. 9, 11, 14 It’s following the same trajectory. 12 GE: The effect it’s having on doctors and the way they prescribe. 16 Absolutely, positively and the backlash of people who are on pain medication, using it responsibly and need it because they’re on MA. 10, 13, 14, 19 They can’t afford acupuncture or meditation or any of the other stuff, massage. 9 They want to stop prescribing it. 9, 10, 13 AS: To people on MA only.  GE: Yes.  AS: Thank you very much right? 14, 18 So there’s a racial component to it and economic.  It’s a class issue. 15, 20 GE: Right.  She’s my best friend. 9, 12 One of my best friends is scared to death that she’s going to get her opiates taken away from her. 5, 6, 7, 9, 11, 12, 16, 18 She has angioedema which are extremely painful.  They never found out why she has those. 15 AS: That’s the backlash that you talked about. 10, 11, 19 GE: There’s a lot of backlash. 17, 19 AS: Where you go to the extreme instead of the more balanced approach. 9 GE: That’s kind of the way the United States does things. 16, 17 Maybe that’s just the way life is. 9, 11, 12, 16 I mean, that’s the way I did with Aaron, from one extreme to another. 16 AS: I did that with my daughter. 5 I didn’t understand it. 9, 12, 16 She was using heroin for two years before I ever knew. 6, 12, 20 I only knew when she nearly died. 6, 12 I found her.  GE: I didn’t know until I took Aaron to the Methadone clinic. 13, 14, 15 AS: What would you say about your…can  you talk a little bit about mothering? 10 I know you already are talking about it. 10, 13, 14, 15 Is there any last things you’d want to say? 9, 13, 16 GE: Aaron had some good friends in Oakland during one of his more sober periods. 6, 8, 12, 18 Though I think he was using medical marijuana when he was out there. 14 I had to call them all when he died. 7 Thank God  I had their phone numbers. 7 He was in contact with them. 10 The young woman, he’d tried desperately to go out to her wedding but had so much anxiety about carrying Methadone on the plane, even though it was a legal prescription. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 18 Was so sure something was going to go wrong that he didn’t go. 15 He hated that about himself. 12 That he never went to her wedding. 15 When I called her and I said, “Mary I don’t know. 7, 13, 14, 15 I tried.” 10 She said, “Don’t you ever doubt that Aaron ever loved you. 13 Or that he didn’t know that you did everything that you could to help him. 13, 14, 15 You were his angel.”  That’s what I would say to parents. 10, 16 That sometimes the person you’re trying to help can’t relay to you how much you do. 5, 13, 16, 18 Or how much they appreciate or maybe they are very self-absorbed in their own illness. 9, 14, 18 They could never had as many chances, had the quality of life while they were alive if they did, could never have had as many chances to recover. 11, 15 It just comes all back to parenting; it’s just a fucking thankless job. 9, 10, 12, 13, 16, 19 [Laughs].  You have to remember that whether you have an addict or not.  I think that’s the other thing.  So many things that I made huge issues about I always made out because Aaron was an addict. 14, 15, 16, 17 There were a lot of things, issues that go on with teenagers and young adults with parents in their lives. 10, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18 It’s all part of growing up. 17 Issues happen. 12 AS: It’s not always about the addiction. 16, 17 GE: It’s not always about addiction. 16, 17 AS: Unless your child is an addict.  GE: Then parents get blamed and then there’s a lot of thanklessness that goes on. 10, 13, 16, 17 I think they’re all angels.  No matter how many mistakes they made. 6, 9, 16, 20 They did it because they loved their child. 13 I do a lot of coaching my Courageous Caregivers group and they’ll say, “What do you think I should do?” 6, 17 I ask them, “What’s going to support their recovery?  Or is it going to support their illness? 14 You know what if you’re not ready to drop the gauntlet on this particular issue that’s your choice.” 13, 14, 15, 17, 18, 19 AS: Right, maybe don’t. 9 GE: “I don’t want you saying, ‘Gloria said.’ 11, 13 You need to make up your mind about this.” 13, 16 AS: You have opened yourself up to, and put yourself in a place where you can be supportive of other parents who are going through what you went through, with the benefit of hindsight. 10, 11, 14, 16, 17 The things that worked and the things that didn’t. 16 That is a way to continue mothering in a bigger picture. 8, 16 GE: Yes, it is.  I have my own supervisor as an unlicensed healthcare professional. 7, 12, 14, 20 I’m not a licensed psychologist or therapist. 6, 9 I’m only a certified recovery coach.  But I belong; I’m registered with the board of unlicensed healthcare professionals. 5, 7, 9, 12, 14, 20 I do have a supervisor that I check in with if I feel like I’m getting hooked by my parents or some of my clients or my grief clients. 10, 12, 16 It brings up my own grief issues. 14, 15 Like you said, you’re never over it. 15 There’s no closure. 15 It’s all good for me until it’s not.  There was a thing in the paper, an editorial in the paper about mental illness, a whole story in the paper about how we’re not taking care of those who are mentally ill. 7, 9, 14 It could have been about addiction.  I wanted to write a letter to the editor so bad Sunday morning. 12, 13, 19 I just couldn’t do one more thing about it that day. 9, 12, 19 You know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 GE: That’s why I’m going up North.  AS: To take a break. 6, 18 GE: It’s really my whole life, in a lot of ways. 11, 16, 17 AS: Do you think you’ll stick with it? 9 What’s your energy like for it?  What do you want to achieve? 13 GE: I really want to put this grief book out. 10, 13 I would love it if some other publisher would pick up Living in the Wake of Addiction. 13 There needs to be a second edition, I already have some updates. 13, 20 Like this whole thing about implied consent which is in the chapter but it’s mostly all around Dr. French. 7, 9 You’ll read it.  That needs to be driven home. 7, 13, 14, 19 I have a whole chapter on alternatives to twelve steps because Aaron never... 9, 12, 15 It was a long time until I accepted that he’s not going to recover in twelve step recovery, start supporting him in something that he wants. 9, 11, 12, 13 He loved health realization. 13, 14 AS: Oh right. 14 My son-in-law, Brandon that totally connected for him. 7, 17, 18 GE: Right.  One meeting in 2007. 13 One meeting in the Twin Cities, no car, they didn’t have the light rail. 7, 13 We were living in Chanhassen so how was he going to get to meetings? 6, 13 AS: There’s so much about access that I just find astonishing. 6, 9, 12, 18 In that way it does remind me of the AIDS crisis. 16 There’s certain people who have access to the treatment modalities, or happen to be at the right place at the right time for it. 6, 9, 11, 12, 14, 16 Then there’s always people who are on the fringe and they could be from middle