o buy a sober house. 6, 7, 9 Do you know what the state is paying me to have this crappy little room, with a crappy little roommate? 7, 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16 You guys ought to run sober houses.” 6, 9, 11 I was thinking all the shit that goes on.  For me to be advocating and writing blogs. 10 He’s just laughing out of the other side of his mouth and saying, “Oh I wish we could have done this better together. 5, 9, 11, 12 Oh Mom I wish we could have done this better together.”  I do a lot of nurturing. 17 It’s totally changed my relationship with my other kids. 16, 17 I could be a pretty harsh, you follow the rules or you’re not okay with me. 12, 18 I’m just not like that anymore. 9, 12, 13 Whoever you are, as long as you’re kind to me, you’re kind to other people in the family, kind to your own children you are okay by me. 14, 16, 17, 18 AS: That’s a pretty big transformation. 7, 8, 17, 18 GE: It happened because of Aaron. 12, 13 I could never have supported Jeff’s recovery through his death the way that I had if I hadn’t gone through that experience with Aaron. 15, 16 I could never have been as patient. 15 AS: You mean Jeff recovering from his brother’s death? 5, 16 GE: Yes.  His anger and drawing the boundaries what I wasn’t going to take from his anger. 6, 14 I don’t know the answer for it. 13, 14, 15 I could never have taken that approach with him if I wouldn’t have. 6, 15 He and I would have been like this the whole time.  Like, “What the hell’s wrong with you?  You need help. 13 Go get help. 13 You’re broken.” 5 I think it’s mostly about me. 9 Shoving aside what happened to him because I was trying to save Aaron. 12, 13, 16 AS: Well thank you. 13 That’s powerful, a very powerful story. 9, 15 GE: You know what’s really sad? 12, 13, 14, 15 There’s a million stories like mine out there. 9, 18 That’s when that first book review, the editor what’s her name? 6, 9 AS: Julianne. 8 GE: I wrote a book review for her.  She said, “Do you want Aaron’s picture?” 13 I said, “This isn’t about Aaron or about me.  This is about all the other people.  It’s about us and Aaron.  I don’t want to make Aaron’s death the star.” 9, 13, 16 AS: Right, the star sad story. 9, 12 That’s the part that’s not being communicated very effectively. 10 GE: That’s what I try, that’s what happened in two or three interviews. 6, 12, 13, 16 AS: That’s what I’m trying to counteract. 10, 16 We need to get Rose on our PR committee. 13 GE: We’re valiant; Aaron was a valiant hero, all those people that tried so hard to recover. 8, 10, 11 The ones that make it, they’re valiant. 8, 16 Aaron isn’t any less valiant then they because he died. 8 The parents that stick by them, valiant, valiant, valiant. 8, 9, 10, 16 Talking about Post Traumatic Stress Disorder various things will trigger and I will just lose it. 9, 12, 16 AS: Mine has been for a couple years the people with the signs. 20 GE: On the street corners? 9 That are showing up everywhere because it’s what my daughter was doing the summer that I just knew she was going to die. 5, 6, 9, 12 Here in Minneapolis she was doing it on 94.  GE: Did she ever want to come home? 13, 19 AS: She did, I let her and then she overdosed in the house again. 6, 9, 15, 19 With her little sister right there, the foaming mouth. 5, 9, 14 We had to call the EMT. 7 GE: You didn’t have Naloxone?  AS: I had just lobbied for it two months before but I didn’t, there was no access yet. 6, 8, 9, 12 It was in that period between March and the middle of May. 8 It was available as of June or July.  She came to before they, we made them take her to the hospital. 6, 16, 19 GE: How did she come to? 13, 19 AS: We moved her and then there was a lot of noise. 8, 17 GE: She came around. 8, 19 AS: Yes.  I’m going to stop this. 9, 10 GE: I didn’t know any of that. 13, 14, 15"
"6","Cole_Bill","Nancy Espuche Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer March 20, 2017 St. Paul, Minnesota Nancy Espuche-NE Amy Sullivan-AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan with Nancy  Espuche at her home in St. Paul. 19 It is March 20, 2017.  We are back together for part two, as Nancy called it, to discuss what happened in the last few months of Lucas’s life and what Nancy is doing now. 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 19 We will just take this as a conversation. 6, 9, 12 Can you say you give me permission? 6 NE: I give you permission, Amy. 6 AS: Where would you like to start? 9, 10, 11 NE: Well, honestly I don’t know where I am right now because I feel so lost. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16 I feel very lost. 9, 16 I think what is starting to happen is the shock is wearing and the reality of the finality is really in my face. 9, 11, 12 Not that I ever thought Lucas would come back, but I guess I did. 10, 11, 12, 13, 19 There was so much action and sorrow that I didn’t make room or allow myself to really think about Lucas. 7, 10, 16, 18 Now I want to think about him all the time and I want to push it away all the time because I am afraid to think about him. 13, 16 I think one of the big challenges for me -- actually, I’ll tell you the challenges my grief therapist told me on Saturday. 6, 8, 9, 10, 19, 20 My situation is a little different in that I had so much trauma for so long. 13, 16, 17, 18 I’m also solo flying.  I’m single; I don’t have a partner to really go through this mourning with and Lucas is my only child. 13, 15 I say ‘is,’ I don’t know what to do with that ‘is’ versus ‘was.’ 13, 14, 15 That’s a big one. 8 I felt left. 17 I really feel left. 16 I fought so hard. 11 I’ve never worked so hard on anything in my life. 11, 15 AS: To keep him sober and safe. 6, 12 NE: To keep him alive. 12 I can’t do anything else.  Lucas had a hard life and a life filled with a lot of suffering and that feels really horrible. 11, 16, 17 That’s where I am, sort of. 17 Every morning when I wake up and often when I go to sleep there is a new song in my head every day. 6, 7, 12, 15, 19 Last night it was John Legend’s “They got nothing on you, babe.” 9, 12, 19 Lucas and I listened to that music a lot. 9, 15, 17 I think maybe that’s a message somewhere. 9 The lack of form of Lucas, of his body, evaporating -- I don’t know. 13, 14, 15, 17 It is so hard to digest. 9, 11 For three months I cried. 8 Who knew you could cry so much? 6, 12, 18 The other piece is the confrontation of the part of me that says you’ve got to go on and the part of me that says I don’t want to. 13 That battle.  There is a part of me that doesn’t give a hoot. 6 About anything including my future.  The healthier, higher vibrational part goes, “Come on Nancy, you’re still part of the living. 6, 8, 9, 14, 15 You’ve got to find a way to live.” 16 That snake rears it’s ugly head and goes, “Really?  That’s scary. 7 That lack of desire for anything is scary because all I have been living with for the last number of years was the desire to keep Lucas alive. 6, 7, 9, 12, 20 He consumed all of my thinking, my finances, my activity, my sleep. 7, 10 AS: The last interview was the beginning of June of last summer. 6, 9 Some things happened since then. 12, 13, 16 I thought fall was pretty rocky. 11, 12, 18 Are you able to back in time a little bit? 19 NE: I think in July it was rocky.  His acceleration of sadness really started in the summer. 9, 11, 12 He was calling me constantly crying, “I’m scared, I’m scared.” 5, 7, 9, 11, 12 AS: What do you know about what he was doing? 13, 14, 15 NE: I did not know in July. 13, 14, 15 In August Lucas called me to tell me that he had been arrested. 7, 9, 19 I don’t know if he called me or his father called me. 5, 7, 13, 14, 15 Evidently he was driving on something. 14 He told me he had a wobbly tire and there was a problem with the tire. 20 All the same stupid stories he made up his whole life. 9, 11, 16, 18 He was in jail.  He called his father, not me, knowing I wouldn’t bail him out. 5, 7, 13, 14, 15 His father said to me that they gave him a breathalyzer that came up clean, but they hired a lawyer. 5, 12, 19 I was thinking, Hold on a second. 20 If his breathalyzer was clean and it was just his tire they don’t put you in jail. 9, 10, 12 What was he doing in jail?  Well, then Lucas proceeds to tell me he had a scale in the car and it was his friend’s scale. 7, 12 Somewhere Lucas must have really thought I was stupid. 9, 11, 12 He really thought I was going to believe this garbage. 11, 12 I called Michael Knoth, one of my contacts in New York who Lucas loved. 7, 10, 13 We had a session and he said, “You need to get to California.” 13 I said, “When?”  And he said, “Today.” 19 I flew out that afternoon. 7 AS: Was this a therapist you had worked with? 6, 9 NE: He was the man that I mentioned at Lucas’s service.  I called Lucas from the plane and said, “I’ll see you in four hours. 7, 11, 13 I’m on a plane.” 13 I learned at that time that Lucas was doing Xanax which he had a grand mal seizure from in college. 7, 8, 12, 17 Supposedly he got Suboxone.  I don’t even honestly remember what it was. 9, 15, 16 He was withdrawing and I had to take him to the hospital one night. 6, 14, 19 AS: You got him out of jail?  NE: No, he was already out.  His father hired a lawyer. 5, 12 Lucas and I really lay in bed for two days and watched television and slept and ate. 17, 19 I knew we were in trouble when I left, but I didn’t realize how much trouble. 6, 12, 14, 18 In September Lucas came in for the state fair. 9, 19 Lucas won me that giant bear in the corner. 8 The day that he was leaving he really didn’t feel well. 16, 19 I didn’t connect this because he wasn’t high. 8 I said, “You need to go to a doctor.” 13 By the time he got to California his legs and feet were so swollen -- he sent the pictures to his father -- but I told him he had to go to the hospital. 5, 7, 20 He had a really horrific infection.  Almost deadly. 9 If it would have kept spreading it would have killed him. 7, 11 AS: Like sepsis or something?  NE: Yes.  But I didn’t know people shot in their feet. 13, 14, 15 He was walking around in his underwear in front of me and there’s not a mark on him. 8, 15 That was September.  The beginning of October he called me one night screaming at me that he needed my help and he was vomiting profusely. 7, 9, 13, 19 He couldn’t stop. 9, 10 I said, “Lucas, I’m in Minnesota.  You’ve got to call an ambulance.” 7 I didn’t ask him what drug he had took, although that was the turning point for me. 14, 19 That’s when I knew we were in serious trouble. 6, 12 AS: You knew he was using heroin? 6, 12 AS: But you knew he was using drugs again? 6, 12, 14 NE: I thought it was Xanax. 11, 12 I ended up calling the Santa Monica police, but they told me he had already called and they were already on their way there. 7, 12, 16, 20 He made up some cock and bull story that he had a kidney stone or appendicitis. 9, 12, 16 I said, “Really?  I don’t think so.”  It just accelerated from the beginning of October -- crying, screaming, “I’m scared.” 5, 7, 9, 11, 12 I went to see my friends for the party in October -- for Monica’s sixtieth -- and he was high as a kite. 6, 8, 12, 18 I still didn’t know it was heroin, and I had a breakdown. 9, 13, 14, 15, 18 AS: Had he not used heroin before, Nancy? 9 NE: He had, but he had never shot before. 15 AS: Was he using pain pills?  NE: He was an OxyContin guy.  AS: But now he was shooting up. 14 When he would say he was scared would he ever explain what he was scared of? 5, 7, 11, 12 NE: “What are you frightened of?” 14, 15 “My future, my life.” 11 I said, “Lucas, you need help and I’m here to support that. 13 Tell me what is happening.” 12, 13 He just called me everyday, “Don’t stop talking to me. 7, 9, 10, 12, 19 Please keep talking. 10, 12 I need you, mom.” 13, 15 I said, “Lucas, I’m here.”  But when I wouldn’t give him money he would say, “You’re abandoning me.” 6, 15 I said, “I think you are confusing money with abandonment. 15 I’m right here. 14 I haven’t gone anywhere.  My bank is closed. 10 It doesn’t exist anymore.” 9, 13 AS: Plus, you didn’t have a job at this point.  NE: He didn’t care. 7 AS: Right.  But you actually had reached a hard place. 10, 11, 13 NE: Correct.  It was all about money.  He was getting jobs and losing jobs.  When I was there at the end of October I was down on my hands and knees. 12 I thought I was having a nervous breakdown. 11, 12, 16, 18 So did Kim and my friends Sierra and Jane. 12, 18 They thought I was having a nervous breakdown. 11, 12, 16, 18 I was pounding on the floor in the garage: “Stop.  What’s happening? 12, 13 You have to tell me.  He just stood and watched me. 9, 12, 17 He was void of emotion.  He didn’t come to the party with me. 6, 13, 19 He lost his wallet, he lost his phone, and his computer was gone. 7, 9, 10, 19 He was aimlessly walking. 15 It was horrendous. 12 I called the psychiatrist and said, “How did you give him Xanax without knowing his medical history?” 6, 7, 9, 13, 14, 15 He was referred by his therapist. 6, 9, 12 I went berserk on him.  I said, “Don’t talk to me about HIPAA [Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act], I know all about HIPAA. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15 Everyone has always called me. 7, 16, 17 Lucas has always signed a release. 16, 17 Xanax?”  Anyway. 16 It just accelerated. 9, 12 The sobbing, the tears, the fear, the pain.  I talked for hours, Amy. 10, 11 AS: How long did you stay in California with him at that point? 9 NE: In October?  A few days. 19 AS: Didn’t he come back for a meeting? 13, 19 When did he visit our meeting? 12, 13 NE: Was that before you interviewed me the first time? 6, 9 AS: I thought when he was trying to get clean after he crashed his car. 7, 11, 12, 16 NE: July.  AS: That was in the summer?  He came and visited and he came to a meeting. 12, 13, 19 AS: That’s when he told us that it wasn’t about us. 20 That must have been the summer, I think.  He came in September for the State Fair. 19 That’s what it was, it was September.  AS: He came with you to the meeting even though he was using. 13, 15, 19 NE: That’s right. 14 AS: He hid it well.  NE: He hid it well.  But he didn’t want to do the recovery walk. 13 AS: That’s right, but he had done it a year before. 14, 20 NE: I didn’t know he was using then either. 13, 14, 15 AS: He was using during that first recovery walk? 9 NE: When he got arrested I asked him how long he had been using and he said for the last year. 9, 10, 19, 20 He told me he was withdrawing on the recovery walk. 14, 20 Outside of Lucas being swallowed up -- everything came so easy for Lucas except this. 19 He didn’t have to try at anything. 16 He was exceptionally smart. 20 He was talented in every aspect of creativity.  He was a superstar athlete. 9, 12, 19 He was charming, he was funny, he was handsome, and he thought he could do this on his own. 11, 12 He couldn’t and I don’t think he could believe it.  I came back October twenty-sixth and I held on for dear life. 11, 19 I would talk to him and the minute he said, “Hello” I could tell if he was high. 8, 10 He didn’t even have to say a sentence to me. 7, 15 AS: Was this because you had spent that time with him in October? 19 NE: No, I always knew when he was high. 6, 8, 12, 16, 17 Always. 16, 17 I would say, “What are you doing?”  He says, “I’m going to work.”  I said, “Really?  You’re high as a kite. 8 You’re going to work?”  This was his response: “Okay, mom.” 15 That’s what he said when he knew that I knew and he didn’t want to admit it. 6, 12, 13 “Okay, mom. 15 I’m going to go now.” 14 Amy, I knew somewhere. 6, 12 I never really allowed it to penetrate my consciousness, but I knew Lucas wasn’t going to make it. 6, 12, 15, 16 I knew it. 6, 12 I couldn’t take it in. 6 I couldn’t accept it.  I couldn’t look at it because who can look at that?  It is horrifying.  In the depths of my soul I knew it. 6, 12 My awakened mind knew it. 6, 12 I couldn’t hide it from myself.  AS: At what point would you say you knew that? 6, 12 NE: Probably four years ago. 20 AS: Really?  I just kept watching him spiral and do nothing. 9, 12 AS: He couldn’t get a grip on anything to pull himself up.  NE: And believe me if he had a fall he had such a net to fall into.  He had so many people rooting for him there, available.  I hate to say he couldn’t.  I also hate to say he didn’t want to. 13 I don’t know what is true. 13, 14, 15 I don’t know which part is true. 13, 14, 15 Maybe both.  I don’t really think that Lucas knew how to live on this earth plane. 6, 12, 13 He wrote me some remarkable stacks of letters and poems. 9, 19 He could present and express when he was ‘locked up’ if you will. 7 In a treatment facility. 9, 16 Not towards the latter parts.  He fought them; he wasn’t interested. 9, 11, 19 But, the minute he stepped back into the real world he couldn’t do it. 9, 12, 15, 19 The world was too scary to him. 7, 15 He couldn’t find ground. 8 He couldn’t find a way to really participate. 16 He didn’t want to play by the rules here. 12, 13 He wanted to set his own crazy standards. 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 I think the thing that is so hard for me too is that he became like a thug. 5, 11, 19 He was like a split person.  He was the person you met, and he was that, and then he was this thuggish, hanging out with sludge, garbage, awful people. 5, 10, 18 AS: I keep thinking of the road trip story with the drug dealer. 9, 12, 13, 14 They are driving across the country. 11, 14, 16 I saw a picture that he had sent me in November. 7 In November he was going to see Tony Robbins in Nevada with his roommate who is very spiritual. 7 He was trying to influence Lucas to the best of his ability. 9, 16, 20 I never really looked at the picture because I didn’t like it. 10, 15 I looked at it not too long ago and it looked like Lucas had a broken nose and a black eye. 5, 16 I was so horrified.  I think -- and his father thinks too -- that he was in trouble. 5 I think people were after him for money.  I think everything that started to come out of his mouth was a lie to everybody. 9, 11, 13, 19 I don’t know if you know this. 13, 14, 15 He called me one night at the end of November: “Mom there is something mentally wrong with me. 7, 12, 14, 19 I’m not right. 14 Help me.”  I said, “I’m here Lucas.  Tell me what.”  I said a lot more than just that. 9, 12, 17 I said, “What thoughts are you having? 11, 12 What is in your head?  What are you hearing?  What are you believing?”  He goes, “I don’t know.” 13, 14, 15 He was sobbing.  I think he knew how far from reality he was going and that he was living in a very dangerous world. 6, 12, 15, 18 He wouldn’t say it.  I said, “Come to Minnesota.  Let’s get you out of California.  I’m here I’ll get you on the next plane. 13 I’ll come out there.” 13, 19 AS: Because he had lived here for a while.  NE: Yeah, but it was a really bad place for him. 11 Then he called me the first week of December at six in the morning and said, “I got it. 7, 9 I had an epiphany.”  I went, “Okay, what happened?” 12, 13 I had heard that before that people suddenly had these epiphanies. 13, 15 He said that he understood what this was all about. 9 And what life was all about. 11 I said I wasn’t following. 12 He said he was talking to my father and that my father was on the other side and my father isn’t on the other side. 5, 10 He understood his addiction and what purpose is here in life. 9, 11 Anyway, it was all very confusing, but for me it gave me such a sense of hope in the moment. 10, 13, 15, 16, 17 I thought he had an epiphany. 11, 12 Now, I think one of two things happened. 12, 13, 16 I think he had a near death experience.  Or I think he had a premonition and maybe he was on the other side. 9 AS: Maybe he had overdosed. 15 NE: Yes.  AS: He would just not be straight with you. 6, 9, 12 NE: Never.  AS: Even around something like that.  NE: No. AS: You would get the final statement but you wouldn’t get anything tha