about him because I wouldn’t give him money. 5, 6, 7, 20 I haven’t really thought about that conversation. 11, 12 But, I did say to him, “If my name wasn’t on that lease you can rest assured that you wouldn’t be getting a dime from anybody. 6, 9, 12, 15, 19 I’m only doing this to safeguard myself because I’m the cosigner.  It’s not for you, Lucas.  I know I said something like, “You are such an ass. 13, 14, 15 I can’t even stand it.” 9, 12, 15 When we hung up I texted him and said, “I apologize.  You are not an ass.  You’re behavior is ass-like and it is very hard for me to watch it and to be witness to it and to be on the other side of it.” 10, 11 He wrote me back, “No, mom. 15, 19 I’m an ass.”  That was our last communication. 9, 10 I did learn also that his ex-girlfriend from Hazelden [Betty Ford Foundation], Audrey, who he liked a lot. 10, 12, 14, 17, 18 I don’t know what happened. 12, 13, 14, 15 She was in California, too.  They hadn’t spoken in a year. 19, 20 I did learn that she -- and I saw it on his phone too -- she contacted him that night and wanted to see him. 7, 10, 12, 13, 19 He went to see her and she never showed up. 7, 15 He died four hours later. 11 If you think I don’t want to call her and kill her I do. 7, 13 If that’s okay to say here.  AS: It’s just a feeling. 9, 12, 16 NE: She never showed up. 7, 15 The text was, “Audrey this is not a game.” 14 She called him. 7 I haven’t read through half of it. 20 He didn’t call me back or text me. 7 My anxiety was so high. 8 AS: So twenty-four hours later is basically when you wake up or later that night? 7, 11, 19 NE: I woke up for some reason that morning after having fallen back asleep with a feeling of doom. 7, 16, 19 My mother goes, “What are you talking about?” 10 I go, “I don’t know, but something with Lucas. 13, 14, 15 I know it.” 13, 14, 15 When he didn’t respond that day my agitation really heightened. 15, 19 I spoke to a bunch of my friends including Kim and I said, “I haven’t heard from Lucas.” 9, 12, 15, 18, 19 She goes, “Nancy.”  “No, Kim.  I’m telling you right now.” 14 People think you’re crazy because you’re kids disappear. 16 Lucas never disappeared. 12, 15 AS: Right.  You know what their patterns are. 13, 14, 15 NE: I know what his patterns are. 13, 14, 15 AS: Some people might not expect their kid to text back. 19 NE: I went to bed thinking he was really busy and I’ll get a text the following morning. 9, 12 I woke up Wednesday morning and nothing. 19 I texted him again.  I just knew. 6, 9, 12 I called Raymond at about four o’clock that afternoon and asked if he had heard from Luke. 7, 10, 15 He said he had been trying to get a hold of him for two days. 16, 19, 20 I flipped out.  I was hysterical. 9 I said, “I’m telling you something is very wrong.”  He said to call his apartment and I said I was too scared. 5, 7, 11, 12, 20 I was afraid to do anything.  Really, I froze in time.  My friend 12 Jane from New York called and said she was my sister. 5, 7, 9 At this point Raymond also posted something on Facebook unbeknownst to me: 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 Has anyone seen or heard from Lucas? 15 The building never called Jane back. 7, 15, 19 They said they would try to reach him. 13, 16 I called back at about five o’clock and they said they couldn’t reach him. 7, 13, 19 I said, “You need to go open his door.” 13, 17 They said that the only people that can do that are the police. 7 At that point my brother-in-law called me and said, “What is happening? 5, 7, 12, 13 Raymond posted something on Facebook.” 9 I said, “We hadn’t heard from Luke.” 15 He said, “Lisa and I have been trying to reach Lucas for two days.” 13, 16, 19 I then called the Santa Monica police. 7 The dispatcher was getting two police to the site. 7, 13 I called my friend Michael and I called my friend Kim. 7, 12 Michael came down; Kim was coming over. 19 The police called and said that no one was answering the door. 7 “We are leaving. 19 I guess he is not home.” 10, 19 I said, “You are not leaving. 19 You’ve got to open that door.” 17 “Because he could be behind that door.”  They then had to get permission from the building, from me. 6 At which point now Ann is here. 14 It is now six-thirty, a quarter to seven. 14 The police called to say they were entering and they would call back. 7, 19 Of course if he wasn’t there they would call me and tell me he wasn’t there. 7 I call back a half hour later. 7, 20 The dispatcher said they were still on site and they would get back to me. 9, 13, 19 Forty-five minutes pass. 7 It is now eight-thirty and my sister is here. 5, 9, 14 She said, “Nancy.  It is a crime scene.”  But I didn’t hear anything, Amy.  I called back. 7, 19 The dispatcher went, “Oh, Nancy,” and I went, “Yeah?”  She said, “They are still on site and they will get back to you.” 9, 13, 19 I said, “You’ve said that now for two hours.” 11, 14 At nine-thirty Lisa called and asked to speak to a sergeant. 7, 10 She said that this was borderline abusive.  We need to know what is happening. 12, 13, 14, 15 I went downstairs to have a cigarette with Kim and I came back upstairs. 9, 19 My sister just looked at me and I fell to the floor. 5, 9, 12, 15 He had been dead since around midnight the morning of the twentieth. 8 They were waiting for the coroner and the medical examiner to show up and that was why it took so long. 14 Ann explained that, although I didn’t hear anything.  All I did was scream.  I couldn’t get a hold of Raymond that night. 19, 20 He must have gone to sleep. 7 It was a quarter to ten here, which is a quarter to eleven in New York, you know, Eastern Time. 9, 13, 14, 15 Lisa stayed here and called Raymond the following morning. 5, 7, 9, 12 We got him on a plane here. 13 My friends 12, 18 Jane and Emily flew in. 7 In the Jewish religion they don’t do an autopsy.  I would have done it anyway, but with the crime scene they automatically do it. 7, 16 They never even asked me. 10, 15 Lisa did everything.  She got in touch with the coroner, the medical examiner, I don’t know who. 13, 14, 15 She got in touch with the funeral home in Pasadena. 12, 15, 19 Palisades is about a half an hour from Los Angeles. 12 Raymond and I booked flights to get out there.  We left Christmas day. 9, 19 They told us they were doing a brain and a full body autopsy. 11, 20 I didn’t know what an autopsy really meant and then I looked. 13, 14, 15, 16 You’re like a shell after that.  Raymond and I went out there.  I didn’t think I wanted to see Lucas, but Raymond definitely did. 12, 13 We asked the head of the funeral home if he thought we should see Lucas. 10, 11, 12, 19 He said, “Yes.”  There was a towel around his head because of the autopsy.  I did see some hair. 12 He had a sheet covering him from the neck down, but it was Lucas.  It looked just like Lucas. 9, 12 I couldn’t get off of him.  We went to the apartment and did work and then I had to leave and Raymond finished it without me. 6, 20 I’m talking as if I’m not talking about my child because it’s too much. 10, 18 It’s just too much. 9, 12, 18 Some days I think I could take those ashes over there and put him back together. 6, 10, 19 Did you see this?  Some of his ashes are in here.  AS: Wow.  That’s beautiful. 6 NE: As a matter of fact I was in New York at the camp and then his soccer team did a beautiful memorial for him. 6, 8, 10, 20 It was amazing. 15 New York?  NE: You have no idea the outpouring from all over this country. 11, 16 Yeah, his soccer team did a thing.  His coaches.  Thirty kids showed up. 7 AS: Was this high school or college? 8 NE: It was high school and traveling. 8 Some of his friends from high school had films of him playing soccer. 8, 12, 18 They gave me that picture.  They had two blown up pictures of the team they mailed to me.  The team was called the Galaxy. 7 They had a Galaxy ball that everybody signed. 8 The coaches were sobbing.  The kids spoke and were crying. 11, 19 It was probably one of the nicest nights of my life. 9, 11, 19 His camp friends and his ex-girlfriend came. 8, 12, 18, 19 AS: His high school girlfriend? 8, 12 NE: The one from camp. 8 The only girl he really ever cared about besides Audrey. 7, 11, 12, 14 When I saw Brooke I was like, “Oh my god.” 10 So many people showed up. 7 Brooke just sent me pictures of her and Lucas two days ago. 7, 9, 12, 19 I got an email two days ago from this kid on his floor that said, “I just learned. 9, 12, 17, 19 Lucas used to play with my dog all the time. 9, 10 I loved your son.” 13 We talked. 10, 11 AS: Was this in California?  NE: You can’t believe how many people in California reached out to me. 13 I had no idea. 11 His lawyer wrote me: “Lucas changed my life. 11, 16 I’ve never had this experience with a client. 15 He was a remarkable young man.” 14 I mean hundreds. 12, 14, 16 I had over a hundred and fifty cards up there. 7 I had no idea the impact. 10, 11 None.  Teachers, the owner of the camp, coaches, my babysitter who was with us for years. 5, 8, 13, 20 Loved Lucas; came to the soccer thing and the camp thing. 8, 19 He either didn’t feel it or couldn’t feel it. 16 AS: He had an addiction, Nancy.  NE: I know. 13, 14, 15 AS: It just hijacks their brain. 9, 12 NE: I know. 13, 14, 15 It is a very hard thing for me to accept. 11 I can’t really embrace -- and I do, up here -- but I can’t embrace that he couldn’t do it.  You know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 I thought he would do it for me. 11, 12 I thought he would do it for me. 11, 12 I really did.  Even though I knew. 6, 12 AS: Even though you know scientifically and intellectually and spiritually that you have to do it for yourself. 7, 13, 14, 15 NE: We were that close.  Having lived with so much trauma and insanity for so many years I also didn’t think that God would let my story end this way. 9, 12, 16, 18, 19, 20 I thought the ending would be good. 11, 12 Somewhere down the line. 6 I didn’t know where that would be. 13, 14, 15 AS: That’s what kept you going through the struggle. 9 Is that what you are saying? 11 I did have hope. 10 Lucas always talked about how he wanted to get married and have five kids and he really did. 10, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17 I thought he would. 11, 12 I thought I would be a grandmother and have a daughter in-law and watch my son change other people’s lives the way he did unbeknownst to me. 5, 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 People wrote me that, “He saved my life.” 11 There was a mother at the service who flew in from Chicago because Lucas saved her son’s life. 7, 11 I didn’t even remember her. 15 She remembered me from the family program at Hazelden. 12, 18 Did she tell you?  NE: She said he was just there one hundred percent for Joey all the time. 9, 12 And Joey had no idea that he was struggling. 9, 11 People asked me, “Why didn’t he share. 10 We had no idea.” 11 AS: So it wasn’t just you. 9, 12 NE: No. AS: That’s pretty powerful. 15, 18 NE: He had so much shame. 18 He couldn’t admit that this was who he could be and this is who he turned out to be. 19 He couldn’t bridge the two and the devil won.  Evil won.  I’m actually afraid to get back his toxicology report. 10, 19 They told me it would take six to ten months. 6, 8, 20 The state of California once they get it back they send it to a secondary firm. 9, 12, 19, 20 They want to make sure the two match. 13, 15, 16 I don’t even want to know what was in his system. 8, 9, 13, 14, 15 I’m sure he had Xanax, I’m sure he had heroin. 15 I mean they found the needle. 13, 16 There was one needle that was empty and one needle that was still full, which makes me think the first needle had a lot of Fentanyl in it. 9, 11, 13, 16, 17 I don’t get it.  When I spoke the neuroscientist, I said, “How do you explain it?” 9, 19 He said, “We really have no idea yet.” 11 I have a theory because listening to Gabor Maté and how he said things often skip a generation. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 I don’t know if all of our drug use impacted our kids. 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 Everybody now, including this doctor -- 14 AS: Do you mean people who use drugs -- parents who used drugs in the sixties and seventies? 9, 10, 14, 15, 16 NE: Because Maté said to a degree that epidemiology now -- that layer that lives above the genetic level that everyone is talking about now. 10, 14, 20 AS: Epigenetics?  NE: Epigenetics.  That everything is stored on the cellular level. 5, 7, 9, 12, 20 That we pass everything on on a cellular level. 7, 20 I wasn’t a huge druggie, but I drank plenty of alcohol and I partied. 7, 14 I certainly had my share of cocaine. 9 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 Certainly I have plenty of friends whose kids did plenty of pot smoking. 12, 18 Some of them have problems.  AS: Yeah, but some of them are fine. 14 NE: Yeah, but the population that is not fine is so big. 8, 14 How come? 13, 19 It’s not just -- I don’t know. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I don’t know if it is technology, I don’t know if it is a breakdown in humanity and a lack of the family unit. 13, 14, 15, 18 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 AS: I think that opioids have a different impact on the brain because we have opioid receptors and our body wants it. 10, 11, 13, 16, 17 We have a place in our brain for that particular plant chemical. 9, 11, 18 NE: Once you start doing them it naturally turns off your own -- AS: Right. 9, 11, 19 And then you need more and more and it changes your brain. 13, 16 That’s what Bob Levy was talking about the other night at the meeting when he came. 10, 13, 19 He was reiterating how different opioids are in the brain than other drugs. 10, 14, 16, 17 Opioids actually can take over your frontal lobe, but the part the opioid is responding to is your old brain, your amygdala, which takes over your frontal lobe. 6, 9, 10, 20 All the lying and the cheating and the stealing and hiding, all that stuff that it does. 9, 10 One thing that might be interesting to you to hear -- because he didn’t say this the first time -- he said they are finding now that genetics and addiction have about a forty percent correlation. 9, 14, 19 If you are related to someone who is an addict or was an addict you have a forty percent chance of becoming one yourself.  But one of the things some of this research is talking about is this kind of shield, and this is kind of like the epigenetic idea of the switch, and they are trying to understand why some of us are so susceptible to addiction and other people just aren’t. 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 16, 17 The analogy he used was a shield: we all come into the world with a shield, but some of us have a really thick shield. 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 Things can happen to us that don’t prompt addiction. 12 Other people come into the world with a much thinner shield and it is very easy for that shield to be penetrated. 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 That to me puts together all of the things we have been learning about and that we have talked about, you and I, and in our group. 10, 11, 12, 16 It is a shield. 14 What we give to our children and what they get from the world and what they get genetically and experientially, who they come into the world as with their own personalities. 6, 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 I think that shield metaphor really makes sense to me and it fits with Maté’s thing about how trauma can create a tendency towards addiction. 5, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17 What’s interesting though is what the addiction really does is it tries to thicken your shield. 9, 14, 19 AS: You try to protect yourself, which is ironic. 16 NE: It is so ironic.  AS: The very thing that makes you feel safer is actually killing you. 7, 10, 16 NE: Right.  They do say that people who really do struggle with addiction are heightened. 9, 15 They are more sensitive. 13 They are thin skinned that way. 16 AS: And often don’t feel at peace in their body or in the world. 12, 15, 16 NE: That was Lucas.  AS: I think we know a lot of kids like that. 13, 14, 15, 17 This very, very sensitive -- where you could touch and it could feel like a punch. 13, 15, 16 Also, Lucas, I may have mentioned this to you, had a lot of neural sensitivity. 13, 17 As a kid he would say, “Get this shirt off of me.”  “It is itchy and uncomfortable.”  He was heightened. 15 “I don’t like this sock. 10 It doesn’t fit me right.” 14 You know? 13, 14, 15 He had neuro stuff, body stuff that was sensitive to whatever it is. 9, 13 That’s what this doctor was saying. 11 He said your brain is completely rewired from opiate use. 9, 12, 14, 19 AS: Levy said that the other night. 19 He said there are parts of his brain that will never heal from his own drug use. 9, 14, 15 NE: They have found, I’m sure you’ve heard this, in mice -- have you heard this about mice and cocaine? 15 Mice who became highly addicted to cocaine they found a place in their brain that they can zap. 5, 8, 11, 19 They zap it and they put the mice back in the cage with mounds of cocaine and they won’t go near it. 10, 19 That is what they are trying to isolate and identify in humans. 16 Neuroscientists at the University [of Minnesota] are studying the brain and addiction. 9, 13 I said, “How close are you?”  He said, “We are closer, but we are still very far away. 9, 16 There are different transmitters for triggers, cravings, and memory. 7, 16, 17 Even though you can get control of one the triggers still remain. 9, 17 It’s not like the cravings ever fully go away. 10, 11, 16 We are trying to study the exact part of the brain where the cravings, triggers, and memory come together. 9, 10, 13, 16, 19 Mice don’t have a complex brain so we were able to identify the craving or the addiction part.”  That is what they are trying to understand: what actually happens to the brain. 9, 10, 12, 16 What gets rewired and what gets activated. 10, 12 Certain parts of the brain get turned off. 19 Look, we hear a song and we think of our boyfriend from four hundred years ago. 12, 20 [laughs]  We smell something and I go, “Oh my god, that smells like camp.” 8, 10 We hear a noise and think of our crazy father. 5, 16 People say, “That reminds me of my father when he went to work.” 5 You go immediately to fight or flight.  AS: I think those are things that -- the song you are waking up with everyday, the songs that are coming back to you as part of that memory bank. 16, 19 It is healing you, it is coming back, it is flooding you with memories that will comfort you in some way. 16, 19 It seems like it is part of the grieving process. 16, 19 NE: It may be part of the grieving process, but it doesn’t comfort me.  It makes me sob non-stop. 9, 10, 16 AS: I don’t mean -- just some things become alive again. 9, 12, 13, 16, 19 NE: Yes.  AS: This happens to me in yoga or something when you aren’t thinking of anything and suddenly something pops in your head and you are like, Where did that come from? 10, 12, 13, 19 Just some random memory. 7, 9 NE: It has been resonating.  That is the interesting thing about epigenetics. 9, 19 Is everything really stored on a cellular level? 5, 7, 9, 12, 20 AS: And maybe a lot is stored that is never really needed or accessed. 5, 6, 9, 12, 13, 15, 17 The shield idea. 11, 14 If you don’t ever come upon drugs if you had a thin shield it might not matter. 13, 14, 19, 20 It just seems so random. 7, 9, 12, 16, 19 What Maté was talking about with grandchildren of Holocaust survivors. 7, 9, 10, 14 Why do they have these high levels of depression? 8, 20 I also know the parents of those people and the parents were the children of the people. 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 They have such heightened levels of anxiety. 15, 20 For one woman if there was less than one gallon of milk in the house she would have a complete nervous breakdown. 6, 9, 16, 18, 19 She would always have to have two gallons in the house just in case they ever ran out. 6, 7, 9, 12, 16, 17 She was anxious; the kids end up with depression. 12 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 AS: You came back and you had the memorial service, which was so beautiful. 6, 19 NE: I haven’t listened yet. 9, 15, 17 That’s what happened. 12, 13 I went into action. 10 AS: That shielded you for a while. 14 NE: It shielded me. 14 It kept me in shock.  AS: I think we stay in shock for a while after trauma like that. 9 NE: I had other friends that came out. 12, 18, 19 I went to New York.  I have these silos, these different compartments of emotion. 16, 17 It’s like that jack-in-the-box.  They come up and go, “Ah!” 13, 19 And the other one comes up and goes, “Ah!” 13, 19 All of them are very different than what I want to have in my heart, which is compassion, and understanding, and adoration, and love for Lucas. 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 But I have so many other things going on right now. 14, 16 I don’t like that. 10 AS: Like what?  NE: Like, “Why did you come here?” 13, 19 I feel tortured. 12, 16 I do, I feel very beat up. 16 In that Nar Anon room people say, “My child is coming back to me, they were who they were.” 7, 19 Lucas was tough from day one. 18, 19 He wasn’t an angelic, perfect little kid.  What he had was what he had, so naturally had everything going for him.  He had a lot of rage and a lot of anger. 17 Last night that’s all I could feel in my head. 9, 16, 19 All of it banging in my walls, telling me where to go, the stealing, the apologies, and then the stealing. 9, 10 You might have been there when I said my therapist in New York said, “Nancy, love is a verb.” 6, 9, 13 When I remember that I feel really bad, too. 16 NE: Because Lucas told me all the time how much he loved me. 13, 18, 20 But he acted contrary to that very often, and before he did drugs he was tough. 10, 12, 14, 15, 18 I was really a single parent. 10, 15, 16 AS: You loved him. 13 Does the rage make you feel like you didn’t love him enough? 13, 16, 20 NE: You know Amy, the rage was tough. 13, 14, 15, 18 AS: Can you hold those two things together: the love and the rage? 13, 16, 20 Or does that not feel -- NE: I think it was safer to have those two things when he was alive. 16 He made it hard to love him sometimes. 5, 11, 13, 16, 18 Sometimes I felt like I didn’t love him at all. 5, 13, 17, 18 There were times that I thought if he wasn’t my child I would want nothing to do with this person. 11, 12, 13, 18 They don’t feed my soul.  There is no give and take here. 6 There is no gentle kindness consistently. 9, 11, 15, 16, 17 Who I am and what I am going through doesn’t matter. 20 I’m left with a lot of output. 10, 17 There was so much output. 10, 18 AS: You were feeling empty. 16 NE: I’m empty.  I feel empty and left. 16 Some people say, “Things were so good for a month or two years or five years and then they relapsed,” but they had a period of time where there was rejuvenation. 8, 18, 20 Sort of a resurrection of a healthy relationship. 14, 18 NE: No, never. 15 Lucas walked out of the first rehab and bought drugs. 7, 9, 14, 17, 19 The second one I went down there and left early because he was doing drugs. 14, 20 The one at Hazelden -- he walked out and did drugs. 14, 17 He never really got sober I don’t think. 6, 15 AS: Would he tell you that he was sober? 6 AS: Was his dishonesty part of the rage, too? 9 Was it all just mushed together? 9, 12 NE: That’s an interesting question. 6, 9, 19 Now that you say that maybe that’s why I feel so left because he didn’t leave me with any truth. 6, 9, 16 If he would have told me he was struggling -- I feel used. 9, 16, 20 I was the one he called all the time. 7 I was the one who heard it all, but I didn’t hear the truth. 15 I was trying to help somebody who was being completely dishonest. 9, 13, 14, 16, 19 And he was counting on me, calling me, and expecting me to be there. 7 And I was for years. 20 And he wasn’t even standing on his face. 9, 12, 15 You know when they say ‘standing on your mat?’ 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 He wasn’t even standing on his mat. 9, 12, 15 He was lying.  He was not true.  Even when I asked him. 10 Even when I said, “Lucas, you are high as a kite right now.” 8, 14 “Okay, mom.” 15 AS: You never got any acknowledgement that you knew what was going on from him either. 6, 12, 13, 14, 15 That would make me enraged. 16 NE: That’s why I think I almost had a nervous breakdown in October. 9, 16, 18 I said, “Do you think I’m a freaking idiot?  Look at you!  What do you think I’m seeing!”  It is crazy making. 16 It’s like having a sociopath in front of you. 14 AS: I don’t know any sociopaths, but it might be worse. 13, 14, 15 Someone who is trying to make you crazy. 16 NE: I started to feel crazy. 9, 11, 16 I am watching, listening there and, “You don’t know what you’re talking about.” 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 17 AS: Right.  Slurring his words and nodding off.  NE: Completely. 19 Maybe that’s it.  Maybe all the work -- AS: With no acknowledgement of the truth of what was happening. 12, 13, 14, 15 NE: Why put me through that? 10 Why count on me that way? 16 Why make me privy to all of your misery, your heartache, your suffering. 16 So I should suffer, too?  And I suffered, and he knew it. 6, 12 When I came home from that trip he called me. 7, 19 He said, “I’m glad you broke down.”  I said, “You’re glad I broke down?”  He said, “Yeah, because you had all of that stored inside of you and you really needed to let it out.” 5, 9, 12, 13, 19 He didn’t say because it was legitimate, he didn’t say, “Because I’m using heroin.”  He didn’t say, “Because I need help.” 13 Maybe that’s it, or a big piece of it. 8 AS: I don’t know anyone who would deny you the right to feel angry in this situation. 13, 14, 15, 16 Even with the great loss and sadness. 11, 12 The anger about addiction and what it does to people is completely justifiable. 9, 12, 14, 19 NE: And as I said he was not easy or the most honest person to begin with. 9 This just exacerbated an already obvious tendency. 9, 12, 15 I wanted him to plop himself on that chair and say, “I’m going to make it all up to you.” 12, 13, 16 The way he used to say. 9, 16 “I’m going to show up and I’m going to be the son you want me to be and the son I want to be for you.” 13 Okay, well you know what? 13, 14, 15 You took that away too. 16 My head goes to that spiritual side.  Lucas and I were meant to be together and this happened for a reason and I do go there. 12, 13, 16 Even though my faith is in the garbage right now I still have that sense of myself and know this was for something and it wasn’t for nothing. 9, 13, 14, 15, 17 There is a woman who is in my grief group who is also in our Nar Anon group, and the other day she said, “I feel so peaceful.” 16, 19 I’m like, “Really?” 10 She’s way ahead of me in this game of time, but she said, “Every day I wake up I know I am closer to seeing my son again.” 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 I’m going, “Really?  Every day I get up my son goes farther from me.” 19 The juxtaposition of those two thoughts. 11, 12, 13 She’s happier than me.  She’s finding peace.  Not peace, but that’s the way she holds it. 16, 20 I have too much rage right now. 14, 18 I did speak to a medium, I should tell you.  Yesterday. 9, 19 She told me that Lucas was really good, and that made me really angry. 16, 20 He’s good and I’m sitting here miserable, suffering. 13 She said what another psychic said to me in October: Lucas was not from this earth plane. 13 He could not find his way on it. 16 He came in like a warrior and was never comfortable or safe here. 15, 19 But that didn’t help me. 13 She said, “Are there a bunch of people that he knew?” 6, 9, 12 I said, “Yeah, he lost a bunch of friends.” 9, 12, 18 “They are all doing this Buddha chanting and talking about what they did.” 10 Because he lost a lot of friends to addiction. 9, 12, 17, 18 She said it was with a bunch of people. 9 She asked who the Russians were around him, and I said it was my grandparents. 7, 8, 10, 16 My mother’s parents. 10, 16 I don’t know if it was them or not, but she said he was good. 13, 14, 15 It didn’t help. 13 I wish it did.  I want him to be peaceful. 13 AS: You want to be peaceful. 13 Being his mother I want him to be peaceful first. 9, 13 She says he is.  AS: But you just said it didn’t help. 9, 12, 13 NE: It doesn’t, but I wish it for him.  It doesn’t yet, maybe it will. 9 I don’t know, Amy. 13, 14, 15 I never thought at sixty-one I would be facing my parents who are eighty-nine, my sister who has leukemia, my dog who is fifteen, and not have Lucas. 5, 9, 10, 11, 12, 15, 16 And not have a mate.  Time will tell.  Was this what you wanted? 12, 13 AS: I have another question. 6, 9 I wondered about the follow-up to when you had his phone and you told me you called the number he had been calling. 7, 12, 20 Did anything ever come of a drug dealer or anything in LA? 13, 14, 19 I tell you he got a text?  It said, “Got Roxy?”  I called the Santa Monica police. 7 That was the second time I spoke to the Santa Monica police. 7, 19, 20 They asked for Lucas’s phone number. 7, 10 I think they were trying to pin people. 16 I don’t know what happened; I never heard from them. 12, 13, 14, 15 I was very tempted to follow up with them. 12 There was a woman there -- I know who she is through these texts. 13, 14, 15 She said, “You’ve got to get off drugs.” 14 But then she was giving him drugs and is an addict herself. 11, 14 I said, “You could call about Cat.” 7 AS: Is that her name? 6 NE: Her nickname or something. 6, 8 I went, I don’t know if I want to put my energy here. 10, 13, 14, 15 AS: Someone said you could call and report her? 7 NE: The sergeant from the narcotics bureau said, “Call me anytime.” 15 I didn’t want to spend my energy there. 12, 13, 19 I was going through emails and everything and I never heard back from them. 15, 19 California is different from Minnesota, too. 16, 17 They go after the dealers much more actively here. 10, 13, 18 No, nothing was put to rest. 9, 10, 19 I see what Sam is going through.  Now they changed the court date. 16 The defense attorney now is trying to separate all the cases. 14, 16 Of course he is.  He is working on behalf of his client. 20 If they find something out and they let us know, great. 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 I told them I want to know. 13, 14, 15, 20 I don’t want to go fishing. 13 AS: Yeah, you don’t want to dig through all of his stuff. 9, 13 NE: I have it all on his phone and his computer. 7, 10 I have stayed away right now. 5, 9, 14, 16 I look through the texts.  There are over two thousand I have to read.  I said, No, Nancy.  You have your whole life to read this stuff. 9, 11 Some of it is really going to hurt you.  He was suffering.  The night he died he was really suffering. 19 I saw those texts.  He was vomiting profusely; he was very sick. 9 That’s horrible to learn. 12, 17 It’s such a crazy thing. 16 I think about the Nar Anon group and I think it is a beautiful thing that I can show up there and other people that have lost their child. 6, 9 AS: How is your grief group doing for you?  NE: It only meets once a month. 8, 13 I have a grief therapist that I started with and I see once a week that I like a lot. 6, 9, 10, 11, 17 Even the grief group is a little hard for me because people are talking about their gratitude. 10, 11 And I’m the only one with an only child.  AS: That would make a big difference I would think. 8, 16 My cabin is empty.  I don’t know what I am going to do. 13, 14, 15 I am proceeding with Facing Addiction; I’m proceeding with Cardboard House. 5, 9 AS: What are you doing with Facing Addiction?  What are your thoughts on that and why that group? 11, 12 NE: I don’t really know yet what I’m doing with them other than I’m collaborating on different things. 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 I’m trying to formalize in my head what I’m trying to do with them and find out what they want to do with me. 13, 16, 17 I don’t really know where we tie the bow. 13, 14, 15"
"7","Coleman_Brandon","Nancy Espuche Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 5, 2016 St. Paul, Minnesota  AS: Alright, this is Amy Sullivan. 14 I am recording an interview with Nancy Espuche, did I say your name right? 6, 14 E-S-P-U-C-H-E. in her apartment in St. Paul on June 5th, 2016. 20 Nancy, will you state your name and your address and then that you give me permission? 6, 9, 14 NE: My name is Nancy 6 Espuche, I live in St. Paul.  I give Amy permission to record and document any way she like, whatever it is we talk about today. 6, 10, 16, 19 AS: Thank you.  NE: You’re welcome. 13, 19 AS: Okay can you tell me a little bit about yourself and where you grew up, your childhood, family, your education? 10, 11, 18 NE: I grew up in Long Island, New York. 8 We originally lived in a place called Great Neck, if anyone is familiar. 7, 11 I am the youngest of two daughters, I have an older sister Lisa who actually turned 63 on Thursday. 5, 9, 10, 14, 19, 20 I am 60, she is two and a half years older than me. 5, 20 We then moved to Jericho, Long Island. 8 My dad was an educator, he was a teacher, and then became a principal in what is known as Bedford-Stuyvesant, a very tough area of Brooklyn and was pretty beloved, and is still a pretty beloved man. 5, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 He ran summer camps for [unclear] every summer, a sleep away camp for kids five months old until twenty. 7, 8, 16, 20 I think it was there that I really learned who my dad was and learned to appreciate him and my sister and different aspects of her being. 5, 9, 12, 16, 17 I had a tough mom; pretty critical, pretty, you know it’s her way or the highway, not nurturing in any capacity. 8, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 20 I’ve learned a lot about her life which was pretty traumatic too. 11, 12, 17, 18 My development as a person really circled around the need for good mothering. 13, 16 As my sister and I both say, we raised ourselves. 5, 9 She did it very differently than I did. 16, 17 My sister now has leukemia, and we are watching that. 5, 9, 14 If it wasn’t for my dad, who is kind and thoughtful and nurturing to a degree, I think life would have been very different for me. 11, 12, 16, 17, 20 I went to school… 8 do you want more? 13 AS: Yeah, keep going. 12 NE: I graduated from Stony Brook University with a psychology degree. 8, 13, 20 I did start my masters at Hunter College in New York City. 9, 11, 20 I was married at the time very briefly to someone I went to highschool with and he became an abusive husband, and I was lucky now thanks to him to get out of the marriage really quickly after a year, and then proceed with my studies. 5, 8, 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19, 20 Then, I got a job that I was at for 31 years on. 20 Moved forward, met my husband when I was 31. 5, 9, 15 We have a funny story that I will reserve not for here [laughter]. 9 Raymond is from France, he was visiting New York at the time. 7, 12, 13 We ended up getting married shortly after, and we were married for 20 years. 12, 16, 20 I am divorced now for eight. 5, 14 We had Lucas when I was just 35, I had just turned 35. 9, 12, 19 Mothering was the one thing that I was desperate to do then in my life. 11 AS: When do you remember having that feeling? 16 NE: Yeah, very young. 14 AS: Before you had a child?  NE: Yes.  I really wanted to be a mother. 12, 13 I really wanted to be a good mother. 12, 13 A nurturing mother, an available mother [laughter].  AS: How was your experience mothering when it actually happened at first. 9, 10, 12, 13 NE: Well, Lucas was a sick child.  So it tainted everything.  We didn’t know it at the time, but at three months old Lucas was a very collicky baby. 5, 8, 13, 14, 15, 20 We now can contribute that to his illness, we just thought he was collicky at the time. 9, 11, 12, 14 But, at the age of about three months, and I was nervous, I was a nervous mom at the beginning, when he was making noise about because he cried so often. 8, 12, 15, 16 And at about three months Lucas started to throw up for a couple of hours, but it started to happen pretty regularly, once a week, but continued to increase over the course of time. 8, 9, 11, 12, 18 We then realized after, you know, he was in and out of the doctors and the doctors kept saying it was stomach flu. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15 And I said, “this isn’t the stomach flu.” 9 I don’t remember exactly when it happened but about a year in a half we rushed him to the hospital. 10, 12, 13, 20 They thought he had twisted intestines, but they couldn’t even get him off of me because he was clinging like a monkey. 9, 11, 12, 15 He calmed down and we went home but that accelerated pretty rapidly my... his dad was in the restaurant business and he wasn’t home evenings and weekends so I was really left to Lucas’ illness, or what became an illness, and it was horrifying because I didn’t know what was happening and he would be up for hours screaming in pain. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 Finally, after I don’t know how long it took we changed doctors, but Lucas was about three. 13, 14, 15, 16 We rushed him up to the hospital.  He had been vomiting profusely for hours and was really sort of out cold in my arms. 9, 11, 17, 20 The surgeon that came in at the time, the pediatric doctor on call, of course won’t look at a baby without getting all the bloodwork done, and realized that all of Lucas’ pancreatic enzymes were off the charts and that he was suffering from pancreatitis. 5, 7, 11, 14, 19 And the only reason my baby would ever have pancreatitis is they have a pancreatic tumor or something pretty deadly. 5, 18 So, that’s when the reality of what we were facing really took hold. 20 From that point forward Lucas was, every week, monitored, blood tests, sonograms, restricted with food, knocked out for six hours with other tests, it was constant; insane. 9, 11, 12, 19 It was a week, it was in January, one month shy of his fourth birthday they ended up doing an endoscopy because something was really obvious. 8, 12, 19, 20 They hadn’t done one, and they found what the surgeon always thought was the case with Lukey. 11, 12, 16, 17 He had a cyst called choledocal [unclear] cyst it was common bile duct. 7, 9 A congenital cyst between the gallbladder and the liver and he couldn’t digest any of his food. 9 He had probably been struggling with pancreatitis from the day he was born. 9, 19 So, he went in and they said once it burst it would be gone. 9, 19 And from that point forward... 9 he had surgery for 7 hours, he was cut pretty open, they also removed his gallbladder. 8, 11, 17, 18 We thought he would be in the hospital for 14 days but, I think this is one of the most telling and most important things to note, when he woke up with tubes everywhere, because he had a bag at the time, I went down to bend down to kiss him and the surgeon was there and with all his might he took his hand and he slapped me in the face and said, “Stupid mommy, stupid mommy.” 9, 11, 12, 15, 16, 19 And the surgeon pulled me and Raymond out.  AS: Who slapped you?  NE: Lucas.  The surgeon said, “I want you to hear me. 13 Children who have this kind of medical trauma, an intervention from birth, grow up with rage, anger, inability to listen to adults. 9, 14, 15, 16, 17 You need to get him into therapy as soon as you can.” 13 AS: Wow.  NE: And we got home and I don’t know who Lucas would have been. 13, 14, 15, 19 Maybe he would have been the same, but he apparently became really belligerent, hostile, tough. 5, 9, 10, 16, 18, 19 Really tough. 18 AS: Just as the doctor had… 9 NE: Yes.  And then he had more medical problems. 14 They thought he had turrets, he started to tick terribly and we were running everywhere. 7, 9, 11, 12 It ended up he had what’s called PANDAS which is from all the stress that he had. 7, 9, 12 There is a correlation now between stress and ticks and it looks like turrets. 9, 14 So then he had his tonsils and thyroids out and was in the hospital again.  Then after that, he was hit in the head in kindergarten and was knocked out for twelve hours with a severe concussion. 11, 15, 16, 17 AS: My goodness.  NE: Then after all of that I got very sick, and he watched me because my autoimmune system just went berserk. 8, 9, 12, 17 So I got very sick for five years and was rushed to the hospital for at least once a week and he would witness that and it was for trauma. 9, 20 So to answer your question in a very long way, motherhood for me from the very beginning was all about crisis. 6, 9, 16 From birth, it was crisis after crisis.  And, it was difficult from day one. 19, 20 AS: Did you feel supported by your husband? 15, 16 NE: Not enough. 20 AS: Were you working full time? 11 NE: Yes.  Now, neither of us could sleep in the middle of the night, when either I needed to get to the hospital for myself because that’s when my problem really would occur, I would wake up and my tongue would be this big. 7, 8, 13, 19 Or, Lucas was not well.  And there was no waking Raymond up.  “Leave me alone, I need to sleep.” 7, 13 So I was pretty exhausted, I was working pretty… 9, 18 ten hour days and, with Luke all night and on weekends. 12, 19 AS: Would it be fair to say you were... you raised Lucas on your own? 5 NE: Yes, it would be.  AS: A single mother with a man in the house. 6, 9, 15 NE: Yes.  In many instances. 9 AS: Yes.  NE: Yes.  He didn’t take an active role with… 6, 10 Lucas was a remarkable athlete. 19 He was like a superstar kid. 9, 12 He is so bright, beyond bright. 14 And, he got into remarkable schools and ended up at the University of Miami and he wanted to go there because they had a good business school. 8, 9, 12, 13 He was a super-star athlete, he couldn’t play nice in the sandbox, but he was recognized for his academics and athleticism. 9, 12, 19 He played for the Junior Olympics... but Raymond is an artist. 8, 9 And Lucas is an all-American kid.  AS: Right.  NE: I was a sports junkie [laughter].  And we were very tight, and we still are. 9 I am really Lucas’ go to.  I’m his universe.  I don’t want to be his universe. 13 I want to be his mother. 13 AS: Interesting. 9, 19 NE: But not his universe.  AS: Do you think you played a part in that? 8 NE: I think I did.  I don’t think I’d do is... play the same role to the degree which I had. 20 But, the habit has been formed. 17 AS: Can you back up and tell me when Lucas was born, what his birthday is? 19 NE: February 18, 1991.  NE: He started experimenting very early. 9, 11 AS: Yes, let’s move on to drugs. 14, 19 NE: You know, he was a risk taker. 6, 13, 14, 15 Lucas was a really big risk taker. 6, 8 I remember at a birthday party he was dared and the police showed up. 6, 7, 12, 19 Nobody knew why, and they said someone from this location called the police. 6, 7, 10, 12 The kids had dared Lucas to call the police and say there was an emergency, and he did [laughter]. 7, 12 I almost had a heart attack, but he said… 9 AS: Wow.  NE: He was a daring kid.  And he had a lot of anger. 17 A lot of anger. 17 We tried therapist after therapist. 6, 9, 10 AS: So beginning from…  AS: What point…  Four years old? 20 NE: People, therapists would say to me, you can’t break him. 18 He’s not breakable right now. 14, 18 AS: What did they mean by that? 16 they couldn’t get into him, into his heart and his head.  AS: They couldn’t reach him NE: They couldn’t reach him. 13 He had such a wall built from all this trauma.  The only thing that Lucas would say is that he felt really different: “Why me?” is still, or, “Why are you doing this to me?” 9, 16, 17 is still a line he uses to this day. 6, 9, 19 And, it was what he said from the minute he could talk. 10 “Why are you doing this to me, mommy?” with his bellyache. 15 AS: Oh, because, oh right. 14 NE: ...Why are you doing this to me after his surgery.  AS: ...his physical problems, he connected those with you, and with other people being in charge of his body and mind. 17, 18 And to this day, when he is blue, or even when I was putting him in rehab, “Why are