urring, I had never heard him like this. 15 And he said “I’m really tired” and I said, “Lucy, what is going on in that room. 7, 12 He’s not tired.” 12 And then I spoke to the girl. 19 And I said, “You are not to leave my house. 6, 9 I want to know what you both took.” 13, 14, 15 And they said nothing.  And I said, “Well here is the deal I’m in New York City and you are not to leave the house I’m calling the police.” 6, 7, 9, 13 Because at that point Lucas had fallen asleep. 7 I called the police, the ambulance showed up. 7 Both of them at this point were out.  They were driven to the hospital, I called my friend…. with the ambulance at my house. 6, 7, 9, 12, 14 I was working.  I was able to get back to the Island. 8, 19 By the time I got to the hospital, a couple of my friends were there. 12, 18 Lucas had Xanax, alcohol, cocaine, and marijuana in his system. 8, 9 The girl who was really in big trouble, I don’t know how she was talking to me, the way she was at first because he was the one who sounded really bad. 8, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 It was awful because when he woke up he was awful to me. 10 Disgusting. 9 And we had somebody come to the house then that wanted to take him away, you know, like… 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 AS: To a residential treatment? 9, 16 NE: And Lucas was leaving three weeks later because he had gotten to an exceptional program in London, for the summer, at a bank. 15, 19 And Raymond and I were very conflicted.  Raymond wanted to send him and I didn’t. 12, 13 AS: Send him where? 12 NE: To London.  Let him go to London.  AS: Instead of to treatment. 9, 16 NE: And he went to London.  AS: Was he 16 at this time?  NE: Eleventh grade, 16 I guess. 10, 15, 20 Then, it was twelfth grade. 20 He was never home. 15, 19 He was getting high all the time i didn’t know what he was doing. 8, 13, 14, 15 A week before he was leaving for college 8, 19 I got a call that he was in jail for a DWI. 7 He was completely stoned out when we showed up to court on X