 video that a couple of citizens here linked up with an LA producer/director. 14 And, they made a video and they kind of let people know they were here, but there was no supervision and no ethical contact. 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 And, it turned out that the choice of the director and producer were to present things out of context in a very hurtful way. 7, 14, 16, 17, 19 That really hurt the community of Pine Point [unclear].  I think I did hear about this... CG: ...and our citizens.  And so, I don't recommend that you watch it. 12 Except, that yes in a way I do. 14, 16 It talks about issues you're concerned about AS: What was it called—the seven fires? 7, 10, 14, 15 CG: It's called The Seventh Fire. 7, 15 And yes, you should watch it. 14 But, when you watch it you need to understand that's what should not be done, because it hurt a lot of people here. 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 And, the tribal council was upset and the community council at Pine Point was upset, and they tried to contact the producer and director, and they sort of blew it all off. 10, 11, 14, 17, 19 And said, ""We can do whatever the 'eff' we want."" 13 So, there's been a groundswell movement here to try to develop some ethical way to instruct interviewers, writers, filmographers... about the ethics of presenting a contextually respectful story about White Earth when it's done. 6, 7, 8, 9, 16 And, that doesn't mean we don't want you to tell the truth. 13, 16 The basic ideas in that video about drug abuse issues and generational trauma and adverse childhood experiences certainly are grounded in fact. 8, 9, 10, 11, 14, 15 They do happen, but the whole video presented things out of context in a quite hurtful way. 7, 12, 16 And the two individuals, neither of whom live here anymore and didn’t at the time that was made, are felt to have opportunistically taken advantage of their having lived here to make that video. 6, 7, 9, 13, 16, 17 So, that isn't why you're here, and it may not have anything directly to