"9","Devich_Stephanie","Janise Holter Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 14, 2016 St. Paul, Minnesota Janise Holter-JH Amy Sullivan-AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan having an interview with Janise Holter on June 14th, 2016. 6 Janise, will you state your name and address and say you give permission for recording to be used? 6, 9, 14 My name is Janise Holter. 6 I give permission for Amy Sullivan to use all the contents of this interview. 6, 9, 15 AS: Thank you.  Could you tell me a little bit about your upbringing, aspects of your childhood that formed who you are, and a bit about your education and career? 7, 10, 11, 17 Whatever you say is totally fine and whatever direction you go off in is fine. 14, 17 If I want to bring you back I will bring you back. 13, 19 JH: Okay, perfect.  I’ll remind you to bring me back if I get too tangential.  [laughs]  Well, I grew up about two miles from where I live now, which is in Crystal, Minnesota. 9, 14 My parents were very young. 10, 14, 16 My mother was seventeen when she had my sister and nineteen when she had me. 5, 9, 15 My dad, we later discovered, suffered from bipolar. 12 He had a lot of bouts of depression growing up, so that was a pretty clear memory of dealing with his quietude or quietness. 13, 17, 18 My mother came from a family of ten and was very connected to her family. 18, 19 They were southern baptists. 7, 9 My grandma was from the South; my grandpa was from Sweden. 6, 7 So, I had a lot of cousins, went to church a lot, loved going to church. 5, 13, 17 Loved being in the really vibrant community. 7 I admit we got a little too vibrant and my mother left before I was baptized. 7 My sister was dumped and I was not because my mother left the church. 5, 9 We got a minister that was actually from Mississippi. 9, 10 He was a little bit too much of what the church was, so my mom left. 15, 18 We stopped going to church when I was thirteen. 9, 10, 20 I was kind of an odd kid. 16, 17 I was in the middle. 8 I have an older sister, younger brother. 5, 9, 14, 20 My parents were married to each other three times. 10, 16, 18 They divorced and married to each other three times in my childhood. 5, 11, 18 So there were periods of time when my parents didn’t live together. 10, 16 I have an older sister who is breathtakingly gorgeous. 5, 9, 20 So, that was an interesting thing to be second to. 9, 19, 20 She was very, very beautiful. 6 I have a younger brother who is four years younger than I am and he actually had an episode when he was twelve where he tried to commit suicide and was hospitalized for a number of months. 5, 8, 10, 14, 20 My mother chalked it up to him having a concussion, but there was clearly some mental illness or something going on with him. 14 My parents owned a store, and I worked in the store. 5, 9, 10, 16 My mom is a folk artist. 9, 15 She paints scandinavian folk art [laughs]. 8 She owned a craft store. 5, 9 She got into that and bought a store in Osseo, Minnesota. 5, 7, 9 Small, little store, and I worked in her store with my dad. 5, 9 I worked in her store from the time I was fourteen until I was in eleventh grade. 5, 9, 15, 20 I got a job at a nursing home, and worked at the nursing home for the rest of my high school career. 7, 8, 9, 11, 19 I worked with my parents and I helped my mom teach classes. 8, 10, 13, 15, 16, 20 She taught a lot of classes in different types of folk painting and ceramics. 8, 16, 17, 20 She was very crafty.  So, middle class. 8, 20 My dad worked for the highway department until the store kind of started to make some money—he decided to quit the highway department, and he worked at the store and helped my mom. 5, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17 My parents finally got divorced for the third or fourth time depending on how you count it, when I was thirty! 5, 10, 12, 16, 20 [laughs]  I always thought of the Woody 11, 12, 16, 17 Allen line: “My parents got divorced, or stayed married even though we begged them not to.” 5, 6, 9, 10, 15, 16 That’s how I felt when my parents finally got divorced because my dad was clearly mentally ill and my mom was keeping it together and they were both being pulled down a hole that was not good for either of them. 5, 10, 11, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17 So, once they divorced, my dad just progressively got more and more—cycles of depression and mania and addiction. 5, 9, 12 He was diabetic, and he had heart attacks.  He didn’t keep taking care of himself. 7, 12 He died at seventy-two.  My mother remarried a guy who was as mentally ill as my father, but the other end of the spectrum. 5, 12, 14 Very, very, religious, fundamental religious. 14 My dad was funny, and bigger than life, and sloppy, and everything, you know, was just sloppy. 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 And my mother married this guy that is very rigid, and very neat, and very religious.  She has been married to him for about sixteen years. 20 She is very religious, very fundamental, very right-wing, very judgmental. 14 My parents were very hands-off. 10, 16 That was how I was parented. 6, 10, 16 I mean, maybe it was the time or maybe it was because they were young. 9, 14, 16 My mom was thirty-eight when I graduated from high school. 8, 15 We just did whatever. 9, 12 I remember playing softball and my parents never came to the softball games. 8, 10, 15, 16, 19 They worked at their store all the time. 5, 9 There was no discussion ever that I would go to college. 8 Never was it even considered that we would go to college. 8, 12, 15 Neither of my parents were college educated. 8, 10, 16 AS: How did you end up going to college? 8, 12 I got out of school and I worked for a couple of years. 8, 20 I started off by going to community college and paying for it all out of pocket. 8, 9, 11, 16 My first round in college was all out of pocket. 8, 9 I always worked full time. 11, 16, 17 I went to school, I worked full-time, and paid all my tuition out of pocket because I was raised that you did not go into debt. 5, 8, 11 My dad was German, and that’s stereotypical German frugality. 9 You don’t go into debt.  You don’t go into debt for education. 10 You go into debt for a house, but education is not worth going into debt for. 6, 9, 10 It wasn’t outwardly said, but it was definitely an attitude that, you know, I would go to college and my parents would be like, “Do you know what you’re going to do? 8, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 They had to see the ends. 12 In my family I am the only college educated child. 8, 10, 18 They had a really interesting reaction when I stopped going to school to be an accountant and decided that cultural anthropology was what I was going to study. 8, 9, 10, 12, 19, 20 [laughs]  That was interesting. 9, 19 My mom could not get it right, the whole, you know, whatever turned out being over four years I was in school. 8, 13, 14, 15, 19, 20 She kept telling people I was going to school to be an archaeologist. 8, 9 I had to just let it go. 9, 12, 19 So that was not a value in my family. 18 In school I did really well. 8 I mean it was valued that I did well in school, but my parents were really hands-off. 8, 10, 16 I want to come back a little bit because I had my own addiction issues in high school. 8, 13, 14, 15, 19 The first two weeks of my tenth grade year, one of my very good friends committed suicide, and that was a very difficult thing for me. 9, 12, 15, 18, 20 I started using a lot of speed to go to school, and smoking a lot of pot. 8, 9, 11, 17 Everybody smoked pot, but I started smoking a lot of pot. 9, 11, 17 Like smoking pot on my way to school. 8, 16 My parents didn’t know how to address this. 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 I didn’t know how to address this. 13, 14, 15 I was fifteen and I had had this really close person—it was the first person, yeah I guess it was the first person that died. 9, 10 It was a person my same age.  It turns out that it was probably because he was gay. 19 I had glimpses of that and I kind of knew that, but it was 1976. 6, 12, 16, 17 It was forty years ago. 20 It was not a part of what you told people. 20 But you knew, and anyways he committed suicide. 6, 12, 16, 17 I responded to that by using drugs and started smoking cigarettes. 9, 11, 14 My biggest lifelong addiction was with nicotine. 8, 9, 11 My parents were both smokers too. 10, 16 My grandfather was a very serious alcoholic. 5, 7 Many of my uncles were alcoholics. 5 I later had an uncle that committed suicide.  So there was a lot of denied mental health issues in my dad’s family. 14, 15, 17, 18 If that wasn’t a family of people who suffered from serious depression—it was a dark and gloomy family. 12, 18 My senior year in high school I kept fairly decent grades, but I smoked a lot of pot, took a lot of speed, took a lot of speed. 8, 17, 20 That was my drug of choice just because it was, you know, it wasn’t a depressant. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 17 I think I was probably depressed and that was how I dealt with my depression. 12, 13 When I would talk to my parents about how depressed I was it was kind of a “get over it” kind of thing. 10, 12, 16, 17 It was: “You know it has been two years since this person died. 13, 14, 15, 20 You need to get over it.” 13 AS: Did you ever go to treatment of any kind? 9, 16, 17 How did you end up managing your— JH: 12 My addiction?  AS: Or ending your drug use? 9, 12, 14 I started getting serious migraines when I was seventeen. 9, 11, 15 I thought I was killing myself. 7, 11, 12 I thought it was all the speed I was taking that was causing this to happen. 11, 12 It scared the shit out of me. 5, 7, 11, 12 AS: It scared you. 5, 7, 11, 12 It scared the shit out of me. 5, 7, 11, 12 Because I was having all these weird things going on and I thought, “Oh my god, I am going to die.” 10, 11, 12, 16 AS: Like those aura things? 16 JH: Not aural, but yeah. 10 My fingers would go numb and stuff like that. 9 It was all coinciding with these amphetamines I was taking.  My children do not know this [laughs]. 13, 14, 15 AS: They don’t know you used? 9, 13, 14, 15 JH: Not to the extent to which I did. 15 It’s just interesting because I am telling you and it’s like I mean I could tell Allison this, but—and I would but— So anyways, I quit using amphetamines, got a job, and moved out of the house at eighteen. 6, 8, 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 Got a job, lived uptown, worked at a record company, and had a blast. 6, 9, 19 Did advertising.  It was the late ‘70s early ‘80s.  I was just kind of going to school part time, thought okay, I’m going to be an accountant because that is really practical and that’s what I should do. 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 17 So, I went to Minneapolis Community College because I could afford it.  Then the plan was I would do the first two years there and then I would, you know, go on and get a degree in accounting and be a CPA. 9, 13, 14, 15, 20 I did it for about a year and a half and I thought it wasn’t—I actually, do you know who Norma Rowe is? 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 20 She was a University professor. 13 Anyways, she is an Anthropology professor. 16, 17 I think she is dead now. 14 She was a professor at Minneapolis Community College and she taught a class that was called Cultural Anthropology. 7, 20 I thought, “I’ll take this as one of my electives,” and it just blew me away, she just blew me away. 6, 9, 11, 12, 16 It was my introduction to feminism, and you know, I was like, “Oh my God, this is what interests me! 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 19 This is what I want to study. 9, 13 I want to study culture. 9, 13 I am interested in this.” 9, 11, 19 [laughs]  I’m not interested in spreadsheets! 9, 11, 19 This was 1970—this wasn’t on the computer it was on paper! 10 So, I stopped going to—I’m just like I’m going to go to the University of Minnesota. 9, 10, 12, 13, 20 She taught there, her husband taught there. 15 I worked at the record company, I became a waitress, I had worked for Republic Airlines for a little while. 5, 6, 19 I always had to work full-time. 11, 16, 17 I could never just go to school. 8, 9, 12, 15 I just couldn’t. 9