trategy? 9 I realized something was going on with Andy. 14 I knew it started out as anxiety and all these other symptoms started adding to his anxiety. 6, 9, 11, 12 I knew that something was going on with him. 6, 12 I contacted Nar-Anon, and I went to their parent or their family’s education—it’s a twelve week thing. 10, 16, 18 I went to this group in St. Paul called Families Anonymous, but that wasn’t until later. 7 I got a therapist that I saw, Nancy was her name. 6, 9 I saw her off and on.  I started getting into Buddhism. 9, 11 I started looking to spiritual things because clearly that was the only thing I could hold onto at this point. 9, 11, 16, 20 The only thing that was going to help. 13 I mean, I don’t know if it is this way for you, but it is this way for me. 13, 14, 15, 16 At my spiritual group that I go to at church this week the topic is, “What was your spiritual awakening?”  Bring a story of your spiritual awakening. 9 I’m like, “Oh my God, I don’t know what to bring because I don’t have a story.” 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 It happened over such a long period of time. 12, 13 And all these things and all these really challenging things that, yes, they bring up emotions and tears. 14, 16 They have got me here and I kind of like who I am [laughs]. 16, 17 You know? 13, 14, 15 That’s tangential, but I don’t like all these… 10 I’m not going to say I’m not going to be one of those people that’s going to be grateful for my child’s addiction.  I responded to it by going inward and outward and reaching out to people. 13 I have good friends. 12, 18 I have people that get what’s going on.  I have people that I can go to and say, “My child is an addict and this is what my weekend was like.” 10, 12, 19 And they don’t judge me.  I don’t know if I lucked out or if it… 13, 14, 15 you know natural selection, how that happened. 12, 13, 14, 15 I have and am surrounded in my life by people like that. 8, 11 They aren’t my family. 18 It’s not my family. 18 AS: The stigma around addic