know that you understand that and I can say that out loud. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 There are places I can’t say that out loud. 11, 17 There are a number of people I can say that out loud to.  Allison was on a respirator for three days. 19 Three days. 19 They said, “We don’t know if she is going to pull out of this opiate overdose. 13, 14, 15 Intentional opiate overdose.” 15 So when you come that close… 13, 19 I came home and that was the third time. 19, 20 That was the third time I had been to that brink with her. 20 It is not that it doesn’t matter because it does matter. 20 It’s that it just gives you this thing where you go, “Okay, I’m very likely to lose my child before me.” 6, 9, 10, 12 This is something that I don’t know… 13, 14, 15 I also don’t often say out loud because I don’t know if it will make people irritated or mad, but I’m going to say it. 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 This is oddly comforting to me.  I grew up in the Vietnam War era, and my uncle was in Vietnam, and I lived next to a guy who’s son was in Vietnam.  All those mothers who had all those children in Vietnam sat in the same place I sit every day. 11, 13, 14, 19 Not knowing whether or not their child will survive that day. 13, 14, 15, 19 Knowing their child is engaged in something so dangerous that their life is [unclear]. 11, 14, 18 Why is that comforting?  To know that I’m not the first person. 9, 13, 14, 15 That I am not the only mother.  That I am not isolated in this being a mother who is on the brink of losing her child.  I know there are other situations that mothers are in where their children are doing dangerous things but that’s the one that comes up in my head. 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19 All these years of my childhood, because as a child that is what I thought about surprisingly enough. 11, 12, 20 I have very distinct memories where as a child of eight, nine, ten, eleven thinking, “I feel sorry for the moms.” 9, 10, 15, 16, 18 And I felt sorry for mothers because they had kids who were in Vietn