 my house: you can’t smoke pot, and you’ve got to do something.” 6, 9, 12 I signed him up for therapy.  “I’m taking you to therapy.”  I’m monitoring everything.  I’m going down when I come home from work and saying, “You need to get up and we are going to go to the parkway and we are going for a walk.” 11, 13, 16, 19 I’m dragging his six and a half foot butt up the parkway. 14, 16, 20 I’m doing all this stuff to try and get him to not do what I know is happening and that is he’s sinking into this mental illness that I’ve seen, you know. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I’ve seen it.  AS: It was familiar.  It was familiar.  You know I didn’t want it to be true. 13, 14, 15 You don’t want it to be true. 13 I came home one time and this is while I'm toggling through this… 19 I’ve had enough. 20 What happens is I—this is a common thing I think. 12 I do all these things and then I’ve had enough and I can’t do it anymore. 13, 16, 20 I just want to curl up in a ball and die. 8, 9, 12, 13 I never would kill myself, but there were nights where I would think, “If I don’t wake up I’m okay with that. 7, 15, 19 I’m okay with not waking up tomorrow.”  [laughs]  I don’t know if that’s going to happen. 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: If I die before I wake…  If I die before I wake…  oh well!  So, I kicked him out because he won’t adhere to my rules. 12 “You can’t live with me.”  He goes to live with his dad who is still living in our house in northeast Minneapolis, but has let it go into foreclosure. 6, 9, 15, 19 Just stopped paying for it. 9, 10, 11, 16, 20 So Ali who is starting to use is living there, and Andy. 6, 9, 11 And the timeline starts to get blurry for me because it is just like—I mean it is a shit storm. 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 16 So, I just knew I had to separate myself. 6, 9, 12 I had to deal with my… 13 I still had to work, I still had all these things I have to do. 9, 16 And, all this stuff is going on. 9 I’m not completely cutting myself off from them. 14, 19 By now I know that she’s an addict. 13, 14, 15 I found out it was heroin on the phone at work talking to someone who was doing her Rule 25 Assessment, getting information from me. 7, 10, 17 I’m at work and I get this phone call on my prep. 7 I know she’s getting a Rule 25 Assessment, this is maybe her second time in treatment. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 I’m in my classroom and I see the phone and I’m like, “Okay, I’m supposed to be getting this phone call,” and I talk to the… 6, 7, 10, 20 “So, Allison has been using heroin for the last year and a half.” 9, 20 Are you kidding me?”  “Oh, you didn’t know that?” 13, 14, 15 “No, I had no idea.” 11 I felt like I had been kicked in the stomach. 9, 17 I almost puked. 9 I almost puked. 9 This is such a distinct memory because I have such a good visual of my own classroom. 7, 9, 20 I remember my kids were gone and there were no students because they were at music or wherever they were. 9, 14, 19 I was walking around with the phone and I remember just rocking back and forth because I knew that I had to get rid of the panic before twenty-eight eight-year-olds came back. 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 15, 19, 20 I was still a smoker at the time and I remember as soon as I got off the phone I went to my purse and I grabbed my cigarettes and I told my co-teacher I said, “If I’m not back in fifteen minutes will you get my kids?” 7, 9, 19, 20 I just walked out the back door and up the block and lit a cigarette and just paced back and around the block. 9, 12, 17, 19 I was a block from the school because I had to smoke so bad. 8 I think I just kept saying, “Oh my fucking God. 9, 11, 12 Oh my God.  Oh my God.”  You know? 13, 14, 15 I bet that is the first I had heard heroin. 9, 15 All of that, you know, ‘60s stuff that I had grown up with. 9, 13, 14, 15, 17 Nw that was Allison.  I think at that point it felt like a death sentence. 7, 15, 17 That is really dramatic and I understand how dramatic that is but that’s what— AS: But you knew immediately the impact of that. 6, 9, 10, 12, 14, 16 Of it being heroin and not Percocet.  I was thinking it was Percocet.  Or Oxycontin.  AS: So get back to Andy. 19 Andy.  So I kicked him out, he went to live with Carey.  I went over, I would call him. 7 He was just getting—I don’t know. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 He was doing drugs, not getting out of bed, or something. 14 I stepped away for maybe a month or two or just like you know I would call him but I was really like, I mean by now they are eighteen and twenty, you know? 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 Carey is sixty—I don’t know how old he is. 13, 14, 15, 20 These are people that I….  So, I call and I talked to Andy and I talk to him and he was not making sense. 7, 10, 11, 17 I went over there and something was tremendously wrong. 12 I didn’t know if it was drugs—I didn’t know what it was. 13, 14, 15 Carey’s elderly mother was living with them at the time, and I was talking to Andy and I was like, “So what’s going on?” 6, 10 And he was not making sense. 17 He was delusional.  I got up.  Carey’s mom was sitting in the living room. 6, 7, 13, 15 Carey was sitting on the couch, and I said, “Do you have any awareness of how sick our child is?” 13 I said, “I’m calling the county. 7 Prepare for it.”  I got in my car and I called my friend and I said, “What do I have to do? 7, 12 Who do I call?” 7 She told me to call COPE. 7, 20 She said, “This is what you say.  This is what you need to say to get people up there. 13 Don’t lie.  But this is how it works.” 14 “This is how the system works. 8, 9, 14 If you say you’ll take him to your house, they will let you. 6, 9, 19 But, you don’t want that. 13 You say he can’t…”  So I called and I said, “What is going on?” 7 And one of the things she said, “Parents tend to want to mitigate the severity of the danger. 12, 13, 15, 16 You don’t want to think that your child is dangerous to themselves or someone else. 13, 18 So you say ‘No, I don’t think so.’  Don’t say that.”  She said, “Don’t say that, if you had any…  don’t lie.  But if you think he is a danger to himself you say ‘My son is a danger to himself.’  And you say it over and over again.”  So, she really was helpful that way for me to advocate for him to be taken in and they took him. 6, 10, 13, 16 They came. 19 They assessed him.  Carey’s mom screamed at me. 15 Screamed at me.  That I was the reason the kids were messed up because I was a lesbian. 8 Oh my God.  He also came from a very religious background. 8, 19 His dad was a missionary and was killed was in Ethiopia and that is a whole other story. 7, 9, 15 [laughs]  She is screaming at me and I’m like, “This is my child. 10 This is my child to fix.” 16 They took a 72-hour hold on… 20 that was his first. 9 They didn’t keep him. 12 He came back and lived here. 19 I mean, there are a lot of details, but he kept smoking pot and kept trying to… 16, 17 I mean they both simultaneously were just going down. 9, 12, 16 It was just one tripping over the other. 9, 12 It just came to me having to step away from both of them in that way that people in recovery step away and not the way people in panic step away. 9, 12, 16, 19 I was stepping away in panic a lot. 9, 12, 16, 17 And that wasn’t helpful and then when I realized, “I’ve got to recover, I’ve got to take care of myself. 6, 7, 13, 14 I’ve got to fix myself.” 16 Not fix myself, but I’ve got to attend to myself. 12, 15, 16 Because I’m not being a good mother.  I’m not being a good mother.  I have to mother.  I have to mother these disasters. 9, 20 That was the first, the very first key to me being able to do it better was to accept it for what it was. 9 Because the whole time I was mothering in panic and reacting in panic I was not accepting that this is what I got. 10 These are my children. 14 I mean they are not what I thought it would be. 11, 12, 16 It is not what I thought it would be. 11, 12 It is not what some of my friends are going through. 12, 18 That's really hard. 11 Because all of my friends’ kids were having successful families. 12, 18 They are of that age of going to college. 8 Not being addicts and schizophrenics.  So, that first place wasn’t a light bulb moment, and still maybe isn’t completely solid, but is the acceptance. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 And that was when Buddhism came in because acceptance is everything. 19 Not accepting is all struggle. 9 You accept what it is.  You accept that it is yours.  AS: That is really powerful. 15 And when it is your children. 14 The other thing that I let myself do and I still let myself do is I let myself mourn my losses. 9, 19 That is something I have learned as an adult that I was not allowed to do as a child. 12, 17 Whether it’s a relationship like my one with Kathy or Jill—but, my children. 14 I have let myself mourn the loss of having the kids I thought I would have. 11, 12, 19 I thought I would have different children. 11, 12, 14, 16, 17 I thought that they were really Waldorf-y kids. 11, 12 [laughs]  I really thought that that’s what I would end up with. 11, 12 Even with Carey’s addiction—I let myself mourn that. 19 I don’t think I still mourn it the way I did. 9, 16 I have really come to accept that this is what I have in the rights to my life. 11, 13, 14, 19 I have two children that have serious mental illness. 14 One is manifesting itself in addiction and the other is schizophrenic. 9 Andy also, they diagnosed him as on the autism spectrum, which I guess also goes hand in hand with some of those behaviors. 10 He was originally diagnosed with Aspergers.  That was the first one. 9 Then that started off a whole round for trying to find psychiatric help for your child when they are an adult. 8, 9, 11, 13, 16 They don’t want to find help because they don’t think they are sick. 13 All schizophrenics—that’s their…  So I’m trying to find places. 11, 16, 17 I am going to say from 2003 to now I had to—I’ve know he is schizophrenic. 13, 14, 15 I had known he was schizophrenic. 10, 13, 14, 15 Because I have been watching him and have been reading about it and I have been seeing him. 11 I will take him to psychiatrists and say, “He is a schizophrenic,” and they say, “Well, it doesn’t really help us to take that diagnosis. 6, 9, 13 Well we’ll put him on lithium…” 10 Well, he’s not going to take it. 6 I can’t force him to take it. 6 That’s what is happening now. 12, 13, 14 He’s on Jarvis which is a quartered medication. 10, 12 I knew really solidly two years ago that my… 6, 12, 20 what I had to do was to step away and watch him walk the road and fall down the hole. 9, 12, 16 AS: Just like they tell us we have to do with our addict children. 9, 14 Leave them alone.  Cut them off.  Kick them out.  It’s harder when someone has—it has been harder with Andy than with Ali. 11 He can’t take it. 6 I’m going to say he can’t take care of himself. 6, 7 There is the mother—because he’s my baby. 5 It is kind of true. 16, 17 He’s can’t— AS: He’s not functioning in this world, right? 14, 15 He can’t make decisions for himself. 16 Here is the difference in…  AS: And he’s now in a hospital? 14 JH: Yes.  He’s civilly committed.  AS: Just for the record. 6, 9 He is in the hospital.  He is civilly committed.  I am working very closely with the psychiatric team.  I am mothering him.  I see him twice a week.  He wants to see me four times a week. 11, 13, 18 I bring him Taco Bell once.  I set up my limits. 17 AS: Did they let you take him out for his birthday? 6, 19 No, and that was okay.  I called his psychiatric nurse. 7 I said “I’m going to advocate for this as much as I need to.” 10, 13, 18 I said, “Can I take him out for his birthday?” 6, 19 She said, “No.”  I have a really good relationship with his social worker at the hospital.  He has been there for months. 8 They all know me. 13, 14, 15 He has been there longer than anybody has.  They don’t know what to do with him. 13, 14, 15 AS: Really?  They don’t know where to send him? 12, 13, 14, 15 Are there are other options? 7 Right now they are trying to get him into the intensive rehabilitat