"11","Englund_Gloria","Chandra Kelvie Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer April 28, 2017 St. Louis Park, Minnesota Chandra Kelvie-CK Amy Sullivan-AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan and I am in a Starbucks in St. Louis Park with Chandra Kelvie. 14 Do you give me permission to record this interview? 6 CK: Yes, I do.  AS: Do you want to talk about where and when you were born? 10, 13 CK: I was born November 30, 1976 in Minneapolis.  I want to say I was born at St. Mary’s, but I don’t think it exists anymore. 9, 13 I have a sister, but we don’t share the same dad. 5, 9 I have a brother and sister who we have the same mom but different dads. 5, 9, 15, 16, 17 Then I have a brother who we have the same dad but different moms. 5, 15, 16, 17, 18 AS: Are you the oldest? 5, 9, 20 CK: I am the youngest. 9, 14 AS: Where did you grow up? 17 CK: I grew up in South Minneapolis.  My dad had a house on Fifteenth and Lake Street and my mom moved around a lot. 6, 8, 9, 15, 17 I moved back and forth between them both until I got a little older and then I was with my dad. 5, 8, 19, 20 AS: What were the circumstances that led to you living with your dad? 6, 9 CK: My dad just wanted me to have a stable place. 9, 11, 12, 13, 18 I think my mom tried but it was just really hard with three kids. 9, 10, 11, 12, 15 I felt that my dad could financially support me better than my mom. 15, 17 I don’t know if this will be in the book, but I have never confronted my mom about it, but her boyfriend was really mean to me. 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I was treated differently because I was biracial and my siblings weren’t. 5, 16, 17 AS: What is your background? 8, 19 CK: I am Hispanic.  My dad was Hispanic.  AS: Was he mean to you physically? 7, 16 He would hang me out of a second story window by my feet and let me go and then catch me again. 9, 10, 19, 20 He would lock me in the porch and say I was sleeping with the porch monkeys. 7 I didn’t know what any of that meant. 13, 14, 15, 16 I haven’t talked to my mom about it, whether she knew it was going on or not. 6, 10, 11, 12, 15 I just feel like I’d rather not know because I am close with my mom now. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I never told my dad because I was afraid he would hurt him because he was a violent person. 15, 20 AS: That’s a lot to hold onto. 17, 20 CK: My dad dated his first cousin for ten years. 5, 9, 20 I had no idea. 11 When I was young I just thought it was his girlfriend. 9, 11, 12, 14 I didn’t put the dynamics together until I was a little older. 5, 10, 20 I just thought we were just going to family events. 9, 11, 12, 15, 18 I didn’t know. 13, 14, 15 AS: That is complicated. 10 CK: It is a lot now that I’m older. 5, 14, 17, 20 It was always the, “Don’t talk about it” in our family type of thing. 10, 16, 17, 18 AS: On both sides?  CK: I’m not that close to my mom’s side of the family, but on my dad’s side for sure. 15, 18 We just don’t talk about it. 9, 10, 12 Nobody talks about it. 10, 14 AS: How old were you when you moved in with your dad? 8, 20 You’re dad must have know things were going on that weren’t good. 13, 14, 15, 16 CK: I don’t know if he did. 13, 14, 15 If he did know what was going on I really think he would be in jail. 13, 14, 15 AS: Is that guy still around? 8, 9 Is he still with your mom? 9, 15 My mom met somebody when I was around ten and he’s a really good guy. 5, 8, 15 I’ve never even heard him raise his voice. 15 I think my mom drank a lot then, too. 7, 14, 15, 17 When I look back my dad was doing drugs back then and I just didn’t know the signs. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 I didn’t know what was going on. 13, 14, 15 AS: When you were small.  You have memory of that.  So you moved in with your dad when? 8 CK: I went back and forth until we moved to Andover when I was around eleven. 8, 15, 19 I would go to my mom’s and visit but I lived with my dad. 12, 13, 15 AS: How was your middle school and high school time? 8 CK: It was fine. 14 I was pregnant in middle school, so I had to leave middle school. 6, 8 AS: Do you want to talk about that? 10, 13 CK: Nobody ever talked to me about sex or anything so I had no idea what I was doing. 10, 11 I got pregnant the first time I had sex. 9 I got pulled out of school to go to the Teen Parent program in Anoka. 8, 16 I went to school there. 8 I should back up. 19 My dad was livid, obviously, and he wanted me to give it up for adoption. 6, 12, 13 I was young and scared and I didn’t know what to do. 5, 7, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 We went to this adoption agency and went through everything and met with families and stuff. 5, 9 When I talked to the doctor before I had her she said if I say that I don’t want to give her up in front of the nurses and the doctors my dad can’t make me do it. 6, 10, 11, 13, 16 AS: She let you know about your power. 13, 14, 15, 19 I did that and it was rough. 18 It was hard. 11 AS: You got pregnant at fourteen then?  I think I was pregnant just when I turned fourteen and I had her when I was fifteen. 9, 12, 19 AS: Talk about that a little more.  What happened when she was born? 12, 13 CK: I got my own place. 11 I got emancipated.  AS: What happened in the hospital? 12, 13 CK: I had her and right after I had her I looked at my dad and the nurse already knew I was going to do it. 6, 12, 14 I just said, “I don’t want to give her up for adoption. 6, 9, 12, 13 I’m not okay with it.”  He left and took her dad’s shoes.  I don’t know why but for whatever reason. 13, 14, 15 I stayed with him for a little bit and finished a little more schooling. 5, 8, 9 She went to school with me because in the Teen Parent program you went to school and then you worked in the day care for an hour or an hour and a half a day and then you went to your other classes. 7, 8, 16, 19, 20 All the girls in this school were pregnant and we all switched off. 8 There were some other staff there too. 9 AS: How many of you were there?  CK: I want to say there were maybe fifteen. 9, 13 AS: Did they come from one high school? 8, 13, 19 AS: When was she born?  CK: March 27, 1992.  I ended up getting my own apartment on Twenty-ninth and Lake Street and I went to South High School. 12, 20 My mom helped watch her while I worked two different jobs. 13, 15, 16, 17 At that age you could only work so many hours legally. 11 AS: You worked and you went to school full-time and you have a newborn? 6, 8, 11 I ended up not finishing school. 8, 12 I went back to finish school, but it was too hard. 8, 11, 19 I had to support myself.  AS: I can’t imagine. 14 Did you ever get connected with WIC [Women, Infants, and Children Program] or any of those assistance programs? 9, 14, 18 CK: I was on WIC.  She was allergic to formula and she had to have goat’s milk or something and I remember back then that it was twenty-eight dollars a can. 17, 19 I did end up getting on WIC. 12 In my entire life I think I have been on welfare for six months. 8, 11 I was determined.  Everybody told me my life was over. 11, 20 There was no encouragement there.  None.  My life was over instead of being like, “this will be a different path” and encouraging me. 9, 10, 11, 14, 16, 17 I remember being young I never felt stable because I was bounced around and back and forth so much. 8, 9, 14, 15, 17, 18, 19 I didn’t want that for my kids. 13 It made me feel like I never had a home really. 15, 16, 19 I did get what’s called Homes Park Village. 7 They are subsidized townhomes and I did end up moving there which helped me a lot. 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 And then I met my youngest daughter’s dad and we ended up getting married and bought a house. 5, 6, 7, 9, 12, 14 We ended up getting divorced, but we were together for sixteen, seventeen years. 5, 12, 20 When did you go back to school? 8, 19 CK: I think Ashley was two.  AS: That is your second daughter. 5, 20 What is your first daughter’s name? 5, 6, 9 CK: My first daughter is Ashley and my second daughter is Asia. 5, 9, 20 When Ashley was two I ended up going to get my GED and then went to Lakewind Dental Academy, which was on Lake Street at the time near Lake Calhoun. 12 I went there to get my dental assisting license. 9 I didn’t like it. 10 I finished all the bookwork and paperwork and I opened someone’s mouth and I couldn’t do it. 17 I ended up getting a job where they made dentures and stuff and I worked there for a few years. 9, 12, 16, 20 I ended up getting my job at Regis and I have been there for fifteen years. 12, 20 I work in the corporate office.  CK: I am an education coordinator. 10 I work for the Super Cuts brand. 7 There is an umbrella, so we own ninety percent of the hair industry. 9, 12, 16 Super Cuts is mainly franchise owned, so I work with the franchisees. 7 Before a stylist can get on the floor they go through a weeklong training so I schedule those. 9 AS: Do you have another job?  CK: I do I work at Abbott [Northwestern Hospital]. 9 CK: I schedule the nurses.  You schedule the hospital every four hours so you have to get the floor staffed every four hours based on their needs. 9, 11, 13 You have the scheduled staff, but people call in. 7, 9 AS: Are you full time? 11 CK: I am a point seven.  AS: How much do you work for Regis? 18 CK: I work for Regis full time. 11 AS: So you basically have two full time jobs. 7, 11 CK: Yes.  AS: You have worked hard your whole life. 11 CK: When I got divorced was when I had to pick up the other job because I couldn’t make it without it. 5, 16 AS: When did you notice your dad’s addiction issues? 14, 15 CK: I noticed my dad’s addiction issues before Ashley was born. 14, 15 Probably around when I was twelve. 8 He would walk around the house like a zombie. 6, 9 I didn’t know exactly what was going on but then I realized it because he would send me to go get his drugs because he couldn’t drive high. 7, 8, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 We lived in Andover and I would drive. 7, 14 I think I was about thirteen or fourteen then.  Go to the houses and get his drugs and then bring him home. 6, 9, 14, 19 I did it because I was scared. 5, 7, 11, 12 AS