 dad and other people from him getting in a car? 7, 19 CK: I think in my mind honestly it was more protecting him than anybody else. 9, 16 Then I remember I moved back home. 8, 19 I got my place until fifteen and I moved back home when I was--he moved because he was living in a woman and he moved into a trailer and I think I was there for about a year. 6, 8, 11, 19, 20 AS: You lived in the trailer with him and your baby? 5 CK: Yes.  I would just stay there because I was scared he was going to die. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12 I was so young. 14 I was scared he was going to overdose and be by himself. 5, 7, 11, 12, 15 And so I stayed, I would watch him--the minute I would even talk to him on the phone I would know he was high. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 I knew instantly. 6, 9, 12 Then I remember I tried to commit suicide once. 10 I just wanted him to wake up. 9, 12, 13 I didn't really want to hurt myself, but I just wanted him to see he was hurting me, and I didn't understand why I wasn't more important than this drug. 9, 12, 13, 14, 16 He came to the hospital. 19 AS: Where did you try to do that? 16 Do you mind talking about it? 10 CK: No, I don't mind.  We lived in Oakdale at the time when he moved into the trailer park. 8 It was called Glandfall. 7, 8 AS: You did that where you were living with him? 6 What happened? 12, 13 Did you take something? 6 CK: I took these pills called trazodone. 7 I took like twenty of them.  CK: I don't remember how--I don't remember where they came from, but I remember taking them. 19 My girlfriend knew something was wrong and she called the police and they pumped my stomach. 6, 7, 9, 12 Now when I'm older I think, ""Why didn't social services step in at any point?"" 5, 9, 12, 14, 20 They had to have known he was high when he came to the hospital. 8, 10, 13, 14, 15, 19 AS: You were fifteen?  CK: No, I was probably—I have to remember because the way I deal with things is I just don't think about it. 9, 12, 13, 16 I had to have been sixteen.  AS: Because you had had that year and then you moved back with him. 8, 19, 20 Do you remember ever talking about what was upsetting you? 10, 17, 19 CK: I was very--yeah and he would say he wants to clean; he wants to do better. 10, 11, 13 He went to treatment several times and every time he would get out he would relapse. 9, 16, 18 AS: Was he ever on medically assisted treatment that you knew of? 6, 7, 9, 12, 14, 16 Was he ever on methadone?  CK: Not that I know of. 13, 14, 15 He tried to hide it for so long because he was a Minneapolis firefighter. 10, 15 AS: Can you talk about his life? 10, 11 What you know about your dad's life and his parents? 10, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16 CK: I know that my grandpa was very abusive to him. 7, 9, 11, 13, 14, 15 AS: Where did your dad grow up? 17 CK: In north Minneapolis, I believe.  He used to tell me about stories of how my grandpa would kind of shave his head, physically abusive to him. 7, 9, 11, 16, 17, 18 My grandma—the Mexican side lost custody of him so my grandpa Jack—I think it was boiled down to who had more money. 7, 9 AS: Was grandpa 7 Jack white?  So they had more money, so my grandma Margaret ended up raising my dad. 7, 12 It was Jack's mom. 15 She was my great grandma. 7, 11 I loved her. 13 She was my grandma. 7 My dad was her favorite, and she knew my dad was sick. 6, 12 She always used to tell me, ""He's sick."" 9, 16, 17 AS: When you were little?  CK: When I was older. 5, 20 AS: So she seemed to have some compassion with that. 19 AS: Did you ever know your grandma on the Mexican side? 7, 13, 14, 15 I did but when he was dating his cousin she wouldn't—I didn't get why we would never go over there. 5, 15 We would see her at Christmas or when they would all get together, but it would never be where I would go over there and visit with her. 9, 12, 13, 15 I didn't understand until I was older why—that she didn't agree with it. 5, 9, 12, 16, 20 AS: She had a point.  [laughs]  [laughs]  AS: What else do you know about your dad's lif