 my husband and I would go and I would always help and it took me a long time to realize I'm not helping him. 6, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 I'm enabling him.  AS: Because you would get him food and bring him what he needs. 13 And then someone was like, ""That just gives him to use his money for drugs because he knows you're going to bring that stuff to him."" 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 I think when I finally moved out of the trailer is I took a nap in his bed and I woke up and there was a needle sticking in my leg. 8, 9, 13 I had to get tested for everything for seven years. 9, 20 I don't know if it was, I can't remember—he used to, I don't know if there was anything in the needle at the time. 9, 13, 14, 15 Probably not.  There wasn't anything left over.  [laughs]  CK: Yeah, I was done.  CK: I was probably seventeen. 15 Sixteen, seventeen.  AS: So that lasted about a year? 9, 20 CK: Yeah, and I just thought, ""I can't do this."" 9, 11, 12 You know? 13, 14, 15 It was just—it was every time he called I would be like, ""What now?"" 7, 9, 10, 12, 14 It was never a happy feeling when he would call. 7, 15, 16, 17 AS: Your whole life pretty much. 11, 18 He was in another jail.  AS: And he would be able to go back to his job? 19 CK: I guess this was after he—I don't know when he—I'm serious I just completely... 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 After he got let go was when he was in and out of jail. 19 I believe when he was working a few years before he was let go they did raid the fire department and found stuff in his locker. 9, 15, 19, 20 I think it is actually online because I remember printing it and reading it. 6, 10, 11 AS: So for you this is like putting piece together about what you experienced, but you never had all the information. 10, 15, 17 CK: Just when I look back now at all of the weird stuff that would happen would make sense. 9, 12, 14, 16, 17, 19 I knew very young he was using. 6, 12, 14 And I didn't—until my twenties was when I realized this is how he was going to die. 14 I remember when I got the call when he—he had a drug induced stroke because he would shoot up and he had a stroke in his brain stem. 7, 9, 14 A week, maybe a week and a half prior to that he had this terrible headache where he was—he had never called me like he was in pain and I took him to Region's hospital in St. Paul and they were like, ""We're just going to give him some—it was either Percocet or Vicodin—two of them because he was labeled as a seeker is what they called him. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 15, 19, 20 I was like, ""Are you going to do any cat scans or anything? 10 And they didn't because they just looked at him as a drug user. 9, 12, 14 AS: What was going on in his brain?  CK: He was having many strokes because basically the nerves in his brain were misfiring and that was what was causing the headaches, but he was shooting up and he had MRSA [methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus] and it went into his blood stream and somehow in his brain—before that he was hallucinating, he would start hallucinating. 5, 7, 9, 11 I donated his brain to science, the coroner asked me to, but then when I got to the hospital when he had the big stroke he was coherent and he was like, ""Do you know her?"" 8, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 And he was like, I mean, he couldn't talk. 10, 16 He lay down and that was the last time he was conscious because he had it in his main brain stem. 9 He was alive for three days before they took him off life support. 11, 19 They said he was never going to—and he has told me he doesn't want to live like that. 13, 15, 20 AS: Can you talk and unpack that story a little more about the treatment at the hospital when you took him for the headache? 9, 10, 16 CK: I was angry.  I called them after he died. 7 I called the patient representative and I told him, I said, ""I feel like..."" I don't know if anything could have been done, but I feel like he wasn't treated fairly because he was a drug addict, and it's crazy because I remember calling the hospital and being like, ""Someone needs to help him. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 He is not capable of taking care of himself. 7 He's hurting himself, he's hallucinating,"" and they were like, ""There's nothing we can do unless he walks in here on his own."" 10, 12 CK: This was way before this incident happened, but I would remember being so frustrated. 9, 12, 13, 16 No one would help and he is an adult, you can't make him get help. 13, 16 I just wanted—he was hurting himself. 9, 12, 13 I remember thinking, ""This is ridiculous.  He is hurting himself."" 12 I remember in the hospital when he died I had to sign a waiver because they had to put him in this machine—it's like a big tube—because they wanted to see what was going on in his brain. 8, 10, 12, 13 AS: After he died?  This was like the first day. 9, 19 The MRI thing.  I had to sign a waiver because he was an addict.  They put tape on his arms right here and right here. 10, 14 When he went in all the needles that were broken in his arms and his hands burned up to the surface of his skin. 5, 13 Because it is a giant magnet. 8 They knew—I didn't know that was going to happen, but they knew. 6, 12, 13, 14, 15 I'm assuming they had seen it before, but they made me sign a waiver that if there's any metal in his body—that explains why they put tape on his arms and his hands. 5, 10, 16 I felt guilty. 17 I felt guilty for a long time because I remember when I got the call I was like, thought to myself, ""Let this be it. 7, 10, 11, 12, 17 Let this be the end."" 12 AS: I can't imagine thinking anything else after what you had been through. 14 Because he had been hallucinating so bad up to that point.  He was at my uncle's at Stacy, Minnesota and he broke into a fire house. 6, 9, 15 Out there they don't stay in there. 9 When there's a call they go. 7 He stole the fire truck and went to my uncle's with full lights, everything. 9, 11, 15, 18 It is a funny story because I can't imagine what my uncle was going through, but he had the full lights on and walked in there fully geared up and put a flash light in my uncle's face and said, ""There's a bomb in the house."" 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 17 He thought people were—the CIA was following him. 11, 12 He really was hallucinating.  AS: And even at this point that's not grounds for mental health— CK: No, they wouldn't help. 8, 13, 14, 15 Not if he doesn't walk in there on his own.  I think that was a couple, maybe six months before he died. 8, 9 AS: Was he using meth do you think? 5 CK: No, he was using cocaine and heroin.  He was doing speedballs. 8 There were always burnt spoons and cotton balls. 8, 16, 17 Alcohol—I didn't know what the alcohol was for. 13, 14, 15 AS: When we talked on the phone I think you talked about what it was like walking into his place. 7, 10, 11, 15 CK: After he passed away. 16 It was sad because he didn't have much. 12, 18 He was an addict so he— AS: Had you been there recently?  CK: I had been there a couple of times. 18 He was at a house—he rented a duplex and he rented the top floor to I think he was a former captain of the fire department, Larry. 6, 9, 15, 16, 17 He rented it from Larry and I think Larry felt bad for him and knew he had some issues. 6, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17 It was hard because I had to warn people and be like, ""You can't just dig around and go in pockets and lift things up because there's going to be needles."" 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16 He would hide them everywhere and I think when he was high he would hide them or put them places and forget where they were. 8, 10, 11, 17 Used ones.  That's when I found out about the needle exchange. 13, 16 I didn't know what to do with them. 13, 14, 15 I was like, ""I can't just throw these out,"" because I knew he had hepatitis. 6, 9, 10, 12 I was like, ""I don't feel right because what if someone gets stuck with these, what if..."" 9, 10, 14, 16 I don't know. 13, 14, 15 I didn't know. 13, 14, 15 AS: So after he passed you collected them all?  I called the hospital and they're the ones that told me about the needle exchange. 7, 13, 16, 20 Access Works.  I think it's on Nicollet. 19 It's almost downtown and you would never know it was there. 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 I remember walking in and there were couches and there were people sitting on there, and I remember walking in and bursting into tears. 9, 13, 15 I just did not know—I had no idea what I was—it just was really sad to me. 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 The people that were there were getting clean needles. 13 And I just thought, you know, it just broke my heart. 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: Because your dad didn't overdose? 15 He died of his drug complications due to his drug abuse. 9, 10, 14 What happened? 12, 13 CK: I didn't stick around. 8, 9 I do remember that she asked me if I was okay. 10 I just said, ""Yes, I'm okay."" 9, 12 I just explained that these were used needles and they were my dad's. 9, 12, 13 She was like, ""Do you need to talk to anybody?"" 10, 13 And I just wanted to get out of there and I just wanted to leave. 6, 9, 12, 13 It wasn't a scary place. 7, 11 It just—I just didn't know this type of stuff existed. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: And your dad didn't either.  CK: I don't know where he would get his needles. 13, 14, 15 I don't know how. 13, 14, 15 I never figured that out. 12, 13, 15 How he would get access to them. 6 AS: Did you ever go through his cell phone? 7 CK: Did he have a cell phone? 7 I never went through his stuff because at that point he was just gone. 9, 12, 15, 19 I remember when I was younger though he was a good dad when he was sober. 5, 6, 14 I remember being on the boat. 7 Those were the happiest times when he was sober. 6, 9, 18 I always think about those times. 16, 17, 18 AS: There was a nice picture, I think he was on a boat. 7 Did you pick that out?  For his obituary.  AS: Do you remember the story about him delivering the baby? 5, 9 CK: I do when they talked about it at the—because the fire department came to the funeral. 10, 11, 15, 19 AS: Because he got some kind of award? 16, 17 CK: Yeah, but he was also in the Star Tribune.  He rescued a young girl from a fire. 14, 15 I always thought it would be really cool to see her. 11, 12, 16, 17 [laughs]  You have to be an EMT for a little bit before you're a fire fighter. 15 She went into labor and he delivered the baby in the ambulance. 5, 12 AS: So he had EMT training?  CK: Yeah, and he couldn't read.  It was just weird to me. 9, 12 AS: You think of all those things as being literacy dependent, and yet, if you can retain stuff— CK: 9, 12, 16 He had been doing that for a long time.  He could fix anything. 16 He was a roofer for a while.  That was his side thing.  He would roof for Donner Construction. 9 He could make anything, fix anything. 16 AS: He was let go of the fire department because of his drug use? 9, 14, 15, 19 Had they worked with him in the past to get him to treatmen? 9, 16 I don't know exactly what they did. 10, 13, 14, 15 I don't know how many times they actually put him into treatment because it was never discussed with me. 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18 He would never tell me— AS: Would he go away? 15, 16 No, it was always outpatient. 9, 16, 17 He was at inpatient at Unity for—this was towards the end after he had lost his job. 9, 12 He worked with the fire department for so long that they retired him early so that it didn't look like anything so he got half of his pension. 12, 15, 19, 20 They did try to help him. 13, 16 AS: And there was a point where—did he show up to work high? 8 CK: You know, I don't know if he did that. 13, 14, 15 I think he would just get randomly tested. 7, 9, 12 When you are a fire fighter you work one day on, one day off, one day on, one day off, then you got ten days off. 15, 19 Then you would work one day on, one day off. 19 So, I mean you had a lot of time off. 16, 17 They would work twenty-four hour shifts, so he would work one twenty-four hour shift and then have twenty-four hours off. 8, 11 I remember when they came to the funeral one guy spoke and he said that my dad was always the first one in and the last one out. 9, 16, 17, 19 AS: He was brave.  Kind of fearless.  CK: Or it was the adrenaline rush, or I don't know. 6, 13, 14, 15 When they said that I was like, ""Was that what he..."" 10 And he told me about the first time he tried heroin. 9, 10, 20 He said it was a high that he never had had before. 8, 15 He said he never got high like that after, no matter how high he would get it was never like that first time. 8, 9, 15, 20 AS: That memory of the first time. 9 Wow.  Yeah I've heard that. 15 AS: Yeah, people describe it as this incredible hug, just this incredible warmth. 9, 12 A feeling of complete peace and calm. 16, 19 No worries, no nothing.  CK: I've always been too scared. 5, 7, 11, 12, 16, 17 AS: Yeah, so talk about that. 10 Your own relationship with it, with substances. 9 CK: I just think I was too scared because I had seen him so many years hurt himself. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12, 20 What he would go through—I just was scared to try anything, anything. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12, 16 Even this I wouldn't take pain pills for. 6 And they did try to give them to me. 6, 16 I was like, ""No thank you."" 10, 13 It's just that—because my sister struggles with—she's had some addiction problems with pain pills. 5, 9, 12 I've seen it.  I've seen plenty of friends that I've grown up, went to school with, have issues with it. 8, 12, 14, 15, 17, 18 It's just insane to me how many people have issues with it. 9, 12, 14, 15 There are a lot of people. 17 That's considered fun for them to take pills. 6, 12 AS: What about shooting heroin?  Do you know people who do that or would admit to it? 13, 14, 15 CK: I don't know people that would admit to it, no. 13, 14, 15 I know that they've done it, not— AS: How old are you? 13, 14, 15, 20 CK: I'm forty.  AS: Is your sister older? 5, 9, 20 CK: My sister is forty-two. 5, 9 AS: That's mostly pills that you hear about? 9 CK: The heroin is more—they call it recreational. 7 They don't do it all the time apparently. 10, 16, 18 To me there's no such thing.  My dad used to say that when he first—he said he did it recreationally or did it to party. 6, 9 And then he couldn't control it. 17 So do you drink socially? 6, 14 I'll drink wine, but I feel like— AS: Was your mom an alcoholic? 5, 6, 10, 14, 15, 16 She hasn't drank in—probably since Ashley was young because she's a juvenile diabetic, too, and it made her very sick and she had to take her health—she had to change. 6, 7, 14, 16 AS: And she was able to do that.  CK: She just stopped, but she would drink a lot I remember. 6, 9, 10, 12, 14, 17, 20 It was like her and my aunts would get together and they would party. 6 That's just what they did, I don't know. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 But it was a lot of drinking. 6, 14, 17 That's where I don't know if her judgment was very good when she was dating the guy she was dating. 13, 14, 15 I don't know. 13, 14, 15 AS: How about your girls? 8 What are they like? 10 When you look back on yourself as a mom? 15, 19 CK: This is what my oldest tells me now—that I was way too strict on her, and I was. 5, 9, 14, 16, 20 I was really scared. 5, 7, 11, 12 I'm a little more lenient with my second one, but with my first it's always like, ""Well why does she get to do that? 9, 10, 16, 17, 20 I couldn't do that when I was young."" 14 It's always like that. 16, 17 But then I realized that I had to let her, my youngest, because I feel like my oldest was like, I feel like I sheltered her too much. 5, 9, 10, 12, 14, 16, 18, 19, 20 She's very smart. 20 She got a full, four year scholarship to the University of Madison, which was only one of ten girls. 8, 11, 13, 20 She didn't end up going. 12 She went every summer, but she ended up going to school here because she had a baby at eighteen, which I thought I was dying when I heard because it was like, I tried to—I told them all how rough it was, I thought I was open. 5, 8, 10, 11, 12, 15, 17, 18, 20 AS: Did they know about sex? 13, 14, 15 CK: Oh yeah. 10 I mean it was probably too much. 16, 18 They were probably like, ""Just stop talking."" 9, 10 My youngest is strong willed, I'll say. 9, 14 She'll be nineteen in June.  AS: Did she finish college? 8 CK: Yeah, she works at the University of Minnesota. 13, 14 I'm not quite sure what she does there, but she just enrolled back into school. 8, 9, 12, 15, 19 AS: And you have a granddaughter or a grandson? 5, 7 I have a granddaughter and a grandson. 5, 7 My grandson is seven months old. 7, 8, 20 My youngest graduated. 8, 9, 14 I was a little nervous about that one. 16 From high school. 8 It was a tough road to get there. 9, 18 Not that she was just—mouthy. 9, 12 She just was very defiant. 8, 9, 12 When I separated from her dad was when she really got—but she's starting to turn around. 8, 9, 11, 19 She just got a job at Wells Fargo. 9, 12 She's going to enroll in MCTC [Minneapolis Community and Technical College].  I don't care what she does, just something. 7, 9, 12 AS: Had they had substance abuse issues? 9, 14, 15 CK: Nope.  I was open with them when they got older why they didn't have a relationship with my dad. 5, 17, 20 I did let them know why. 13, 14, 15, 19 They don't know specifics as far as the stuff 9, 13, 14, 15 I've been through—they know some of it, but I just didn't want them to have to know their grandpa that way. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 AS: So it was just better to not know him. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 CK: I think so just because at the end it was so bad. 9, 12 AS: They were pretty young because he died eight years ago? 14, 18, 20 CK: Has it been that long?  Wow.  It doesn't even seem that long. 15, 19 It was May.  I think you're right, and I can't believe it's been that many years. 14, 20 I just put it so far in the back of my mind. 9, 10, 12, 19 It's probably not healthy to do that, but it just helps me because I don't want to sit and think about how he lived. 9, 12, 13, 14, 18 AS: The thing is too when we're ready, when we're strong enough, or motivated enough, something sparks it, then we do. 9, 20 CK: I just think it was so hard because I looked up to him. 9, 11, 12 He was a fire fighter, he was my dad, he protected me. 15 I was a daddy's girl.  I just didn't understand why wasn't I more important than that. 9, 12, 16 Why can't you see you're hurting me? 12 And that was really hard. 11 AS: And that's nearly impossible.  Do you know that now? 13, 14, 15 AS: You know it intellectually, but you still feel that sadness. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 Because you know he would steal from me. 9, 13, 14, 15 He would steal from everybody. 9 It got that bad.  AS: In these last four years? 9, 20 AS: So as soon as he was retired there was nothing else for him? 12, 19 He tried a little bit. 10 I can't remember how many times he went into treatment, but he would be good for a little bit, and then he would fall back. 9, 16, 18, 19 Then he would try to sober up a little bit. 6, 16 It didn't ever last very long. 9 AS: There's no long period that you remember of months and months? 8 CK: No. And I always wondered—he would get arrested and get out. 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 I don't think he was ever caught with it, it was just paraphernalia. 9, 12 It would never be on him, like drugs. 14, 15 But I guess it's because he would do them. 10 AS: He would get off?  AS: Because do you think they knew him as a firefighter? 6, 12, 15 CK: I don't know. 13, 14, 15 I just think there was never any—he had paraphernalia on him and that was it. 9, 12, 15 He would get off on it.  He would do it again a few months later. 8 Don't they like arrest people for being high and driving? 8, 9, 14, 19 I guess I never thought about the fire fighter thing. 10, 11, 12, 15 AS: Oh yeah. 10 I know people who have been arrested just sitting in their car not even driving. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 CK: That's crazy. 16 AS: And kids who have gotten off when they have crashed on the side of the road. 9, 15 It seems pretty random who gets busted and who doesn't. 7, 9, 16, 18, 19 CK: I guess I never thought about that. 10, 11, 12, 15 I would just be like I don't know if it's because he was a user and that's why he would get out and say he would go to treatment. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I don't know. 13, 14, 15 AS: Have you ever requested any of his records? 6, 7, 9 CK: I could get them, I haven't ever.  I remember after he died the bill collectors—I'll never forget T-Mobile. 15 [laughter]  AS: So he did have a cell phone! 7 CK: Yes!  He did have a flip phone at the end. 7, 12 He did, but it was like they would call non-stop and I'd be like, ""He's dead."" 7, 9, 10 And this would be a year later. 20 And they were like, ""There's no way to take him off this collection."" 6, 10, 16 And I was like, ""You're not getting your money. 10 He is deceased.  Do you need me to send you something?"" 12, 13 They were like, ""It's not going to stop."" 9, 10 I just thought, ""How insensitive."" 9, 11, 12, 13 For a year I got those calls. 7, 20 Then I remember my grandma thought—my grandma was really selfish. 7, 11, 12 His mom. 15 His mom who didn't raise him. 15 I haven't—I've seen her maybe three times since the funeral because it was so—she made me pay her back for the flowers she put on his grave. 9, 10, 16, 18, 19 AS: Because you were the beneficiary— CK: Of nothing!  [laughter]  I mean I don't know why people thought I was going to get this big payout because I knew he didn't have any money left. 6, 8, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I was his beneficiary.  He had, I remember the fire department called me and he had I think it was fifteen hundred dollars, and I said, ""Can you send it to the funeral home to help pay for that."" 7, 12, 13, 15, 16, 19 That was the great inheritance she thought I got. 11, 12 I really think she did.  When we got the cards and everything she made me open them in front of her and the people that gave me money—I had to give her half. 6, 7, 16, 17, 20 I specifically remember a check for six hundred dollars and she was like, ""Now you know you wouldn't get this unless it was for me because these are people I know."" 7, 10, 13, 14, 15 And I was like, ""So what are you saying?"" 10, 11 And my girls were sitting there. 8, 13 I just thought, ""You know, you'll have to answer to someone else bigger than me someday for what you're doing,"" in my mind and I gave it to her. 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 I think I had to give my grandma over a thousand dollars for food and stuff she had contributed to the funeral. 6, 7, 9 And that was really hard. 11 I just don't know how to forgive it. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I know people are like, ""You have to forgive."" 6, 10, 13, 14, 15 And I don't know if I have that in me. 13, 14, 15 AS: Is she impoverished?  She lives in Shorewood.  AS: She didn't raise him?  She's the one that lost custody? 9 My grandma Margaret raised him. 5, 7 I didn't even have enough money to pay for his urn. 15, 16, 20 They let me make payments until I was able to pay it off, and I never—I just really have never had a relationship with her like that. 9, 12, 15, 16, 19 After the first cousin thing and I got older we had a relationship, but it was more like Christmas and holidays. 5, 9, 19, 20 After that I cut it because I feel like my other cousin she would have never done that to ever. 5, 15, 16 When it's your grandma—I think about that with my grandkids. 7 How can you feel okay with that? 16 How can you feel like you are going to benefit from this somehow? 14, 16 I don't know. 13, 14, 15 It was really hard. 11 I know the family is like, ""Well, that's your grandma."" 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 18 My aunt, my dad's sister is like, ""I don't think she's malicious in what she does."" 5, 9, 10 I really think she is.  I really think she knows what she's doing. 13, 14, 15 AS: It's hard to imagine a grandma being malicious, right, we don't want to think about the consequences of that. 7, 11, 13, 14 CK: I really just feel like it was really heartless. 9, 12, 16 I feel like, ""You don't really care what I was going through."" 7, 10, 16 I'm sorry, just random things are coming to me. 7, 9, 10, 12, 16 I remember my uncle had given my dad an air compressor and my dad had pawned it and it was in the pawnshop. 6 My grandma——this is not even two days after my dad, after the funeral she's like, ""Well, he pawned his compressor,"" and I'm like, ""Grandma, I can't go get it, it's in his name."" 6, 7, 10, 15, 19 I had to call a police officer; I had to do all these things to get this air compressor because I was trying to do the right thing. 7, 14, 16 My dad pawned it, who shouldn't have pawned it, I understand that. 9, 12, 16 So, I went to get this air compressor and it was just a source of contention for me. 9, 12, 15 It sat in my garage for over a year, and I was like, ""You hounded me about this."" 10, 20 They never picked it up, so I donated it when I moved. 8, 15 I was like, ""It was that important to you,"" and I felt bad. 10, 17 I felt like, you know, this was my dad who did this stuff. 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 17 I'm trying to just do something right; try to make it right somehow. 9, 12, 14, 16 I just was like, ""You can't even let me mourn my dad without—I know how my dad was. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 I know what he did wrong."" 13, 14, 15 I just was trying to do the right thing, and then for it to sit in my garage for a year? 9, 12, 13, 14, 16, 20 I would get so mad every time I would see it.  AS: Where do you think you got your moral compass?  Your sense of wanting to do right? 13, 14, 17 You said there were things you loved about your dad. 13, 16 CK: I remember there were times where—I don't know where I got it because when I was young I would watch my dad beat up his girlfriend really bad, and I remember thinking, ""I'm never going to let someone do that to me."" 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 I remember that.  I don't know where I got it. 13, 14, 15 I don't know. 13, 14, 15 I don't know if it was just—I just remember I never liked the way I felt as a young child. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18 The situations I was in I always just felt scared or uncomfortable, you know. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 AS: Do you feel better today? 16, 19 CK: I do because I know it's me who I'm responsible for and my kids and I don't have to rely on someone else to take care of me. 6, 7, 13, 14, 15 That's a good question. 6, 9 I guess I don't know. 10, 13, 14, 15 I think working around good people—I really learned a lot from the people I work with. 8, 12, 17 There are three women who I work with who have all been there the same amount of time. 18 AS: Did you have good support from friends when your dad passed away? 12, 16, 18 Do you have a support system? 8, 9 I don't really, so I've always just—I think that's one thing I could do better with my kids because when they're having a hard time I'm like, ""You've got to just pick up. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 17 You don't have time to feel sad about this."" 12, 16 And I do find myself doing that because I was like that.  I remember when my dad died my ex-husband was like, ""You've got to just pick up and keep going,"" and I remember that was probably the beginning of the end with him. 9, 10, 12, 15 He just would not let me mourn. 9, 12, 19 I didn't have time—not that I would have ever fallen apart, but just can people around me just give me a moment to do nothing and just sit? 6, 9, 12, 13, 15, 20 And it was never like that, so now I see that I do that with my kids and I try to correct myself, but I do see that in myself, like, ""No one is going to do this for you."" 10, 14, 15, 16 Kind of a little insensitive I think, I mean, honestly that's how I feel. 9, 13, 16 I know and I see it in me, and I try. 13, 14, 15, 16 AS: It might read as insensitive, but it seems like you had to do it for survival to keep yourself going because a lot of bad things could have happened to you. 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 You could be not the person that you are right now sitting in front of me. 13, 14 Do you know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 It takes—you can go one way or the other, and I remember thinking that as a small kid: 6, 16 I'm not going to live like this when I'm older. 5, 20 This is not how I'm going to live.  I'm not perfect.  AS: That came from inside you. 19 Like I said I'm not perfect, I just knew I wanted a stable place to live, I wanted a family, I wanted to just try to be normal whatever that means. 6, 9, 11, 12, 13, 16, 18 AS: Do you ever talk to your mom about your dad? 10, 15 You said you guys are close.  We have talked, yeah. 10, 11 He was abusive to her, too, physically. 7, 9, 11 They were never together though, they were separated when I was a baby, so I've never seen them in the same room except for a courtroom. 5, 7, 11, 15 I remember when we were going to court for custody with my mom and my dad. 9, 15 My dad—I remember we lived in these apartments, I don't know how old I was, I can't remember, I was really young. 13, 14, 15, 20 I don't remember the circumstances, but I remember my dad grabbing me and running, running down the street with me and I remember the cops throwing him on the ground. 7, 8, 9, 11 I remember I thought they were going to hurt him and I was so scared. 5, 7, 11, 12 Not that he was—I think he was just taking me from my mom. 9, 12, 15 I don't know why, I don't know any of the circumstances behind it, but I remember watching the police do that to him. 7, 9, 13, 14, 15 We lived in an apartment on Lake [Street] right by K-Mart. 14, 20 [laughter]  AS: That's still an intense place. 9, 11, 15 I remember it was in the summer and there were all kinds of people out watching. 16, 17 This was on the street. 9 He took me from the apartment building. 20 The courtroom I just remember they would ask me, ""Who do you want to live with? 7, 9, 12, 13 Who do you want?"" 13 And I would say whatever anybody wanted to hear. 12, 13 It wasn't what I wanted because I didn't want to hurt anybody. 12, 13 I think about that now, like I was way too young for that. 14, 16 Way too young. 14 AS: I hope they have learned something. 10, 12, 17 I'm just sorry for all the people who had to experience that in the seventies and the eighties. 9, 10, 12, 15 I think the eighties was probably the peak of that.  CK: I think they have.  And they would ask me in front of both of them.  Like, how?  [laughter]  AS: So what is your take on addiction and people who struggle with it? 6, 9 What do you notice and what do you wish was different? 16, 17 Do you read about it or think about it very often? 12, 15 I think people associate it with people who have had rough lives, but I don't think that is at all what it is. 18 I think it's the people we hang around, the people we—as young kids—who we associate with, where if you're daring—I just feel like you can't pinpoint it to one reason why people—sometimes there's no reason and it's just curiosity. 5, 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 16, 18 Some people aren't strong enough to overcome that curiosity. 9, 13, 19, 20 Some people are.  Some people can do it one time, and that's it and be done with it and some people can't.  I think it doesn't have any bearing on how you were raised. 5 AS: What do you wish would change about the way we deal with addiction from your perspective? 13, 16 CK: I wish the medical field would care a little bit more. 7, 14 I really wish they would not treat them as not people or that they don't deserve health care or that they don't deserve to be treated kindly. 7, 14, 16, 17 I see it all—I even see it now. 14, 15 I see the way the nurses talk about it at my job, and I don't say anything. 10, 16 AS: What do they say?  CK: They're like, ""Oh, yeah, they're just here to get their fix and then they're back on the street again. 9, 10, 12, 16, 19 But guess what? 10 They're fixed up when they leave the door so they'll be in next week for their next..."" you know? 6, 13, 14, 15, 16 It's stuff like that. 9 I know they're probably frustrated because I work at Abbott [Northwestern Hospital], which is in the middle of—you know? 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I see it all day long. 19 I guess I'm not a healthcare provider, so I don't know how frustrating it is to have to deal with people like that, but I know what it's like to have to live with someone like that and know that they deserve to be treated the same way anyone else would, regardless of—not that they should be prescribed pills and leave, but, treat them—I just remember how my dad was treated when I went into regions. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 It was like—they just treated him like he wasn't a person. 9, 12, 16 I remember like, ""Can you please do something? 10 Can you please scan his head?""  Because my dad never complained about headaches or anything, and I was like, ""Can you just do something? 9, 10, 12, 15 And they were like, ""There's nothing we can do. 10 We gave him two—"" I don't remember what it was, and sent him on his way. 7, 16 I was like, ""You're not going to do anything?"" 10 AS: And later he was back in there in the MRI? 19 CK: It was about a week and a half later. 20 He was transported by ambulance to Unity Hospital and that's when he had the stroke. 7, 9 I never asked how—who called. 7, 10, 15 I know it was his girlfriend, but I didn't know her very well. 12, 13, 14, 15 She was a user, too. 9 Something must have happened, I don't know, and that's when I got a call saying, ""Your dad's in the hospital. 7, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 We think he may have had a stroke. 9 Can you come down?"" 13, 19 Then when I got there I remember the nurse saying, ""Do you know her?"" 11, 13, 14, 15 And his mouth was open and that was the last time he was conscious. 9, 17 I remember when the doctor pulled me into the room and said, ""You have to make a decision."" 7, 16 And I struggled with it because I struggle with religion. 9 I don't know what I believe. 13, 14, 15 I believe in something I just don't know what. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I don't know what type of religion he was because he was trying to comfort people—the hospital chaplain. 13, 14, 15, 16 I'm just looking at everybody and I was just like, ""This does not comfort me."" 9, 10, 12 I asked if I could speak to him alone and I just said, ""I hear you saying he's going to go to a better place and you're praying, but what if you don't believe that? 9, 10, 11, 12 What if you don't know?"" 13, 14, 15 And I can't even remember how he explained it to me. 15 He explained it somehow with being born and— AS: Because he was trying to convince you that your dad should be taken off? 6, 16 CK: No, he was trying to convince me that he was going to be okay. 16 That he was going to be in a better place. 11 I think that's how he was comforting everybody.  I was just sitting there and I was like, ""This isn't working for me."" 9, 10, 12, 13 [laughs]  AS: You started to say that you never say anything to the nurses—what would happen if you did? 9, 11, 12, 15 What would you say?  CK: Sometimes I just want to be like, ""You have no idea what it's like to be that person or a loved one of that person, you know?"" 5, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18 AS: Would you get in trouble for saying something like that? 11 CK: I don't know. 13, 14, 15 AS: One of the things that I keep coming up against is that the only way—and this isn't to put any guilt onto you—but the only way that we can break that stigma is by calling people out on it. 7, 9, 10, 12, 16, 18 It's the same with sexism and the same with racism.  It's just the next thing we have to do or keep doing on a new topic. 6, 9, 12 AS: I had that experience of my daughter being referred to as an ‘OD’, and it just pierced me in a way. 5, 9, 12, 16 And my sister who is a doctor—my daughter is completely unconscious, completely hooked up to everything you could imagine—my sister who had come, who is a family physician, came up from Texas and she saw me and she just went into the hall and was like—because this guy was a resident or something—""It would be really good if you didn't say that in front of family."" 5, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 18, 19 And they do, it is part of the work, they can't think of everyone with all these feelings and all this. 16 They are in a field where they're supposed to be helping people who are suffering, right? 6, 13, 14 The nurses at Unity were very, very nice to me.  They have a different approach at Unity. 16, 17 CK: Yeah, I felt like they did. 17 I felt like they had compassion for what he was going through, for what everyone was going through at the time. 17 I didn't feel like they treated him just like he didn't matter. 9, 12, 16, 20 There is one other thing.  I remember when he was dying they gave him morphine and my grandma had a really hard time with me okaying him to have morphine. 7, 11 She said, ""He doesn't need that."" 13 I said, ""Grandma, he's probably in there withdrawing on top of going through all of this and he is trying to fight this."" 7, 14, 16 This is my thought. 11, 12 And she didn't want him to have morphine and it was like, ""I don't care what you think at this point."" 7, 10, 13 AS: Could it matter at that point? 20 CK: Right, it didn't.  But these were the challenges I had in the hospital. 10 I remember them telling me, ""He's not going to make it,"" and my grandma, for almost two days, the family thought that he was going to come out of it because he would twitch, but they told me when you twitch, when they do pain tests on him you don't go in, you try to get away from the pain and he would twitch in—his hands would twitch in. 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 16, 18, 19, 20 I remember I told her I didn't want all kinds of people at the hospital. 13, 16, 17, 20 I just wanted to deal with this as him, me, you, and my aunt, and the whole family was up there. 9, 12, 13, 18 I was so angry.  I didn't leave the room—they were in the waiting room—I didn't leave his side. 6, 7 For three days I sat there. 19 I had to wear gloves because he had MRSA. 13 I just didn't like it because I was like, ""My dad is not going to want people to see him like this."" 9, 10, 12, 13 His fever was like one hundred and six, and it was just bad. 9, 12 Antibiotics did nothing.  After he had the stroke he was done. 9 I don't know why it took three days for them to finally say—because I remember the nurses telling me very early, ""It's in his main bloodstream. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 He's not coming out of this.""  They didn't say it like that, but they were very nice about it.  I just said, ""I want to know, honestly, I want to know the truth,"" because I needed to prepare. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I needed to know what I was doing. 13, 14, 15 I knew his wishes—we had talked about what he wanted. 6, 10, 11, 12, 13 He didn't want to be kept on life support. 11, 13 I mean probably all kinds of other stuff will come to mind, but it's just that I've never really sat and talked about it. 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19 AS: I'm just so honored that you sat and talked to a total stranger about it. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12 CK: It feels good to talk about it. 10, 16 AS: Good.  Well, you're really a remarkable person to have gone through what you did and to hold on the way you have and to get through that. 16, 20 You must have come into this world pretty darn strong. 9, 13, 15, 18, 19 You're not a newbie! 6 You've got some power in you. 15 That's a powerful story. 9, 15 I'm really sorry that you lost your dad. 9, 10 I'm sorry about all of it. 10 CK: Thank you.  I think he's—there's a museum, I don't know if it's still there, I should look—it's of fire fighters. 9, 13, 14, 15 I'll have to look it up and see if I can find it.  AS: Look it up and share that with me.  I would appreciate knowing more. 13, 14, 15 CK: And the fire department gave me all of the awards he won for things he had done. 15, 16 And the picture of the girl in the Star Tribune.  It has her name on it, but I just—I should share that with you. 6, 9, 12 AS: Yeah, I would love to see that. 13 CK: I think it was in Minneapolis.  It looked like she was Native American, I can't—I don't know. 13, 14, 15 AS: Thank you,  Chandra. 14 CK: You're welcome. 13, 19"
"12","Espuche_Nancy","Rose McKinney Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 16, 2016 St. Paul, Minnesota Rose McKinney-RM  Amy Sullivan-AS RM: Yes, my name is Rose McKinney and I give Amy permission for this interview. 6 AS: Thank you.  Rose, could you start by talking a little bit about what your childhood was like, where you grew up, your education, and your career. 7, 9, 10, 11 What you do today. 19 RM: I am the youngest of three daughters. 5, 9, 14 There is a fair amount of gap in between, which makes things interesting. 9, 16, 18, 19 I have one sister that is seven years older and a sister that is twelve years older. 5, 9, 20 So my parents had me a little bit later in their life. 10, 11, 16 Before 1966 it was kind of a rare thing. 16, 17 My mom was almost forty-one when I was born. 9, 15 Had a great childhood. 11 Growing up my parents owned a business. 9, 10, 16 Prior to that they had moved around a fair amount with my dad’s jobs. 8, 18 Before that he had been in the army. 19 My sisters had transplanted childhoods. 5, 7, 9, 11 My childhood was pretty much all in one place. 11, 18 I grew up in Des Moines, Iowa.  Close with my sisters. 5, 9 Close with my parents. 10, 16 A couple of interesting things about my background. 8, 9, 16, 19 I went to boarding school at age fourteen. 5, 8 I went back out East. 9, 19 I spent my high school years away from home. 8, 16, 19, 20 In some regards, that may have been the sanest thing that could have happened. 9, 12, 13 I was a good kid, but I didn’t take things for granted. 6, 7, 16 I would push my dad’s buttons and we would get into round and round discussions. 8 I think that it was probably a good thing that allowed me to begin to see those ideas and opinions and independence which probably brought us closer when we did get together at holidays and summer were really enjoyable times. 9, 11, 12, 18, 19 They liked to hear about what I was thinking versus the day to day stuff. 9, 10, 18, 19 I went to college. 8 I originally thought that I would like to be a broadcast journalist. 9, 10, 11, 12 I thought I wanted to be the next Jane Polly on the Today Show. 11, 12, 13, 19 Interview interesting people. 9, 19 Hear their stories. 9, 18 I quickly learned that the route to become that was not something I was interested in. 9, 11, 12, 13, 17, 19 I didn’t want to—by who, what, when, and where. 13 The kind of life of a reporter. 11, 16, 17 I found that I was really interested in telling deeper stories. 9, 11, 18, 19 I wanted to know why organizations weren’t talking about all these other things. 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 They said, “Oh you need to be in public relations.” 13 I had no idea what that was. 11 I took a PR class and the very first day of class we talked about the definition and building mutually beneficial relationships and helping organizations create understanding. 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16, 19, 20 That’s pretty much what I focused on in college and started my career in public relations. 7, 8, 9, 11, 15, 18 Met my husband while I was still in college and we got engaged and got married right after I graduated. 8, 9, 14, 15 That takes me into my motherhood piece. 6 I had been working for about nine months and I got pregnant. 8 In 1988, ‘89, there was not job sharing.  There was not flexible hours. 11 We didn’t have email!  AS: You couldn’t really work from home. 19 RM: There really weren’t any of these things. 16 I remember going to my boss and saying, “You know, I’m not sure that I can come back full time after this baby comes.” 5, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 They said, “Well, put together some sort of proposal.” 10, 17 “What do you think?”  And my daughter ended up being born three weeks early and I never got my proposal put together. 5, 10, 12, 15 They started calling me and saying, “Hey do you think you could at least finish the newsletter project? 6, 7, 9, 11, 13, 19 Do you think you could work on the publicity for this client?” 20 I was able to freelance and be a mom. 15 It was pretty incredible. 12, 18 I was freelancing a little bit part time.  Mothering, young mother at age 23. 14 Three years later baby two came along in 1992. 19, 20 At that point I was still doing some freelance work and a lot more volunteering like in a Montessori school and these kinds of things. 8, 9, 16, 17 I had an opportunity through a freelance project to go back to work full time in 1996. 11, 19 I loved that opportunity. 13 Working full time. 11 We were lucky to have some nannies that worked out really well for our family. 18 And then we got pregnant with baby number three. 5 And we said, “Oh my gosh. 17 I loved my job. 13 Let’s just see what happens with trying it this way.” 9, 12, 16 So I had been the stay at home mom with the freelancing and I had been the full time mom and it worked out really well with baby number three to continue working full time and not freelance. 5, 9, 11, 15, 19 That’s kind of the motherhood journey. 16, 17 AS: As your kids got older, can you talk about your son, was he the middle child? 5, 8, 10, 20 Can you talk about what he was like? 10 What your other kids were like? 10 How you navigated the difficulties? 20 RM: Great relationship.  In fact, because of the three year difference between Julia and Ryan, Ryan and I were really close. 10, 20 She was in Montessori school. 8 In the mornings, drop her off for a couple of hours and then Ryan and I had a lot of one on one time together. 11, 14, 17 Which was really special.  I think to this day we have a close relationship. 19 We enjoy spending time together one on one. 12, 19 I credit it back to those early years. 12, 19, 20 We would have those mornings together.  Then, pick Julie up from preschool, go home, have lunch, naps. 6, 8, 19 I would work on projects.  Life was pretty good. 18 Ryan always had a good sense of humor. 16, 17 He was always a very mature kid. 16, 17 He would hang out with his older sister and her friends. 5, 9, 12, 18, 20 He was kind of the tag along in the neighborhood. 8, 16, 17 He was the youngest in the group of six or seven kids that all hung out together. 9, 14 The interesting thing with Ryan is he was always so good natured and happy and everything. 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 Every once in awhile if he would get out of sorts or fussy or irritable, backtalking, what not. 10, 17, 19 I would get frustrated and send him to his room or something like that. 7, 9, 12 The interesting thing is that generally within a matter of minutes he would be asleep. 7, 9, 19, 20 Or he would be getting sick.  I came to recognize when he was out of sorts he was either exhausted and needed a nap, or was, you know, an ear infection was coming on or a cold. 9, 13, 14, 15, 17, 19, 20 The getting sick would maybe show up the next day or something. 9, 19 It was intersesting because at the time you don’t realize it. 9, 14 This kid is being crazy, or separation. 16 Then you would go, “Oh, now I get it.” 14 Like anything you would recognize, “Oh, I need to pay more attention. 13, 15, 16 Just because he isn’t taking naps anymore regularily I need to see if he is tired.” 9, 12, 13 And say, “Don’t react to the behavior.” 10 So fast forward, I wish that had been in my mind. 9 Hindsight.  I can say, “Oh, we missed some things. 16 AS: Can you give any examples? 6 RM: I think when he would, he got into high school we started to notice he was struggling around junior year. 8, 9, 11, 20 Didn’t want to participate in a lot of family things. 13, 16, 17, 18 Back talking, argumentative, keeping to himself, breaking the rules. 10, 11, 12, 18 Not anything bad.  Just little stuff. 9 Didn’t seem interested in anything. 9, 11, 19 He has always been such a smart kid that school was always kind of boring. 8, 16, 17, 20 We got concerned about that and went to the doctor to rule out if it was depression or who knows what was going on. 12, 13, 14, 15 Even at that point my husband and I said, “Do you think he could be using drugs?” 14, 15 We didn’t have any real, hard reason to believe it. 11 But we weren’t naive enough to think that his behavior and his mood couldn’t be related to that. 20 That is one example of the differences in how he is behaving. 6 He is not the same person right now. 14 What else could be going on in his life? 11 He will tell us now that he didn’t feel like he fit in. 14, 16 And yet, he had tons of friends. 12, 18 He would say he didn’t feel comfortable in all these social situations and yet he was always mister center of attention. 9, 13, 15, 16, 17 I think there are a lot of times where your perception of yourself is not necessarily what other people are seeing and experiencing. 17, 18 My thought now is when there is this big gap between what one person perceives and what the self perceives, you need to stop and figure out why and what. 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14 So, we noticed it.  We tried to stop it. 9, 10 Couldn’t get at anything.  At that point he couldn’t articulate what was going on.  You couldn’t even have the deep conversation to get at it! 12, 15 AS: Did you bring him to a doctor around that time?  Or did you just go yourselves? 9, 12 RM: We took him to a doctor.  That was actually very disappointing. 10 My husband took him. 15 They had been very close throughout childhood. 11 You know, Boundary Water trips, coaching sports, watching movies. 13, 14, 15 Just really lots of good, active father son time. 5, 9, 10, 17 It was my husband that actually identified it. 10, 15 Said,  “I think something is off.”  I was a little more like, “Yeah, you know, teenager.” 10, 13, 14, 15 They went and that ended up being somewhat dissapointing because the doctor ruled out anything physical. 12 “Maybe some family counciling would help. 11, 13, 18 It’s tough being a kid these days.” 19 My husband asked the doctor, “Did you do a drug test?” and the doctor said, “I don’t think that’s what’s going on. 9, 10, 14, 15 I just think its really tough being a kid these days. 9, 12, 19 He’s a good kid.  Just some counseling.” 9 I don’t know if anything would have shown up at that point or not, but I am apalled that as long as they were doing blood and urine tests anyway that they wouldn’t at least check. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 And again, it might have come and said no, there is nothing in the system. 8, 9, 13, 19 AS: But if you don’t check, you don’t know. 13, 14, 15 RM: Exactly. 10 That was one of the first frustrating things. 9, 16 From there we did go to see a counselor. 10 Both independently and together. 12 The counselor would talk to us and say, “Yeah, it sure sounds like maybe that’s what’s going on.” 9, 10, 15, 16 And then he would talk to our son and he couldn’t get anything concrete. 10 So, there are these two different things going on. 16, 17 I believe the counselor knew there was drug use, but because my son wouldn’t come right out and say it, or he always had some kind of excuse, he could snow ball or tip toe around. 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 We had group sessions and it just didn’t work. 9, 12 When we started finding marijuana and that kind of stuff then it would just get into the arguments over, “Well it’s good for you, or everybody does it, or get off my back, or it should be legal.” 9, 11, 12, 16, 17, 19 Again, it just went round and round and round. 8, 9, 12 We did find evidence senior year of high school that it was more than pot. 8, 20 We kept saying, “This just doesn’t seem like it could only be pot.” 9, 11, 12, 19 You know? 13, 14, 15 Yet we didn’t— AS: What was the evidence?  RM: We found strips of aluminum foil with burn marks in the car. 7, 9 Took it to the police who said, “Yeah, it’s likely heroin. 7, 10 Could be meth or something. 5 Likely heroin.”  AS: This is his senior year? 20 RM: This is his senior year at this point. 20 And yeah, ask him about it. 10 “I’ve never seen it. 15 I don’t know what that is.” 13, 14, 15 And we said, “You know what, you are responsible for other people in your car.” 7, 13, 14, 15 He would just come up with all kinds of wild things. 9, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 “Well, maybe someone was in my car when I was at class.” 7, 9, 20 [laughs]  I mean this is the type of thing. 16 We would get into these logical things that were, you know, if someone was watching us they would be like why? 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 There was just all these circular arguments. 9, 12 You would just get lost in it. 9, 12 So, whether it was him or someone he was with, clearly someone was using heroin.  Fast forward a couple years after that when he was in inpatient treatment. 9, 16, 20 He comes forward in our first family meeting and says, “I want to tell you I’ve been using opiates and heroin.” 9, 13, 18, 19 And we just looked at him and said, “Yeah. 9, 12 We know this.” 13, 14, 15 And he thought it was some big confession and he still made it sounds like it had only been a few months. 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 16 AS: How long was it?  RM: At least a couple of years. 9, 20 If he had been using full time, or regularly, it was there. 11 I thought back to all the times that I had found a roll of tin foil in his backpack or a roll of tin foil in the car. 7, 11, 12, 18, 19 All those things and you are like, “It’s been there.” 10, 16 AS: Right in front of you.  Right in front.  And we knew it. 6, 12 I mean you can do plenty. 16 You can talk about it, you can encourage conversation. 10, 12 We went and got smart, we went and got knowledgeable, we found out about it. 13, 14, 15, 20 But when I say, “What can you do?”  The cliche that always comes to mind is you can always lead the horse to water but you can’t make it drink. 6, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 And the adage that you can salt the oats.  I feel like that was kind of— AS: That made his life more difficult towards recovery? 11, 16, 17, 20 And not even necessarily more difficult, but you can make more encouragement. 15, 16, 20 You can say, “Hey, we can help. 13 College is possible when you go to treatment. 9, 16 We might be able to help you out with the car. 7, 13 We can do things.” 16 Because the drugs have hijacked his brain, even if those offers sounded good he couldn’t give up. 6, 10, 14, 15 It takes a long time for parents to, or anybody that loves somebody that is using, to come to understand that there is really nothing you can say or do that is going to be compelling enough for them to go, “This thing that I survive on, that I enjoy, or that maybe I don’t enjoy it anymore but I survive on it, I can’t give that up.” 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 16, 19, 20 They can’t see that road forward. 9 AS: What was your relationship with him like at this time?  RM: We maintained regular contact. 10 Call, text, have him come over for dinner. 13, 19 We probably did see him at least once a week. 9 Sometimes maybe it was— AS: While he was using? 5, 9, 18 RM: Yeah, while he was using.  Most of the time it was pleasant enough. 20 As long as we avoided talking about use. 9, 10 Or talking about going to treatment or something. 9, 10, 16 We would have this back and forth between should we continue to try and talk it through and get him to see what is going on and get some help? 10, 13, 16, 19 Which would usually escalate and not go anywhere. 10 Or, should we just let him know that the family is here and the home is here and that we love him, and that he is welcome, and let him know too that guess what? 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 While he is choosing these other things right now, our life is going on. 11, 14, 16 Guess what, we are going on vacation? 10 Guess what, we are going to a movie.  Our life is still going on and you could be part of that. 9, 11 AS: Did you just kind of naturally have that response? 9, 12, 16, 17 Did you get help from other people that were familiar with addiction or teenagers? 13, 18 Early on, right at the start of 2011, things had really gotten out of control. 9, 11, 14, 15, 16, 17 I will back up a little of the history. 9, 19 He had graduated in June 2010. 8 He had a scholarship to go to college and then decided not to do that, and he was using. 8, 12 We had a horrible summer of running away, and being out at all hours, and sleeping all day. 7, 11, 16, 17, 19 He was living the addiction lifestyle. 6, 9, 11 We were still figuring out what was—I mean we knew he was using pot. 6, 9, 12, 16 We had found the strips of tin foil. 9 We knew things weren’t right. 6, 12, 14, 16 We were in that sorting out period, and seeing a counselor off and on. 10, 17 He decided at the end of the summer that he was not going to go to college. 8, 12 Which on the one hand was disappointing because a) he had this scholarship and b) we were excited for him to be out of the house. 6, 9 [laughs]  He announces that he is going to go to community college and keep working his job. 8, 12 We are like, “Then the ground rules are,” and that ended up being a horrific semester. 8, 9, 12 We could tell that his…  he wasn’t happy. 17 He was always angry. 16, 17 He was always tired. 12, 16, 17 AS: Was he living at home? 6, 19 RM: He was living at home. 6, 19 I would check the mileage on the car. 7 He would say he was going to be one place and not. 11 During this, the counselor we were working with, our son was a tennis player, Ryan did decide that he might go to school that second semester. 8, 9, 10, 15, 20 We jointly decided that it would be good if he stayed in tennis. 5, 9, 12, 15 So, we paid for him to stay in tennis at the health club and continue working with the team. 9, 14, 15 It was a very talented team and in fact was a team that qualified for nationals. 10 Some of these kids played at state and went on and did phenomenal things. 8, 9, 16 He would go to practice, but somehow the miles between home and practice were a lot more than they should be in the car. 7, 10, 17, 19 We know in hindsight he was making his rounds. 8, 13, 14, 15 He would say, “Oh, after practice I’m going to such and such with so and so.” 10 Of course, that wasn’t what he was doing.  We just kept catching him in a lie, catching him in a lie, catching him in a lie. 9, 10, 12 For a while, it was data finding.  Like being a detective.  Then after a while you keep finding the same things and it still doesn’t make any sense. 9, 12, 16, 17 All you can say is this is addiction.  This is bad.  Anyways, at the last minute, he did decide he would go second semester and the school said they would honor his scholarship. 8, 9, 16, 17, 20 A spot on the men’s tennis team was still open. 9, 15, 17 This is when things really—this is the turning point. 16, 19 We took him up on Sunday and said goodbye and that week didn’t hear from him. 19 I texted him a couple of times. 18 I thought, you know, part of it is he needs that space. 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: Was college far away? 8, 16 RM: Up in Duluth.  St. Scholastica. 9 Not that far, a couple of hours. 11 I was headed out of town for a business trip and my husband and younger son were going to come with me and spend a weekend. 5, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 That morning I tried to contact him again. 10 Didn’t hear from him.  The whole weekend we were in New York didn’t hear from him. 12, 19 Didn’t hear from him.  We both said you know, if something was wrong I’m sure we would have heard. 13, 14, 15 So, that Sunday when my husband got home, he checked the phone records and there had been no activity on the phone. 6, 7, 10, 15, 19 This is not good.  Not good.  We could see some calls coming in. 7 That night, at the hotel, I got a phone call from Ryan and—let me back up. 7, 19 When we dropped him off for school that Sunday I’m giving him a hug and I’m saying, “Clean slate,” and he said, “I know mom.” 8, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 He said, “I won’t fuck up again.”  So that Sunday when he called me he said, “Mom, I fucked up again.” 7, 19 And I said, “What happened?” 12, 13 The way it went down is that that Friday night, he and the college kids had been partying. 6, 8, 16, 19 Drinking and what not.  Drinking, marijuana, and some pills and I’m not sure what. 15 He passed out in the snow. 14 This is January in Duluth, subzero temperatures.  He was taken by ambulance to the ER and then put into detox. 6, 10 At that point the school was trying to work with him and the coach was trying to work with him. 8, 16 The coach, when we had been talking before, and I had said, “You really need to keep him on a short leash. 10, 12, 13, 16 School and tennis.” 15 We talked a little bit. 10, 11 I didn’t ever tell the coach what had been going on those six months, but I just said it has been a really rough six months and senior year was rough. 8, 9, 12, 18, 20 I said, “You don’t know how much he needs to be on this team and in classes. 8, 13, 14, 15, 18, 20 If he’s got structure maybe he’ll find a path forward.” 9, 14 The coach said, “Yeah, yeah, yeah.” 10 After this had happened the coach said, “I didn’t realize. 12, 13, 14 Now I know what you mean by a short leash.” 13, 14, 15, 16 And again, we couldn’t control it. 17 He couldn’t control it. 17 But, maybe he would have gotten more than a week, I don’t know. 9, 13, 14, 15 So, fast forward again a couple weeks later. 9 I get a phone call, I get home from teaching. 7, 19 It is about ten o’clock at night. 19 This time it is the Dean of Students: “Mrs. McKinney, don’t worry, Ryan is okay, but I need to inform you that we have just sent him in a taxi to a hotel and we are going to put him up for a week. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 17 He has been using drugs in the dormitory. 14 He has been talked to. 10, 11 He has ignored our conversations. 12 Therefore, we are revoking his housing privileges.”  He wasn’t kicked out of school because he wasn’t failing his classes. 8, 20 Talk about a rock and a hard space. 11 You can go to school here but you can’t live on campus and eat in the dining hall. 8 Where does he live?  We’ll put him up for a week in a hotel. 10 Oh my gosh. 17 Well, he just plummeted. 5, 9, 12 At this point he is using all the time, he is not making friends, well, not those friends. 12, 18 Depression is sinking in.  He doesn’t have anywhere to go.  We are trying to—is there an apartment, is there someone you can room with? 7, 16, 20 He isn’t a problem solving—at all.  He doesn't actually want to solve this problem at all. 10, 13 He stays on the sofa at somebody else's place for a while. 9, 11 Then, of course, he gets sick.  It is difficult to get transportation to class so then he’s not going to class. 7, 20 By the middle of February, he’s not going to class, he doesn’t have a place to live, he has no income. 8, 11, 13, 19, 20 It’s a disaster. 9, 20 At that point, this is a long answer to your questions, I had sought out a therapist because this was a lot to deal with. 6, 9, 13, 17 I had had one appointment and was kind of describing what was going on. 16, 17 It was on a Thursday. 19 Saturday my husband and I were going to go up and see my son and sit down and have a face to face with him. 13, 15, 19 Try to figure things out. 13, 16 So, we go up there, we pick up his stuff at his friend’s place, we have that in the car. 7, 9, 11, 12 We go and have lunch. 6 Overall, it was a friendly conversation. 12 One of the things he had been interested in was the military. 9, 11, 16, 19 Even at the end of high school when he wasn’t sure he wanted to go to college, he thought maybe he would go into the air force or do something like that. 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 15 He went down for his meeting and he admitted that he smoked marijuana. 13, 17 They said, “Okay, you have to wait for thirty days. 19 Don’t smoke for thirty days and you will be fine.” 14, 19 Of course he couldn’t do it.  He kept postponing that. 9 Another thing that had come up in high school was he looked into the naval academy. 8, 13, 19 He had started the application process. 9, 10, 11 He did not finish it, but he started the process. 9, 11 He was in the top twenty candidates.  He had a high likelihood of getting accepting. 8, 10 This shows how smart he is. 20 So we are at lunch and we said, you know, you could always reopen your application and try that direction for next year. 6, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 20 There is still time. 9 Just trying to get him to think about options. 7, 9, 16 My husband had gone to the bathroom. 7, 15 I said get your laptop and we can pull stuff up and see what we could do. 9 He looks at me and he goes, “Mom, dad’s going to kill me. 7 I don’t have my laptop.”  And I said, “What do you mean you don’t have your laptop?” 16 “I sold my laptop.” 20 And then, “I sold my laptop because I had to pay some rent to the people I was staying with.” 9, 16, 19, 20 Well we know it wasn’t for paying rent. 11, 13, 14, 15, 16 That was the, “Oh my gosh.” 17 At that point we said, “You know what? 13, 14, 15 We are going to get into the car and go home. 7, 19 You are welcome to get into the car with us and head down 35 back to Minneapolis. 7, 13, 19 And that will give you a couple of hours to figure out what you are going to do. 6, 11, 13 Because you know what? 13, 14, 15 You are not bringing this chaos back into the house.” 6, 9, 19 That was crazy talk. 10, 16 AS: Had you offered him treatment along the way at this point? 9, 12, 16 RM: Well, counseling.  AS: But not treatment. 9, 16 RM: Right, because at that point we didn’t really know that that was what he needed. 13, 14, 15 We didn’t quite have the handle on what he was using, how he was using, and any of that.  At that point then he came back. 19 He lived with some family friends that would benefit from some rent. 12, 14, 16, 18 We paid for him to be able to stay there. 9 We thought close with trusted people but not in the same house where things will turn into these round and round discussions. 6, 8, 9, 11, 12, 16, 19 We would see him on a regular basis, several days a week, talk to him on the phone. 7, 10, 19 He was still thinking of the military at this point, but the reserves were—work together could never make that appointment. 9, 15, 16 We know why he couldn’t make that appointment. 13, 14, 15, 16 It was just kind of like this pretend effort toward things. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 Finally, things were getting worse and worse. 16 He was becoming quite depressed. 12 The lies were out of control. 17 Delusional lies.  The family that he was living with one day the son called me and he said, “I don’t think he is going to work. 6, 7, 18, 19 He is telling me this thing about how his bike got stolen and all of this.” 9, 18 Things just don’t add up to me.” 9, 12 And I said, “Well let me tell you what has been going on.” 19 He goes, “Yeah I think this is what is going on.  This is what I’m observing.”  One particular day Ryan couldn’t get out of bed. 18, 19 The friend called and said, “He hasn’t left the house, he hasn’t gotten up, he’s just…” 6, 7, 9, 12, 15 My husband and I come, and he was in a deep depression. 13, 15, 19 Just feeling terrible and rotten. 9, 15, 16 At that point I just asked him, “Do you think that the drugs are making you feel better, worse, or the same?” 9, 10, 12, 14, 16 And he said, “Well, I don’t think they are making me feel better.” 16 We thought that was a huge insight. 11, 12 We said, “We really think that you need to go into a treatment program.” 9, 13, 16 The counselor at this point finally recommended he should go to counseling and get some psychological testing. 9, 10, 12 They said, “Until you are sober we can’t address the mental if there is in fact mental. 6, 10, 14 So, you need to get sober.” 6, 13 He wouldn’t go and he was supposed to try and find a place on his own because he didn’t like what we were recommending. 6, 10, 11, 12, 16 That didn’t come up with anything. 13, 19 We found this place out in Montana called the Wilderness Treatment Center. 7, 11 We thought he would really like it because it was for boys fourteen to twenty-four, nice age range. 7, 8, 10, 11, 12 Hiking, backpacking, and he likes—that kind of stuff. 9, 10, 16, 17, 19 He halfheartedly—I wouldn’t say halfheartedly—he agreed to go. 20 He was going to go the next day. 19 We were getting packed and filling everything out and that afternoon he wanted to call his grandpa to say happy birthday and he said he was going to tell his grandpa but he didn’t. 7, 12, 13, 17, 19 He also wanted to go see his girlfriend. 12, 13 They were kind of on the odds at the time and he wanted to go see one of his best friends from kindergarten to tell him what was going on. 9, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17, 18 He didn’t come home that night. 13, 19 Which we could have— The next morning he showed up and my husband was there when he came home and he didn’t know where he slept. 7, 13, 14, 15, 19 He said, “It doesn’t look like he slept anywhere.  He didn’t sleep at somebody’s house.” 6, 7, 9 We found out later he never did go to the friend’s. 12, 15 Who knows? 13, 14, 15 He came in and he fell asleep on the sofa in our home downstairs. 7, 9, 15, 19 This is late morning.  He stayed asleep until ten o’clock at night. 5, 7, 9, 19 Meanwhile, I’m getting his bag packed, finishing all the paperwork, got the plane tickets, they are supposed to leave the next morning. 6, 13 He wakes up at ten o’clock at night and it was the worst night of my life because my husband and I decided that my husband would go to bed since they had to get up early and I would stay up with Ryan and hopefully he would go back to sleep. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 15, 19 Of course we ended up staying up for hours talking about, I wrote a blog about this, how did we get here? 9, 10, 11, 12, 19 He says to me, “I just don’t understand how we got here?” 9, 12, 16 [laughs]  AS: Your son said this?  And he’s like, “I don’t think this is the right thing for me. 10, 14 I don’t think I need this.” 13 At first it’s, “I don’t think this is the right thing. 9, 14 I don’t think I need this.” 13 And then it got ugly.  Because of dad.  All this stuff. 9 And I was just adament, “Nope, tomorrow you and dad are getting on a plane. 9, 12, 13 At the end of sixty days we’ll talk.” 10, 12, 19 I tried to put it in the positive: “You know what? 10, 13, 14, 15 You will feel better. 16 You deserve to feel better. 16 All these great things.” 11, 16 So, the next morning of course, he is refusing to go.  And my husband is like, “Get in the car.” 7, 10, 15 We were adament.  “You get in the car and you go.” 7 The frist leg of the flight was fine. 9, 14 And they had to stopover in Salt Lake City and he was refusing to get on the plane and my husband was like, “You have to get on the plane.” 9, 10, 13, 15 But, I don’t know if this is true but it is a federal offense if you don’t get on the plane. 13, 14, 15 [laughs]  AS: You told him it was a federal offense! 20 [laughs]  RM: Because he had a ticket! 13 And you are on the jetway, you can’t go back! 16, 19 Once you’ve given them your ticket which you have just done. 6, 9, 12, 13 It was one of those puddle jumper planes from that point. 13 Unfortunately they weren’t seated next to each other on that flight [laughter].  They got to the airport. 8 The counsellor was there to pick him up. 7 They hugged each other and said they loved each other. 13 That was a positive goodbye. 13, 14 My husband got on a plane and flew back home. 7, 13, 15, 19 A couple days in, we got the call that he was okay, not talking to him, the counselor. 7, 10, 19 He was okay, he hadn’t quite gotten into the groove. 15 He was being polite, participating, and everything.  We would have a chance to talk to him the next week. 10 Couple days after that get the phone call from the counselor: 7, 10, 19 “Is there more information you can give us, things you can share? 6, 16, 17 He has got the guys here convinced that he doesn’t belong here.  The guys are convinced he doesn’t belong here.  He is insisting. 9 You don’t have on here that he uses opiates. 9 Are you sure that he’s not using opiates?” 15 I said, “Well, we found the foil and I have a picture.  We can send you the picture.” 12 He said, “Because he is behaving like somebody who is withdrawing from opiates. 14 He said he insists that he doesn’t. 9 He insists it’s just marijuana.” 9, 12 We are like,”Yeah, see, this is what we have been up against. 10 He doesn’t behave like someone who just uses marijuana. 9, 12 We found the foil but we don’t know for sure. 13, 14, 15 And he never injected so there were never marks.” 15 He ran away from that program a week in. 7, 16 Runs away; no phone, no wallet. 7, 16, 19 Crazy stuff that happened from there. 9, 12, 13 We hired a private investigator to find him. 9, 12, 14 Got him back to the Twin Cities because we thought he should at least be close to home. 9, 11, 12, 19 That was another one.  We couldn’t pick him up at the airport. 8 Some neighbors picked him up for us.  With the idea to find out where he wants to go. 11, 13 The options were go to treatment somewhere else. 7, 9, 16 Go somewhere.  AS: How long did it take the investigator to find him? 6, 9 RM: Not long.  Maybe a day or two. 19 You’re in the middle of nowhere and, yeah. 8, 10, 14 AS: How was that time for you?  Did you sleep? 7 RM: Adrenaline. 6, 14 Problem solving mode.  Trying to keep things calm. 12, 16 We didn’t share a lot with family at that point. 17, 18 AS: Had you shared anything up to that point? 12 We did the need to know basis. 13, 14, 15 We didn’t know what was happening. 12, 13, 14, 15 We didn’t want to have a gazillion people throwing their ideas, or trying to help. 11, 13, 16 We are trying to be pretty stealth in what we are doing. 9, 16, 18 AS: Were you and your husband always on the same page about what to do in this situation? 13, 15, 16, 17, 20 RM: Mostly. 9 We were mostly on the same page. 9, 20 We realized very early on, and we have a strong marriage, that we needed to be unified. 9, 13, 14 We would make decisions together. 16 We would talk things through. 10, 16 A little bit of that balancing each other out.  I think some of it is probably gender. 12 I was more of the let’s find out what is going on, let’s talk about it. 10, 19 My husband is more “I’m going to sit him down and he’s going to…” 13, 15 [shouting]  I’m exaggerating, but it was really helpful that we would talk things through and support each other’s decision. 10, 13, 16 It was also important because there were also times that we weren’t both available to make decisions. 16, 18 For example, when he had told his counselor that he wasn’t staying at treatment. 6, 9, 10, 16, 19, 20 Between the time he said that and the time he actually took off, there were lots of phone calls back and forth. 5, 7, 10, 17, 19 When he finally did leave that morning, the counsellor called and said, “He left. 6, 7 We’ll let you know if he shows back up.” 13, 14, 15, 19 I had a major client presentation I had to go on. 7, 18 I could have said something, but I thought, “You know what? 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 My husband is on it as well. 15 We just made that decision right then and there. 9, 12, 14, 16 In the next two or three hours if you have to make a decision, you make that decision and I’ll support you and I won’t second guess it.” 10, 11, 16, 20 That was also a really good turning point in our marriage as parents because we continued then for several years to have those points where ideally we would both make a decision, but sometimes we had to let the other one do it. 5, 10, 11, 13, 16, 18, 19, 20 Sometimes it just didn’t make sense because you’ve got other kids, other responsibilities. 5, 9, 12, 16, 17, 18 We couldn’t put our lives on hold every time that something crept up. 10, 20 Which happened a lot. 12, 13, 17 By that point I had been going to Nar-Anon which I found helpful. 13 I did a—called Serenity Summer. 7 I did a blog post about that. 9 I started taking Friday afternoons off and I blocked the time out on my calendar and I would sit outside every Friday afternoon from Memorial Day to Labor Day with a pad of paper and a stack of books. 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 And these were things like the Four Agreements and Buddha. 16 I had an abbreviated version of the Tallmud and I’m not Jewish.  And poetry books and I had been learning to meditate at that point, too. 12, 16 So, a lot came to me during those periods of meditation, which I never realized. 14, 15, 17, 19 That brought me a lot of serenity and peace. 9, 17, 18 Being able to weather what was—during that first chaos. 9 Well, it wasn’t the first chaos. 9 During that first chapter I really did find that Serenity Prayer helped, being able to stop. 9, 10, 13, 16 It was also during that period of time that being a writer professionally, or at least that is part of my job in public relations, that a paragraph came to my mind. 9, 19, 20 That paragraph began the start of Our Young Addicts and some of that writing. 9, 11 I think it was because in my mind I would always frame things like worst case scenarios: what would happen if I had to announce that he had overdosed and died? 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 What would happen if we had to share things with the family? 12, 16, 18 What would happen if—? 12 I know that is a sad thing, but when you work in my field we deal a lot with crisis and being prepared with those statements. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 17 Same kind of thing. 16, 17 I framed things in my mind in terms of how would I— AS: Convey this message? 16 RM: Convey this message.  So, this kind of paragraph came to mind for me around what was happening. 8, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 At the time I didn’t really know that I was being told by whatever that I was getting a message to write and do this. 13, 14, 15, 20 Interestingly, shortly thereafter, that’s when I ended up sending emails to the Pioneer Press and to Renew magazine and basically saying, hey, nobody is telling the story of what it is like to be stuck in the muck. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16, 19 AS: As a parent. 10, 16 RM: As a parent. 10, 16 From this perspective.  They said, “Write about it.”  And I started writing about it. 9, 11 Nobody ever wants to be on this path. 11, 13, 14 I wouldn’t wish it for anybody.  I think only if you have been on this path can you appreciate what I’m about to say now. 14 Only if you are on this path can you appreciate the gifts you have gotten in any other way. 14, 15, 16 The relationships that I have made, the self awareness and understanding, the life lessons, sense of gratitude, sense of—lots of things like that. 5, 9, 11, 12, 16, 17 I have looked back and I feel like I am richer because of it. 16, 19 I’m sure that is true of all kinds of scenarios with other diseases and other things. 6, 15, 16, 17 I feel like I grew through this process. 16 I don’t look at anybody the same anymore. 13 I teach downtown. 19 AS: What do you teach?  RM: I teach public relations and communications. 10 When I get to campus early, sometimes I will see homeless people. 5, 8, 18, 19 Maybe they have stopped in the student center and they are sitting at the table, or 9, 10, 13, 20 I see somebody at the bus stop or I see a kid. 9, 10 I now think about them differently. 14, 16, 17 What was their childhood? 11 What is happening in their life? 11, 12, 13 What kind of help do they need? 13, 16, 17 Or maybe I run into a frazzled parent and I don’t know what is going on. 9, 10, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16 I don’t judge them anymore because I’m like I wonder—something is happening. 12, 13 It is probably not about the interaction that we are having. 10 There’s also—I’ve noticed, and I’ve blogged about this one too—there is a silent language. 13 I wish, and maybe through this project it will happen, more people will talk about what is going on. 9, 10, 12 We were always pretty open. 16, 17, 18 I wouldn’t just start telling the details. 9, 11, 12 But if people asked me I didn’t shy away from what was going on. 10, 16 There is kinda this silent language and you will be at lunch with somebody and you will ask about their kids and you will get this, “Yeah…” 6, 13, 16, 17 And they don’t answer the question. 6, 9 And you can let it pass, but now I’ll start being like “There was a time I used to answer that question in that way. 6, 9, 11, 14, 16, 19 It was because, and I’ll tell why,” and oh my gosh will they open up. 17 They gave me a clue, I gave them a clue, and then they made a decision to either share or not share. 16 Like,  “Oh my gosh, that is happening in our family, or that happened in my family or that happened in my neighbor’s family. 12, 13, 17, 18 Overall—let's get to the stigma word. 9, 19 Overall, we did not experience a lot of negativity in that realm. 17 There were certainly some families that we would talk to that didn’t want to believe it kind of thing. 9, 10, 13, 16, 17 Or minimize it or change the subject. 16 But, not any like, “Oh, that’s the McKinney family,” or, “We don’t want to associate.” 10, 13, 18 None of that.  There were people that, they would ask how are things going and they wanted to hear the “Great!” or “Guess what! 12, 13, 16 Things turned around! 8, 19 He’s better!”  I think they would get tired of they are even shittier than the last time, and I would tell them and they would be sorry they had asked. 9, 10, 12, 15 I would get some of that.  But not really any of the negative stigma persists. 9 AS: Why do you think that?  Have you thought about why that would be for your family in particular? 11, 12, 18 RM: I think two things. 16 With people that were in our lives at the time during Ryan’s high school years, they witnessed how hard we were trying to get him help. 8, 11, 13, 16, 20 How hard we were trying to figure out what was going on. 11, 13, 16 I think they had more of a sense of appreciation. 17 That didn’t seem to enter into it from people that didn’t know us. 13, 14, 15, 19 As I said, I think we are at a changing point now. 14, 16, 18 Maybe it is just the time that we came into this where there is a lot more of the, “Yeah, I’ve been through it, I know someone’s been through it.” 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 17, 19 There is just a lot more, I think, acceptance. 9, 12, 17 That doesn’t mean that it is better yet. 16 It is no longer a surprise anymore for somebody to say they are dealing with addiction in their family. 13, 18 A few years ago I think that was still the thing. 9, 20 Again, I think how we talk about it matters, too. 10, 20 I think if we talk about our experience in honest terms then we send a really positive message and allow people to respond. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14 If we use stigmatizing language, if we use stigmatizing negativity other people come back to that as well. 9, 13, 19 Or, if we don’t and they use that “they are just a useless junkie” I think we can role model or counter that. 9, 12, 15 We may not be able to change them or their language or perceptions, but I think we are finding, maybe it is just a Minnesota thing, we are finding that people here are embracing and being a community and talking about things. 9, 10, 12, 13, 16 It is a much more open conversation today. 12, 17, 18, 19 AS: I want to talk more about that but I also want to back up to talk about your experience as parents in the treatment world. 9, 10, 13, 15, 16, 19 In family programs, how you as a mom became engaged in your son’s recovery process. 5, 15, 18, 19 Not just you personally, but how did professionals engage you and what was that experience like? 9, 12, 16, 20 RM: Overall, we worked with some really good professionals. 20 They cared; they were good at what they did. 7, 11, 12 They were what you would hope. 10 I feel like there were enough unique things in our situation in terms of just how much in denial our son was, how much he could convince people that nothing was going on. 9, 12, 13, 16, 18, 20 Sometimes we would get to a point with a particular professional where, “I don’t know what to do!” 5, 13, 14, 15, 18, 20 because he wasn’t following the model. 12, 15 AS: He didn’t fit the mold of the addict. 14, 20 RM: So that would be difficult. 20 Again, one of the challenges, because he was over eighteen at this point, before we got him into any programs is that he wasn’t signing release forms. 10, 17 Therefore there wasn’t a lot of access—that frustrated me as a parent to no end. 6, 9, 10, 12, 16, 17 A) we had information, B) we had insights, C) we needed to be part of the success; part of the process. 13, 17 Sometimes I felt very shut out by that. 5, 17, 18 They would say, “Seems like things are going really well now.” 14, 16 And I would go, “Really?  Because that’s not what I am experiencing!”  It is a challenge of the system because when they are working one on one with a client they are that client’s advocate. 8, 9, 10 They are not the parents’ advocate. 10, 16 Sometimes there is a divide between what is going on, and I felt like a lot of times they wanted to change us or make us change or have us accommodate things. 5, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18 It’s like, you know what? 10, 13, 14, 15 Truly we’re not perfect, but up until that point of junior and senior high school there had been a good relationship and things had been going well. 8, 16, 20 Really where the communication disfunction happened was in the drug induced state. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14 So, no, we were not at our best at all. 9 That was not our main operating style. 9 That would get kind of frustrating. 9, 16, 17 Even in the Al-Anon world, many positive things to say about that but, okay, work on yourself. 13, 14, 15, 16 Okay, cool. 17 But I have a crisis or a chaos thing here.  I have someone who needs help, I have someone that doesn’t realize they need help. 13, 14 They could die.  Cool, but I should make my list of amends and take care of my things so I can take care of myself, but what I really need is someone to get my kid in treatment and help my kid stay in treatment and help him be successful. 6, 7, 9, 12, 13, 16 AS: While you felt supported in some ways as a parent or mother you weren’t supported in the ways that you really needed to be. 10, 13, 16, 17 Did this lead you to creating Our Young Addicts?  RM: I felt like I wanted to share this experience because I knew we weren’t the only ones going through it. 6, 12, 13, 17 I have really found a lot of things elusive in terms of information. 16, 17 You Google something and you get something that was completely irrelevant. 14, 19 All these places had bought up all the search terms and you look up ‘Minnesota this’ and you get some place in California and you Google non twelve-step and you get some place in Florida that is a twelve-step. 7, 9, 11, 12, 17 I did feel like I wanted to try to create something where people could find information and share perspectives. 12, 13, 16, 17 I don’t think there is one right way. 14, 16 I think that we need to know what our options are so that we can try different things. 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 If this doesn’t work try this. 16 If this doesn’t work try that. 16 Certainly for my son, it took different tries to find something for him. 16, 17 Then there is the readiness side, too.  It wasn’t that the approaches were bad, he just wasn’t ready. 9, 12 Let me go back to professionals. 19, 20 There were two that stick out to me that were just kind of terrible. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 One, we had been talking with an intervention group and thinking that that might be a way to get my son to go to treatment. 9, 10, 16 At the end of the day, in our gut we didn’t feel like that was going to be the right approach. 12, 14, 16, 19 In fact we thought that might create a greater wedge. 10, 11, 12 We were getting hesitant about moving forward. 9, 13 At that point, the professional that we were talking with started attacking me and saying that I was in denial about my kid’s problem and that I was preventing him from getting better. 9, 10, 11, 15, 20 It was—we walked out of that meeting and never looked back. 13, 15, 17, 19 I was irate.  What they were trying to do, because then it was if you don’t want our intervention services then we need to get you into our family program because you need help. 13, 14, 16, 18 You need to heal your family. 13, 18 I said, “You know what? 13, 14, 15 I’m going to Al-Anon, I’m seeing a therapist, and I’m really happy. 6, 9, 17 And I’m doing my Serenity Summer, I’m really happy!” 17 [laughs]  We had another one where, again, Ryan didn’t want these traditional methods, he wasn’t interested in twelve-step. 5, 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 We thought you can’t force somebody into something. 11, 12 He had gone into this outpatient program which had a harm reduction philosophy. 9, 12 I didn’t entirely understand it and I think harm reduction is a tough concept for parents because we think and know they need to quit. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18 At this point medication assisted [treatment] was not being introduced as a part of this harm reduction. 9, 10, 12, 16 It was more we will meet you where you are at. 13 If you are using you can use and we won’t kick you out. 9 He was taking advantage of this program.  We had had a ton of psychological evaluation that really gave a pretty clear picture of what we thought was going on in our son’s life. 11, 12, 18 We gave it to the treatment program and they said they wouldn’t even read it or consider it. 9, 15, 16 They said, “He doesn’t have any of those psychological problems.”  And we said, “We think he might be having a dual occurring—and here’s why,” and she said, “I don’t put a lot of credit in that stuff.” 9, 10, 12, 17 I was irate that she would not even consider another professional. 15, 20 She said, “I can do my own evaluations.”  You don’t have to agree with it, but why wouldn’t you at least acknowledge the work of a colleague? 9, 13, 14, 15 Just to get another perspective on things. 9, 16 At that point it became a wedge between family and my son where I felt like it was them again us. 5, 17, 18, 19 That’s just not—I’m saying we want to work together. 9, 11, 12, 13 And crazy stuff too: “He doesn’t feel like you are supporting him. 9, 16 You should let him come back home.” 13, 19 We never said he couldn't come home but these are the conditions. 13, 15, 19 “He says he wants to go back to school.” 8, 11, 13, 19 No shit he doesn’t want to go back to school! 8, 13, 19 I finally said, “You pay his tuition? 16 Because we’re going to be flushing money down the toilet to pay tuition. 16, 19 He won’t go to class. 20 You want him to go live at your house? 6, 9, 13 Okay fine, live at your house. 6, 9, 14 You leave your wallet and purse out. 6, 19 You leave your son’s birthday money within grasp and you see what happens. 6, 12, 19 Leave your car keys out and see if the car is there.” 7 Those are terrible things to say about your own kid. 15, 16 RM: That’s the craziness.  You are asking us to bring chaos back into our home. 13, 19 We have a younger kid. 5, 14 There are some times—I understand the restraints of eighteen plus and privacy and releases, and part of Our Young Addicts is that we are a community. 9, 12, 16, 18, 19 We need to surround this young person with all kinds of things. 8, 13, 14, 16, 17 It is not just treatment and recovery and relapse prevention. 9, 12, 15, 16, 18 We need to surround them with love and we need to surround them with nutrition and we need to surround them with living and we need to surround them with lots of things. 5, 6, 8, 13, 16, 17 AS: When did you start Our Young Addicts, and why do you keep doing it? 9, 11, 12 Then maybe you can tell me about your son’s recovery? 9 RM: Informally, it started with some writing that I did in 2011 for the Pioneer Press. 9, 11, 17 That was a biweekly column.  At that point I was posting as RM: Real Mom. 9 I wanted to be completely honest, but at the same time protect identity. 9, 12, 13, 14, 19 That was the best way to do it. 9, 16 Not use any names but be completely open about everything else that was happening. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 17, 19 At that same time I was interacting in an online parenting forum. 6, 10, 16 There were several moms and dads and we were posting and supporting each other. 9, 15, 18 The person who facilitated the forum was moving out of the country and she was going to shut it down. 11, 16 She said, “I’m shutting this down.  I encourage you to exchange your contact information if you are comfortable.” 10, 16, 17 A few of us did and one other mom and I in particular said, “We should start blogging or tweeting or doing something.” 9, 11, 15, 18 We started with a little bit of blogging and we came up with okay, these are our kids, these are our addicts. 9, 11, 19 Shortly thereafter she decided it wasn’t quite for her, and so I kept it up and started the tweeting and started doing more. 9, 11, 12 It started out as an opportunity to take that Pioneer Press column and get it to a bigger audience. 6, 8, 9, 11 Over the past two years, really, as Ryan has been in recovery, I started to formalize it a little bit more in terms of, okay, I write about our experience. 9, 11, 17, 20 I have guest bloggers. 9 Started doing things in schools—conference, building resources, being more of a hub. 8, 16 The reason that I continue to do it is A) our journey is not over.  I think there will always be something there. 16, 17 More importantly, it’s about experience and letting people share their experience so others can take something from that. 6, 19 It’s about sharing resources.  “Hey here is something that worked for me.”  Or, “Hey here is something I heard about. 15 I never used it but maybe check it out.” 9, 15 And hope. 10 I use that phrase a lot. 9, 17 When you are stuck in the muck you have hope, but you really have to continue to keep the hope alive. 9, 10, 12 I was talking to another mother yesterday. 9, 10, 14, 19 Have you talked to Gloria Englund? 10, 11 I was talking to her yesterday and one of the things she said about grief was there are two places for it in this scenario. 9, 10, 11, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 There is the grief when you realize your kid is going down this path and that the dreams and hopes that you had for this kid, that they had for themself, are no longer possible or are not current. 10, 14, 16 And then of course there is the tragic grief when that kid passes away. 16 I think I experienced a lot of that first grief. 9, 17 Our whole familiy did.  When the kid that we knew and loved was unhappy and in dire straits and struggling and not behaving. 6, 9, 12, 13, 17 The behavior is a symptom.  AS: And unable to help himself. 13 RM: And unable to help himself. 13 Unable to see the problem.  There is a grief there.  It was during that point of grief that I was finding sources online, or not finding sources online. 6 Going to Al-Anon meetings and talking to people and writing. 10, 13 To me, I think that the feedback that I’ve gotten is that it is very approachable. 15, 19 It is not pushing one particular perspective. 18 It’s also showing people through our experience that it is possible to continue your life and to not get gobbled up by this. 11 Keep that possibility alive that recovery is possible.  No matter what happens you can make it through. 12, 16, 20 You can keep on. 12 I realized that two years in July is a huge milestone. 9, 14, 20 I have every confidence that this is going to continue.  Yet, I also rationally know that addiction, and particularly the opiate addiction, is fragile. 13, 14, 15, 18 AS: The recovery is fragile?  Or you hear about people decades later having a relapse. 18 There is always, I wouldn’t call it fear, but there is always that little possibility that this path might detour. 7, 14, 16, 17 AS: Right.  It is having fought cancer or being diabetic, that you are always aware it could come back if you don’t do certain things. 13, 16, 17, 19 With cancer you can’t know. 13, 14, 15 It really does help to think of it long term. 13 This is my journey as a mother with this child.  This is how it’s played out. 8 And you have to figure out a way to move forward in grace with that. 9, 13, 16 RM: Our Young Addicts are a community of—and professionals. 20 That is really important to me.  It’s not just parents and it’s not just professionals. 9, 10, 12, 16, 20 So, to the conversation we were having a few minutes ago, sometimes because of the constraints you can’t have that open conversation with the professional because they are working with your kid. 5, 7, 9, 12, 17, 18, 20 But, you could have a conversation with another professional and get their weigh on it. 12, 20 AS: Who is not working with your kid.  RM: And you might go, “Oh, now I understand what they might be thinking, or here is something else that I could try.” 9, 12, 14, 16 I think it’s really important to foster that parent professional relationship. 9, 10, 16, 20 AS: Outside of the context of services rendered. 12, 14 RM: Bingo!  So this community of parents and professionals is concerned about the number of young people using drugs and alcohol. 10, 14, 16, 20 Depending on the statistic the number is going up, the number is going down, the number is stable. 9, 12, 18 Doesn’t matter. 20 One is too many.  No matter where that person may be on that spectrum: 20 I just found out my kid used marijuana for the first time. 9, 12 Is it a problem?  Maybe not.  Maybe it is.  He seems to be using it a lot. 16, 17, 19 It’s recreational.  Here is what you keep an eye out for. 12, 16 Oh, it has turned into use. 9, 19 Oh, it has turned into abuse. 9, 19 Oh, it might be addiction.  We want to get into treatment. 9, 13, 16 Oh, they’ve relapsed. 18 Oh, they’re in recovery.  I wouldn’t call it a continuum. 7 There is a spectrum of different times and different ways that people are using drugs and alcohol. 14, 16, 17, 18 Again, trying just to give people a place that they can get information and share information. 6, 9, 11, 12, 16, 17 We’re not a support group.  We’re not set up to be a support group. 17 More of a sharing community.  Online gives people a lot of access. 6, 17 Started locally here just doing some more programming type things. 7, 9, 12, 16 Face to face is also important.  You can’t do it all online. 6 AS: The parallels in our journeys are very interesting to me. 9, 19 A few years ago I was looking for something like this and thought there was nothing, and started thinking about how could I create something like this. 9, 11, 12, 20 A place where information could be shared and stories could be shared. 9, 11, 12, 17, 18 It’s very serendipitous and wonderful to meet you and see another person with that same desire to share information. 12, 13, 17 Yet, I think about our backgrounds and your PR background actually gives you a whole set of tools and you already have all these tools— RM: It’s this intersection of personal and professional. 6, 8, 10, 16, 17, 19, 20 AS: And that is exactly what I’m striving towards. 9, 10 Using my skills as a historian to try and bring some kind of awareness to a situation and document what is happening. 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 RM: It’s amazing what families have done. 15 We hear a lot about the mom projects and I know that is where you are focusing. 13, 14, 15, 17 It is absolutely amazing. 15 I think we can and should coexist because each one is a little different in terms of what they are doing, what they are offering, and what they are all about. 9, 16, 17 I do hope somehow someway we can develop a collective parent’s voice. 10, 16 I’m not sure that that collective voice is getting heard yet from a policy standpoint. 9, 12, 15 From a clinical standpoint. 9, 12 That might be a future orientation or iteration of this.  How can we take this project and this project and this project and this project? 6 So many of these unfortunately have come through somebody’s loss. 13, 19 They are memorializing their loved one with the creation of something. 13 Yet, unfortunately, if everybody does that, then we have a gazillion of these.  AS: Which is kind of where we are right now. 14, 16, 17 When you look, when you start digging around online. 6, 8, 9, 11 RM: Not to minimize—  AS: Shatterproof is scaling buildings with people.  I don’t know where to start documenting some of this stuff. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15 It is clearly—there is a need among parents. 10, 13, 16 The collectivism is really interesting. 9, 19 RM: I am hoping there is maybe some way to build a coallition of these things. 9, 16 We are each doing something that is different and needed. 13, 16, 17 We are each trying to fill in a piece that didn’t exist before. 9, 16 I think the other thing is that sometimes it is hard for people to find these things. 5, 11, 16, 18 Just like it was for us. 9 Hard to find…  AS: You and I were having a parallel experience in 2011 even. 15 RM: I do hear that one specialist that we didn’t work with, I got to know him after the fact. 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 We were talking about support groups and what not and he said, “There is a need for a parent support group that essentially does what Our Young Addicts is doing but in a face to face model. 7, 10, 13, 15, 16 I’m sure I could fill a room for you week after week.” 7, 15 He said, “When you go to Al-Anon its about working on yourself, not trying to solve your loved one’s situations.” 13, 16 And he said, “Parents in particular, they need someone to say, ‘Have you heard about Tapestry? 9, 13, 15, 16, 18 Do you know about this? 13, 14, 15 Have you done this, do you know about this. 13, 14, 15 Not to say, “Here is what you need to do.” 13 Or be able to go in and say, “You know what? 13, 14, 15 My son’s place is suggesting that he do this. 9, 11 What do you guys think?”  Because in most of those support groups they discourage any cross talk. 10 And I understand that and there is a reason for that and it is a good reason. 9, 12, 16 But, that doesn’t mean there isn’t a reason for interaction and sharing. 10, 16 AS: Especially when your child is under thirty.  RM: I agree!  AS: I notice the benefits of Nar-Anon to some parents whose children are in their thirties and forties and they’re still navigating addiction and there is really truly nothing they can do about their child at this point. 9, 10, 14, 16 Their influence is nill. 20 RM: Very true.  AS: And yet, the parents of younger people don’t—didn’t you also find some kind of relief in those meetings to just feel like I am among people who understand me, who are living in this crazy world, this crazy life. 5, 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 But, yet, when you are in crisis you don’t want to be working on yourself. 13 RM: No. Not in crisis.  That brings us to another point that might be interesting for your history. 9, 19 The distinction of being a young person with addiction versus an older person. 5, 9, 14, 20 To me, as a mom, as a parent, we have a very different relationship with that person that is using. 10, 15, 16, 17 A lot of the protocols and the practices are really geared toward, I think, adults. 10, 12, 17 Either spouse relationships, or adult relationships. 9 AS: For best practices? 9, 10 Even for things like detachment and letting go and even setting those boundaries. 15, 16, 17, 19 At eighteen while your kid is legally an adult, if they don’t have the skills and the mental capacity because of the drugs to be doing these things then your job as a parent is not yet done. 7, 10, 14, 16, 20 You have not transitioned them, or they have not let you transition them to independence. 7, 12, 13, 19 So, at a time that your kid should naturally be making that transition to independence and adulthood, they are hijacked by this brain disease that isn’t allowing them to make these smart decisions. 7, 12, 13, 16, 20 AS: And yet, the law won’t let us override those because of their condition. 6, 19 RM: I think the same thing is true in a lot of the treatment programs. 9, 16, 17 What happens when you put an eighteen year old, or even a twenty-four year old, in a treatment program with someone who has had decades of challenges with this? 9, 10, 12, 15, 16, 20 Who also has some different things at stake. 6, 9, 16, 17 Their relationship, maybe children, jobs, financial at stake. 6, 9, 14 I was leaving a meeting the other day at Minnesota Adult and Teen Challenge to wrap up some conference things. 13, 16, 19 There were a couple of men and I am going to say they were probably thirties or forties.  They were discharging, they were finished, and they were leaving and moving onto whatever was next. 19 They had their duffle bags and one was waiting for a ride and they were saying goodbyes and wishing each other luck. 6, 11, 14 I was thinking about it and I was just in the waiting room and it wasn’t a private conversation. 7, 9, 12, 14 There were somethings I could definitely tell. 5, 16 There were some relationship things someone needed to work with with their spouse. 9, 13, 16 I was like man, they were graduated, I know they are going to have some after care stuff, but they are going back into a situation where they have been absent now for an x period of time. 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 What a challenge. 10 Think about it even for our young kids. 14, 15 For Ryan, he’s taking classes at MCTC [Minneapolis Community and Technical College] right now. 8, 14, 20 Doing great. 11 But, the traditional college experience won’t be his. 8 What are you going to do at twenty-four years old? 20 You aren’t going to go be with the eighteen and nineteen year olds in a dormitory. 20 That experience is gone. 19 I think that in the treatment programs those young people haven’t fully grown up. 9, 11, 14, 16, 17 Their brains aren’t fully developed. 11, 16 They don’t have the perspective on life that somebody older has. 5, 11, 20 We need to see more things that begin to look at how do we help this person at this phase in their life and not throw them in with everybody else? 11, 13, 16 You know what? 13, 14, 15 While there are commonalities in addiction, they are not all the same.  Even differences in economic and cultural upbringing.  I even remember Ryan saying sometimes, he was staying in a homeless shelter and we would go pick him up and he would get angry because, “People give me such shit that you pick me up in this nice car and…” 5, 6, 7, 9, 11, 15, 18, 19 AS: Why are you taking a bed?  Why are you taking a bed?  RM: Exactly. 10 Or, how do you—you’re sitting in group and you’re listening. 9, 13, 15, 17 Again, some of the research you look at, the adverse childhood effects. 11 AS: ACE?  A test and also— RM: Absolutely. 9 But, you know what? 13, 14, 15 Not every kid, and certainly not my kid, experienced those things. 9, 16 How, in a group setting, do you have somebody that is talking about the abuse situation or growing up with the alcoholic parent or these things. 5, 9, 10, 13, 16, 17 Sexual abuse. 9 You’re sitting there going the worst thing that ever happened to me was they took my Nintendo for a week… 9, 12, 13, 15 AS: Anecdotally, do you think that might—a person from a more affluent background dismissing their drug use? 8, 9, 14, 16, 19 Are you thinking more that young people need to be more placed together with more similar circumstances? 9, 11, 13, 14 RM: I’m thinking maybe some of the similar circumstance piece, maybe not even similar circumstances, but keeping in mind it’s not one lifestyle. 9, 11, 12, 15 It’s not one experience.  You’re going to have a more honest contribution and group conversation if you feel like there is some compatibility in your experiences. 9, 12, 16 You know, I don’t know if I have an opinion on the rest of the question. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 I think the young versus the old is probably the most important factor to keep in mind. 10, 12, 14, 20 AS: For long enough they do end up experiencing some of those adverse childhood, or maybe we can make it average teenage effects because they enter into a very dangerous world. 9, 11, 12, 15, 16, 18, 20 Where many bad things happen to them because of their need for the drugs. 12, 13, 14, 16 The law, sexual assault, selling themselves. 7 RM: Violence.  AS: Violence, being beat up, being abandoned. 15 There is just so much that the drug experience of being an active addict creates adversity. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 18 RM: Absolutely.  They get in this survival mode.  This is the other thing about being a mom and being a parent. 10, 15, 16 We realize, maybe not fully, but we have seen enough on the news and TV to know that they’re entering a very dangerous environment. 6, 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 18, 20 You don’t want them to. 13 I think that is another reason why we tend to do what the experts call enabling. 7, 12, 15 Because oh my God I can’t let him sleep on the street. 7, 9, 19 AS: We are so afraid because of the stigma of the people sleeping on the street. 7, 9 RM: Not even the stigma, but just the fear of what he would become. 9, 12, 13, 15, 19 Ryan has talked about—well when you are walking around and you have no place to stay, you might as well do it high. 8, 9, 10, 11, 15 Because you are feeling so bad. 16 You don’t feel like there is anywhere for you to go or call. 7, 16 The places you can go you don’t have transportation to. 7, 11, 17 I do think about, and I feel terrible, I feel terrible about how terrible he felt a lot of times. 15, 16, 17, 18 The first time he didn’t have a place to stay. 9, 11 The first time—you know? 9, 13, 14, 15 A lot of those things. 16, 17 And, certainly, maybe not the safest to be around. 8, 9 Again, no stigma toward those people or judgement. 9 They landed where they are for whatever reasons too. 8 But it doesn’t change the fact that they are not a good influence, or that they are not safe. 10, 16, 20 AS: Is there anything else you want to talk about? 10, 13 RM: We covered a lot. 12, 17 AS: I just wanted to ask a final question. 6, 9, 12, 13 What impact did you have on Ryan ultimately getting into what is now almost his two years in recovery? 9, 10, 14, 20 Going back to leading the horse. 19 RM: The story there was he had gone to a residential program, inpatient. 9 It was the first time he had made all the arrangements and he had recognized that he needed to change and that kind of stuff. 7, 9, 13, 16, 17 Then it didn’t fully work. 11 We knew that when he was discharged that he wasn’t fully engaged and that he wanted to get back to at least smoking pot. 6, 9, 11, 12, 13, 17, 19 That’s not going to work.  The halfway program he was in had a lot of, not a lot of supervision but a lot of rules. 12, 16, 17, 20 Talk about the dichotomy.  Things didn’t work out so well for him and he relapsed. 18 Pretty hard and pretty fast. 9, 11, 18 We were getting worried.  At this point we did a family intervention. 18 He said, “Thanks, but no thanks. 13 Not today. 19 I know I need to do something but this isn’t it.” 13, 14, 15 At that point he was so fragile and we were so concerned and the interventionist said you ought to set up the boundaries. 9, 17 We went the opposite direction and started saying, “Do you want to stay here tonight? 9, 11, 13, 19 Do you need a shower? 13 What do you want for dinner?” 13 He was staying home more and more often. 9, 12, 15, 19 It was a revolving door.  Things got to be pretty bad with the revolving door because we were back where we were in chaos. 18, 19 Some money went missing again. 16 It was, I think it was July 9th, he had come home, we were out, and our younger son texted us that he just came home and what should I do? 5, 9, 12, 13, 14, 19 We said, “Let him in,” and he said, “I did and I don’t think anything is going to happen. 12 He’ll probably shower and eat something and fall asleep.” 7 We are driving home and thinking about what we are going to say. 14, 19 We are kind of going through what we are going to do, and we get home and we start having this conversation with him and it’s clear in the middle of this conversation that he is nodding off. 8, 9, 11, 12, 16, 17, 19 He’s not really participating coherently in the conversation anymore. 12, 13, 16 I’m not sure if he was technically overdosing or close to overdosing or what. 7, 15 We just looked at each other and we were like, “He’s not even here.” 9, 12, 15 We decided it was time to go to bed. 12 We said goodnight and he said, “Yeah, goodnight.” 19 We went upstairs and then I heard him come upstairs a minute later and go into his room and close his door. 7, 9, 13, 15, 19 The next morning he said, “What is it you want me to do?” 13 I said, “It’s not what I want you to do. 13 Here’s what you need to do. 13 I said you need to call a place by the end of today and you need to start a program. 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 He went to the office with me that day and slept on the floor under a desk. 19 Typical thing that he had been doing.  It got to late in the day and I said, “Have you called any places?” 7, 11, 17, 19 And he said, “Oh no, now probably nobody’s going to answer.” 14 I handed him a sheet of paper.  He had been really adament about the three things he wanted. 12, 13, 16 He wanted outpatient, he didn’t want twelve-step, and he wanted Suboxone. 9, 12, 13 I had done a lot of research and it was really hard to find that trifecta. 11, 17 I handed him a sheet of paper with three places and I said, “You need to call these places before we get home, which is in like one hour.” 7, 11, 13, 17, 19 He called one and talked to them for a little bit and said, “No, I don’t think that’s the right one.” 7, 10, 11, 14 I heard him say, “Yeah I guess I could probably get a ride there tomorrow.” 6, 10, 15 I’m like yes you could. 14 The next day was July 11th and we went to Valhalla Place. 19 I think at that point— AS: Was it Valhalla that he went to?  RM: Yeah, Brooklyn Park.  I didn’t go with him—he started their outpatient program. 9, 11 He started on the Suboxone. 9, 11 I asked him a couple months later, right before he was wraping up the outpatient program, I said, “What is it about this program that is working for you? 8, 9, 10, 14 And that the other programs didn’t?”  He said something along the lines of, “Well, I really like the way they treat me. 6, 10, 16 They are respectful.”  Then he kind of quickly goes, “You know it’s not that the other things weren’t. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 But this was the first time that I didn’t want to go back to using and I didn’t want to go back to the life that I had. 9, 11, 13, 19 Interestingly, he went to treatment sometimes because he had to. 5, 9, 16, 18, 19 He went to treatment because he needed to once. 9, 13, 16 But the time that worked was when he had to, he needed to, and he wanted to. 12, 13 I think that in part, the foundation that we kept throughout this journey of being in contact with him and continuing to tell him that he deserved a better life and that we wanted to help him get help and that we would be there for him. 10, 11, 12, 13 Keeping those boundaries of what we could and couldn’t have in the home. 19 We never wavered from our feelings on it. 12, 15, 16 Knowing that we made the right decision at the right time. 14, 16 The professionals sometimes say this is what you have to do. 5, 18, 20 Well, it depends on the situation. 12, 13 I think we read in his situation at this point two and a half years ago that he needed us to provide him a foundation. 13, 20 If he wasn’t getting sleep and he didn’t have a place to shower and he didn’t have access to food, there was no way that he was ever going to be able to see the way to get better. 6, 7, 11, 16 AS: That’s great. 11 I’m happy for him RM: I am too. 17 AS: Happy for you.  RM: The last thing I’ll say in closing is recovery is not easy either. 9 I’d much rather be dealing with recovery than not. 13, 18 We’ve had to do a lot of, well, the same things you learn during the addiction. 12, 16, 17 Being able to let go, make their decisions, live with the consequences, be there to support but not to enable, and continue to tell them you are proud of them and you love them. 13, 16, 19 Give them the hugs, the encouragement.  It didn’t happen overnight. 8, 12, 19 They aren’t going to get better overnight, but the best thing has been the trust returning, the relationship returning. 8, 9, 19 Seeing not one hundred percent the same person that he was, but a lot of the same. 17 Good sense of humor, engaging conversation, the personality. 12, 16, 17 It’s possible.  Again, is it possible for everybody?  But you can’t stop trying. 9, 10, 16 All you can do is keep trying. 12, 16 AS: Thanks Rose.  RM: Thank you. "
"13","Espuche_Nancy 2","Lori Lewis Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 18, 2016 Oakdale, Minnesota Lori Lewis-LL Amy Sullivan-AS LL:  This is Lori Lewis and I give Amy permission to record this. 6 AS: Thank you.  Could we start off by talking about your own childhood? 9, 10, 11 Where were you born?  What was your family life like? 10, 11, 18 Where did you go to school? 8 LL: I was born in Milwaukee, Wisconsin.  I grew up in White Bear Lake, Minnesota.  I had a great childhood. 11 We had a lot of fun. 17 My dad is an alcoholic. 5 I am the oldest of five. 5, 9, 20 I was raised in an alcoholic situation. 5, 13 I think I was nine or ten when they separated.  We didn’t lack anything as far as love—my mom was always there for us, always providing what she could with what she had. 13, 15, 16, 17 From what I remember I was always loved and it was fun and even though I was the oldest of five and had a lot of responsibilities after my dad moved out. 5, 8, 9, 13, 15, 16, 17, 20 I can honestly say I had a good childhood. 9, 11, 16 Went to school in White Bear, graduated in 1983 from Mariner the last year before they split schools. 8, 9, 20 Anyways, great area to grow up in. 11, 16, 17 We had fourteen kids we were always playing kick the can or something. 16, 17 Really fun.  It was good outside of—I saw a lot of things that in an alcoholic family that you probably shouldn’t. 5, 16, 17, 18 You know, it helped develop me who I am as a person now. 13, 14, 15, 16 AS: Was your mother a single mom for very long? 15 LL: She got remarried when I was probably twenty I think, which unfortunately was to another alcoholic. 5 That marriage did not last very long. 9 Maybe a couple of years. 20 Then she swore she would never get married again and she hasn’t. 15 She is just this wonderful lady. 9, 12 Positive attitude. 13 Very, very strong, but I think that’s where I get my optimism from and my positive attitude. 9, 13, 14 I try and look for the good in things because I could very easily spiral down. 16 AS: She provided that example for you? 6 LL: Yes.  She’s seventy-four going strong. 9 Doing good.  Independent in her own home. 12, 19 AS: After high school what did you do? 8 LL: After high school I tried college a couple times and wasn’t ready. 8, 10, 18 [laughs]  I wound up just working. 9, 12 I worked in a couple of different restaurants bartending and waitressing. 5, 7, 9, 12, 15, 16, 17, 19 Honestly, I made so much money back then. 9, 16, 18, 19 My mom kept saying you got to go to college! 8, 11, 15 LL: I know! 13, 14, 15 So that’s what I did for a while and went out and had fun with my friends. 12, 18 We did the bar scene back then, too. 5, 19 Just had fun. 9 I was working at a bar called Hog’s Breath up on Rice Street, do you know where that is? 5, 7, 13, 14, 15 It was packed every Saturday and anyway that’s where I met my husband. 5, 15, 16, 19 But, it wasn’t until I had my second child that I really took a look at my life and said, “Okay, I have two young children here. 11, 14, 20 He was bartending too and doing construction. 5, 9, 12, 15 I started going to school for nursing. 8, 9, 11 AS: Had that been something you had thought of doing? 11, 12 LL: It is interesting because no, I had no idea I would be interested in the healthcare field. 7, 9, 11, 14, 19 After I had Ryan—would work different shifts. 8, 16, 17 I just wanted to be home. 9, 12, 13, 19 I love being a mom. 13, 15 I just wanted to be home with my kids. 9, 12, 13, 19 I didn’t want to miss anything. 13 I opened up a home daycare. 7, 17, 18, 19 I did that until Ryan was in first grade, Jenna was in kindergarten. 9, 15, 16, 17, 20 While I was doing home daycare was when I went through school. 7, 8, 18, 19 I would get up before the kids would come in the morning. 13, 19 I would study. 9 I would study during their naptime, and I would study at night. 9, 19 I would lock myself downstairs and tell Keith, “You have to watch the kids.” 9 I was very driven and I wanted to get A’s and do my very best. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14 AS: When did you go to classes? 8, 20 LL: I went in the evenings and he was home with the kids. 15, 19 It was very tough because I went part-time until I went to St. Kate’s and was in the nursing program. 18 You have to go full-time evenings. 11, 15 I think just being with the kids—there are always sick kids, and nurturing them, and figuring out what they had. 9, 12, 16, 17 That led me to nursing.  AS: Are you currently working as a nurse? 16 What is your specialty?  LL: I started out, once I graduated back then, you could only work in nursing homes. 8, 9, 11, 19 I started in a nursing home but quickly moved to—they call it a sub acute unit. 7, 8, 9, 11, 19 Patients from the hospital not quite ready to go home. 19 I think now they call it transitional care. 7, 13, 14 I just loved that. 9, 12, 13 I remember one guy with an open chest wound, that’s why he was there because his wound wouldn’t heal. 9, 17 He had open heart surgery. 17 It was open and we had to clean it with triple antibiotics and pack it and I just loved it. 9, 12, 13, 17 There are some people who just couldn’t do it. 9, 12 I knew I wanted to go into med surge. 6, 12, 13 I quickly transitioned and went to Hudson Hospital at that time and worked on the med surg unit. 7, 9, 13 AS: And that means surgery? 16 LL: Yeah, post surgery. 9 Anything really can come into a med surg unit. 13, 19 That hospital was really small so they cross trained you in every area.  I wound up working in the emergency room, which was funny because I ended up working with an ER doctor that I went to school with. 7, 8, 12 I remember looking at each other and I’m like, “Are you Butch?” 10 And he’s like, “Are you Lori?” 10 It was really funny.  From there I went to Regions Hospital because I was really interested in working in a bigger hospital. 8, 9, 11, 19 Started working in the ER there.  That was after I had had my third child. 20 Worked in the urgent care for our clinics and then the hospital and I was working like the 5:00 pm to 1:00 pm shift. 7, 8 Then transitioned to OB, which I worked up until three years ago. 7, 13, 20 Because I had a back surgery so I can’t go back to nursing. 19 I could, but not on the floor.  Which really bums me out because I love patient care. 7, 13 AS: What do you do now? 14 LL: I work at the ISNT department with computer programs for, I don’t know if you have heard of EPIC, but it’s electronic healthcare. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15 Everything is electronic.  And anaesthesia for the surgery. 9 It is still really fun and allows me to apply my nursing because they need nurses and physicians—all kinds of people to take the clinical piece and bridge a gap between technical people who are just focused on computers. 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17 It is nice because it gives me another avenue to apply my skills and still have that connection with healthcare. 6, 7, 9, 14 I would love to go back to nursing. 13, 19 I miss OB nursing.  AS: But you hurt your back on the job? 19 LL: No, they don’t know what I did. 13, 14, 15 I mean one of my kids was eleven pounds twelve ounces. 16 AS: But nursing is pretty physically— LL: Yeah. 7, 18 I’ve ended up having another surgery since then. 12 I have had two within the last four years. 9, 20 They said you probably shouldn’t go back. 19 Some of these women who have c-sections and they are three hundred pounds and you have to lift them and help them. 13, 18 But, you know what, I love my job that I’m doing and someday—even if it is phone triage—I love the education piece of the nursing, and that is why I loved OB I think. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 19 AS: So much talking to patients. 10, 18 LL: And new moms, yeah. 6, 10, 15, 18 AS: And new babies. 6 LL: Oh yeah! 10 And who doesn’t love that? 13 AS: So, talk about your children and how you approached mothering. 10, 14 You were clearly very busy. 9 You talked about the daycare part. 7, 10, 11, 18, 19 But, as they got older, what kind of a mother were you? 5, 16, 17, 20 LL: Well we were—I say ‘we’ as in me and my husband—we were very invovled with our kids. 15 That was our focus. 15 I come from a family of five and I wanted to have a big family because I just loved it. 8, 9, 12, 13, 18, 19 It was so much fun and that’s what I wanted my kids to experience. 12, 13, 18 That was our focus. 15 If someone wanted us to go out to dinner or do something, which was it good or bad? 12, 13 Probably not—we needed our time alone, too, but if there was something going on with the kids we did that. 13 Whether it was sports or swimming or Girl Scouts, whatever.  Plus, it was fun.  I’m a really outgoing person and I like to sit with the other moms and chat. 10, 13, 15, 18 You know? 13, 14, 15 So, it was, that was our time too.  AS: Being with other parents? 10, 16 LL: Yeah, yeah. 10 So, we always were very involved with them. 16, 17 Always very honest with the kids. 9, 16, 17 Very open. 17 There were some times when you are too open: 17, 18 “Quit being a nurse.”  We would talk openly— AS: Yeah give me an example. 6, 10, 17 LL: Ryan and Jenna are a year apart. 20 Ryan and Jenna were in the kitchen and we were making something to eat and Ryan’s friend Zach who lived right up the street was sitting here. 9, 12, 13, 14 We had started talking about, oh, in class they were learning about health and sex education and they were in high school and talking about diseases and all this stuff. 6, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 20 I said, “That’s very important.  You need to wear condoms. 13 You want to make sure you are ready. 13, 15, 16 You don’t know what is going to happen in the heat of the moment,” and Zach is beet red. 12, 13, 14, 15 Just beet red. 9, 12 Tall and skinny and curly, curly hair and he is laughing hysterically. 5, 7, 9, 12 I’m like, “What is so funny? 10 Do you guys not talk about this at your house?” 6, 9, 10 He is like, “No, that is why I love being over here!” 10, 13 So, we were always open and we still are. 9, 16, 17 We always told the kids, “Don’t worry about the consequences about something. 11, 16, 17, 20 If you are somewhere and you are drinking and you don’t feel safe—I don’t care if you are in Duluth, I don’t care—we will get you a ride home. 6, 7, 14, 16, 19 Always reach out to us.” 13, 16, 17 But kids, they don’t.  And we always told them there will be consequences based on what the action was and the outcome, but know that you can always call us and we will be there for you. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19, 20 But even as the kids got older—the kids when they were younger, Ryan was just going on nine and I had Wilson our last son. 5, 9, 12, 14, 15, 20 For years there were—it was funny because when I told the kids we were pregnant again Ryan said, “Oh, that’s it. 20 I’m never getting to Disneyland.” 8, 15 So, when Wilson was a year and a half and Ryan was nine and a half we took all the kids. 20 When they were younger we did so much as a family. 5, 14, 18 When they got older into junior high and then high school that’s where you could see the definite separation between the older two and the younger two. 5, 8, 14, 20 AS: You have four children? 14 Four, yeah. 10 Jenna is my only daughter. 5 Cal is twenty.  Wilson, our youngest, is sixteen. 9, 14 Ryan would have been twenty-five.  You could definitely see the separation.  Then it was harder because they are teenagers and they wanted to go off with their friends. 11, 12, 13, 18 The younger two, we were still all involved in sports and clubs and groups. 5, 9, 14 You know what? 13, 14, 15 I was the mom, too, who I always knew—I thought I knew—where my kids were. 6, 11, 12, 15, 16, 17 I was always the parent that as they got older I would call and find out, talk to the parent where they were going if they were invited to a party or a pool party or whatever. 5, 6, 7, 10, 16, 17, 20 How many chaperones?”  All of Ryan’s friends knew, his friend’s moms would call me because they knew I would do it. 6, 7, 12, 15, 18 Even Wilson now, he’s like, “Mom, you do not have to do this!” 10, 14 I’m like “Wilson, I will do this up until you are eighteen!  I want to know where you are!” 13, 14, 15 I’m probably a little bit overprotective.  Controlling, yeah, which I have learned I have no control over anything. 10, 12, 17 Except for what I eat and what I wear.  [laughs]  We just were involved with our kids. 9, 12 AS: That’s good.  Can you talk about when you started being aware that your son Ryan started having problems? 9, 10, 11 How did that appear and when?  Did your daughter have any troubles? 5 Was it with the two of them being so close?  LL: Ryan was in his junior year at Tartan. 8, 20 Jenna was a sophomore. 8 We suspected he was smoking pot, but we never had any proof or anything. 15 One night I came home from work and I was nursing so I was working the evening shift. 8, 15, 19 It was like midnight and I heard something downstairs, so I thought, “Oh I’m just going to go check.” 9, 11, 12, 15, 19 He was smoking pot downstairs. 9 That told me if he is comfortable enough doing it in the house, he has been smoking for a while. 6, 9, 20 At that point I went and got my husband up and we dealt with everything. 13, 15 I wasn’t naive enough to think that was it and he was going to stop. 9, 10, 20 After the third time of him getting caught downstairs we got him into an outpatient treatment at New Connections in St. Paul. 9, 16, 20 It was a thirty-day treatment where he actually went to school there, too. 8, 9, 10, 16, 19 It was all day long. 19 After the thirty days he went back to school and finished out his year as a junior. 8, 19, 20 The whole senior year was really uneventful. 15, 20 At that time Jenna wasn’t doing anything.  In fact, Jenna was dating this big jock in high school. 8, 10 She was a volleyball player. 8 They would go to parties and they would come home and I’m like, “You guys just left an hour ago.” 9, 10, 12, 13, 19 “Well, there was drinking there so we left.” 6, 14 And I was like “Good job.”  Anyways, it was really uneventful. 15, 16, 17 He was about twenty when he moved out with his girlfriend Camille. 8, 12 Yeah, I think he was twenty.  Anyways, everything was fine. 14, 16, 17 AS: Did he go to college? 8 LL: He tried college a couple of times. 8, 10, 18 Actually, just wound up stopping going, which frustrated me. 9, 10, 12 If you didn’t want to go you should have just come and told us. 9, 12, 13, 19, 20 Now we are $4,000 now are considered F’s because you didn’t go. 12, 14 We did some kind of petition thing because he was really depressed at that time, too. 12, 16, 17 All this was happening at the same time. 12, 13 We got him on antidepressants, which he refused to take. 6, 9 He didn’t like putting pills in his body, which is interesting in the way things panned out. 9, 10, 16, 19 He went back, tried again, and just didn’t like it. 9, 10, 12, 19 He actually job hopped from then on quite a bit. 10 He, though, is very talented. 11 He taught himself how to play the drums, the guitar, the keyboards. 5, 14 He did photography, painting, drawing. 14 That was when he was the most content. 15 That is what he wanted to go to school for. 8, 12, 13 We said, “Well, let’s try that.” 16, 19 And he just never went back. 9, 12, 15, 19 When he was living with his girlfriend we suspected that there was some pot smoking and possibly other stuff. 6, 9, 12 We confronted him and he’s like, “You know, don’t worry about it. 10, 11, 13, 14, 15 We never really thought anything. 11, 12, 15 No legal troubles, he’s working.  Then we started to see it decline in his girlfriend. 6, 9, 11, 12 He would ask us for money for rent because he couldn’t hold a job. 16, 20 In hindsight now, looking back, you can see the progression. 14, 19 One day she called me up and she just said, “You know I just got off the phone with Ryan. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 He’s at the apartment. 20 I’m really worried about him.  He’s saying that nothing matters anymore. 11, 13, 20 He doesn’t want to live.” 13 So I call him up and he sounded really bad. 7, 10 I must have been off that day. 19 I don’t even remember. 15 I went over to his apartment and noticed that he had some cuts. 20 To me, that was just a cry for help. 9, 12, 13 Whether he was really trying. 16 We are not going to ignore this.  I convinced him to go into Regions ER.  It was during that visit that they found benzos in his system and narcotics. 8, 9, 12, 13, 15 We would find out that he took from me after my back surgery. 19 AS: So pain meds LL: Pain meds.  So, Oxycontin.  I went to look for him and sure enough they are gone, and I don’t know how many were in there. 13, 14, 15, 19 I had it after back surgery and only needed so much andn I didn’t lock them up. 13, 18, 19 I didn’t think we had to.  So, whether he had been using them before and realized I had some or realized that’s what started it. 9, 11, 14 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 He went back home because that was at the end of November, and I think it was the end of December, January, he was like, “You know what? 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 Things are very stressful. 9 I haven’t found a steady job.” 9 This must be right around the crash in 2009? 14 LL: Nope, this would have been—because he graduated in 2009—must have been around 2012. 8 So, he was fine for a long time after that. 14 After he graduated from high school. 8 Went on a long time.  A couple years. 20 But, so anyways, he said, “Can Camille and I and the dog,” which is a 120 pound sheep dog, “move in until we can get caught up on stuff?” 9, 10, 16, 17 I said, “Sure, as long as you are doing it for the right reasons. 14 You will get a job.”  And, his girlfriend, I always loved her. 12, 13, 16, 17 She comes over every once in a while. 13, 19 And the dog, everybody loved the dog. 10, 13 At the end of that time—they moved out in the end of January—I noticed that you couldn’t even have a conversation with Ryan. 8, 12, 15 He was so, he was moody since he has been out of the womb.  That’s just the type of kid he is. 9, 12 But really, really moody with John.  Lost a lot of weight, looked pale, was sick a lot. 9, 17, 18 I never expected, you know—we question, are you using anything? 6, 9, 13, 14, 15 Never thinking heroin, but you know, are you using narcotics again, or what is going on here? 13, 14, 15 AS: What would he say?  LL: No, don’t bother me about it.  He would get really irritated.  He would leave. 6 So, he would get sick of it and he’s like, “I’ve had enough of this. 10, 20 I’m going to move out.”  He moves out with his buddies.  We don’t want—we want to make sure. 13, 15, 16 “I know you are in a bind, too,” and I said, “You’re welcome to stay here until you can find a place.” 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 So, we loved her. 13 She was just a really good gal. 9, 12 But, so shortly after that, he had brought laundry over for me. 9, 14, 16, 18 We dropped him off and some of his buddies picked him up and I thought I would do the laundry, and that’s when I found the needle. 11, 12, 13, 14 I was like, “What the hell was going on?” 10 So, I call Camille and she’s like, “You know what, I can’t get a hold of him either,” because she was trying to get to him through a friend of his. 7, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 Through that phone call they suspected he had been using as well, which I found out from him later as well. 7 They actually knew he was using. 6, 10, 12 And you know what? 13, 14, 15 They didn’t know what to do. 13, 14, 15 They flat out said, “We’re coming up with a plan.  There were three of us that were going to take him against his will and take him up to Duluth for a week.” 6 AS: They were going to deal with it on their own? 13 LL: Their brains aren’t developed. 16 They don’t know. 13, 14, 15 One of his friends really had a hard time, Brent. 11, 12, 16, 18 He has been over here a couple times. 18 The more he comes over the more he divulges. 13, 19 He feels tremendous guilt, and I understand. 9, 12, 16 Two of his other friends were just over here two weekends ago and they sat here for four hours talking. 9, 10, 11, 12, 18, 19 These are twenty-four year old men that wanted to talk to, you know, it was so much fun. 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 20 Tears and stuff, too. 9 I think it’s good for them to talk, too because it helps them work through their guilt. 10, 13 At that point, when we found the needle—I don’t remember all the details because you are just in crisis mode. 9, 12, 13 We took him into the ER.  We took him into St. John’s at that time.  I know he had to be going through withdrawls at that time. 13, 14, 15 He was still actively using. 9, 10 An ER doctor was going to discharge him. 17 I went to go to the bathroom and told the ER doc, “How can you discharge him? 7, 17, 20 He’s going through withdrawls. 14 You did testing. 9 You know he is using something. 13, 14, 15 You can’t detect heroin.  It comes up as a narcotic. 13, 15, 19 If you discharge my son here, he will probably die and I will hold you responsible. 17, 20 I don’t care what you have to do.” 7 They went in and talked to Ryan and put him on a seventy-two hour hold. 10, 11, 15, 20 I had left because he was so irate and upset. 17, 19 I figured the best thing to do was just leave for a while. 6, 9, 12, 13 I get a call from my husband. 7, 15 They are discharging him, and I couldn’t believe it.  I couldn’t believe it.  I wound up going there before they discharged him. 17 We came up with a plan, talked to a social worker. 10, 11, 19 The social worker, after talking to him, she said, “He needs inpatient treatment.” 9, 10, 13, 16 I’m like, “Yeah, and the ER doctor was going to discharge him.” 10, 17 They tried to look for a bed. 10 As you probably know there is nothing. 13, 14, 15 I think Hibbing was the closest one, and we couldn’t get him in for three weeks. 9 We took him home, helped him go through withdrawls. 13, 14, 16, 19 Watched him the whole weekend. 12, 19 Then they called up and said, “We can get him in. 7 We have an opening in outpatient treatment at St. John’s. 9, 16, 17 Would you like to do that?” 10 Well, “Sure,” while we continued to look for a bed. 18 Well after about two weeks, we wound up getting a call. 7 He was going to outpatient treatment. 9, 16 He seemed to be doing okay, very emotional though, crying a lot, which I thought, “Okay, he is working through things,” but he was still using. 9, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19 So, he wound up in the ER so sick from withdrawals. 14 So, they said we need to kick him out of teatment because he has been using. 13 AS: He was using erratically enough that he would go into withdrawls, then use again. 7, 9, 14 LL: Yes.  When all that stuff happened when we found out he was using it around June. 9, 12, 13 It must have been 2013 now, yeah. 10, 14 Again, there are no beds open anywhere. 17 So, we wind up going to, what is it up the road here? 9 I can’t remember what it is called. 7 Canvas Health.  So, he’s in an intense inpatient treatment in the evenings so he can continue to work his day job, which he did have a really good job at Target. 9, 15, 16, 19 And AA meetings. 13 So, that went okay for a while.  Then, in October he relapsed. 18 Not relapsed, he was continuing his using. 18 At that point I called up St. John’s again and I said, “This is ridiculous. 7 We need to find a bed for my son. 13 I don’t care what I have to do.” 7 I sat at this counter and called every ficken inpatient facility. 7, 9 I mean even outside of Minnesota. 15, 16 Trying to find, and there are no beds.  So, anyways I was just frustrated. 9, 12, 16, 17 I wound up getting ahold—at this point I didn’t even care if our insurance covered it. 7, 12, 15, 20 I wound up getting a hold of Hazelden. 20 They actually had somebody leaving and they did have a bed. 10, 19 They didn’t have anybody on the waiting list, which I found was odd. 9 It is me sitting here. 13 Everything happens on a Friday where you are like, “I need to get through the weekend with my son.” 10, 12, 13, 19 You are so anxious as a parent. 10, 16 They did a phone interview with him. 6, 7 Did a phone interview with me. 6, 7 We got him in on Monday for a chem dep [chemical dependency assessment] because nobody would take anybody without a chem dep assessment. 6, 9, 12, 19 Trying to find someone to do a chem dep.  Quite frankly, HeathPartners, we have good insurance. 7 I know the ins and outs, and still it was a battle. 9, 13, 14, 15 AS: You still struggled even though you work in health care and you know who to call. 7, 9, 13, 14, 15 LL: I knew who to call. 6, 7, 12 I knew the back door numbers. 6, 12, 19 Like you say, you are in crisis.  I feel so bad for parents who don’t have the resources or the knowledge because I felt like I was on my own trying to deal with this. 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 Anyways, we wound up getting him into Hazelden. 16, 17 By this time it is like mid-October.  He was in, of course, only twenty-one days. 19 Quite frankly at that time I didn’t understand heroin. 7, 9, 12, 16 I didn’t understand the disease of addiction. 9, 12, 16 I didn’t realize how severe this was. 14 I wish to God somebody would have said to me honestly, all these counselors—and he’s at Hazelde! 9, 10, 16 The best place. 9, 11 One of the best places. 9, 11, 17 I wish they would have said, “If your son does not find recovery it’s not a matter of if he’ll die, it is when.” 20 That’s harsh, but—and quite frankly it’s all in hindsight. 7 Would I have been more frantic and anxious? 7 I don’t know back then— AS: If someone had said that to you? 13, 14, 15, 19 LL: I don’t feel like we were given enough resources. 6, 16, 20 I was Googling stuff. 9 AS: Did you go to the parent program at Hazelden? 10, 16 We went to the parents and siblings. 5, 10, 16 It was a four day—I asked all the kids to go. 10, 19 Jenna was furious at the time.  She didn’t want to go. 13 I didn’t find out until later, the first day she didn’t go. 9, 19 Then I just begged her to go. 9, 12 She said, “Do you know why I don’t want to go?” 13, 14, 15 I said, “Of course not.”  She said, “He had dealers cal