g on.  Confronted him about it.  AS: Is he at home or in an apartment? 19, 20 LL: He’s at home. 19 Later, we would find out that he used the same night he came home. 9, 19 He had it stashed somewhere in the house. 6, 9 We called up. 7 He went back into Hazelden for a two-week time frame. 19 This time he went to Center City.  We got discharged from there and— AS: Were they offering any medication-assisted treatment? 9, 10, 16, 17 LL: At that time they had put it on the one that starts with a B— AS: Buprenorphine? 9, 10, 11 LL: Yes.  He was discharged with Vivitrol. 17 They gave him the Vivitral shot before he left there. 15 We were responsible for finding a place. 11 He did go to IOP, intensive outpatient program, but because he wasn’t going consistantly, he ended up getting kicked out of there, too. 9, 12, 15 They give me the Vivitrol. 6 They are like, “You are a nurse. 10 You can administer it.” 9 I asked the counselor, and I said, “Do you know anything about Vivitrol? 10, 13, 14, 15 If I give this to my son while he is actively using he could overdose and die.” 6, 10, 15 I’m like, “You have to do a urine test first. 9, 10, 19 I don’t have a urine test at my home.” 9, 19 Again, here I am in crisis mode.  AS: So now they are using you. 14 Yes.  It is ridiculous.  I called up our clinic in Woodbury. 7 He went in with the Vivitrol.  They sent him back home. 7, 19 He was super pissed off: “They can’t do Vivitrol there they don’t even know what it is.” 12, 13, 14, 15 So, I called up a nurse there who wound up being very helpful. 7, 13 I used to work up there at that clinic. 9 She said, “Let me know what I can do to help.” 13, 14, 15 I’m just balling. 8, 9, 12 I don’t know what to do and I don’t have any resources. 13, 14, 15 It’s ridiculous.  She wound up getting us a number for Valhalla Place in Woodbury.  Ryan did go there.  They did the urine test. 9, 19 He must not have had anything in his system because they gave him the injection. 8, 9 AS: For outpaitent? 15 LL: N