15 AS: Who told you to leave him? 6, 20 LL: The ER providers.  Not a counselor. 10 An ER provider and the nurse.  This nurse was wonderful.  They find out it's addiction and they treat you like crap. 16 I don’t care. 7 This one was really was empathetic. 14 She was just like, “I’m sorry. 9, 10, 12 We see this a lot. 17 The best thing you can do right now is leave him here.” 6, 9, 14 It was heartfelt. 17 Monty and I came home and he showed up when he got discharged. 7, 17, 19 I found out when his friends came over two weeks ago. 12, 18, 19 That it was Mike was the one that gave him a ride home. 6, 19 I had no idea. 11 AS: Because it was so cold? 20 They dropped him here? 14 LL: Yes.  I had packed a suitcase and left it by the door.  He thought he was going to stay here. 9, 11, 12 I said, “Ryan, you can’t.  I have everything in this suitcase.  I don’t know where you are going to go.” 13, 14, 15 Monty and I were up all night. 19 We were sick to our stomach. 9 It was frigid.  People die in that!  He wound up staying with a friend that lived over there and after two days he called and said, “Can I please come home?” 7, 9, 12, 13, 19 I said, “Under the conditions that you go back into treatment.” 9, 16, 19 And he did at Hazelden.  Here is the other thing, too.  I didn’t know that we had other options at the time. 7, 13, 14, 15 You are in crisis mode and you go to whoever has a bed open. 17 I don’t feel Hazelden was the right place for him. 11, 14, 16 One reason was because they follow the twelve-step, but they are very faith-based. 9, 12 We’re spiritual, Ryan was spiritual but—we went to church when the kids were little, but cramming that down his throat.  But I didn’t know. 13, 14, 15 I just didn’t know. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 He got discharged from that one. 17 I said to the counselors, “I don’t know where he should go. 10, 13, 14, 15 I feel like he is using at home. 16, 19 He shouldn’t be coming home.” 19 My husband and I were not on the same page through this whole thing. 15, 20 He didn’t want him to go to inpatient treatment. 9, 13, 16 He thought Ryan and him could do it through AA meetings. 11, 12, 13 AS: That he would go with him to AA meetings? 13 LL: No, that Ryan would go.  But I started going to Al-Anon after the first time Ryan was in. 9, 11 The first four or five meetings, I would go for Ryan. 9, 13 Then at the sixth meeting I was like, “Oh my god I’m here for me.” 10, 13 I learned a lot about myself. 12, 17 A lot of good skills to use on Ryan. 7, 9, 17 In fact, Ryan had said one time, we were in the kitchen, you know how they tell you to talk about the: “I feel, I think, I need.” 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 I started doing that with him. 9, 11 He knew exactly what I was doing because that’s what they learn. 6, 10, 12 He said, “I don’t like how you have been changing.” 16, 18 I would not argue with him.  I would give him a reason, which is really hard. 6, 11 You have to practice this. 10 AS: It is very hard. 11 LL: I tried to get my husband to go. 10, 15 I said, “The skills I’m learning are working on him. 7, 12 I’m not going around and around in these argumentative circles like you are.” 8 AS: Your husband and Ryan were arguing, but you were working to pull yourself out of it? 15 LL: Yes.  It was just funny though because we both stood there and laughed, Ryan and I, when he said that to me. 9, 11, 12 I knew it was working and I needed to keep going. 6, 12, 13 We would go on Saturdays. 19 He would go to AA and I would go to Al-Anon.  End of January until around May—he was sober for a long stretch of time. 6, 9 Him and his girlfriend had come back together. 12, 13, 19 He said, “I want to make dinner for someone tonight.” 13, 16, 19 And I said, “Oh, okay.”  Because she cut all ties, even with us. 15 She changed her phone number. 7, 16 She wanted to have nothing to do with it. 12, 13 I give her credit. 6, 12 She needs to be strong. 9, 13 I said, “Okay.”  And he said, “I don’t have any money.”  I’m like, “Oh, shit.” 10 I go, “I’m not going to give you cash but here’s where my credit card is. 6, 7, 12 You can take it and go to the store, but I need a receipt.” 5, 6, 9, 13 He went, and here I walk in and it’s Camille.  My heart was just—I was so happy. 9, 12, 17 They got back together during this time. 19 He was really trying. 16 He loved her so much. 13, 18 I kept telling him I said, “I know you do but you need to do this for yourself. 13, 14, 15 I am worried that you are back in a relationship and with her. 19 Not that we don’t love her, but because you’ve got a relationship with her and you know her you could get right back there faster. 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 You know what I mean? 13, 14, 15, 16 You mean get back to drugs? 14, 16, 19 LL: Using.  Yes.  Because she just loved him, too. 9, 12, 13 I can’t believe she did not see what was going on.  AS: She didn’t see what was going on?  LL: No. I found out later again that yeah, they would have friends over, they would smoke pot, they would take pills. 6, 10, 12, 18 Ryan wound up getting way out of hand. 16 She didn’t tell me.  It was around May I think that we started noticing again. 9, 11 We had sat Ryan down after they got back together and I was like, “Here is the deal. 10, 13, 19 Here are all our concerns.  If Camille suspects anything she will confront you.  She will tell me.  I will confront you.  We want to support you in your recovery.” 13 He was all for it and everything, but it was around the middle of May that we suspected he was using again. 8 I found out later that his friends, I don’t know what friends, dropped him off in the ER. 12, 13, 14, 15, 18 Outside of Regions Hospital because he had overdosed. 15 AS: Put his body out?  LL: I don’t know the details. 13, 14, 15 Left him there.  The reason I found out was because I got an ambulance bill because even at Regions the ER cannot go outside of the building and pick up the patient. 15 You have to call 911, which I have been in that situation before. 7, 13 Where there is a guy outside Regions having a heart attack and we had to call 911. 7 Something about legal—that was May 15th.  We had suspected again so got him back into Hazelden again in June. 19 This time there was a big change in him. 8, 16 He did not want to be there. 13 He was not getting anything out of treatment. 9, 16 He was so depressed. 12 It was terrible going up there. 15 He was angry.  It was over Fourth of July weekend that Camille and I went up there to see him. 12, 19 I talked to his counselor and said, “He’s different. 10, 11, 16, 17 What is the plan for him?”  He’s like, “He’s got to want to do this for himself.” 10, 13 I’m like, “I’m sick of hearing this. 10 I’m telling you my son is going to die.  You’re telling me that my son needs rock bottom.” 13 I was “Like rock bottom is death.”  As a parent that is the one time I did lose all hope. 10, 16 I was hopeless. 10 I was sick to my stomach. 9 He was mad at me.  We got into an argument.  I started crying. 9, 11 I left.  Finally he came with Camille and I was crying and I just told him, “Ryan, this is hard for me, too. 9, 11, 12, 19, 20 I am sick to my stomach. 9 I am worried.  I am scared to death of you.” 5, 7, 11, 12 He even said too, “I am sorry. 10, 15 I am scared too. 5, 7, 11, 12 They are weaning me off of Suboxone.”  He was going to go to a sober house because we told him for sure he couldn’t come here. 6, 9, 13, 15, 19, 20 AS: He couldn’t go to a sober house on Suboxone? 6, 9 Because of that we are trying to sneak around and find a doctor that gives Suboxone and I said, “Ryan they will test you positive for Suboxone and kick you out of the sober house.” 6, 8, 9, 13, 14, 16 It is maddening.  That is a risk we were willing to take until we had time to find somewhere else. 6 Monty went and picked him up on Monday when he was discharged from Hazelden. 17, 19 He brought him over to the sober house. 6, 9, 18 He was so pissed off at us, he didn’t want to talk or anything. 10, 13 Monty went to help move him in. 13 That was just how Ryan was. 9, 12 He would get really pissed about something and after a day or two he would come back and talk rationally about stuff. 9, 10, 13, 19 That’s just the way he was, so we didn’t bug him and Tuesday night he did call me. 7, 9, 12, 16, 19 We talked through things and he was like, “Will you bring me my blanket and pillow and some differnt things from home?” 10, 11, 16, 19 His favorite licorice.  “I will come over after work,” because I was working in St. Paul then and the sober house was very close. 6, 9, 13, 19 I went and picked him up and we went grocery shopping and talked about things. 10, 11, 16 He pointed out over there in St. Paul, I don’t know if you know where it is, it is an old brewery they were converting into artist’s studios. 9, 13, 14, 15, 20 We would talk about the future and he did seem a little bit agitated. 10, 19 I asked him if it had something to do with his girlfriend. 10, 12 She was in Wisconsin Dells with some friend and it was the first vacation she had ever taken in her life. 6, 9, 10, 11, 12 He was jealous because there were guys there, too.  I know. 13, 14, 15 I’m like, “She needs to go have fun, too. 10, 13 She is working through this.  She is sticking by you. 9 She loves you. 13 You have to understand that. 9, 12, 16 You have to let go. 19 She needs to have fun.” 13 We went back, dropped them off. 14, 19 He took his stuff. 9 I just remember, this is just hilarious, I just gave her a super huge hug and he just looked so good. 9, 12 I tell him I loved him and how good he looked and he was like, “Shh, the windows are open the guys will hear you!” 10, 13, 17 I was like, “I don’t care!” 7, 10 I pulled away and part of me wanted to just take him out for dinner or something. 6, 9, 12, 13, 16 I knew he was agitated. 6, 12 I know Ryan, and he just needed time. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I called him up and I’m like, “Oh, I left the licorice in the car,” and he was like, “Oh, I’ll get it tomorrow,” and I was like, “I’ll stop by after work tomorrow.” 7, 9, 10 That Thursday I had a lunch in Mears Park with two of my colleagues and we were walking back and I got a phone call from a St. Paul police officer. 6, 7, 15, 19 He said, “Can I come to your work?” 13, 19 And I’m like, “Why?” 10 All this stuff going through my head. 9 He said, “Well, your son Ryan overdosed.” 15 I said, “Okay, he has overdosed before. 15 What does this mean?” 16 He said, “Can we just come to your work and talk?” 9, 10, 12, 13, 19 I said, “Okay if this has anything to do with my husband or kids you have to tell me right now.” 14, 15 That’s when he told me. 20 AS: He did tell you on the phone? 7 LL: Yes, they actually came to Mears Park and met me and drove me to my car. 5, 7, 10, 14, 19 Part of me so still—July 10th it will be two years. 9, 20 I am angry at Hazelden for discharging him to a sober house where 1) they won’t let them have medication, and 2) the sober house was going through a transition of house leaders. 6, 7, 9, 10, 13, 19 Yeah, which did worry me. 11 They told me at that sober house, we talked to the guy, the lead that was leaving, and for an hour on the phone. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 19, 20 Every kind of detail he could think of. 16, 17 He had told me that during the week the guys have to be out of the house from 8:00 am to 1:00 pm. 6, 9, 20 They need to be looking for jobs. 13 Which I thought, “That’s weird. 11, 12 How do you hold them accountable? 20 Are you doing drug tests when they get back?” 9, 14, 19 AS: He overdosed at the house? 6, 9, 15 LL: He overdosed at the house on Thursday at 11:30 am they figure. 6, 9, 13, 15, 19 My questions is— AS: He was alone? 6, 9 His roommate who had also been in Hazelden—Ryan was breathing really heavy at around 10:30 am. 7, 8 He was probably in the process of dying at that point.  He was snoring and so he left to go out in the commons area because Ryan was so loud.  When he came back up around 11:30 am that’s where he noticed Ryan wasn’t breathing and called 911. 7, 19 Again, why weren’t they checked on?  Him and his roommate, they were supposed to be out of the house. 6, 7, 9 I’m just pisssed because if anyone would have checked on him they would have been able to arouse him at 8:00 am when he was supposed to be out of the house. 6, 9, 12 And the stupid roommate. 7, 9 Why didn’t he try to arouse him? 9, 16 Had he used heroin? 9 LL: Yes.  Someone in the house had given him $20, which they are not supposed to do. 6, 9 He had a bus pass. 9 We had gotten him a bus pass. 9, 15 So what they think was he took the bus, made the connection, came back to the house, and used. 6, 9, 16, 19 It shows that the heroin addiction was way bigger than he was. 8, 16 He did want to get sober. 6, 13 He even said to Monty one night, “Dad, am I ever going to get better?” 15, 19 When I would talk to him, too, I was like, “Please help me understand. 9, 10, 12, 13, 16 Help me help you because I don’t understand.” 9, 12, 13, 16 He just said, “Mom, it’s not just the physical craving when I’m in withdrawals. 9, 12, 14 It is psychological.  That is all I can think about.”  I said—he was so worried when they were weaning him off of Suboxone.  Because the Vivitrol didn’t work for him AS: I have heard that. 15 He’s like, “The Suboxone is so helpful for me. 10, 13 It helps with so much of the cravings.” 13, 18 He was worried, too.  Part of my frustration too is, I think him name is Marv Seppala. 6, 9 One of the directors at Hazelden. 14 I did get a hold of him and talk to him. 10, 20 I had requested all of Ryan’s progress notes and read through everything. 9 AS: Ryan releassed them to you?  LL: This is after Ryan died.  I got all the progress notes.  Every single progress note was from a psychologist, psychiatrist, counselor: 9, 10, 15 “Is at high risk for relapse if discharged.” 8, 17, 18 What is interesting is the way we got in contact with him was I went to an all-day seminar. 9, 10, 15, 16, 19 It was on heroin in the community.  It was so good.  But there were people there I knew, too. 6, 12 Another director from Hazelden, a lady—I can’t remember her name—stood up there and said, which just pissed me off, she’s like, “We cannot be telling people that they need to hit rock bottom. 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14 Their rock bottom is death.  We are now starting to use Suboxone,” which they did start using with Ryan when he was there. 9, 11, 14 “We believe in Medicaid.”  When she was done and the group got to ask questions I asked three really direct questions to them. 6, 9, 10 After I went up and talked to her and said, “I have to tell you I am so pissed off right now.” 10, 11, 14 I sat there and talked to her and she was wonderful, she was listening and here she has a son in active addiction right now. 9, 10, 11, 14, 15, 17 She said, “I want you to talk to Marv Seppala and share your story with him.” 9, 10, 13 He called me and was very gracious and very nice. 7 We talked through everything. 10, 11 He said, “Would you be willing to talk to these counselors?” 10 I said, “Yeah, but I want you to read through all the progress notes I read through. 13 You can contact me and you can point out the errors. 10 And you can understand why I’m so frustrated. 9, 12, 16 Why there has to be change.” 16 AS: Right.  It is not my job to be educating you people after my son has died in your care. 7, 10 LL: I know. 13, 14, 15 Now I am at the point where I’m really frustrated. 9, 12 I want that sober house investigated. 6, 9, 13 I want to hold Hazelden responsible for not helping us get him into the right place. 11, 13, 14, 20 When I told them that I don’t feel that they know about the sober houses that they are sending people to. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 I’m at the point now where my grief is turning into frustration. 9, 14, 19 I’ve had two years now to attend all these different things. 12, 14, 15, 16, 17, 20 Learn about the disease of addiction itself.  All these different resources, talking to other parents. 10, 16, 17 A lot of this was preventable. 15, 17 It was Ryan who needed to get sober himself. 6, 13 I don’t think he had enough support and tools in the places that are supposed to be—Hazelden is—there are so many errors. 6, 11, 17, 20 I think with me being in the medical field and being a nurse and able to identify those—I feel that Ryan was failed by the healthcare system as well. 7, 8, 9, 14, 16 There are a lot of things that I think we can change. 16, 17 When I share my story I am so involved in getting change to happen. 9, 12, 16 AS: Can you talk about that experience from the moment of losing your son to what made you want to keep talking about it? 10, 12, 13, 15, 16 As a mom, was it grief that motivated you? 15 Was it anger that motivated you?  How did it play out?  LL: It is a combination.  I had my second back surgery a month after Ryan died. 8, 19, 20 I was off—because this time I had effusions—I was off for three months. 8 I had a lot of time to process; to educate. 10, 17 People gave me so many different books, which were very helpful. 13, 16, 17 A month before Ryan died another young man in the area had died that Ryan knew. 6, 8, 12, 14 You would think that that would scare him. 7 His mom was actually a St. Paul police officer. 7, 10, 15 I have since been in contact with her. 10 Another boy died.  A good friend who lived in the area said, “I’m really sorry. 10, 12 I don’t want you to—but have you heard about so and so?” 13, 15 “No, I haven’t heard anything. 15 I haven’t been on social media.  I have just been isolated.” 9, 12 Here it was a friend of Wilson’s, our youngest. 9, 12, 14 He played baseball with him. 8 His older brother died of heroin overdose. 5, 15, 20 They weren’t releasing what it was, but we knew what it was. 6, 12 She was a concerned parent, too. 10, 16 She was like, “Something has to be done.” 10 I’m like, “I know. 10, 13, 14, 15 I have been trying to look into this.” 16 I had been contacting the St. Paul Pioneer Press. 10 The Washington County sheriff, the Hennepin County sheriff—anybody I could to figure out how we could get a forum. 13 I had already been working on this.  AS: This is while you are recovering from the surgery?  I saved all the e-mails and contacts and everything, too. 10 That just fueled me. 9, 12 I just couldn’t sit there. 9, 12, 13 Part of it was grief.  Part of it was anger.  So, that continued to get me to move and as a result, got me connected with the right people. 14, 18 Pete Orput the District Attorney. 9, 10 His two boys are actually in recovery. 8, 10 He fights like… 10 I love him. 13 He got me in touch with Cheif Mueller and Sheriff Hutton and Know the Truth program. 14, 15 That is when we stared doing the forums around here. 8, 9, 12 They were only gong to do one forum, and I said, “One forum is not enough. 20 You need to do a forum for each city.” 13, 20 The good thing is Chief Mueller has five kids that go to Stillwater, and he is right in that. 6, 14 He knows the statistics. 9, 13, 14, 15 So he helped fight for more forums. 13, 16 We had one at Tartan, one at Woodbury— AS: You are having them in the schools? 8 LL: One at North.  In the schools, yeah. 8, 10 I had been working with the schools, too. 8 Directly with Tartan, and the head lady at the district—she was like, “I don’t know if we can have something like that in our school. 8, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 We have to pay for it.” 16 Because we are in Washington County she found Mueller, who said, “They don’t have a choice, Lori. 17 This is my county, this is my jurisdiction. 7 They will be holding one. 20 We just need to work on dates.” 9, 12, 13 I finally wound up getting in connection with all the right people. 14 At that time too, we were working with the St. Paul officer because we were trying to figure out, okay, what all did Ryan pawn? 13, 16 We didn’t know we were missing it until we went to go get it. 13, 14, 15, 16 We got connected with a St. Paul officer, Sandra Kennedy, who happens to live out here. 12, 14, 18 It is just weird the way it all—she was very helpful because we were fighting with the pawn shop because they were telling us we had to file charges— AS: Charges against who? 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 LL: Charges against Ryan.  AS: You’re deceased son?  LL: Yes.  I’m like, “My son is dead.” 10 I finally called her up, just was balling. 7, 8, 9, 12 She was like, “Okay, I am on vacation now. 10, 14 I’ll be back. 19 You are off on medical leave right now, right?” 6, 14 She said, “Does it matter what time I stop by?” 9, 10, 20 She came over and returned some of the things because she searched the whole area and returned some of the things. 16, 19 Some of the things must have been sold. 16, 20 I can’t find my laptop, his laptop, which makes me sick because there are pictures on there that I’ll never retrieve. 15, 16 She was really helpful. 13 She told me, “You need to come to a group called Survivor Resources in St. Paul.” 7, 13, 19, 20 It is right in the police department. 7, 14 There are other officers there that lost kids to heroin. 9 One of them was Ryan’s friend that had died the month before he died. 8, 12 That is his mom who is a St. Paul officer. 15 Thank God for that group.  It is other parents that have lost their kids. 9, 10, 16 They know exactly what you’re going through. 10, 13, 14, 15 I feel fortunate. 16 I’ve got very good friends, supportive work environment. 12, 18 We are a very close family. 18 I have so many people to lean on.  There is no way of knowing—nobody can know. 13, 14, 15, 16 These people knew and it was a group of parents who had lost their kids to either drugs or accidents. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 14, 16 Some people were twenty years out. 20 We had more coming that were new. 6 It helped me to know that—honestly Monty and I walked around for six months in a fog. 8, 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 Even still now I don’t remember things. 9, 14, 16 I could be in midsentence and I don’t even know what I’m talking about. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15 It is because I am still preoccupied with saving my son. 9 It’s all that would’ve, should’ve, could’ve.  Just some of the things that you’re feeling that you can’t even tell anybody else because they think you are crazy. 9, 15, 16 They know. 13, 14, 15 They get it.  They helped us get through first holidays, birthday, all that stuff and what to expect and that it is okay. 9, 13, 16, 19 It was so helpful. 13 I haven’t been there for a while now because I feel like I am in an okay place right now. 11, 14, 16 My husband needs to go somewhere because he is still a mess. 9, 13, 15 Every year they do what is called Walk for Hope, Walk for Remembrance at Como Park. 7, 20 Last Monday night we went there and did that. 9, 19 My husband still can’t do it, but there is a big group of us and that is put on by Survivor Resources. 8, 9, 10, 15 I saw all the people and I went with—and all the people who lead it and I say, “I’m sorry I haven’t been there. 10 I have been doing okay.”  But I will come back and see and everything. 13, 19 I honestly could not have gotten through without… 9, 15, 16 We both went to psychologists that Hazelden, actually, recommended. 9, 10, 12 But after four or five times it’s just like I am not gaining anything anymore. 9, 12, 13, 18 She is very good.  We actually tried a spiritual healer, too. 10 We went as a group because I wanted the kids to go, too, and just know there are resources out there. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 Because Monty and I were just a mess. 9, 12 We are just now within the last few months are able to help our kids because we were so lost. 8, 9, 12, 13, 14 Not only did they have that year and a half that we dealt with Ryan, but now they had a whole other year and a half where we were absent and that’s not fair to them. 7, 13, 14, 20 Each one of them has gone through trying to deal with it. 13, 16 We talk about Ryan all the time. 10 It is hard. 11 Sometimes we get choked up and cry but we keep him present. 5, 7, 12, 18 On his birthday they made burritos because that was his favorite thing. 16, 19 I told all the kids, “I don’t care what you have to do, but be here.” 7, 20 I just wanted everyone to say what you miss about Ryan because I think it is important for them, too. 9, 12, 13 It was fine—we did laugh a little bit. 14 We were teary.  We actually signed—have you ever seen those floating lanterns? 10 We all signed it and said ‘Ryan’ and it started raining and we still have it, we haven’t done it. 9, 11 The kids are all struggling in their own way. 9, 16 Our twenty-three year old started drinking heavily. 6, 9, 11, 14, 20 Wound up getting a DUI last June. 9 They were always good about calling Uber. 7, 16, 17 We recognized that she was drinking and, “No, Mom I’m not,” and so thank God she got the DUI. 6, 13, 14 She has been going to class. 20 In fact last Thursday she graduated. 8, 9, 10, 19 We’ve seen such a change in her. 16 I think part of it, too, it’s just the age she is at where she’s getting old enough and she is getting more responsible. 9, 12, 20 They just bought a house. 6, 7, 9, 12 She understands. 9, 12, 16 Her brain has developed to where she understands the consequences that it caused for everybody. 9, 12, 16 She doesn’t want to go back there again. 13, 19 She’s been doing great. 11 Unfortunately Cal, the nineteen year old, well he’s twenty now, never grieved Ryan, which we knew. 6, 12, 14, 15, 20 It breaks my heart because he’s my—Cal is really quiet, but, very attuned to your feelings. 16, 18 He has been ever since he was little.  Just so loving. 9 I remember one time I was pregnant with Wilson and Cal was like three.  I was just huge, fat, I had been tired of being pregnant, and I almost started crying. 9, 11, 12 I thought, “I can’t cry with him here,” and I was trying on maternity clothes. 11, 12, 16, 17 He looks up at me—and his little cheeks—and he goes, “Mom, you are so beautiful.” 6 And I thought, “You are going to make some woman the happiest.” 9, 11, 12, 16 He is one of those kids that is really quiet and he takes everything and he started drinking more and more and more. 6, 9, 11, 14 And this girlfriend he was with, she had heroin issues. 12, 14, 15 Psychological and chemical issues. 9, 14, 15 Actually, her mother it turns out, graduated a year after me and my sister. 5, 8, 9, 19, 20 Cal recieved a DUI back in October. 19 He has all those court issues then. 14, 15 On Easter he just never comes home, which is unlike him. 9, 12, 13, 15, 19 For consumption.  Call the jail: “Cal’s in here.  We haven’t posted anything yet because he was booked a few hours ago.” 9, 11 Anyways, he gets a second DUI. 16, 17, 20 Shortly after that he is up at the park at 7:00 o’clock at night with his girlfriend. 12, 19 She calls, she is hammered. 7, 12 I said to Monty, “I can’t deal with this. 13 Cal is so drunk.” 11, 14, 15 I had to go out in the car to get him in. 7 Monty drives his girlfriend home, and during this time Cal wakes up a little bit and just unloads. 7, 9, 12, 14, 19 We had suspected.  He just looks at us with hate in his eyes. 9, 12, 14, 16 This is this kid who had—it is just pure hate. 9, 12 I suspected.  I said to my mom, “I think he blames us for Ryan’s death.” 15, 17 She said, “No he doesn’t.”  I said, “Mom, you don’t know the way he looks at me. 13, 14, 15, 16 Yes, he does.”  He was drunk and everything came out: 11, 14, 15, 19 “I blame you and dad for Ryan’s death. 17 If you would have let him come home this wouldn’t have happened. 12, 13, 19 You don’t understand. 9, 12, 16 I lost my friend. 9, 12 I looked up to him.  I lost my big brother.” 5, 8, 9 And my heart just broke. 9, 12 He went on and you know, “He came to me in a dream the other night. 13, 14, 15, 19 Told me how much he liked my art and that I was doing a good job.” 10, 18, 20 And just, God, my heart. 9, 12 Anyways, later that night, I had him lay on the couch. 16, 17, 19 I was in here doing something and Monty finally came home from dropping his girlfriend off and Monty yells at me” “Lori, get in here.” 12, 14, 19 Cal is unresponsive.  I did the sternal rub and he was just flopping and I’m like, “Call 911,” and Monty is like, “I can’t.” 9, 10, 12 Just mental block from stuff with Ryan. 9, 14 He is like, “Lori, I can’t.” 10 I’m like, “We need to get into the car now and get to the ER.” 7, 10, 13, 14 Brought him to the ER and even as a parent I’m like this is more than alcohol. 10, 15, 16, 18 I begged the ER doctor to do a drug test and he wouldn’t. 9, 14 And later, now we found out, now that Cal is in treatment, he had done Xanax that night and alcohol. 9, 14, 16, 19 Had we not found him he would have died.  I have yet to write a letter to the ER doctor that treated him that night but— AS: Why wouldn't they run a drug test? 9, 11, 14, 16, 19 LL: Because Cal is eighteen and he can, “Well, let’s wait for him to sober up and sign a consent to do it.” 6, 7, 19 Again, these ER doctors need to listen to the parents. 9, 10, 13, 15, 16, 17 You don’t know my son. 13, 14, 15 I know my son. 13, 14, 15 I know this is not just alcohol. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 Part of Cal’s legal stuff is he had to get a chem dep. 9 He started going to outpatient treatment. 9, 11, 16 He told them he was drinking with his girlfriend the night before. 6, 12, 14, 19, 20 He had snuck over there to see her to bring her a little turtle that he found here in our yard.  [laughs]  AS: He tattled on himself about drinking? 6, 14 So he would be kicked out of the program?  LL: No he didn’t know he would be kicked out. 13, 14, 15 We had to go there and get everything and they told us. 20 And Cal is like, “I didn’t know, I was just being honest.” 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 I’m like— AS: It’s so ridiculous. 10 LL: I know. 13, 14, 15 They recommended inpatient treatment. 9, 12, 16 Again, three week wait for a bed.  I told Monty I said, “I cannot watch him for twenty-four hours. 11, 20 I don’t have the energy to do that nor do I want to do that. 13 I don’t want to worry.” 11, 13 We called his sister-in-law. 5, 7, 9 She lives up in Nekoosa, Wisconsin out on some land up there in the middle of nowhere. 8, 14 That is where he went until his bed was ready.  He has two cousins: one six months older and one six months younger. 5, 8, 14, 20 His cousins would come down here and stuff. 5, 9, 13, 19 They haven’t seen each other for a while, but that’s where they went.  Someone called us and said, “We are able to get him here earlier.” 7 I said, “Okay he is up in Nekoosa.  We need three and a half hours, more than that, a day to go get him.” 11, 13, 19, 20 And yeah, so that’s where he stayed. 5, 9, 10 I can’t lose another son and go through this again.  AS: How long has he been in treatment? 9, 16 LL: I pick him up on Wednesday, it will be twenty-five days. 19 They would only do twenty-one days. 19 I know. 13, 14, 15 That’s another thing— AS: And he’s twenty?  He turned twenty in April. 19 Again, I have huge concerns.  When I was talking to him on the phone, I’m like, “They are discharging you on Wednesday? 7, 10, 19 That’s not even…” 15 He thought it was twenty-eight days. 11, 12, 19 I’m like, “That’s not twenty-eight days.” 10, 19 I go, “Cal, I’m really worried about you,” I said, “I’m really worried about you coming home.” 19 He wasn’t getting liquor here at all.  He would get somebody to buy it for him. 7 His counselor said, “I’m not worried about him coming home because that’s not where he got it.” 10, 19 He said, “You guys don’t want to have liqour at home.” 13, 19 I said, “You can’t hang around your friends. 12, 18 They all drink. 6, 14 Not to the extent that you do. 15 Casual drinking, on the weekends. 6, 12, 14, 19 I don’t think you are strong enough. 9, 20 I think eventually you will get there.” 15 His response was, “Mom, you don’t worry about it. 11 You don’t have anything to worry about.” 11 AS: Oh, really?  I don’t have anything to worry about? 11 LL: I told his counselor. 10, 20 I said, “That’s a red flag to me, and it should be for you, too.” 12 If he was ready to come home he would have said, “Mom, don’t worry about it. 11, 13, 19 This is my plan.  I don’t plan on hanging out with those guys for a while.” 18 Here I am frustrated. 9, 12 Right now I could see Cal going either way. 14, 16 I don’t think he’s an alcoholic. 5 I think after Ryan’s death that caused it to get worse. 9 I think he’s at a point right now where he could go really either way. 14, 16 As a parent I can’t. 10, 16 We told him too, we’ll support you in recovery. 20 My husband and I are consequences— AS: 15 Will he come back here and live? 13, 19 Is that the plan?  LL: We talked to the counselor: 10, 11 “You have a very supportive environment.  He understands this is an addiction and it was more powerful than Ryan. 9, 12, 15, 16 Alcohol is more powerful than him right now. 14, 15 They had him write a letter to Ryan, which he read in front of the whole group. 19 It was very—he just let loose and was very emotional. 9, 12, 13, 19 They’ve already gotten set up to go to intensive outpatient treatment. 9, 15, 16, 17 I guess we will just support him into his recovery. 9, 10, 12 It is really hard for us because I know the outcome. 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 Some people say, “Oh, alcohol is not as bad.”  Yes it is.  Yes it is.  My poor sixteen year old. 20 He has been through so much and seen all this. 18 Now he is sixteen and he’s going places. 11, 17 I’m like, you know, I go through the same things. 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 Call parents and everything and he is like, “Mom, I’m not going to do drugs.” 10, 14, 16 “That’s what Ryan said, that’s what Jenna said, that’s what Cal said.”  Three of my four, you know? 13, 14, 15 He goes, “Mom, I’ve already been to parties where they have offered me that and I just say no.” 9, 12 I’m like, “Oh my God, Wilson, I’m so proud of you for doing that.” 10 But, quite frankly 7 I think for myself when I was a teenager and that’s a thing you try and get across. 16 I had a picture of an addict—this woman wearing a bomber or whatever.  These kids come from really good families. 13, 19 They are with these friends and their friends have done it. 12, 18 They feel safe, they feel comfortable. 16 Goes out the window, you know? 13, 14, 15 I was that age, too.  Thank God that that didn’t come because if my friends were doing it and those were my good friends and I trusted them and was with them all the time. 9, 12, 13, 18, 19 AS: You probably would have.  LL: Yes.  It is so scary, you know? 7, 13, 14, 15 It’s not just our kids. 9, 12 It’s grandma who went in for knee surgery and got hooked on Vicodin and didn’t wean her off of it and now she’s buying it from—it is anyone. 7, 14 I have hope and I’m optimistic. 9, 10 I’m trying to raise awareness and help change some of these things within our own healthcare organization, at Hazelden, at these sober houses. 6, 7, 9, 13, 14, 16 Especially for medication assisted treatment. 9, 10, 16 If there is something out there that will help them. 13 We both thought that would’ve helped my son. 11, 12, 13, 16 We weren’t given the chance. 6 Whatever we can do to try and prevent it and bring awareness. 15, 16 Even the symptoms for other parents— AS: I didn’t know my daughter was nodding off because of heroin. 5, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 LL: I know! 13, 14, 15 AS: I thought she was over tired because she was a night owl and she would stay up too late. 9, 11, 12, 19 So by the next night at dinner when she is like nodding I would just tell her to get up and go to bed. 9, 12, 19 You’re frustrating me sitting here in front of this dinner that I made. 9, 13, 16 Just go to bed! 9 Of course she would get up and go to bed.  [laughs]  For a parent to know all of those signs. 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 The flu type symptom, the nodding off, long sleeve shirts, spoons missing. 16 I couldn’t figure out where the frick—I would go to Target and buy spoons because… 7, 13 That is another thing about Cal because that night when he was drunk—he has talked about it in counseling. 10, 11, 14, 15, 19 He feels tremendous guilt. 12, 16 Looking back he knows he drove Ryan to dealers’ houses. 6, 7, 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 Because Ryan said, “Stay in the car I’m just going to run in and get my phone charger that I left here,” or whatever. 7, 9, 11, 12, 17 He also saw Ryan taking spoons and knew what he was using them for and didn’t tell us. 6, 12 He feels a tremendous amount of guilt, too. 12, 16, 18 I want him to understand that even if he had told us that wouldn’t have changed the outcomes. 9, 12, 13, 15, 16, 19, 20 The disease was bigger than Ryan. 8 AS: How do you deal with that as a mom? 13, 15 As a parent? 10, 16 Do you still feel like you could have done something more? 9, 16 LL: Oh yeah. 10 I think for me—the avenues I have taken of speaking out, being involved, and trying to make change happen helps me. 6, 12, 13, 16 It’s my therapy because it helps me continue to fight for my son even though he’s gone. 13, 15, 19 I look back now and Monty and I always—God if we would have—we were ready to mortgage the house to put him in the Hazelden fellowship inpatient program for three months. 6, 8, 9, 10, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 But then we are like, “Okay, we spent $40,000. 19 Is that really going to help him? 13 And what is that taking away from the rest of the kids?” 9, 16, 19 It is such a dilemma.  We think about that, too.  If we had gone and went to a different sober house. 6, 9, 16, 17 If we had identified the symptoms sooner.  If we—again it is so out of our control. 17 AS: But yet as a parent— LL: 10, 16 You still feel that way. 9, 16 AS: You still think you can do something to help your child. 9, 13 LL: If I had stayed and taken him out to dinner that night because I recognized that he was agitated. 5, 6, 9, 19 Would that have prevented him from getting the money, going on the bus? 9, 15 It is all that stuff. 9 You drive yourself absolutely crazy. 7, 14, 16 I never used to have anxiety. 9, 15 I have tremendous anxiety now. 12, 14 I am still thinking about ways that—what could I have done? 9, 16, 17 It is frustrating. 9 Your emotions are all over the place. 11 There are times where I feel Ryan now. 14, 16, 18 I used to hate it when people would tell me that because I’m like, “I don’t.” 9, 10 I dream about him, I feel him now. 14, 16 I can feel happiness. 16 There are days, too, where I see Cal’s pain and I think God dang it this disease is still affecting our family. 9, 18, 19 I am angry at Ryan for dying.  We were supposed to work through this together. 6 I never know where I’m going to be when I am going to break down next. 13, 14, 15, 18 If I smell him or hear a song I completely lose it. 14, 19 It is just—our lives still seem unmanageable. 9, 12, 19 Not to the extent that it was when he was using, but we isolated ourselves back then because we didn’t want anyone to know, or we were exhausted, or we never knew what was going on with Ryan. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 We still do that now. 9, 14 We don’t care about the same things. 7, 16 The things that mattered before don’t. 12, 16, 20 AS: Those outgoing parents that you were around with everybody else’s children, you’re not that anymore? 8, 10, 13, 14, 16 LL: Nope.  Don’t have the energy.  It’s not that we don’t care. 7 It’s just that it’s not what matters anymore. 9, 12, 13, 20 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 It is weird.  It is hard to explain. 11 Some of the times even going to family functions shortly after Ryan died. 15, 16, 18 I’m like, “You guys we are going to go. 10 We are going to cry.  It is our first holiday without him. 9, 19 Let’s time box it.  If we stay for an hour and we just really need to get out of there, that’s fine.” 9, 12, 13, 14 My family understands. 9, 12, 16, 18 That is kind of how we are now, too. 14, 16, 17 We go out and do stuff but you will be sitting having dinner at a restaurant and someone will start crying. 7, 9, 11, 13, 19 That’s okay.  Let’s just go to the bathroom. 7, 9, 12 We will finish our meal and leave. 6 AS: You said people were very supportive of you.  Do you feel like your speaking out has helped other people? 13, 16 You are saying you are still fighting for your son. 9, 11 Have there been any rewards for the kind of mothering you’re doing for other people? 16, 17 Whenever I speak at those forums there are always parents that come up after and they are like, “Thank you. 10, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19 This is what I’m seeing and at least now that I know I’m not alone and there are other resources.” 9, 13, 14, 15 I’ve had other parents contact me and say, “You know what? 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 My friend so and so—this is what they are dealing with.” 12, 13 AS: Can they contact you? 10 Are you open to that? 17 LL: Yes, absolutely.  At Health Partners they did a story in our newsletter and it goes out and it hits 25,000 employees. 6, 9, 13, 19 Just the comments that I got on there, through social media. 9 They said typically they get like five hundred to nine hundred hits. 7 They had over 20,000 hits.  That tells us.  I’m like that is what I’m trying to tell people. 16 People know that people are suffering but then people may not know that their neighbor is going through this. 13, 14, 15 A big part of it is the stigma and people won’t talk. 8, 9, 10 I mean that is another thing. 16 We hid it from our family for six months. 8, 18 I have a very close knit family. 18 The first time we would make excuses and the second time he went in and I was like, “Ryan, I need support, too. 9, 10, 13, 16, 20 I told grandma and my siblings.” 5, 7, 20 He almost went white. 9 You could just tell, even for him, it was such a relief to not have to hide this. 9, 12, 15 Everyone sent him letters. 7, 19 I think the way he thought people would react to him was just not. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16 That was good, too, and that showed me that quite frankly the people that are going to support you are going to support you through anything. 7 It doesn’t matter what it is. 20 The people that don’t and are uncomfortable.  Some people at work.  I recognize they can’t deal with it. 13 They avoid me and that’s okay.  I’m fine with that. 14 There are people that come up and say, “I don’t know what to say. 13, 14, 15, 19 I just want to say I’m sorry.” 9, 10, 12, 13 It is odd.  Death is odd.  Especially for a young child. 14 So yeah, it has helped me. 10, 13, 16 It has really helped me with my other children, too. 13, 14, 16 In fact, the other things that don’t matter to me—I sepnd more time, not that I didn’t before. 10, 16, 20 We were so busy running running running. 7, 9, 11 The counselor. 10 When I went up to Cal, when I went out to family, I could only go a day, not the four days. 18, 19 I had to write a letter to him and he had to write a letter to me, and he hadn’t told anyone that his brother had died. 5, 19, 20 After I read the letter, everybody was crying. 11, 19 The counselor came up, and I said, “I know you are struggling with your brother’s death. 5, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 19 This has a lot to do with it. 17 I know you hate me and blame me and that breaks my heart. 13, 14, 15, 17, 18 If you can deal with that the rest of your life and you are sober and can deal with your emotions I will take that.” 6, 9, 11, 13, 19 The counselor came up and said, “Cal, I didn’t know your brother died. 5, 10, 13, 14, 15, 19 You didn’t share that with any of us.”  There were eight of these guys and he said, “How many of you are in here for heroin addiction?  Cal,  I want you to talk to these guys. 10, 13 I want you to try and understand for your brother.” 5, 9, 12, 13, 16 He said to him, which shocked me, “Your brother did not die in vain.” 5 It caught me off guard, too.  He goes, “Lori I’m going to tell you something.”  Because Cal had to read his letter to me, too. 19 It was very apparent that he looked up to Ryan a lot. 10, 16, 17 I didn’t realize they were as close as they were. 14 He said, “If he looked up to Ryan as much as he did it was just a matter of time before he would follow in Ryan’s footsteps and eventually tried it. 9, 10, 12, 15, 18, 20 He may have saved your life, Cal.” 11 And all this time I had never, ever, ever thought about having another child at—it didn’t even cross my mind. 11, 12, 15 AS: Have another child what?  LL: Use.  Because they looked up—I don’t know if that would happen, but it scares the hell out of me. 7, 12, 13, 14, 15 It was interesting. 9, 19 Every time I attend anything I learn something more. 12, 15 I attend whenever I can. 12, 15 AS: Do you still go to Al-Anon? 9 In fact, I went back—for me it is probably just some mental thing but I can’t go. 9, 10, 12, 14, 19 I went back once by myself and hated being there because when I had been there Ryan was in the ambulance. 12, 19 And my two friends that I had met through Hazelden wanted to go there, too. 5, 12, 13, 18 They were like, “Will you go with us?” and I was like, “Sure,” and I can’t go back. 10, 19 AS: Not to that same group you mean? 16 LL: No, because it is a different group—but anywhere. 16, 17 Survivor Resources is good for me, which I should go back to. 19 I can’t go back to Al-Anon. 19 I know it is probably a mental block. 13, 14, 15 I really do, but I can’t.  I learned good tools there but it’s just too painful for me. 9, 12, 17 Because Ryan and I would laugh after at Al-Anon.  Do you go to Al-Anon?  AS: I go to Nar-Anon.  LL: I don’t know if Nar-Anon does it, but you would put a little saying out and they would pull it out and it was just funny because Ryan was telling me on the way there that I was such a perfectionist. 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 I said, “Maybe I am but I have to be in control of things because otherwise, for me, I feel like things aren’t getting done.” 16, 17 There are certain things. 16 That thing I had read that morning was something about you can’t control—something about perfectionists. 9, 17 I go here and I handed it to him and we both started laughing. 5, 9, 11 He was always telling me, “You work on your program, I’ll work on mine.” 16, 17 It’s just that. 9, 12 It is too heartbreaking. 18 You know we should have still been doing that. 9, 13, 14, 15 No, life had a different course. 11, 16, 17 I can’t go back, but I did learn a lot. 12, 17, 19 AS: That makes sense. 16, 17 Anything else you want to say? 13 How do you think about yourself as a mom through this disaster? 9, 15, 20 You just talked about perfection and trying to fix things. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16 How do you relate to yourself as a mother?  LL: I still feel that I am a terrible mom because I couldn’t save my son. 9, 15, 16 That is a thing I have to work through.  I’m like, “Did I do something wrong? 10 Is there something I could have done better?  Am I a terrible mom?” 15 My poor daughter she is like, “Stop, Mom.” 5, 10 I just will always doubt myself. 9, 12, 16, 17 I could have understood him more. 9 I could have spent more time or spent more time with him in his art stuff. 9, 19 There is always going to be that. 16, 17 As far as the other kids I pick my battles more.  I realize that some of these little things truly do not matter. 14, 16, 20 But the things that do I am going to confront you on it. 16 There are going to be consequences.  I just told them, “You have to understand that I can’t. 9, 12, 16, 20 This is the way I have to deal with things now. 13, 14, 16 Because of what is happening. 12, 13 I can’t help it.” 13 I said, “Call me on it.”  In fact Jenna, Monty, and I were sitting in the kitchen just last week and we were talking something about Cal and I was talking a mile a minute and Jenna was like, “Good God, Mom. 9, 10, 12, 13 Settle down.  You are so hyper,” and I was like, “Am I? 10 So you know that is fair. 13, 14, 15 Call me on it because I don’t understand. 9, 12, 16 AS: You’ve kept, even through this tragedy of ongoing problems, that openness with your family? 15, 17, 18 LL: I’ve tried to, yeah. 10 I think it is important.  I don’t know what else to do. 13, 14, 15 I’ve let go of some control because I know… 13, 14, 15, 17, 19 part of it is I’ve let go of control, but I’ve set expectations and I’m trying to follow through now. 12, 14, 16, 17, 19 We lacked that I think with Ryan, which is unfortunate for the other kids too because it is like, you know— AS: An expectation for sobriety? 10, 13, 14, 15 LL: For sobriety, for honesty, if I am asking you to do something I want it completed. 9, 13, 19 I am holding you accountable. 20 It is hard because one day Cal was standing in the kitchen and he came home sometime after his second DUI. 5, 9, 11, 12, 19, 20 I checked his eyes, I checked everything: 14, 16 He even started crying. 9, 11, 15 He’s like, “Mom, please don’t do this to me. 10 I’m not Ryan.”  It just broke my heart. 9, 12 I realized that I am interrogating him. 14 I’m not coming from a loving mother it’s coming from fear.  It is hard to keep in check. 11, 12 You know, I do my best. 9, 13, 14, 15 I have slowed down a great deal since. 11, 13 I was that mom who was involved with everything with their kids. 15 Doing all the right things 14, 16 AS: Yet you still think you are a terrible mom. 9, 15 LL: Yeah, yeah. 10 AS: What does that say to you?  Do you have to think about mothers— LL:  I know. 13, 14, 15 It is interesting that you even say that because even just now sitting here talking with you I have these other mothers that come to me and they are exactly like I am. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 They have done all the same things. 16 Yet I tell them, “You know what? 13, 14, 15 You are a good mom. 15 It’s not your fault.  It’s out of your control.” 17 Isn’t that funny?  But it is hard. 11 I will always feel that there is more we could have, should have done. 16, 17 Because we are held to some standard that isn’t possible to achieve? 9, 12 LL: Yes.  That is our job as parents: to love, support, protect. 10, 13, 16 That is the thing.  AS: But when you do all of that and you still lose a child and you know you’ve done those things and you still blame yourself as if we were super human. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 LL: Exactly. 10 It is played out multiple times a day in my head. 8, 18, 19 I imagine always will be. 14, 16, 17 I don’t think I can go to therapy or anything for help. 13 It just is. 9, 12 AS: Anything else that you want to say? 13 LL: I can’t think of anything.  I mean we just miss him dearly. 9, 12, 16 There is a huge, huge, huge, huge void.  It is weird because you want to say you feel that presence that he once had here is completely gone. 13, 14, 16, 19 You knew when he was here. 6, 12 He was harassing his siblings, he was loud, he was obnoxious, he was funny, he would always try to get a rise out of you. 5, 16, 17 He was always playing his guitar. 16, 17 There is just this silence. 9, 12 It’s just hard. 9, 11, 12 I feel bad for any parent who has to go through this. 10, 16 Not even any parent. 10, 15, 16 Any family. 18 And the friends. 12, 18 When his friends were over here the other day I get it that they are struggling, too. 9, 12, 18, 19 Thank you for taking this on, too.  I had a really nice time sitting here chatting with you. 13 AS: Thank you,  Lori. "
"14","Evanson_Robin","Ian McLoone Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer March 30, 2017 St. Paul, Minnesota Ian McLoone-IM Amy Sullivan-AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan.  I am here in St. Paul with Ian McLoone at Alltyr Clinic.  Can you state your name and say you give me permission? 6, 9 IM: Ian McLoone, I give you permission. 6 AS: Thank you.  Do you want to start with your childhood? 9, 11, 13 IM: Sure.  AS: Where did you grow up? 17 I grew up here in Minnesota.  St. Louis Park mostly. 9 I was the eldest of four kids. 9 I was an overachiever throughout grade school and high school. 8, 20 I was a big athlete and loved playing baseball. 8, 13, 19 AS: Can you give an example of being an overachiever? 6 IM: I always got really good grades, was in the gifted program, was held up as an example in each class. 6, 16, 17, 20 I always had a lot of feedback like that. 16, 17, 19 Positive feedback. 13, 19 I didn’t really get in trouble.  I hated getting in trouble. 12 The first ten years of my life my family was really close and loving and secure dynamics at home. 9, 11, 18, 19, 20 I really would describe the first ten or eleven years of my life as idyllic. 9, 11, 20 My dad was a professional musician for most of his young adult life. 8, 11, 14, 20 When he met my mother he was going back to school and worked in the field of nutrition and wellness and eventually got an MBA selling weight loss programs to doctors and clinics throughout the country. 5, 7, 8, 11, 15, 16, 18, 19 He was a representative for Optifast or Nutrisystem or one of those things. 7, 8, 9, 16 Novartis was bought by Nestle. 7, 9 My mother stayed at home with us. 5, 9, 19 She was almost ten years younger than my dad. 5, 9, 14, 20 When they met he was thirty and she was twenty-one. 5 She had us: me, my sister two years later, my brother after that, and then four years later my youngest brother. 5, 9, 14, 20 AS: When were you born?  Right around eleven or twelve my mom started getting sick mentally. 9, 11, 14, 15 She started having more symptoms of depression and bipolar disorder and got into some drugs: cocaine, meth, heroin, and prescription drugs. 5, 9, 11, 14 My dad was travelling at the time a lot. 17 He would be home every weekend, but he would be gone for a couple days at a time. 12, 19 It must have been when my youngest brother was maybe four or five—I was thirteen or so—and she was spending longer and longer periods of time downstairs in the basement on the computer behind a locked door. 5, 9, 10, 12, 14, 19, 20 I didn’t really think anything of it.  AS: Were you in charge? 17 IM: A little bit, yeah. 10 One day she was obviously very emotional and all of us kids were at home. 13, 19 She said, “Stay here, don’t go anywhere.  I have to step out, but I’ll be back.” 9, 12, 19 We didn’t see her the rest of the night and my dad was out of town I’m pretty sure. 9, 15, 18, 19 At one point one of our cousins must have come over and hung out. 5, 13, 19 I came to find out later that she was really depressed and in a bad spot and she went to Methodist hospital in the parking lot, slit her wrists—did it the right way so they would take her seriously—and went in for the first of what would be countless hospitalizations and rehabs and stuff. 6, 9, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 She was sick for several years off and on in rehab, half-way house, stable, fall off, rehab, halfway house. 6, 9, 16, 18, 19, 20 They kind of started to split. 9, 11, 16, 17 Something else happened and they broke up. 12, 13 She stabilized for a while. 9 AS: Did you live with your dad?  Soon after that she came out as bisexual or gay and was dating women. 18, 19 Again, she got several years of stability. 9, 20 She met this woman and they had a child together. 5 She went back to school and was working on her Master’s and was teaching. 8, 9, 19 I’m in high school and continued to play baseball. 8, 18 I dabbled in drugs and partied and loved partying and having fun, but wasn’t enough to get me in trouble or negatively impact my life. 6, 10, 11, 13, 14, 20 My senior year I was the ace of the pitching staff. 9, 20 I had been on varsity for at least two years at that point. 9, 13, 20 We went down to Florida for spring training and it went really well and I played really well. 8 We came back and were playing the season opener against Hopkins at home and I started the first inning and I couldn’t get out of the inning. 9, 11, 17, 19 I was walking people and they were hitting runs off of me and my shoulder was aching. 11, 15 It hurt like hell.  I had to leave the game and sat out. 6 I saw a doctor and got an MRI done and learned I had tore the cartilage in my shoulder. 7, 12, 17 That ended my season. 12 So, I didn’t really think anything of it and I finished school. 8 I had decided to go to University of Oregon. 12, 13 I took a year off and lived in Portland to establish residency so that I could go to the U of O as an in-state student. 8, 9, 20 That was all fine. 14 Meanwhile, my mom and her partner started to fight and not get along. 9, 11, 13, 15 At one point she had a recurence to addictive substance use. 9 Her partner withdrew and took the child with her. 13, 14 At that time gay marriage wasn’t legal and she hadn’t yet adopted the baby. 5, 8 She had no parental rights, period. 10, 14, 16 That just spun her off into a bad place. 9, 11, 12 She ended up getting really sick. 12 Crack and heroin and stuff like that. 9 That was going on throughout my whole college experience. 8 My sophomore year of college I came back to get the shoulder surgery done. 8, 19, 20 I was told that if I ever wanted to play catch with my kids when I grew up I would need this surgery to fully heal. 10, 11, 12, 13, 20 I came back for my sophomore year and had the surgery. 8, 19, 20 Up until that point I loved drugs. 13, 14 They were great, but I didn’t do them all the time. 11 I didn’t do them during the day or the week necessarily. 19 It wasn’t getting in my way. 16 I remember doing the surgery and getting out and going to my dad’s house and sitting in the basement and taking an extra dose of Vicoprofen and just loving it. 6, 9, 12, 13 I had one of those moments when the clouds parted and the angels sang and I was home literally and figuratively. 13, 15, 19 After that it was pretty much off to the races. 18 AS: What year is this? 20 From that point on I would buy pills off the street from whoever I could get it from. 7, 9 It wasn’t quite full on dependence, but I had a love of opiates. 11, 12, 13 That continued throughout my junior year. 8, 18, 20 My senior year I did an internship in Costa Rica, so I didn’t really use opiates while I was there. 9, 20 When I moved home I had one semester left. 8, 9, 19 I moved into a house where the guy who owned the house and was going to be my roommate did oxycontin together. 6, 7, 8, 9, 18 I just fell way into it right away. 9, 12, 14, 15, 16 Oxycontin continued throughout the school year. 8, 18, 20 In order to pay for it I had started shipping mushrooms from Oregon to Minnesota because you could get four hundred percent profit. 7, 9, 11, 14, 16 AS: What kind of mushrooms? 7, 16, 17 IM: Psilocybin mushrooms. 7 Magic mushrooms. 7 That wasn’t too much of an issue because my buddies here could get rid of them like that. 15, 18 It was so much easy access there. 6, 18 I would just overnight them in a FedEx box. 8, 9, 12, 19 I hadn’t even learned what the laws were or what was protected. 12, 15, 17 I figured it was mail and people can’t go through your mail. 12, 13 I just figured you could ship it out and no big deal. 8, 9, 12, 13 It was fine for a while, but one day I needed cash and I had been doing a bunch of opiates and was not in a good place. 9, 11, 13, 14, 19 The overnight shipping in the box I had packed was going to cost eighty-five dollars. 8, 9, 19 If I could get it into the smaller box it would only cost twenty-five dollars. 9 Being the fucking privileged idiot I was I was just like, “What could even happen to me?” 9, 10, 12, 15 I switched the packaging in the shipping store. 5, 9 Obviously the dude behind the counter saw I was being weird and looking shady and he called the 7 Eugene police department and they came to my house and arrested me. 6, 7, 9, 19 My poor roommate was coming home as they arrived and they asked him if they could search his room—because they only had permission to search my room, and they didn’t find anything. 6, 7, 10, 19 They asked him if they could search his room and he had a big stash. 7, 8, 9, 10 We both got into a lot of trouble. 17 That was going on right as I was finishing school. 8, 14 I graduated and a week later that happened. 8, 12, 13 I was out in Eugene with no reason to be there, no family, no job or anything and was just miserable. 9, 12, 18 My opioid use was spiking. 9 Eventually I went back home to Minnesota. 19 My mom had been out of rehab for a while and was dating this guy who had offered to put us up in an apartment in St. Louis Park totally paid for a year. 10, 12, 15, 17, 19, 20 It had two bedrooms and we would each have our own space if I would come home and move in with my mother. 7, 13, 14, 19 I figured it was my turn because my siblings had been doing all this shit the whole time dealing with all of it. 5, 12, 13, 19 It was my turn to come help. 13, 19 I did and the best thing to come out of it was that my first week I was there I was out at the Cabooze seeing a show and happened to meet this girl there. 9, 12, 13, 19 She was also into that scene of jam bands and hippies and fun. 15 I was standing along the bar and she thought I was with her friends or knew her guy friends that were there. 5, 6, 9, 11, 12, 18 We started talking, but I wasn’t. 9, 10, 11 We exchanged phone numbers and I called her the next day and we went on a date. 7, 16, 19 Ten years later we are married and have three kids. 20 It turned out well. 19 AS: Can you back up to when you got into a lot of trouble? 17, 19 What happened in Oregon? 12, 13 IM: They let us go that day because we told them that we would find a way to snitch on some people for them. 16, 19, 20 I really didn’t have a dealer to snitch on and the people that I did know I had no interest in doing that to. 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 My roommate though knew a dude who was responsible for more drugs than my roommate was, and he ended up being a confidential informant. 6, 7, 11, 12, 14, 17 In return we both got light sentences. 7, 15, 19 We were charged together and we both negotiated this similar light sentence. 7, 15, 17 It still was a Class C felony, which can be expunged. 9 I had to do three years of probation here in Minnesota. 10, 20 I had to go back out there and serve a week in jail and do work release and community service stuff. 9, 19 That was a full year later I want to say. 11, 13, 20 Felony on my record really made life uncomfortable and was a big pain in the ass. 6, 8, 11, 16 I had to go meet with the probation officer every month. 8, 10, 13 It was not good.  AS: How long did you continue using when you moved back to Minnesota? 8, 19 IM: I moved back home and I continued using oxycontin for several months. 8, 18, 19 The guy I got it from one day told me he didn’t have any more oxys but he did have black tar heroin. 19, 20 I smoked it and it did the same thing that oxycontin did. 17, 18 None of the horror stories came true. 9, 18, 19 I didn’t die.  It was identical almost except that it was a fraction of the price and way easier to get. 9, 10, 16 From that point on I switched to heroin and smoked heroin for the next couple of years. 17, 20 Then I shifted over to intravenous use for the next while. 8, 9 Things got really bad.  My wife didn’t know I was doing it for a long time. 13, 14, 15 I would just lie to her about it. 9, 12 When she finally find some tin foil with the big black lines on it I told her it was opium. 6, 8, 20 That worked until she found needles and then I had to tell her I was doing heroin. 13 We would have a big fight and tell her I would swear it off and that I was going to change and I wasn’t going to do it anymore. 8, 13, 16 The next week she would find more needles. 13 We got married and then bought a house and then had our first child and the whole time I was lying and trying to hide it. 6, 7, 9, 16 It all came to a head in 2010. 19 I had been going to the methadone clinic, which was helpful, but then I just started getting heroin and mixing cocaine with it and doing speed balls and fell in love with that. 5, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 15 AS: But you were on methadone? 5 IM: I was on methadone, yeah. 5, 10 The methadone would dull the heroin high, but if I mixed cocaine with it it was awesome. 5, 8 I did that for several months and then I lost my job. 8, 9 IM: I was running a food shelf for a non-profit because I was fluent in Spanish. 7, 11, 14 I was the language guy of the agency. 13 AS: You managed to hold a job, be married, have a house, have a baby? 5, 6, 9, 20 IM: Yeah, like I said I was kind of the overachiever. 10, 16, 17 It was really easy, but a big pain in the ass too. 8 It would have been a hell of a lot easier if I wasn’t putting a needle in my vein three times a day. 10, 13, 17, 18, 19 My employer had gotten suspicious and I was taking long lunch breaks and spending a lot of time in the bathroom. 6, 7, 12, 15, 17, 18, 19 I got a new job at another non-profit and within the first week they knew something wasn’t right with me. 6, 9, 12, 14 They let me go and I was on unemployment for the summer. 19 My son had been born in January and we had moved into the house earlier in November and I was on unemployment and my wife was working. 6, 8, 9 She had to go back to work sooner than she had planned because I wasn’t working. 19 I was taking care of my son half of the time because we had this other half time daycare that was essentially free. 7, 18, 19, 20 I got so sick.  I spiraled.  It all came to a head one afternoon in the summer when we had some family friends over for a barbecue. 5, 12, 18, 19 I still needed to make another purchase of heroin for a buddy of mine that night. 9, 13, 16, 19 My friends were over and the guy I was getting heroin for was in another part of the city, but my dealer came through. 12, 13, 18, 19, 20 My big plan was that I was going to pretend that I was cleaning off the grill out in the alley and my friends were in the backyard so I would just go around the garage and hop in the car, buy the heroin, and hop out, come back out, and have the clean grill and everything would be fine. 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 We are sitting there and I didn’t think anything of it. 13 All of a sudden one of my neighbors walks by down the alley.  Right across from us this big conversion van is there and the door slides open and this whole swat team comes out and arrests my neighbor. 8, 9, 13, 17, 19 They subdue him and then one of the sargeants comes over and says, “You! 13, 19 What were you doing in that car? 7 You come over here. 13, 19 Get on your knees.”  There is a shotgun in my face and my friends are all like, “What the fuck is going on?” 10, 12, 15, 18 “Did you know he was doing this? 13, 14, 15 Did you know?” 13, 14, 15 They patted me down, found the drugs, and arrested me in front of my wife’s really good friends. 9, 12, 14, 18, 19 I went to jail and spent a couple of nights in there. 19 My wife, bless her heart, she worked her ass off and got me an attorney and the attorney got me out.  She had even put money on my commissary so they gave me this check for forty bucks on my way out and I was like, “Cool.” 10, 15, 16 I cashed it at the bank, met up with my drug dealer, came home, and I wasn’t welcome at home. 5, 13, 14, 19 I had to leave. 6 For the next three months I spent it worming my way back into my house with my wife and then getting caught using and then having to go to my dad’s house and worming my way back in. 6, 8, 9, 16, 19 She kicked me out one night and my dad wouldn’t let me come home. 13, 19 That was the moment when I had to make a choice. 13, 15, 16, 17 He was just like, “Dude, come on man. 9, 10, 12, 13, 19 Stop what you are doing.  You’ve got a kid and a wife and things you’ve got to do.” 16 I said, “Okay.  If I go to rehab will you let me stay at your house tonight so I don’t have to sleep on the street?” 6, 7, 9, 19 The next week I did a Rule 25 Assessment and I went to Eden House. 9 Do you know about that? 13, 14, 15 AS: No. I have heard of RS Eden, but tell me more. 15 IM: Have you heard of the Synanon group? 15 They were the original therapeutic communities developed in the late fifties but mostly in the early sixties and seventies. 9, 15, 16 They break you down and then build you back up. 18, 19 King baby, hot seat on the bench. 5 AS: These are those people?  What is king baby? 5 IM: Somebody who acts like a baby but thinks they are the king. 5, 10 It is really fucked up.  Back in the day they would shave your head or put you in a diaper if you were king baby. 5, 10, 19 At Eden House they would do that back until they got in trouble for it in the seventies. 9, 15, 19 They had to tone down some of the blatantly abusive stuff, but everything else horribly abusive. 9, 11 From day one they were pressuring me to come off methadone. 5, 13, 19 They really wanted me to stop the methadone. 5, 9, 10, 12, 13 I wasn’t really sober and it was Hitler’s drug, all that shit. 6, 14 They never explained to me what the research says or science or getting my consent. 7, 15 It was just old school nonsense SynAnon bullshit. 8, 9, 12, 20 AS: What year was this? 20 I bought into it. 7 A lot of it was prison mentality. 14, 17 You have to go along to get along, but on the side people are doing drugs and smoking fake weed and doing shit like that. 14 I worked my way up in the hierarchy of the clients and was the executive client or whatever. 16 The main client.  I would be the chaperone for things, or I would lead meetings. 13, 16 AS: You were on the good side.  I was the ideal client, but I was also smoking fake weed and acting a fool and playing along but acting both sides. 10, 11, 13 One day one of the other clients had a pass and I was his chaperone. 19 We went to his house and it was pretty uneventful. 6, 9, 15, 18 At the last minute he asked me to give him a ride back to rehab. 6, 9, 10, 19 We had to be back by seven. 19 His dad said, “I’m not giving you a ride.” 6, 11 We took a bus and went back home and explained what happened. 9, 12, 13, 19 We were an hour late or something.  We submitted a UA [urin test] and they were negative and everything was fine, or so I thought. 9, 11, 12, 14 The next day was my pass and it was my son’s first birthday party. 6, 9, 19 I went home and we had a birthday party. 6, 19 Family and friends were there. 12, 18 It was a little odd because I was still in rehab, but everything was okay. 9, 19 I get this phone call midway through and the guy on the line said, “Hey, you’ve got to come home now. 6, 7, 13, 14, 16, 19 Your pass is revoked and you’re on ban.  You come home right now.” 13, 14, 19 I was like, “It’s my son’s first birthday party and I’ve got family and friends here. 6, 9, 10, 12, 18, 19 It’s kind of a big deal.” 8, 13, 16, 17 He said, “I don’t give a fuck. 6 Come home now.” 14, 19 I excused myself, went home, and then I was put on the bench for the next three days. 9, 10, 19 AS: What does that mean? 16 IM: That means you sit on a literal bench out in the hallway. 13, 16 You can’t participate in groups, you can’t visit with any of the other clients, you can’t attend lunch and talk to people. 6, 10, 12, 13, 15 At the end of the day you have to go straight to your room. 6, 7, 9, 12, 19 You can’t watch television.  You’re on ban.  You’re persona non grata.  The only group that you can attend is your primary group, but all the other groups you are banned from. 12, 15 AS: This is because you came back an hour late because you couldn’t get a ride? 6, 19 It didn’t make sense. 16, 17 When the program director came in that Monday she was like, “I can’t be co-dependent. 10, 12, 14, 19 I can’t let you let my feelings about your son’s first birthday dictate how I make a decision on this matter. 9, 16, 19, 20 You have to be on ban and on the bench until I say so.”  I think that was the moment that I became utterly fed up with that model. 5, 13, 15, 19 It felt like in my heart that there had to be another way. 16, 17 Had they managed to get you to get off of methadone? 5 IM: I was tapered way down. 12, 16 Usually what they do is you taper down to thirty miligrams and then you stop for a couple of days. 9, 10, 19 Then you take suboxone for a couple of days, and then you’re done. 6, 19 I was down, down, down, down, and actually that weekend before I was supposed to make the transition off my mom came to visit. 6, 7, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16, 19 We sat down and she was like, “Ian, why are you so antsy to get off methadone?” 5 “Everybody says I need to get off of it and that I’m not really sober if I do.” 6, 13 She said, “Dude, do you know the science about it? 13, 14, 15 It is incredibly effective. 12 All the messages you’re hearing is stigma. 9 It’s not grounded in truth.” 8 She said, “Ian, you’ve got a baby. 5 You’ve got a wife.  You’ve got a life to take care of and a house and all these things. 6, 7, 9, 11, 16 People are rooting for you.  You have one chance to get this right and you should use every tool at your disposal and take advantage to make this most likely to be successful.” 6, 9, 10, 14, 16 I was like, “Oh, yeah. 10 I am happy when I’m on this stuff. 9, 17 It does make me feel normal and fine. 14, 16 I can sit and do things and be a human being. 13, 16 Why am I in such a rush?”  I held off on that to their great displeasure, but I stuck to my guns. 9, 11, 15 AS: How long were you there?  IM: Four months. 8 At the end of four months I moved into the sober housing that they had and would just come for groups all day. 6, 8, 9, 12, 13, 19 It was pretty much the same I was just living in a different location. 6, 9, 10, 12, 16, 17, 18 One of the kids that was in the program got busted for drugs or something. 9, 14 They cornered him and made him write a list of all the people that he had ever heard of doing drugs or fucking around. 8, 9, 12, 14, 15, 16 My name came up as someone who had done the fake weed. 6, 19 They confronted me about it and thought I was injecting drugs while I was there. 11, 12, 14 I did cop to smoking K2.  They kicked me out.  I was going to go into longer-term sober housing, but because that was no longer an option I was able to go back home to my wife and our kid. 6, 19 It ended up being such a blessing in disguise. 12 I just had to find another continuing care plan so that my probation officer didn’t kick my ass. 7, 9, 10, 12 I did and I did evening outpatient at Fairview and completed it and it was fine. 9, 14, 15, 19 Somewhere around there I decided I would go back to school and pursue a Master’s degree. 8, 9, 12, 19, 20 Right around that time I found the University of Minnesota’s Addiction Studies program. 13 I got into that and loved it. 13 At the end of my second semester the program director announced that they were doing an Integrated Behavioral Health Master’s program. 9, 12, 14, 20 A full Master’s degree. 9, 11, 20 I was admitted in the first cohort of student in the program, and she had gotten a grant from the state to develop a center of excellence for the study and dissemination of practice in cocurring disorders. 7, 9, 10, 15, 16 She offered me a graduate research assistant position. 9, 12, 13 That paid all my tuition, a good wage, and I had some incredible experiences. 12 AS: What made you want to go into addiction medicine? 13, 16 I just want you to articulate that a little bit. 9, 12, 13 I know it is implicit, but you talked about the Eden model and Synanon. 10, 11, 13, 14, 15 IM: I had two felonies.  First of all I thought there was no way I was getting a job doing anything else, but I could get a job being a counsellor. 7, 9, 11, 12, 16 I think the experience at Eden House really made me question the conventional wisdom that was driving not just the program at Eden House, but everything that you would hear among people in recovery. 6, 9, 12, 14, 16 How AA was the only way, it works if you work it, it is one hundred percent effective if you just do what you’re told. 9, 12, 14, 16, 20 The whole time I am going to AA meetings, but I’m not able to disclose that I’m on a medication and I go to work with a sponsor and he tells me to get off of it, and it was all messed up. 10, 13 When I found the addiction studies program and got into my first couple semesters I realized, “Holy shit. 9, 14 None of that shit that people talk about in meetings and in rehab that I went to is grounded in science. 8, 10, 13, 19 It is all lore.  It is all mythology and it doesn’t stand up to scientific scrutiny.” 9, 12 That was really motivating.  As I was working in my graduate assistantship I started to become aware of some other folks in the field who were doing things. 9, 11, 13, 16, 19 That’s when I met Paula DeSanto and was just floored by her approach and the way she looked at things. 5, 9, 12, 16 That was my favorite class that I took in my whole graduate program. 20 She stopped teaching at the U, so they just asked me if I would teach that class. 9, 10, 12, 20 I will get to teach that, which is pretty cool. 17, 18 I read an article on thefix.com and this doctor was being interviewed about medications and why there is such stigma against medication. 6, 9, 10 I was reading through and going, “Good point! 11 This guy knows what he’s talking about.” 10, 13, 14, 15 I scroll down and I click on his name and look at the link of his clinic and it turns out it was in St. Paul, Minnesota. 6, 19 I said, “What the hell.  It wouldn’t hurt if I sent him an email to see if he would want to have coffee and I could pick his brain a bit.” 7, 13 I met Mark Willenbring in 2012. 5 We had lunch together and I was just enthralled and fascinated by what he was talking about. 6, 9, 10, 12 I asked if I could shadow him and hang out and learn from him. 10, 12 He ended up overseeing my clinical internships and then once Alltyr Clinic got started I started very early on seeing his patients and doing therapy and counseling. 9, 11, 12 After I got licensed I had a half a day here and the rest of time at traditional rehab. 9, 19 Over time I ended up working with Melanie Heu at Pangea Care. 12 They do culturally specific programming and different language specific tracks. 13, 16, 17 I helped to develop the Spanish language track there. 13, 16 While I was there I had maybe a day or two days a week and then over time built up my caseload here. 9, 19 I built up my caseload over there and two years ago this coming August I moved over full time here. 8, 9, 11, 20 I have been full time here ever since. 11 AS: What is the model here? 15 IM: We are an addiction psychiatry specialty clinic. 16 In the continuum of care there is a gap of services. 7, 14 If you go to your primary care doctor’s office and you screen as a heavy drinker and your primary care doctor wants to help you get some help historically they probably would just have a rebah that they could refer you to. 6, 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14 The problem with rehab is that the educational and professional requirements of the staff of a rehab are notoriously very minimal. 9, 10, 19, 20 Very few doctors are going to want to refer their patient to a counselor who has got a GED and intrust their medical care to a doctor. 7, 9, 10, 13, 14 Most patients don’t need or wouldn’t meet the criteria for long-term intensive rehab in a residential setting. 13, 15, 17, 19 If you have a sleep disorder your doctor is going to refer you to a sleep specialist or a neurologist or a neurology clinic or a sleep clinic. 7, 9 If you have schizophrenia your doctor is going to refer you to a first episode psychosis clinic or a mental health clinic. 9, 14 Up to this point there has not existed a medically anchored addiction psychiatry specialty clinic. 7, 9, 12, 14, 16 We are trying to fill the gap on the continuum of services. 14, 16 We have psychiatrists on staff, we have a nurse, we have four Master’s level trained counselors, and we provide fully integrated treatment for substance use and all mental health disorders under the same roof with the same clinicians. 8, 9, 10, 11, 14, 16, 20 Every patient that comes into our clinic gets assigned a primary therapist and primary physician. 6, 8, 9, 13, 19 The first in-take evaluation you spend an hour with a therapist gathering history, finding out course, severity, symptoms, and past treatment. 6, 9, 12, 16, 19 Then you spend an hour with the addiction psychiatrist where you really dig into the important stuff and develop that first initial treatment plan. 9, 12, 16, 19 If a patient needs a high level of care like a structured living setting and additional support than what we can offer in a patient clinic setting then we have partners that we can refer them to to get sober housing and LINE and IOP [intensive outpatient treatment] if necessary. 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17, 20 We remain the constant in the patient’s team over time. 9 We’ve got patients that work with us for a month and patients that work with us for five years. 8, 20 It all depends, but it’s not a set program. 12, 17 All patients’ treatment plans are individualized. 9, 16 As things come up or the facts on the ground change, we change our treatment plan using the latest, best science and research to form our approaches. 8, 9, 10, 13, 16, 17, 19 AS: How many clients are you serving right now? 14 IM: I’m not sure. 15 That’s a good question. 6, 9 I don’t know off-hand. 13, 14, 15 We have a research assistant right now that is crunching numbers and things like that. 9, 11, 14, 16 Since we have opened it is over three hundred I would say. 12, 14, 17 AS: And that was just a few years ago? 9, 12, 20 A couple of summers ago Julie Rehovet who was the program director for the IBH [Integrated Behavioral Health] program until recently asked if I would be willing to teach a course with Dr. Willenbring. 10, 14 We taught psychopharmacology together.  They had it the next semester but it didn’t really go well. 9 The instructors didn’t really do a good job and she offered me the gig to teach that. 9, 12 I have been teaching psychopharmacology for a little while.  Like I said just recently they wanted to start teaching the synthesis seminar in client centered care—Paula DeSanto’s class. 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 15, 20 I’m going to give that a go this summer and see how that goes. 6 AS: How did things resolve with your wife? 16 How did she deal with your addiction? 13 IM: It was so fucking hard. 11 I was such an asshole to her.  I really feel badly. 16 AS: You still feel badly? 9, 16 IM: I put her through the wringer. 10 She did not sign up for that.  All I could really do was work my ass off to try to repair things and make things better and be responsive. 16 I’m madly in love with her and she is the love of my life. 11, 13 AS: There must be something more there on her part too because you don’t have to stay with someone through addiction. 9 If it is your child it is one thing, but if it is your partner it is different. 13, 16, 17 There is more to you than your addiction.  IM: Thankfully. 11 She certainly could have cut me loose on numerous occasions. 9 AS: Did she find support where she needed it? 13 IM: No, not really.  She went to some Al Anon meetings and some Nar Anon meetings, but it was either WASP-y parents of folks who would talk about spending the weekend on their boat in between meetings, or she was the token wife of an addict and everyone else was there for their kids. 7, 10, 12, 13, 16, 19 That was really tough. 18 We have still gone back and forth on maintenance and stuff like that and it has always been an issue. 9, 15, 16, 17, 19 I got off methadone a year and a half ago, but that is always a question. 6, 9, 16, 17, 20 Is there still a part of you that has cravings? 9 Because they know now that it is really a brain thing. 13, 14, 15 It’s not some sort of depraved part of you. 17 It is an actual mechanism in your brain. 10 IM: Yeah exactly. 10 I switched to buprenorphine.  That has been really nice.  I got disillusioned going to a methadone clinic all the time.  Not because I didn’t like methadone and it wasn’t incredibly helpful. 5, 10, 12, 13 It had really minor side effects.  But the system is so over regulated. 8, 9 There are five regulatory entities that oversee methadone.  It’s insanity.  It is ghettoized.  The treatment plans you have to do are junk. 9, 16 AS: You can only get it in certain places. 11, 17 You have to come every four week and you can’t go out of town. 13, 19 Going to my primary care doctor’s office every couple of months was huge. 7, 8 AS: Could you describe your typical work day here? 19 IM: My typical work day is just back to back individual therapy sessions. 9, 12, 19 First of all we are an out of network private pay clinic. 9, 14, 16 We don’t take insurance. 6, 7 We don’t see too many people who are on Medicaid or Medical Assistance. 9 We also really don’t have too many patients that are really wealthy either.  There are a couple that I can think of whose families are very affluent.  Most of our patients are solidly middle-class working adults. 8, 20 We have some younger patients whose parents are helping them and maybe have come to Minnesota for rehab. 5, 9, 10, 13, 14, 16, 19 Went through the wringer a dozen times and finally found us. 18 AS: Do you have a lot of people who have been through multiple rehabs? 17, 19 IM: I want to say that is probably the majority of our patients. 13, 18 We do have a niche among patients that are on more of the mild to moderate end of the spectrum of [unclear] disease disorders. 12 They come home each night and have three or four glasses of wine and can’t stop. 9, 10, 13, 19 They feel like that is too much and they have tried to cut back and quit and have found that really difficult to do who would never in a million years leave their life for thirty days and go to an inpatient rehab program or spend five nights a week going to a three hour group or doing an IOP program. 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 15, 16, 18, 19, 20 We have a really solid niche of patients that are working professionals, especially thirty to sixty year old women who work or have busy lives and have struggled with drinking for five, ten, or sometimes twenty years but never found a place that they felt could serve them well. 5, 6, 9, 11, 14, 15, 17, 18, 20 They will initially come in and we will develop a treatment plan which is often some combination of anti relapse medications and behavioral therapy. 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16, 18, 19 As a team we will work together and find an approach that works. 14 AS: Do people have different plans for how often they come in? 12, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19 AS: That too is very individualized.  IM: Completely. 19 Often times it is patient driven. 7, 14, 15, 18 If we think that they aren’t coming in enough and they are having symptoms and struggling then we will make recommendations, but it is very collaborative and patient driven. 7, 9, 12, 14, 16, 20 If something isn’t working or they aren’t getting the support they need or are in crisis then we will refer them to Paula or a sober house and get them stabilized. 6, 9, 13 There’s noting magical about the treatment a person receives in in-patient rehab. 9, 16, 19 It is just delivered on-site. 9, 12, 13 Once people realize that it makes a lot of sense. 14, 16, 17 AS: What do you see in the future for opioid treatment? 9, 16 What do you see as the best case scenario? 9, 15 IM: Back in the seventies if you had depression you would go to your doctor and they would refer you to a psychiatrist and nobody wanted to prescribe antidepressants because they were dangerous and had a lot of side effects and there was a narrow therapeutic window. 9, 12, 13, 15, 17, 18 If you didn’t get help from you psychiatrist then you’d be committed for six months in the state hospital and treatment was essentially fresh air and sunshine. 7, 8, 9, 13, 16 In the eighties and nineties there was the Prozac moment. 13, 15 Prozac hit the market and was the first to come of many low side-effects, well tolerated, effective antidepressant medicines. 9, 13, 19 Nowadays, if you have depression the first person you go see if your primary care doctor. 7, 9, 19 They try something and in one out of three people it works on the first try and then if it doesn’t work they try a second one and they refer you to therapy and then maybe a psychiatrist and then maybe if you’re circling the drain and doing really poorly then you’ll go to a hospital for inpatient treatment and ECT [electroconvulsive therapy] for treatment resistant depression. 9, 14, 16, 20 If you have addiction the first place you go is the hospital. 9, 11 You go to inpatient treatment for thirty days and then build out from that. 9, 16, 19 All of our treatments were all devised using samples of convenience: 6, 9, 16 those who were hospitalized in a setting who were really sick. 17 All of our treatments were developed for the sickest of the sick. 6, 9, 16 Then we say that is what addiction looks like for everybody.  That’s like looking at an asthmatic on a ventilator in the ICU and saying that’s asthma, so we need to devise all our asthma treatments using that as the model for the illness. 6, 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16 Most of us are hoping to see that the first line of treatment for alcohol use disorder or opioid use disorder, and hopefully eventually stimulant use disorder, as being the primary care office or clinic. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 15, 16 If the initial treatments don’t work then referring for specialists. 6, 9, 16 What we need is a Prozac moment for alcohol and stimulants. 9, 13, 15 We don’t have anything that is widely adopted, easy to use, and patented so there is a big push to promote it. 8, 9, 15 We have it for opioids. 10 If primary care doctors would adopt it it could be effectively treated and managed in a primary setting with little to no stress. 7, 9, 16, 17 For alcohol use disorders we have several effective medications, but they aren’t being widely adopted partially because of the fact that there’s not a big incentive to use them. 8, 9, 10 A lot of doctors don’t know or want to find out about it. 13, 14, 15, 17 AS: They also don’t know how to deal with addiction. 13, 14, 15 It will be education and training and getting new people. 6, 10 IM: That’s what we are trying to do here as we try to spread the word about this approach. 16 Most of our patients have jobs and families.  AS: Not to mention the cost of rehab. 9, 19 There’s not just the actual monetary cost, but the cost to the family, employer, spouse, and children. 9, 10, 12, 14, 18 There are so many rings around that model that are disruptive. 15 IM: Hugely disruptive.  AS: Thank you. "
