13, 14, 15 We were totally shocked. 17 AS: What did heroin mean to you and Dean at the time?  AP: Heroin meant to me you lived under a bridge and you were from a bad family. 16, 18 You were brought up in a dysfunctional family, not to say that ours wasn’t. 9, 18 Not a mom and a dad living together, graduating from high school and going to college. 6, 8, 15 We were in shock.  It took me two years to tell people that he was a heroin addict, my friends. 12, 18, 20 It took me three years to go to Al-Anon. 20 I started with Al-Anon. 9, 11 Then I worked back over to Nar-Anon. 19 How many times has he relapsed? 18 I can’t tell you.  He went to Salvation Army.  He used. 9 Everybody there uses. 9 Then he was in and out of treatment. 9, 16 Do you want to know the details? 13, 14, 15 AS: Just how many times maybe. 9, 18 AP: He was in Teen Challenge twice, Salvation Army; he went to Fairview five or six times. 18 He went to Unity Hospital and then up to Cambridge to Dellwood.  Did Maddie ever go there?  AS: Close, but no.  AP: He went to someplace in St. Cloud. 11 He ended up living at Serenity Village for a while. 6, 12 Fairview was the most focused. 9, 15 Focus 12 was in St. Cloud.  He was at Cornerstone in St. Paul sober living. 6, 9 I think he was in treatment fifteen times. 9, 16, 18 Let me pause this.  DP: Ann was so frustrated at the end and frustrated with me because I didn’t follow the book. 9, 12 Now that he’s gone, her problem really is should she have been following the book. 12 AS: In what way? 16 What do you mean? 16 DP: No enabling, no help, you’ve got to draw the line, we’re hurting him, you’re not helping him. 6, 12, 13, 14 AS: You’re hurting him by helping him. 12, 13 DP: He needs to help himself. 13 She’s reevaluating whether or not that really…  AS: That’s what I’m coming up against.  That’s what I’m discovering.  DP: Then you say, “Where’s that line that allows you to fudge on this but not on that?” 6 You’ve got to do it case by case.  You’ve just got to li