hought he didn’t call on Sunday. 7, 11, 12, 19 He said he was going to call. 7 We didn’t think anything about it.  It was probably four in the afternoon.  It was a really nice day that Sunday. 19 Spencer was riding the bike with the neighborhood kids here. 8 AS: You mean Aidan? 16 AP: Aidan.  The groundskeeper at church came driving up with his girlfriend, we know them fairly well. 8, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 He’s a former coke addict. 17 He’s a really good friend of Greg’s. 12 He said, “Come in the house I have something terrible to tell you.” 6, 9, 15 I thought he had gotten kicked out of the sober home. 6, 11, 12, 15, 19 Dean and I were both there.  He said, “Spencer overdosed and died.” 15 I called my sister Susan to come over right away and Jane. 5, 7, 9, 13, 14, 16, 19 They came over and Claire and then I called Jamie. 7, 19 Then we talked to the medical investigator. 9, 10, 11, 14 She said it was really odd when they found him because there was a needle next to his arm. 13 He was face down in the bathroom. 7 This is the first floor bathroom where everybody is coming and going. 7, 9 They had to jimmy the door open, it was locked. 17 The syringe was half full. 11 She said, “Usually you never find that. 15 They’ve used the whole syringe.” 9 She said, “We also found some vomit on his pillow upstairs. 9 We’re going to do a full autopsy on him.” 11 I had told them he was… 20 [Interruption due to vacuum cleaner]  AS: She was going to go ahead and do a full autopsy. 11 AP: She said, “We also found two packets of heroin in his wallet. 19 We’re able to lift the DNA off of it.  We’ve got a cell phone, too. 7 Do you happen to know what his passcode is?” 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: This is the medical examiner? 14 AP: Investigator. 9 AS: Let’s back up. 19 The owner of New Heights sober house comes to your house? 6, 9, 13, 19 AP: No, his friend. 12 AS: A friend of his who knew you from church. 6, 12 AP: Greg had called Dean’s cell phone and couldn’t get ahold of us. 7, 20 Greg is the owner of the house. 6, 9 He didn’t know how to get a hold of us when we didn’t have our cell phones. 7, 13, 14, 15, 20 That’s why he called his friend from our church. 7, 12 They were able to find our address. 14 He came over and told us, he and his girlfriend. 12, 19, 20 AS: Were you two alone?  Was Aidan here?  Aidan was here, he was out riding the bike.  We were just goofing around with him. 8, 9, 12 When they told us, some neighbor must have watched him; I have no idea who was taking care of him while this was going on. 7, 11, 17, 20 We called my sisters and then talked to the medical investigator. 5, 7, 9, 10, 11, 14 Then they wondered if we had the passcode to Spencer’s phone. 7, 12 Aidan had given it to me right before Christmas because we had suspected that he was using. 6, 9, 14 We knew he was using. 6, 12 AS: Aidan told you what the passcode was? 20 AP: Spencer’s phone had some of his games on it. 7, 10 Aidan gave us the passcode.  They were able to get in his phone and go back and do the trace of telephone numbers, trying to find a person of interest. 7, 9, 16, 19 That’s those emails I showed you. 7 That’s all we know right now. 13, 14, 15 He lived with us the last two years. 9, 20 He probably was clean maybe six months. 8, 9 The way I figure it he probably started using again last summer. 9, 11, 13, 16 Benzos, heroin, pot, I don’t know what but he was using something other than heroin. 13, 14, 15 We had to call the police twice to come and get him because he was acting so goofy. 7, 10, 13, 19 AS: Goofy or violent?  AP: He was waving around and we wanted to take him to the hospital. 6, 8, 12, 13 He wouldn’t go with us to the emergency room. 7 He was just waving all over the place. 9, 11, 12 He could barely stand, could barely talk. 5, 9, 10, 12 The first time the police took him to Fairview detox. 7, 9, 10 They used a seventy-two hour hold. 9, 15, 20 “No problem at all based on our interview with him.” 6 At one thirty that morning we get a call from some kid down at the U who’s found him walking along the light-rail tracks. 7, 15 So Fairview released him.  He had obviously had his stomach pumped. 9 I don’t know what he took. 13, 14, 15 When I get his medical records, I haven’t done that yet. 6, 7, 14 Christmas 9 Eve it was just disgusting. 9, 12 Right before church…  AS: This past Christmas Eve? 9 AP: He had previously used. 9 He just went down like a pancake in the pew. 9, 12 You know how packed it usually is. 10, 13, 14, 15 We had the whole family over here, cousins, nieces, nephews. 5, 18 He had obviously used again and Jamie and the kids, everybody was here. 9 He would refuse to go upstairs. 9 We couldn’t bodily take him up, we weren’t strong enough. 6, 9, 20 He just sat there. 9, 12 My whole family was exposed to him. 18 I said, “This is just what addiction is. 9, 12 This is what they act like.” 10 Dean and I said, “Let’s just forget about being bothered by it.” 9, 12 This is what the disease manifests itself as. 9 At one point he was sitting next to my niece and said, “I don’t want to be this way at all. 13, 16 I’m so sorry. 10 I just don’t want to be this way.” 9, 12, 13, 16 He always wanted to go into treatment. 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 He never fought it. 15 Probably two years ago, we had to throw him out. 20 He lived on the streets for a couple months. 8, 9 Maybe not even that long. 15 He got beat up.  He finally called and said, “I’m ready to go to treatment.” 7, 9, 16 As a mom I just know that he wasn’t going to recover. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I had his funeral planned out in my head for at least the last year, maybe even the last two years, Amy. 9, 15, 20 It was tearing Dean and I apart. 20 I felt bad as a mother not being able to protect my marriage from that. 17 Dean felt bad and I always would get upset with Dean because he was such an enabler. 16, 17, 19 But is that so wrong with what happens? 12 Then I have felt tremendous guilt because we don’t have to deal with the ramifications of heroin use anymore. 9, 10, 12, 13, 17 I can’t tell you what that feels like to not have to have that constant worry, that constant pain all the time. 9, 11, 16 We have the pain of not having him.  AS: So you feel guilty that you’re relieved? 16 AP: Yes.  AS: But being relieved means that your son is no longer in your life. 11, 16 AP: I remember the first time going back to Nar-Anon. 9, 19 I was walking out the door after, I think it was Christy, but she said, “I felt so bad for you. 9, 15, 17 Everybody went around the circle and here you don’t have your son anymore.” 13 But what I was feeling was that I’m so glad I don’t have to go through what they’re going through anymore. 13, 16 I felt always so inadequate in dealing with it; I thought I worked enough of them at home. 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19, 20 I know that some of these processes are—I was so totally confused with Rule 25, never having to deal with that. 9, 13, 14, 15, 17 What you do, getting so many conflicting answers?  I’d get so frustrated with the people I would talk to on the phone who would use acronyms for everything and think you knew. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12 I was supposed to know what that meant and I didn’t. 6, 13, 14, 15, 16 I was so frustrated in dealing with the insurance, trying to get ahold of the right person. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 16, 20 So frustrated with dealing with counselors at different rehab facilities and knowing what they put in to try to help. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 What they give, the gifts they have. 6 AS: But you were frustrated with them? 9, 12 AP: Because I couldn’t get them to understand what he was going through. 9, 12, 16 I guess it all comes down to that I know so little about addiction but I know so much about it. 10, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 It’s so confusing to me.  As a mom I would never want any mother to go through this, even living through it with your child still being alive. 6, 9, 13, 15 In fact, I think it’s almost worse, unless they’re in successful recovery. 9, 10 AS: Even then it’s always on your back. 16, 17, 19 AP: It’s always in the back of your mind. 16, 17, 19 You’re never going to get rid of that feeling. 15, 16 I want to do something and I get angry. 13 It’s the anger, I felt so numb and angry these last three months since he’s died. 8, 9, 17 I’m angry because I can’t remember the good parts of it.  I’m so angry about the addiction parts of him.  I felt so numb. 17 I said, “How could this have happened?” 12, 13 Look at those pictures.  That a disease could be that insidious.  I often felt like, especially the last six months when he went off the deep end with using again, he’s dead but his body is still working. 8, 9, 10, 12, 15, 17, 20 Like a zombie.  AS: At what point would you say you started to detach from him? 9, 11 Was it like the last six months, back in the fall? 8, 9, 19 AP: Yes.  Even before then.  It was at least in August because I remember I was seeing a therapist at Hazleton. 6, 9, 19 We had gone through all these different techniques. 16, 17 She said, “I just don’t see that you need to see me anymore.” 9, 12, 13 Dean and I went back and I knew I had to break my ties with her, being an individual therapist, when Dean and I went to her. 6, 9, 12, 18, 19 Dean and Spence and I went to therapy in the fall and, this is off the tape, just this nincompoop. 9, 12 AS: We’ve had plenty of people talk about their inadequate professional support. 10, 20 AP: Spencer there,  “Don’t you realize he’s using?” 14 We’re sitting in a family therapy session. 13, 18 AS: At a renowned institution for recovery. 9, 14 AP: “Can’t you see the signs?  Can’t you pull him out of this?”  Then Dean and I started seeing her. 9, 11 AS: Not the same person?  Or the same person?  AP: The same person I saw.  Not the one for the three of us.  The good one.  I just love her. 9, 12, 13 She was able to get through with Dean about how this enabling was not helping. 13 Then looking back, I’ve had many conversations with the director of the family program at The Retreat now about this issue between when you’ve lost somebody, enabling, and detachment. 9, 12, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19 They still don’t believe in MAT over at The Retreat. 9, 16 AS: I think we’re on the brink of change, at least some people I’ve talked to say we’re on the brink of change with it. 9, 10, 11, 16 You want to keep the addict alive as long as you can in hopes that they will recover. 10, 12, 13 The bottom with opioids is death. 10 There’s no coming up from that.  Can you go back a little bit about feeling; I wonder if last fall when you were so frustrated and angry with him, do you think that you just kind of maxed out? 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 That you just became so worn down and exhausted by the addiction that you had to detach to just maintain your sanity? 5, 9, 12, 19 AP: Yes.  AS: I don’t want to put words in your mouth. 10, 13 Before you jump ahead to enabling and the kind of critique of that, what was that like for you as a mother to get to that point? 16, 17 It’s years of addiction, it’s fifteen treatments. 6, 9, 16, 20 AP: What got me to that point?  I really started buying into the Twelve-Step program. 7, 9, 11 I really felt really tied in to, there’s nothing I can do to change this. 16, 17 I’m just going to take the fourth step out of here. 6, 9, 12, 20 I truly believe that in order for me to get healthy and to survive this I needed to rely on my higher power. 8, 13, 14, 15, 18 I started becoming very spiritual again and did a lot of reading on spiritualness; I read a lot of Karen Hesse’s stuff. 9, 11, 17 Really reading about not being able to deal with another person’s addiction. 11, 13 Her book, hearing her speak, just attending and doing more step work myself and thinking about it and doing more readings. 9, 11, 12, 15 I just knew I had to rely, for me, on God, my higher power. 6, 8, 9, 12, 15 I almost had an epiphany, I remember one day I woke up in the morning and I just felt, I knew it was black and white: there’s nothing I can do about this anymore. 6, 9, 12, 13, 17, 19 There’s absolutely nothing I can do.  It took me a long, long time to get there.  Mothering doesn’t work, nothing, there’s nothing I can do that’s stronger than heroin and what it does to my son. 9 The only thing stronger than me is God. 9 I thought if I can survive his death. 11, 12 I knew that’s what it was going to be, I’m just going to have to give in to God. 6, 9, 12 I think that’s when I felt detached. 17 I have to let God do his will with Spencer. 19 AS: Was there a little bit of peace in that?  AP: Yes, there was a lot of peace in that. 17 I hear messages coming from the outside.  That’s where you should feel guilty as a mom. 15, 16 You couldn’t be part of that peace.  I’m not explaining this very well.  I had no part in it anymore. 13 It was between Spencer and his higher power, or my God. 8, 15 I knew there was nothing I could do. 6, 12 That’s hard for a mom to say that. 11, 15 AS: It’s the opposite of how we’re trained and raised and feel. 5, 13, 16 AP: I was kind of a controlling person. 16, 17 Hopefully 11 I’m not that much anymore. 13, 18 That’s kind of the way I was brought up to be, I had to be controlling. 9, 16, 17, 18 I have no regrets about doing everything I was able to do.  I have no regrets that way at all. 16 I did too much or a lot. 17, 18 I know there was nothing more I could do. 13, 14, 15 I have great peace with that. 11 I have trouble remembering him before without drugs. 14 That’s what I have to work on in this next time, getting over the numbness and the anger of that.  AS: Do the pictures of him as a child help? 13 AP: This is the first time since the funeral that I’ve brought them out. 9, 18 AS: Thank you for sharing them.  Shelley said, “Mom, you’ve really got to look at these to make sure they’re okay before we put them out.” 10, 15, 16 The last seven years I had to look at those pictures, some obviously he was using. 9, 20 I wanted to make sure there weren’t any obviously using pictures there. 12, 13, 15, 16 I had recorded on my phone with him right before Christmas, of him flopped over on the couch, passed out from using, his head in his cereal bowl. 6, 7, 9, 14 AS: You had taken pictures of that? 6 AP: It helped for me to look at that. 13, 16 That might perpetuate the anger.  I don’t know how I feel about that right now. 13, 14, 15, 16 I’m trying to think of what else. 16 AS: I wanted to ask you something and now I just completely forgot. 9, 12, 13, 14, 19 AP: I joined these other; they’re primarily mom sites, closed Facebook pages for parents or loved ones of addicts that are dead. 10, 13, 15, 16, 20 One is Grass, which is a national organization that doesn’t have a chapter in Minnesota.  It’s a Twelve-Step program for moms or anybody who’s lost a loved one. 9, 13, 15, 18 It’s primarily mothers.  It’s just so disgusting to look at, but it’s a very healthy site for people to vent. 9, 12, 13, 14, 18 AS: Why is it disgusting? 9 Because so many people have lost their children? 9, 14 AP: Yes, so many women or moms can’t get over it. 15, 18 I should show you some of the posts from it. 9 You probably can’t get on it.  Then there’s another one with Compassionate Friends, it’s the same way. 12, 16 I find there’s little support for people like me in the Twin Cities.  There’s Gloria’s group, but Dean can’t stand her. 9, 12 AS: I know what I was going to ask you. 13, 14, 15 You and Dean, what I heard is that you went to the sober house after Spencer died. 6, 9, 15 Can you talk about why you did that? 10 What happened, just for this record? 6, 9, 12, 13 What made you do that, what did you say and how was it received? 16 AP: I still don’t even know what time Spencer died at. 9, 13, 14, 15 It says so on the death certificate, it says two in the afternoon, but he probably died before that. 10 When Greg couldn’t get ahold of us, after we talked to the medical investigator we talked to Greg. 9, 10, 11, 14, 20 Greg told us that he was not in the house when Spencer died. 6, 9, 20 He was coming back from his church. 19 He didn’t get there until one.  All the residents there were traumatized.  There were about twenty vehicles and it was cornered off. 12 The police investigators had interviewed about eight of them. 6, 7, 9 He said, “I don’t know what to do about this. 13, 14, 15 I’ve got all these traumatized people.”  I said, “We can come over and talk to them.” 10, 13, 19 Greg said, “Would you?”  Dean and Shelley and I went over there Monday night, the day after Spencer died, which is when they always have their group meetings. 13, 16, 17, 19 It was packed.  We told them what we had been through and told them how we felt and told them how happy Spencer was at the sober house. 6, 9, 17, 20 How thankful he was that he was there. 13 We told them not to give up hope, there’s so much hope in recovery. 6, 10, 18, 20 Everybody was crying. 11 This beautiful girl, she was absolutely gorgeous, was just sobbing. 6, 9, 12 Saying, “I feel so bad for what I put my parents through.” 10, 16 So many of them said that.  A lot of these people that live in the sober home parents have disowned them because of the addiction and the collateral damage with addiction. 6, 10, 16, 17, 19 It was very soothing for Dean and I to hear the outreach that they gave. 13 Several of them came up to us afterwards and told us how much they liked Spencer, how kind he was and what a compassionate person he was, which was really helpful to me. 10, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 That’s how we brought him up to be. 9, 18 Then I had to have the person that found him show me everything and show me how he was laying when he was found.  I had to have his roommate show me his room. 7 I laid down in his bed to see what he would see when he was alive.  All this is helpful. 13 AS: Do you want to go inside so we can get Kleenex? 13 AP: Oh yes. 14 We’ve been back a couple times now. 14, 18, 19 I met a woman there, it was probably two or three weeks ago, that came up to me and said she went in to Fairview the same time that Spencer did. 5, 19 They developed a friend relationship. 12, 16 She just wanted me to know what impact Spencer had on her. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 She said, “I just remember Jamie and Aidan had just come back from his Boy Scout meeting. 9, 12, 13, 19 He was in his little Boy Scout outfit running around Fairview Recovery Plus floor.” 7, 11 Just hearing those things, I only can think of, sometimes I don’t want to hear stories from his friends from after high school because he stole from them or did something. 5, 8, 9, 12, 13, 16, 18 All I’ve heard is bad the last seven years just to hear something good is just so nice. 9, 12, 15, 20 AS: What did you do at his funeral?  You talked about how it took you two or three years to tell people that your son was an addict. 10, 11, 20 I think something changed in you by the time of his funeral. 16 AP: Yes.  We wanted J. R., our pastor, to be very open about addiction. 9, 12, 13, 17 You were gone. 19 AS: I was out of town. 19 AP: I can give you a CD of it if you want. 6, 13 AS: Yes.  It was a very kind of addiction based sermon. 16, 17 We just said we didn’t want to sugar coat anything about his life, but we want to celebrate his life. 9, 11, 12, 13 He had very good parts of his life. 11 He had a wonderful life until addiction took over. 11 It was kind of two parts. 16, 17 We had his good friend John talk. 10, 12 John talked a lot about the younger days and growing up and knowing what struggles Spencer went through. 5, 9, 10, 11, 13, 14, 15, 17, 19 Then Greg the sober home guy, he spoke too about addiction. 6, 19 There were a lot of people from his sober home in attendance. 6, 12, 15, 17, 19 I think four pews were filled with our people.  AS: From Nar-Anon?  AP: Yes.  Several of his high school friends attended and said, “We just knew what a good guy Spencer was before drugs took over. 6, 8, 9, 12, 14, 15, 18 That’s the memories we have of him.”  I don’t know how many people; there were a lot of people there. 13, 14, 15, 17 At the end, J. R. just gave; we gave the hands on the back kind of thing and said the serenity prayers in closing. 9, 12, 16, 17, 19 That was very powerful. 15 gets so pissed off.  AS: This is your pastor? 9 AP: Our pastor. 9 This is the third heroin death since January. 20 AS: The third? 20 AP: Third or fourth. 20 Our church always hosts the stuff with The Retreat about recovery stuff. 9, 16, 17 AS: What church is it that you go to?  AP: It’s Wayzata Community, it’s a UCC church.  The only reason we started going there is because of Spencer’s addiction. 9, 11 A friend of mine goes, says, “You should come to the service with me. 12, 13, 19 It’s so calm and soothing.”  Then I met the building and grounds guy there, who’s a former addict. 5, 8, 17 AS: He ends up being friends with the sober house director. 6, 9, 12, 14, 18 AP: He knew Spencer because when Spencer worked landscaping that church was one of the places they had accounts. 6, 8, 11, 12, 17 It’s connecting the dots.  It was a very open; we didn’t want to cover up anything about addiction. 13, 17 Dean and I and Shelley have grown so much being open about it. 17, 18 We didn’t want Spencer’s death to be anything different from cancer or diabetes or anything else or have any stigma attached to it. 9, 13, 16, 17 There’s no reason not to talk about addiction as part of a celebration of a life event. 10, 11, 15 AS: Aidan is how old? 20 AP: Seven. 15 What does he know about the cause of his father’s death? 5, 9, 13, 14, 15 AP: We’ve tried to stay age appropriate with him. 9, 10 We’ve always told him since he was about three that his dad had a brain disease. 16, 17, 20 When he died we told him that he died in his sleep. 7, 20 I mean he wasn’t asleep I guess technically. 7, 10, 16 Aidan has been very quiet about his dad’s death.  We’ve been, every occasion we’re with him, we tell Spencer stories, funny stories. 9, 18 He loves hearing that. 13 I went to his end of the year first grade picnic and started talking to one of his best friend’s dads. 9, 10, 11, 12, 20 He said, “This kid just told me that Aidan’s dad died this morning. 9, 12, 20 I knew a kid in his class’s dad died. 6, 12, 20 I didn’t know it was Aidan’s died.” 13, 14, 15 I said, “What did he tell you he died of?”  “Brain disease.”  It was that morning that this little kid told his father. 5, 20 I said, “Well, that’s what we told him, but it was a heroin overdose.” 15, 20 The little kid’s dad is a special ed teacher at Minnetonka High School and deals a lot with kids who have had terrible anxiety either through relative’s addiction, their parents, or them dealing with it themselves. 10, 13, 15, 16, 17 He totally got it. 17 It was good having that conversation with him. 12 We told his Boy Scout leaders the true cause. 9, 20 I don’t know how to. 13, 14, 15 Jamie’s got the name of all these child psychiatrists, but she doesn’t feel the need to call them yet. 6, 7, 9, 13, 16 That’s probably okay.  His teacher at school, he’s had a male first grade teacher that has been very good for him. 8, 9, 20 He’s been wonderful.  I don’t know what to think. 13, 14, 15 Now I feel, I see Dean, we’re parenting his son. 10, 16 I don’t know if that’s such a good idea. 11, 13, 14, 15 We’re being more than grandparents. 7, 10, 16 Is he staying with you? 9, 19 AP: He stays with us like every three weekends because Jamie has to work those weekends. 9, 12, 19 We try to help her out throughout daycare and financially we’re helping him. 7, 13, 16, 18, 19 Although one of the best things we ever did was take out life insurance policies on the kids when they were babies. 6, 7, 9, 11, 16 We’ve been paying them up every year. 11, 16, 20 I would recommend that Maddie and Brandon take out an insurance policy. 6, 7, 12 I think we paid twenty-four dollars a month for years. 8, 20 I thought we stopped paying it but we didn’t. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 20 Then now Aidan has Social Security. 14 Spencer was never able to financially support Aidan, very rarely. 15 We were always doing it. 16, 17 It’s good what he couldn’t provide in life he can provide in death now for his son. 11, 14 Part of the mothering or grandmothering is we have to take care of Aidan. 6, 7 We want to. 13 AS: Why are you kind of critical of that? 16, 17 AP: It gets back to that damn enabling thing. 13, 19 Am I enabling Jamie?  We’re helping her. 13 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 I just want to get that word out of my vocabulary, that detachment right now. 9, 12, 13, 14 AS: I’m not a fan of them now. 14 Not after my tenth interview with mothers, you being number ten today. 6, 15, 19 I’m not seeing the benefit. 14 AP: I’ve never heard anything or read anything about mothering when your child dies. 15 Enabling and detachment aren’t a good thing.  AS: No, they don’t help us. 13 AP: Have you heard other mothers say that? 15 AS: Yes, many.  It seems to me there’s a continuum somehow, there’s like a measured kind of—I’m just thinking this out loud. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17, 19 When you get to a point mothering your addict child that you’ve done everything you feel you can possibly do then you have to save yourself and realize that your child has to figure this out on their own. 13, 14, 16 That’s where that pop psychology idea of enabling and codependency comes in. 11, 12, 13, 19 As parents we are codependent. 10, 12, 16 We’re dependent, our children are depending on us for their lives, and addiction just throws that whole thing into this strange… 7, 9, 12, 14 It’s like a hall of mirrors in a way for parents. 10, 16 In any other disease or disorder or mental illness, however you want to think about addiction, doing everything we can is completely and utterly acceptable and expected. 13, 14, 19 For some reason when we get into Twelve-Step program and this whole codependency thing, I think a lot of it comes from Al-Anon and spouses of addicts—that whole movement. 9, 12, 13, 17, 19 Doing the care work of your beloved addict, you become part of the problem instead of looking at addiction as the problem, lack of resources, lack of treatment, lack of money, lack of knowledge about addiction is the problem. 7, 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 It’s not the mothers and fathers wanting to help their children live to the other side of addiction. 5, 13, 14 That’s where I’m really, really thinking hard about this because it’s not working. 11 Yet, when I ask my daughter, she will say, “It had nothing to do with you, Mom. 5 Thank you for not giving up on me, but you could not have stopped me.” 9, 10, 11, 20 That’s the in between space that we need to talk more about. 10, 13 AP: Going back to the comment about forcing or allowing them to make decisions on their own. 16, 19 I feel that the disease robbed Spencer of the development of his frontal lobe. 16 So that he couldn’t reach that point. 13 He did make a comment when he was living on the streets, when we threw him out, that that made him realize he needed treatment. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15, 16 That was the best thing for him when we threw him out. 9, 15 It didn’t change him to grow anymore and develop breaks in his brain or other things that the frontal lobe produces. 13, 16, 17, 18 I don’t know that much about the brain science just what I’ve been taught. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18 He could never survive that. 15 He could never develop those skills and make a turn around. 7, 8, 15, 16, 19 AS: He needed to be in sustained recovery for a very long time for that to happen. 9, 12, 13 Tomorrow he’ll be thirty-five.  AS: Tomorrow is Spencer’s birthday. 19 AP: Earth Day is what I’m calling it. 7 AS: That’s lovely, Ann. 13 AP: That’s when he came to earth. 19 AS: Should we stop? 9, 10 AP: Yes.  AS: Thank you.  AP: This has been so helpful to me. 13 AS: Your courage and your willingness to talk to me so fresh in grief, I just want to say I was not going to ask you. 9, 10, 12, 13 AS: Well, I was going to ask you months ago when I decided I was going to do this. 8, 12 When he died I realized, “I’m not going to bother her.” 14 Then you came back to Nar-Anon so quickly and I was getting to the end of my interviews and I thought, “If she’s at the meeting tonight I’m going to ask her.” 6, 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 As a document in this moment that freshness of the grief is so powerful. 13, 15 I’m so grateful to you for being willing to talk about it and be so honest. 9, 10 Starting the Nar-Anon that you did two years ago, our connection in the St. Paul group, all of that has been, you’ve just been a really incredible force for a lot of people to feel at home in this turmoil that we live in. 9, 12, 16, 17, 19, 20 AP: I need to keep coming back. 12, 13, 19 Sometimes I feel like I don’t fit there anymore. 5, 13, 14, 16, 18 I need to be there. 13 I’d like to ask Barbara. 5 Did you interview Barbara? 5, 6 The one who came to our group right before Spencer died, who lost her son? 9, 14, 19 AP: Lost her son three years ago. 9, 20 I haven’t talked to her about this issue and I wanted to explore that. 10, 11, 12, 13, 15 AS: Which issue? 15 About enabling?  AP: Enabling and detachment and everything.  I guess I need to think about this some more. 10, 13 AS: She’s also three years out and you’re three months out. 8, 20 AP: Anyways, I don’t know if I told you, The Retreat is finally having a grief support group. 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 20 It’s starting August 20. 9, 11 I don’t even know where to post it. 9, 13, 14, 15 I was going to post it on our Facebook page. 9, 20 They’re for people like me.  I’m really curious to see how they’re going to; it’s a Twelve-Step grief support, to see how that goes.  AS: Maybe just go and see if you like it before you start posting about it. 9, 10, 11, 12"
