.  He’s got diabetes and he’s been asking for his needles. 13 I don’t know what’s true or not. 13, 14, 15 Were they in a fight?  Is it that he’s trying to get her in trouble or he’s trying to get away from her? 16 I think they both know that they shouldn’t be together. 13, 14, 15 It’s in my home and it’s in my space. 19 I don’t think we should be living together. 6 I told her today. 19, 20 We went to the cabin.  I’ve set this boundary and I haven’t kept it. 17 My mind—it’s that mind chatter that says, “Okay, she goes out there.  What are the chances of her not relapsing?”  At least she’s got a roof over her head. 9 She didn’t for years. 20 AS: But she’s using.  KP: I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 AS: You don’t know, right. 13, 14, 15 So the unknown—no matter if she’s in your house or not in your house—is still there. 6, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 20 KP: It’s that constant. 9 At least she’s living somewhere and she’s in treatment. 6, 9, 16 KP: Yes, she’s at New Way every day, in outpatient. 9, 19 AS: They’re drug testing her, right? 9, 14 KP: I think so.  She’s on methadone. 5 AS: She’s staying on it? 9, 19 KP: She’s still on methadone. 9 AS: So what are you doubting?  KP: She’s not working a program.  AS: Even though she’s going to outpatient? 9 KP: I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 I don’t see any change in her behavior. 16 It feels like using behavior is starting over again. 9, 11, 16 AS: So you saw a change. 16 KP: We went to a cabin, and they slept for three days. 19 They didn’t do anything the whole time we were up there.  That’s what scares me. 7 They’re swearing it’s nothing.  How can you possibly sleep for three days and three nights? 7, 19 We were kayaking once, they didn’t go to town, they didn’t go fishing, and they didn’t do anything. 19 They slept.  They did it Memorial Day, same thing.  It doesn’t feel right. 14, 16 [long pause] 9 That’s what’s bugging me.  AS: That feeling, that familiar feeling that you’ve had many times in the past when you’ve known things. 9, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18 KP: My gut’s usually been accurate. 10 Trust your gut. 9 It’s usually really accurate. 10 I’ve got strong intuition about things. 9, 16 It doesn’t feel good. 16 AS: You know what it’s like to live with active addiction and deception, which is part of the addiction, is the deception and lying. 10, 13, 14, 15 KP: And lack of motivation.  AS: Does she have a job?  KP: No. AS: What did she say today when you said, “This isn’t working out.” 19 KP: For the first time she said she was going to call Greg about sober living. 6, 7, 9 She’s said it a million times before. 18 I think she’s got that one foot in, one foot out.  The feelings that come up for me, the anger, which I’ve been working on and trying to be more compassionate and understanding and knowing that even if you’re in recovery it’s really tough. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19 It takes a while. 6 It’s a whole different dynamic. 16, 17 AS: It can take up to two years. 6, 20 KP: I know, but is that the behavior that goes along with it? 13, 14, 15 Just doing nothing? 9 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 Do you know? 13, 14, 15 AS: I saw a lot of working the program and working towards goals and being accountable to social workers and counselors and people outside of her family. 10, 17, 18 KP: That’s what I think is lacking.  I believe that that has to be a part of recovery, the community, the connectedness. 18 Setting and having the support system is huge. 8, 9 AS: And deciding you’re going to do something with your life not just be not using. 9, 11, 12 KP: Right, just be there. 9, 12 Just go. 9 Whatever you do every day. 19 AS: But the state of not using isn’t recovery. 9 It’s just not using. 9, 12 That’s what’s happening. 12, 13 There’re no meetings. 13 She likes the treatment that she’s in. 9, 10, 16 I don’t know how long she’s there. 13, 14, 15 She was court ordered to be there, but she likes it. 10, 12 She said, “I trust the group. 9 I can talk about anything I want to.” 10, 13 She doesn’t talk to me at all. 10