 14, 17, 18, 19 It was so extreme.  It was completely foreign to me. 14, 19 I was that desperate that I had to go there.  AS: To protect yourself.  Did you take yourself to the hospital? 6 KP: No, somebody called an ambulance for me. 7 I remember calling Shawn and saying, “Would you come see me?” 7, 11, 13, 19 She wouldn’t come see me. 13, 19 That was really painful.  Even then the drugs were more important. 14 AS: You told her how you felt? 17, 20 KP: Yes.  AS: That’s the power of addiction, isn’t it? 15 KP: It can manifest itself and grow and morph within each one of us. 9, 17 It can take over every part of our being. 6 I think if I had been in a more spiritual place at the time I don’t think it would have been that extreme. 11 I just didn’t believe in anything. 9, 12 I didn’t believe there was a God.  I didn’t believe there was a higher power. 8, 15 It was just like, “I’ve had enough.” 9, 10, 12, 20 Why does this keep happening to me? 12, 13 That’s how I felt. 17 What did I do to deserve this?  AS: Right, and that nothing you’re doing is helping. 13 KP: It took a long time to get there, to realize that there’s nothing I can do except love her and tell her if she’s ready. 13, 14 She wasn’t ready.  She went into treatment so many times for the family or for us or for me. 9, 16, 18 She’d say straight out, “I’m not ready. 6, 9 I don’t want to quit.” 13 AS: Do you know how many times she’s been in treatment? 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18 KP: I think this is her ninth. 20 She’s very proud to say that.  It’s odd.  That they would say, “Oh, this is my ninth treatment.” 9, 16, 20 I just cringe. 9, 12 She never went through it. 15 She didn’t stay. 9 She never stayed, all those times. 5, 9, 15, 18 I think she stayed the first time at The Retreat; she went through Meadow Creek the first time she stayed, and then she went through Park. 5, 9, 16 So three out of the nine, she spent any period of time then. 19 To me it doesn’t count.  What’d you get from that?  Maybe it was a baby step forward each time. 5, 9, 12 I don’t know how long she’s been clean. 13, 14, 15 She said she’s done meth twice since January. 5 Amy, I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 She told me she hadn’t done anything. 20 AS: So the deception isn’t over yet.  How are you today? 19 How are you since you were hospitalized?  KP: I’ve been on an uphill.  It was just kind of one of these, in my mind, like a one-time feeling. 9, 12, 16, 17 I’ve never felt it before or after. 15, 17 I went through some pretty intense treatment. 9, 15, 16, 18 I went to DBT.  Are you familiar with DBT?  AS: Yes.  KP: Last summer, and that was helpful. 9, 13 It gives you new skills to use. 6, 7, 9 It’s like a different language. 13, 16, 17 AS: The hospitalization was a year ago April? 20 KP: Yes.  AS: So like sixteen months ago. 8 KP: I did that last summer. 9 I have a fantastic therapist and we do EMDR, which has helped me tremendously with all of this. 6, 9, 12, 13, 16 It’s amazing how a session can change my perception or my reactions to things. 10, 15, 16 It’s fantastic. 9 Those tools—that work—has kept me stable ever since then. 9, 18 I get angry.  I’m trying to work on the anger part of it. 16 I know you’ve been there AS: Hang in there. 13, 14, 15 I have, but I have to say the anxiety doesn’t go away. 16 It becomes part of you. 13, 19 It’s part of your story with that child. 9 It’s something that she’ll be living with and I’ll be living with. 6 KP: It gives me hope when I see other moms, other families, other parents. 6, 10, 15, 16, 18 AS: We need that hope to survive. 10, 13 It was those other people in the meetings whose kids were four or five years in recovery that helped me when my daughter was homeless by the river. 5, 13, 16, 19, 20 KP: Is she still on methadone? 9 AS: Yes.  KP: Does she talk about getting off of it? 10 AS: Yes, they’re tapering down really slowly.  KP: Are they both taking it?  AS: Yes.  KP: I support it now. 14 I wish I would have been more knowledgeable, but she hates it. 13, 14, 15 They want her on a higher dose so she’ll feel better. 8, 13, 15, 16 She sees the psychiatrist this week. 9 We were talking about the system, that part of it. 8, 9, 10 I’m rambling, I’m sorry. 10 It’s okay.  KP: That whole idea of trying to find help, starting with no insurance. 7, 9, 11, 13, 16 MA has been actually pretty great. 10, 11, 18 Through Medica she’s gotten a lot of benefits. 14, 15, 17 That way once we figured out that whole navigating thing. 12, 13, 16 She couldn’t have done that navigating.  I had to do that piece.  She could never have figured it out. 12, 13, 15 It took me months. 8 Then trying to find her a psychiatrist, which has been a new thing. 6, 9, 16 I called the U of M Department of Behavioral Health or Mental Health and Addiction. 7 They said, “Well our one psychiatrist just retired and we’re not taking any new patients.” 6, 9, 12, 19 This is not like Nystrom, one of the other smaller psychiatric clinics. 9 AS: It’s not a small practice. 10 KP: I said, “Can you give me a referral?” 6 “No we don’t have any referrals.  I have no idea what to tell you.” 11 I was just like, “I’m the mother of this addict.” 9, 10, 12 I just went on this whole rant about how can you not have an idea of where to point people when this is so prominent? 7, 9, 11, 12 I called a psychiatrist that I know. 7, 9, 13, 14, 15 Why I didn’t go that route in the first place? 9, 11 She gave me the name of one in Plymouth, Plymouth Psych Clinic or something. 6 They got her in in a week.  She goes Thursday. 19 You had to have the tenacity as a mother to keep at it. 12, 15, 20 We don’t take no for an answer. 6 KP: You almost have to go through personal connections to find a resource. 9, 16 If you go down the normal channels of MA or Medica, any of those channels, you don’t get anywhere.  Or you get three to four months. 8 We start with a physical thinking, “Oh, you’ll get a referral.” 9, 11 Took her to Fairview, had a physical, they said, “Here’s a couple names.” 6 It’s at least thr