"20","Holter_Janise","Charles Reznikoff Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer January 17, 2017 Minneapolis, Minnesota Charles Reznikoff-CR Amy Sullivan-AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan.  I am with Dr. Charles Reznikoff at the Addiction Medicine Center at HCMC [Hennepin County Medical Center] in Minneapolis, Minnesota.  It is January 17, 2017.  I am trying to get a whole picture of the people who are involved in what is going on right now with opioids in treatment and recovery and what has happened in the past. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 16 That said, I would like to be able to paint a picture of who are the kinds of people who are doing this and what their personal story is. 9, 10, 16, 17 Can you tell me a little about your family and growing up and how you got interested in medicine. 9, 11, 17, 18, 19 CR: I grew up in Madison, Wisconsin.  Both of my parents were professors at the University of Wisconsin. 10, 13, 16 My dad’s dad was a famous doctor in New York City -- he was a hematologist. 9 My mom wanted to be a doctor but because of circumstances in her life that wasn’t available to her. 9, 11, 12, 13, 15 I grew up in a very academic family. 18 Both my parents were geneticists. 9, 10, 16 I grew up talking about genetics and biology over the dinner table every day. 10, 19 My mom was Catholic. 15 I think she is now a recovering Catholic, you might say. 14 I was brought up Catholic and my mom was very into service. 9, 15, 18 Anyways, I grew up always told from a young age that I was going to be a doctor or a priest. 9, 14, 16, 17, 20 It sounds terrible, but I think my mom meant the best by that. 9, 10, 15, 16 My dad was really mellow about that -- he never told me what he wanted me to be. 12, 13, 15, 20 But, my mom wanted me to be in some form of service. 12, 13, 15, 17 I think she would have accepted if I didn’t, but from a very early age I was told I was going to do one of those things. 16, 20 By the time I was twelve I knew I wasn’t going to be a priest. 6, 9, 12 [laughs]  I crossed that one off the list! 9 That led me to be a doctor.  I think other relevant things in my family was that my sister was the smartest person I had ever met. 5, 9, 16, 18, 20 She was my older sister and she is a mathematician. 5, 8, 9, 20 She was a very rigorous and demanding thinker.  It sounds terrible to say this but she was verbally aggressive. 8, 10, 15, 16 I don’t mean that to be abusive. 9, 11, 16 I mean that if you misspoke she would correct you and if you were illogical she would correct your logic. 16, 19 If you used poor grammar she would correct it. 9 I still use poor grammar but the ability to deal with a critical verbal environment came from my sister. 5, 9, 13, 19 She also has a little bit of OCD [obsessive compulsive disorder] so I grew up with some mental health issues in the family. 14, 15, 18 My brother is one year older than me. 5, 20 He is adopted. 8 He is currently a safety manager at a construction worksite. 9, 13, 14, 16 He is ten months older so we grew up almost as fraternal twins. 5, 8, 9, 14, 20 My parents couldn’t conceive another child so they adopted my brother and then immediately conceived me. 5, 8, 10, 16 We grew up like fraternal twins. 14 He has a much higher risk for addiction and anxiety. 8, 15, 18 At age twelve, thirteen, fourteen I saw him smoking cigarettes and weed and drinking. 6, 14 He was getting in trouble.  As soon as he could he was getting tattoos and taking all the risks.  The way I think about it is whatever ‘dumb’ is I did ninety-five percent of it and he did one hundred and five percent of it. 16 Overall, childhood was excellent. 7, 11 I was very sheltered and protected. 12 It was a safe and wonderful thing.  I grew up in this amazing, academic, intellectually challenging circumstance. 9, 15 With my brother I got almost a twin-like experience when we were getting in trouble together. 5, 9, 10, 14 With my sister I got this older sister who was very rigorously demanding and intellectually challenging. 5, 9, 20 My parents were these very smart intellects. 10, 16, 20 My elementary school was like lily-white. 8 Very affluent, white kids.  There was one person of color in my elementary school. 8 My middle school was forty percent black just by coincidence of the districts of those different schools. 8, 9, 12, 16, 17 My high school was back in the other district with the University brats in Madison, Wisconsin. 8, 9, 13, 19 AS: Which high school was that? 8 CR: Madison West. 9 It was a great school. 8, 11 I don’t know if it is anymore, but at the time it was. 13, 14, 15 I would say I was pursuing the doctor thing, but I hadn’t really thought deeply about it. 11, 12 It seemed like a good path, and it seemed like a good fit. 14, 19 It was being put in front of me. 10 Then out of high school I got into a program called the Medical Scholars, which I don’t believe happens anymore. 7, 8, 12, 13 The University of Madison Medical School has one hundred and fifty medical students per year. 9, 13, 14, 20 Fifty of those spots -- one third of the medical school -- is reserved for Medical Scholars. 8, 14 Medical Scholars get in coming out of high school. 8 Basically you apply to a program out of high school at the University of Wisconsin. 7, 8, 13 You have to be a Wisconsin resident, you have to go to University of Wisconsin for undergrad, and if you maintain a certain GPA [grade point average], which was very challenging, and do certain prerequisites, they grant you automatic admission into the medical school. 7, 8, 13, 14, 20 What Wisconsin wanted was to capture what they thought were their bright students and keep them in Wisconsin or in Minnesota. 9, 11, 12, 13, 14 Keep their applicants in the state. 9 They did this as a lure.  I got into the Medical Scholarship program.  My pediatrician was on the admittance committee. 8 I don’t know if that’s nepotism or whatever you call it. 7, 13, 14, 15 [laughs]  I have really just had incredible luck along the way. 9, 12, 16 It is not like I earned everything I am. 10 I’m not saying I’m incredibly successful, but I am a doctor so I have a lot of things going for me. 11, 12, 16, 17 When someone has all of that going for them I am just so aware of all the little turns of luck I had. 9, 12, 19 Within the University of Wisconsin’s forty thousand person campus, Medical Scholars is like a liberal arts school dedicated to biology and pre-med embedded within the undergrad. 8, 10, 13 I had all the benefits of a big undergrad, yet none of the problems of being in a gigantic state school. 8, 9, 14 It was an incredibly focused pre-med education program. 9, 10, 12, 15 You have to get a good GPA, and they would dictate fifty percent of your pre-med courses and you had to get basically all As in your pre-med courses. 7, 11 All of the rest of your course credits -- do whatever you want; do enriching your careers, take philosophy, take Spanish, take whatever. 6, 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 The typical pre-med is stressing out about their GPA to get into the medical school spots. 8, 9, 14 I was basically studying to learn. 7, 9, 11, 12 I had to get a good GPA to maintain my Medical Scholar standing, but I wasn’t trying to outcompete my colleagues. 9, 12, 16 It was amazing. 15 I met the GPA bar by like .01. 5 It was literally a miracle.  It was like a B plus in organic chemistry instead of a B that did it. 9, 16 It was literally that close.  AS: But you stayed with it. 5, 9 You continued to enjoy it. 18 CR: What is really does is it gives you a really enriched education. 6, 10 You can take philosophy and Spanish and history and all these courses that make you feel more like an enriched person. 6, 9, 16 Meanwhile you work your butt off in your biology classes where you can take some risks in your other courses. 6, 8, 20 The typical pre-med is so anxious about their GPA that they will take fluff so they will get good grades in the fluff to focus more on the bio-sciences. 6, 15, 20 I could take more risks with my curriculum. 6 That has set this precedent for me with this kind of pay-it-forward thing where a lot of people enter medical school feeling like they competed their way in -- I feel like I entered medical school with this like, You’ve been given this, do something good with it. 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 14, 16, 17 I had incredible fortune. 12 I didn’t feel like I was a doctor until human anatomy. 16 The first week of medical school you start dissecting bodies. 8, 9, 11, 14 At that point I was like, Oh, wow, this is what being a doctor is and I loved it. 10, 13, 14 Human anatomy was probably the most important class I ever took. 20 It was incredible. 12 I don’t feel like I knew what being a doctor was until medical school. 6, 8, 12, 14, 16 In some ways that’s the story of an entitled person. 9, 16, 17 Someone affluent who had the silver spoon.  I didn’t have to stress out about my career until I was already in medical school. 7, 8, 9, 11, 14 And then when I was in there I was like, Yeah, this works for me. 10, 14 I had it easy.  I really did.  I had a really good path. 14 AS: The important thing is that you realize that. 14 CR: Oh yeah. 10 I am very lucky, compared to some of the things our patients and other people have to fight against in their young life. 11, 12, 14, 16 AS: How did you get into addiction medicine?  Did you have a personal connection? 16 CR: I think that almost everyone’s got someone in their family that is addicted. 9, 18 My sister had some mental health issues; my brother was alcoholic and later got into cocaine and opiates. 5, 9, 14, 15 When I was in medical school there was a scandal in Madison, Wisconsin where some cop caught a news reporter using coke. 6, 8, 13, 14 The news reporter, rather than taking some felony cocaine charge, said I’ve got a good deal for you. 6, 13, 17 He said, I know of at least a dozen firemen that are selling cocaine out of the fire station. 7, 9, 13, 14, 15 I will give you those names if you give me a plea bargain. 5, 6 Of course because the cops and the fire stations usually have competitions, the cop was like, Yes. 9, 10, 15 This guy names thirteen names of these firemen that were using and selling cocaine. 6, 7, 15 AS: Do you remember what year this was? 20 It’s in all the newspapers. 6, 13 You would be able to find it.  Among those names, he listed my brother who was a fireman at the time. 5, 6, 9, 15 My brother was certainly alcoholic and had certainly used cocaine. 5, 9 Eleven out of the thirteen people were selling cocaine out of the fire station. 7, 9, 15 It was a huge deal and they got fired and went to jail. 12, 13, 15 Two of the people that were listed didn’t have any evidence. 9 My brother was one of them. 5 So my brother was caught in this fire storm of the fire union versus the fire police chief. 5, 7, 9, 15 Someone had seen my brother do cocaine in a bar late at night. 5, 19 No doubt he did; no doubt.  But lots of people use cocaine at 2:00 AM when they are twenty-three years old and they just got this new job and they have money. 5, 6, 9, 12, 17, 20 All the seriousness of the accusations of the people selling the drugs -- no one ever linked my brother to that. 5, 7, 14 I don’t link my brother to that. 5 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 He was one of two people that were front page news in the newspaper for a year. 6, 13, 20 AS: Even though he was still part of it all. 9 CR: Ultimately he was exonerated.  The charges were all dropped against him. 14, 17 It put him under such stress and scrutiny. 9, 10 He was an alcoholic. 5 He was exonerated of all charges. 17 He was allowed to keep his job. 12 After six months of being on the front page my mother was tortured by it. 8, 12, 20 You can imagine being his mom. 14, 15 In the end, he was wrongly accused of this. 9, 12 Two months later he got his third DUI [driving under the influence] and lost his driver’s license. 7, 8, 9, 14, 20 After that he was fired as a fireman. 12, 15 Joe has since gotten sober. 6, 15 After that he got sober from alcohol and hooked on pain pills. 6 Then he got sober from pain pills and now he is married, in recovery, a safety manager at a construction site, and a union welder. 6, 9, 13, 14 I saw this whole process go down.  We did an intervention for my brother. 5 AS: Were you in medical school? 8, 14 When did you start medical school? 8, 9, 11, 14 I graduated in 2002. 8 It was 2000, 2001 when this was happening. 12, 13 That may have been subconscious and it may have directed some of my thoughts but I was not explicitly becoming an addiction doctor to treat my brother. 5, 11, 12, 16 I was actually really clear with him. 10 I didn’t want to threaten him and be like, I’m doing this because of you. 10, 13, 15 I was also not doing this to help you. 13 I’m not doing this because of you, or to help you. 13 I’m doing this because it is right for me. 14 I’m doing this selfishly.  When I got into opioids and the pain world, Joe, my brother, had not come out as addicted to opioids. 5, 10, 13, 15, 19 When he finally told me he was hooked on Percocet, I was already deep into this world. 15, 20 Going down the opioids path was good for me and it had nothing to do with my brother. 5, 10, 14 Only later I found out he got hooked with opioids. 10 Just like every other person in the county that is introduced to opioids. 7, 9, 10 That was a very influential, early thing that happened to me. 12, 13 I think also dealing with my sister’s mental health issues affected how I interact with patients and think about mental health. 5, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 It’s easy, in this story to be like, Oh, he had an alcoholic brother. 5, 9, 10 But I also had an OCD sister. 5, 9 Both these things had equal influence on how I think about and interact with patients. 10, 16, 20 I did an addiction rotation in medical school in that context -- while all of that was happening. 8, 12, 13, 14 I talked to the addiction doctor at the University of Wisconsin. 10, 11, 13 His name was Rich Brown. 6 There was a Randy Brown and a Rich Brown -- both of which work in addiction at Wisconsin.  In this case I talked to Rich Brown, and he was cool. 10, 11, 17 AS: What do you mean you talked to him? 10, 11, 16 CR: I emailed him and I was like, I’m struggling with what I should do with my brother. 5, 9, 10 Do you have any advice?  He emailed me back and then I did an addiction rotation.  I went to internal medicine residency at County Hospital -- here, HCMC.  I didn’t know if I was going into addiction or not, I didn’t know what I was going to do. 13, 14, 15 I was just enjoying residency. 9, 12 I did find that working with patients who had addiction wasn’t like Oh, an alcoholic. 5 I don’t want to go into the room. 7, 13 Then when I come out of the room I feel gross and weird. 7, 13, 16, 19 A lot of doctors are aversive to working with addicts. 17 Or they find working with addicts aversive, I should say.  That’s a really common thing.  Doctors are humans too.  Some doctors are like, ‘I feel really weird dealing with the health consequences of obesity’ because they think obese people caused this by themselves by eating too much and gaining weight. 9, 10, 13, 14, 16, 18 ‘They have bad knees because they are obese.  I feel morally compromised.’ 16 Some doctors have that thought. 11, 12 Some doctors have the chainsmoker opioid user who has a heart attack. 9 For me, honestly, if there is anything, I don’t know if there is a bias, but patients I work with that have diabetes -- I will do it, but it’s not thrilling to me. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16 I leave the room and I was like, I had to do that because it’s part of my job. 6, 7, 10 Whereas other people love that. 13 They go into that field.  We all have our things. 16 It just so happened I discovered during residency that when 9, 12, 13 I’m in the room with a patient that’s addicted I’m not stressed out. 7, 9 I’m happy to be there, I feel like I’m delivering care, I can look them in the eyes and relate to them, they seem to relate to me back, and I didn’t question that. 6, 7, 9, 14, 16, 17, 19 During residency I realized that was unique. 14 Most people are avoiding those patients whereas I’m drawn to them. 14 It’s probably because I saw it happening first hand with my brother. 5, 9, 12, 13 I know my brother is a good person, and I love my brother, so I know this person right here is someone’s sibling and I can look them in the eye and treat them as a sibling. 5, 13, 14, 15, 16 I think that contributed.  The fable I tell about how I got into addiction medicine is when I was a first year resident, I saw this young, black, gang member named Anthony. 5, 6, 9, 14, 20 He called himself Ant. 7 He had a tattoo of the word ‘ant’ on his arm.  He had congenital heart defect and he came in for his heart problem. 19 When he was there he confided in me that he was a heroin user and 9 I didn’t know what to do. 13, 14, 15 I was an intern.  He went home and a couple of days later, as I was walking down the hallway a phone rang. 7, 15, 16, 19 A receptionist picked it up and said, Yeah, actually yes, he’s right here. 9, 10, 14 Someone just called this phone and asked for you, Charlie. 7, 9, 10, 12 I just happened to be walking down the hallway. 9, 12, 13, 15, 16 Crazy coincidence.  I was surrounded by people that saw this happen. 8, 12 I picked up the phone and it was Ant and Ant was crying. 7, 11 He said, I just injected heroin and I don’t know what to do. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 There were people yelling in the background and he was crying and he said, I’m worried, I injected heroin and I don’t know what to do. 8, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 I didn’t know what to tell him so I told him to go to the emergency room, which probably was not even the right answer. 7, 13, 14, 15, 20 I didn’t even know what to tell him. 13, 14, 15 All of these people were like, What happened and I told them that a patient that I saw three days ago randomly called this phone number and asked for me and confessed that he had just injected heroin. 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 19, 20 In some ways that was my vocation calling. 7, 10, 16, 17 I was like, That’s my future calling. 7, 10 That was a true story. 9 The other, more real, practical reason I got into addiction medicine was that my senior year, then as a chief resident, in my chief year, I would always work out in the gym. 10, 16, 17, 20 Gavin Bart, who is an addiction researcher and is my current boss, would work out beside me. 16 He would talk to me and he said, Look, if you want to take this job in the addiction department, we’ll account for fifty percent of your time with addiction work and the other fifty percent you can self determine. 6, 10, 13 Sounds eerily familiar, like the Medical Scholars program where it’s like here are fifty percent of your work you will have to work really hard for and we are going to account for and then we are going to give you freedom. 6, 11 Taking a job here pays thirty percent less than a community job, so it’s not like I’m going for the money. 10, 16 What do you mean a community job? 16 CR: Like if I went to a community hospital and just out of general interest I would have made at least thirty percent more money. 9, 12, 16, 19 He didn’t give me a financial pitch, he gave me a professional enrichment pitch. 6, 20 He just said that if I liked addiction to come do a fellowship and then come to the addiction division and you’ll be able to have a lot of freedom to self determine your job. 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 17, 18, 19 It was just such a great offer. 9, 11, 12 Then when I assembled my dream job it’s this diverse patchwork of different things. 14, 16, 17 Everything balances each other.  There is a lot of addiction, but a lot of it is non-addiction. 17 He let me develop myself professionally and he trusts me. 9, 16, 19, 20 I saw this opportunity to work within a professionally enriching setting with a good boss. 17, 20 AS: When did you start with him? 9, 11 CR: Residency was 2002 and then chief residency was 2005 to 2006 and then fellowship was 2006 to 2008. 15 I have been here since January 1, 2008.  When you say fifty percent with addiction medicine does that involve the clinic?  CR: Yes.  AS: Can you describe what you do?  CR: About half of the weekdays of the year I am responsible for being on-call for the methadone clinic, which could be super mellow or super busy. 5, 7, 9, 12, 19, 20 It allows me to be in my office to take phone calls, multitask, do academic projects. 6, 7 From 6:00 AM until 1:00 PM, six hundred patients might come through these doors to the methadone clinic and we need a doctor on call. 5, 7, 13, 19 It could go smoothly or it could go crazy. 16 About half of the days when this clinic is open I am on-call and then the other half is another doctor. 7, 17, 19, 20 Methadone is a big component of my addiction work. 8 Every Wednesday afternoon, I do a tobacco clinic. 19 AS: This is one of the other things you do? 16 CR: This is one of the other components.  Well, the tobacco clinic is within the addiction domain and is something I have chosen to do.  I don’t know if that counts as my addiction part. 13, 14, 15 What Dr. Bart needed me to do was be on-call for the methadone clinic. 5, 7, 13 That’s what he needed. 13 Outside of that ten percent of my time is dedicated to tobacco work. 10 Ten percent of my time I drive to Rice County and work in Rice County and I work at a Suboxone clinic. 7, 14 Ten percent in tobacco, ten percent teaching at the University of Minnesota. 13 Twenty-five percent is general medicine hospitalist work. 9 I work with medical students and medical residents taking care of patients with pneumonia and heart attacks and what not. 7, 9, 14 The rest of it is on-call for methadone. 7, 9, 19 That’s busy. 9 CR: It’s a lot of things. 16, 17 The methadone is so hit and miss that you can have a lot of side projects. 5, 17 So I have a lot of side projects, extra curricular projects. 17 AS: What happens when you are in here at the methadone clinic? 5, 12 What do you typically get called out of your office for? 7 CR: Someone appears oversedated, someone wants to change their methadone dose, someone has been continually been using drugs despite our best efforts and we need to do an intervention. 5, 9, 11, 13, 14, 16 AS: When you say other drugs what do you mean? 14, 16 CR: Could be opiates, could be cocaine, could be alcohol.  Any combination of drug use plus being on the methadone dose and whether or not it’s wrong or they appear oversedated. 5, 9, 14 Sometimes they have a question and they want to speak to a doctor. 5, 6, 9, 13, 18 Or they are dissatisfied in some way. 16 Often the counselor has a question; the counselor feels like they are up against the wall or they have hit a roadblock and they need to brainstorm what is the next best step. 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16 AS: Have you gotten to know a lot of patients? 13, 14, 15, 17 Do you have patients that have been here for years? 20 CR: Yes.  I think the stereotype about addiction medicine is that it is this series of emergencies because an addict who is not in care is a series of emergencies. 7, 9 An addict who is seeking care isn’t going to the emergency room, isn’t going to the urgent care. 7 They are hospitalized, and in jail, and in detox. 10 An addict who is in care isn’t like that at all. 7, 10 An addict who is seeking addiction medicine is in long-term medical management of care. 7, 14 Whether they are getting a medicine or they are at support groups.  These addicts that get into care are these long-term patients working towards stability. 7, 9 You get these long-term, incredibly fulfilling relationships with people. 12 There are people that I have seen sixty times within the last eight years -- literally sixty times. 9, 18, 20 I have seen them and fifty plus of those times they are doing great and just checking in. 9, 11, 12, 18 Less than ten of those times they really need help for some reason. 13, 18 They are relapsing or they are worried about relapsing or they are being triggered in some way. 12, 16 Taking care of an addict as an addiction doctor is not a series of crises. 7 Seventy plus percent of the time you are managing people in stable recovery and you are just trying to keep them there. 9, 12, 15, 16, 18 In that sense it is really fulfilling. 17 At any given time, twenty to thirty percent are in crisis. 6 Every day there is something new. 6, 19 The vast majority of one’s patients are in long-term stable recovery. 9, 18 I think that is a misconception of addiction medicine: that you are dealing with people that don’t want to be there whose lives are blowing up, who are lying their pants off, and who are reprehensible characters. 10, 13 It’s people who have accepted that they have a disease, who are working to get back to a relatively normal life, and who are working hard. 11, 19 Most of them are in treatment. 9, 16 We help them get there and help them attempt to have a perfect life. 11, 13 It is really rewarding and that is a misconception of the job that I do.  AS: Speaking of that, I’d like you to talk a little about the stigma of methadone. 5, 9, 10 In interviews that I have had and other conversations there is a stigma that you don’t want to be on methadone because you don’t want to come to a clinic like this. 5, 6, 9, 12, 13, 19 There are class and race assumptions that go along with methadone, not to mention in many of the support groups such as AA [alcoholics anonymous] and NA [narcotics anonymous], to be on a medicine is to go against. 5, 15, 20 CR: It is changing. 16, 18 AS: It is changing, and I would like to see if you could talk about stigma and methadone and if you have seen a change and when that started? 5, 9, 10, 11, 16, 18 CR: I think there are a couple of different reasons why the stigma for methadone is there. 9, 16, 17 I will lay out what I think is the biggest one first. 8, 9, 11 It is basically a misunderstanding about addiction. 7, 9, 11, 12, 16 I am going to come back to that one once I find the words for it. 13, 19 Number two: the easier one to explain.  In a methadone clinic twenty years ago you would have a lot of black people. 17, 20 A huge number of African-Americans, a lot of poor people, and whatever the other oppressed group in your local community is. 17 For us it might be Native Americans, poor people, black people, and if you happen to be caucasian you probably had a mental illness. 8, 12, 14 The demographics of a methadone maintenance clinic -- the demographics of heroin twenty years ago -- was black, urban, felons. 15, 20 Because of that I think there’s some component of, I don’t want to go to that clinic with all those people I don’t identify with. 13 If you’re an affluent, urban, caucasian person, the idea that going to a clinic that is highly black, urban, poor, with some mental health and felonies mixed in -- racism and classism took over. 8, 11, 14, 20 That was the first thing. 9 Now, I entered the field of addiction just as heroin was affecting white, suburban kids. 9, 12 You just roll your eyes: this is something that has been endemic in the North Minneapolis black neighborhood for decades and decades and decades. 8, 9, 12, 14, 16 Now that it is affecting affluent, urban kids people are freaking out.  I get it.  But I roll my eyes at it. 14, 16 I do think how democratic opioid addiction is will force the stigma to change. 9, 16 Opioid addiction is absolutely democratic.  Opioids absolutely have no racial, gender, or age preference. 12 This is absolutely a democratic addiction and it is fatal.  Now, a New York Times article about a Mexican drug cartel looked at a map of America and they said, Where are the regions already controlled by gangs? 7, 14, 17 We aren’t going to get into a gang war to sell heroin in North Minneapolis. 7 But, Wayzata, and Eden Prairie, there are no gangs there and there is a lot of money there. 17 There was a concerted effort of the Mexican drug cartel to look at a map of America, look at existing gang territory, and go to other regions. 7, 9, 14 That came on the tail end of the pharmaceutical opioid epidemic. 12, 19 Obviously the epidemic affected people who had insurance. 7 The pharmaceutical thing disproportionately affected people that had some sort of insurance and didn’t hit the working class as much fifteen years ago. 7, 17, 18, 20 The pharmaceutical thing was more white.  The Mexican drug cartel rode those coattails to those same communities that were getting the pharmaceuticals with their three dollar co-pay from their insurance. 7, 14, 16 It’s more complex than that, but opioid addiction has been democratized in the last five years and the only good thing about the new demographics of people: women, caucasians, suburban; these groups were less affected by heroin twenty years ago. 6, 8, 9, 18, 20 It was more male, African American, and urban.  Obviously it is negative when other groups get affected.  The only positive thing about it is that I think it will dramatically affect the stigma going forward. 7, 9, 13, 14 When only urban black men are affected, when HIV [human immunodeficiency virus] only happened to gay, male, IV [intravenous] drug users, you can’t help but to think of it as a gay disease. 9, 12, 13, 14 When it starts happening to straight people you realize it can happen to everyone. 6, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14 I think that is what is happening with opioids right now. 10, 12, 13, 14 People realize they had false ideas. 11, 14 That gets back to the methadone thing. 5, 19 The treatment was mistaken for the demographic thing twenty years ago. 6, 9, 16, 20 Two is that another thing that has bedeviled methadone maintenance, which is kind of a specific point, but relevant, is that methadone tablets for pain can very clearly cause death in pain patients. 5, 15, 16, 17, 19 There have been many very important warning from the CDC [center for disease control] that methadone causes death when given for pain. 5, 6, 9, 17 Recently, there was a Star Tribune article on this where I was weirdly misquoted but then people say, Methadone for pain is so deadly, why are we giving something so deadly to the addict themselves? 11 This is what I was trying to get at. 16 People don’t understand that once you’re an opioid addict, methadone reduces death, prolongs life, improves pregnancy outcomes, reduces incarceration, reduces IV drug use, reduces Hepatitis C and HIV transmission. 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 19 Once you are an opioid addict, the medicine helps stabilize the addict. 9, 13 Once you are an addict, you have an incredible high death rate. 8, 12 Methadone lowers the death rate in that person in a controlled setting. 17 If you are a pain patient -- not addicted, but in pain -- you should have a really low death rate and methadone raises it.  If you are an addict you have a high death rate and methadone lowers it. 8 The pain patient in theory shouldn’t be at risk of incarceration and all the other stuff. 7, 9 The point is that in saying that ‘methadone kills pain patients, so why are we giving it to drug addicts,’ they misunderstand that we are talking about two distinctly different groups of people and the addict is at incredible risk of death. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 16, 17 They are totally different groups of people. 16, 17 It’s like saying insulin would harm someone without diabetes, so why are you giving insulin to someone with diabetes? 11 It’s like methadone helps someone with addiction, so why would you give it to someone without addiction? 6, 13 The reason is because over and over since the fifties it has been proven to save lives.  I think that since all the stigma and talk is going to go away when you realize that young, caucasian, affluent kids that are dying, we need to have something to make these kids not die. 8, 9, 10, 13, 14, 16 That is a racist idea that we have let it go so long in the African American community. 9, 11, 19 That is a sad thing. 12 The good thing is that now that it is hitting other communities we are finally going to wake up. 14 The addicts themselves who enroll in a methadone clinic, if there is anything they don’t like it is the attendance requirement. 12, 15 The attendance requirement is funny because the addicts don’t like to attend because the first ninety days you have to go six days a week. 9, 10, 12, 15, 19 The community is often surprised to hear how close we monitor people on methadone maintenance. 12, 15, 18 We observe dosing six days a week for up to six hundred patients. 19 There is a doctor on-call every day. 7, 19 This methadone clinic sees more people every year than the emergency room does. 5, 7, 20 Up to three hundred patients a day come here and are observed. 13, 19 It is an incredibly tight monitoring program. 12 We are giving them a powerful medicine, but it has been proven to save their life and it is in the context of very powerful monitoring. 11, 15 Totally different from methadone for pain when they give you a bottle of pills for a month's worth and tell you almost nothing and we have almost no regulation on the doctor's prescribing those pills. 5, 6, 8, 9, 16, 17 It is a totally different context. 16, 17 Part of the stigma that comes from patients is they call methadone ‘liquid handcuffs.’ 7, 9, 13, 19 It comes in a liquid form. 13, 17, 19 They call it liquid handcuffs because they’re really kind of stuck here. 7, 9, 16, 17 They feel stuck here. 9, 16 This gets me back to trying to articulate what I was going to say at the very beginning. 16, 19 A lot of people think they are on methadone and then will be tapered off and then can be done. 12, 17 Then I’ll be cured. 12 What methadone is not is a cure for addiction. 5 I hope someday we have cures but we don’t. 10, 19 Before you enter the methadone clinic it means you have opioid addiction, which means you have high risk for death, HIV, incarceration, bad pregnancy outcomes, et cetera. 7, 8, 13, 16, 19 When you enter our clinic, we can’t make that go away. 16 We can only manage it with a drug. 14 A lot of people enter our clinic and think, Maybe I’m addicted to methadone now. 5, 14, 17 You’re not addicted to methadone now. 5, 14 You are still addicted and there’s no getting around that. 9 They feel like they are stuck on methadone. 9, 16 In some ways you’re stuck with opioid addiction and you need to find the best way to manage it and methadone is one tool. 9, 13, 16, 17 I think a lot of people express their frustration at opioid addiction directed at methadone. 5, 9, 17 They’re frustrated with the fact that they have an incurable disease and there’s no way around it and it has incredible consequences for their life. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16 It manifests as showing up to a methadone clinic six days a week and feeling beholden to that liquid methadone because if you don’t you’re in a lot of trouble and then you get angry at it. 5, 9, 16, 17, 19, 20 I think doctors see that as well, for example, for dialysis patients. 6 If you are a dialysis patient you show up for dialysis three times a week, do a three hour dialysis run, and it shifts fluids in and out of the body and pumps blood around and it feels really weird and uncomfortable. 8, 11, 16, 18 You become reliant, dependent on the dialysis machine. 8, 12, 13, 19 If you skip you die in two weeks.  A dialysis patient with die without it in two weeks.  They are both totally dependent on dialysis for life. 11, 12, 17 Many, not all, come to resent dialysis and what it represents in their life. 7, 11, 13, 19 They can become angry at their dialysis unit, angry at the dialysis nurses and doctors. 13, 19 Not all are unhappy. 17 They come and get it quietly. 13, 19 Many patients become resentful at this ball and chain. 7, 8, 13, 19 They mistake the dialysis for the kidney failure. 6, 9 They mistake the methadone for the heroin addiction. 5, 6, 9 That’s a really common confusion.  Long winded answer.  AS: Methadone has an image problem from all sectors.  From society, from the patients themselves, and from the twelve-step recovery communities. 9, 12 CR: I’m going to sound like what I’ve heard Obama saying. 10, 11, 15 He keeps saying these things like there are these forces and demographics at play in America that will take us on a path, whether we have steps backwards or not, we are on this path and we can’t stop it. 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 16, 19 These things are changing. 16, 18 It’s a good change. 16 I think the same thing about treatment of addiction. 9, 16 In some ways it’s bad news because addiction is so democratized now, but it will force us to change. 6, 13, 14, 16, 17 The twelve-step programs not liking methadone -- I’m not even worried about it. 9, 12, 15 Just give it ten years. 6, 9, 20 You can be in twelve-step programs, but you can only blame the dead person for their death so often before people will just reject it. 9, 12, 15, 17 You cannot blame the dead person for dying. 17 It just sounds cruel. 9, 10, 12, 16 Unless you have another way to keep those people alive you’re ideology is going to need to change -- and it will change. 12, 13, 16 Just like it changed for anti-depressants and all things twelve-step programs went back on. 9, 12, 16, 19 I’m not against twelve-step programs. 9, 12 I think it’s a good thing.  We have seen Hazelden Betty  Ford begin to backtrack on the opioid thing. 19 All the dinosaurs that don’t believe in the life saving care, they are going to come around because they have to. 7, 8, 11, 13, 19 AS: There is accountability now because you also have a whole new demographic of rich, affluent, white people who are not going accept that your program didn’t work because they paid for it. 6, 14 CR: Exactly. 10 I think a lot of those things are going to change. 16, 17 I’m not worried about twelve-step programs or Hazelden Betty Ford. 9, 12 They are changing and they have to change. 16, 18 I am happy that I spent those hours in the gym with Gavin Bart who coached me. 11, 17, 19 I will say one other thing.  People in the government and people in the insurance companies don’t flinch for a second about methadone. 7, 20 They know that methadone keeps people out of prison and keeps people alive. 12, 13, 14, 15 There is no insurer in Minnesota that has done the actual math in methadone maintenance clinics that doesn’t pay for them. 10, 15, 16 Every insurer pays for them. 15, 16 The typical clinic with collect fifty percent of their bills and the insurance companies will negotiate or people won’t pay or that treatment isn’t covered. 7, 9, 12, 16 We collect over ninety-five percent of our bills.  The only people that aren’t paid for are people who are clearly abusing the system and still relapsing and they get their funding cut off rightfully so. 8, 9, 11, 14 Every insurer is like, Oh, so you’re telling me for five thousand dollars this heroin addict gets six days a week plus urine screens, drug tests, nurses and doctors visits, monitoring, social work; wrap around services for a heroin addict, for five thousand dollars a year. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19, 20 You just need to save one emergency room visit and we’ve made a profit. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 16 We easily do that for every patient.  Methadone is just one of the best bargains in healthcare, so almost every insurer is going to pay for it. 5, 7, 9, 12, 14, 15, 16 That tells you that the monied interests love it because it saves money. 9, 13, 19 The government is very clear-eyed about medication assisted treatment; there is no stigma there. 9, 10, 16 This just keeps you alive. 9, 12 The people who look at this with analytical eyes all really clearly understand the value of methadone and suboxone for the treatment of opioid addiction. 9, 12, 14, 16 The people that get their eyes clouded with their stigma, their ideology, their belief system, and aren’t just being analytical about it throw their ideology about it and get moralistic and they blame dead people for dying. 8, 9, 12, 14, 16, 17 One more thing about the stigma of addiction is that [A. Thomas] 9 McLellan published an article in JAMA [Journal of the American Medical Association] in 2001 in which he took four diseases and compared them: asthma, high blood pressure, diabetes, and alcoholism. 6, 8, 9, 11, 12, 15 He made a grid and you say, What is the genetic contribution to these diseases? 6, 16 It turns out that asthma, hypertension, diabetes, and alcoholism all have fifty to sixty percent genetics. 9, 12, 15, 19 Fifty to sixty percent of if I’m an alcoholic is due to my genetics. 5 Second, what is the curability of those diseases? 6 None of those diseases is curable. 6 What is the treatability of those diseases? 6, 16 All of those diseases have treatments, but not cures. 6, 9, 16 What is the patient adherence to doctor’s recommendations? 12 All of them have comparable patient adherence.  Whether you tell a diabetic to not eat sugar or an asthmatic to not smoke a cigarette or a hypertensive to not use a salt shaker or an alcoholic not to drink alcohol. 5, 6, 9, 14, 15 When you’re telling a person to change their lifestyle behavior, whether it is in the alcohol or the salt shaker, you get the same results. 9, 11, 16 About thirty percent of patients just don’t follow doctor’s orders -- whether it is alcohol or salt or sugar or exercise or weight loss or whatever it is. 9, 12, 18 Thirty percent don’t follow doctor’s orders and seventy percent try to. 12, 15, 16 Many of those don’t succeed.  Alcoholism is just like diabetes, hypertension, and asthma in its genetic risk, patient reaction to news, treatability, and curability. 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16 If you forget you’re stigma it looks like any other chronic disease.  The final line on the bottom of the comparison is access to treatment. 6, 9, 16 All those other diseases are given access to treatments, but alcoholics are not. 5, 6, 9, 16 This was a really powerful, thoughtful argument made by McLellan saying basically in every way if you are analytical and put your stigma aside, alcoholism is every bit the same, chronic disease but for some reason they’re not given treatment. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 15, 16 There are treatments available; they are no less good or worthy of patients than the hypertensive that continues to use salt. 6, 9, 15, 16 They have no more curable than a disease.  I think that is something we’re still slowly wrapping our heads around. 8, 9 AS: There is such a moral stigma and judgement against people. 9 It’s been called a disease for a very long time, but we don’t see it as we see other diseases. 6, 7 CR: Here is another thing I would point out.  In 1975 if you had a heart attack they would put you on bed rest for six weeks and tell you that you are stressing yourself out, you’re an A-type personality, and because of your lifestyle you’ve given yourself a heart attack. 6, 9, 10, 11, 16, 19 In other words, your heart attack was blamed on your personality. 16, 17 Now, if you have a heart attack it’s bing-bang-boom: cholesterol, diabetes, hypertension, put a stent in, give them the common cocktail of medicines, and they are back at work in two or three days. 6, 9, 10, 15, 19 Nobody cares what your personality is. 7, 16 Ten years later in 1985 if you had an ulcer people would say, Your family has given you an ulcer, you’re worrying too much, you eat jalapenos. 6, 11, 18, 20 Crap like this.  Now if you have an ulcer, no one cares what your lifestyle, personality, anxiety level, jalapeno, or coffee intake is. 6, 7, 9, 11, 16, 20 Do you take Ibuprofen or Advil? 6 Do you have cancer?  Do you have an infection called helicobacter pylori? 7, 10 Correct those things and you are back at work in a day and your ulcer will be healed in two weeks. 16, 19 No one cares about your stress level today if you have an ulcer. 7, 9, 19, 20 This is human nature.  There used to be this disease called consumption. 7, 9 There was a consumptive personality. 16 That turned out to be tuberculosis. 19 Or gout was the king’s disease.  Gout has nothing to do with being a king.  It has to do with that you eat foods that are high in oxalate, which kings happened to do because they had money back then and it was trendy. 8, 12, 13, 19 AS: Or hysteria. 9 CR: Hysteria! 9 There are lots of examples of this. 5, 6, 17 When we don’t understand a disease fully, and more importantly when we don’t have tools to treat it, we don’t have analytics to measure it, we always describe these diseases to personality. 6, 9, 11, 12, 15, 16, 17 It’s just human nature. 9, 12 When we can’t define it, when we can’t measure it, and when we can’t cure it. 14, 15 AS: Does it surprise you that we are still there with addiction? 9 CR: No. Brain diseases are more complex. 6 It’s just a more complex disease. 9, 12 Depression is probably about ten to fifteen years ahead of addiction in terms of stigmatizing it. 9, 20 The difference with depression was when Prozac came out. 19 People say good and bad things about it: the Prozac revolution, the Prozac brain. 16 What Prozac and all the similar antidepressants that followed -- Prozac is actually not as good as an antidepressant as those that preceded it. 10, 12 There were better antidepressants.  But, Prozac was so safe that any primary care doctor could give it out basically willy-nilly. 6, 7, 11 It’s main advantage was safety, which allowed it to be used in any primary care clinic in the country. 7, 9, 11, 16 By putting a tool in the hands of every primary care doctor, suddenly a primary care doctor could ask their patient about their mood. 7, 10, 13 Suddenly, if the patient had a bad mood the primary care doctor could do something right there to help them safely. 7, 13, 14 Not perfectly effective, but moderately effective.  By putting a tool in the hands of the average doctor, you basically began the process of destigmatizing the disease. 7, 9, 10, 11 To have depression in 1980 was totally different than having depression today. 16, 17, 19 Having depression in 1980 would have kept a politician out of office. 8 Today we have a governor that has had depression. 19 AS: And we can talk about it and people know about it. 10, 13, 14, 15 CR: We can talk about it. 10 Great!  I voted for him knowing that and I don’t regret it at all. 13, 14, 15 I think it’s appropriate.  When we start putting metrics and tools in hands -- not BS, but things that work and really make a difference for people’s lives -- we are going to see. 5, 9, 10, 11, 16 You need metrics. 5, 13 If we need a blood test or if you can measure and quantify something with a blood test, or an x-ray and you have a tool to fix it and it goes to every primary care clinic in the country it changes everything. 7, 9, 11, 13, 15, 16 It is out of the shadows now. 14 It is quantifiable, it’s visualizable, and it’s treatable. 16 Right now addiction is hard to quantify and treatment is still in this shadowy, ghetto corner of medicine. 9, 11, 14, 16 That’s why I think Suboxone should be in primary care clinics, not just to gain access, but to destigmatize. 6, 7, 9, 12 AS: Can you talk about Suboxone a little bit? 10 Is the clinic that you work in in Northfield [Minnesota]?  CR: We actually moved to Lonsdale for practical reasons; they actually have a great space. 8, 10, 11 I know have a Suboxone clinic here in Minneapolis at HCMC. 13, 14, 15 I’m not taking any patients at that now, but I have a Suboxone clinic in Lonsdale, Minnesota in a family practice setting. 10, 14, 17, 18 All the doctors that work in that clinic are family practice doctors. 10, 18 Every other Monday 19 I see patients in Lonsdale.  Yesterday I saw twenty-three patients in five hours. 9, 11, 19 It’s crazy. 16 It’s incredibly rewarding. 12 Yesterday literally two of my twenty-three patients were using heroin still. 9, 19 The rest were sober. 6, 9, 19 I get drug screens, I check their prescription monitoring program, but more so I just know these patients. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I meet with them regularly. 13 One of them was given a cruise as the best salesman in their company. 6, 9 She was awarded a cruise to Hawaii.  One of them just got offered a major promotion at work. 9, 12, 18 These people are really thriving at work and are really happy. 17 It’s incredibly rewarding work for me. 12 Suboxone is like that thing I said about Prozac.  Prozac isn’t a better antidepressant, but it’s safer, so therefore it could be given out more easily in a primary care facility. 6, 7 AS: Can you talk about the difference between suboxone and methadone? 5, 10 CR: Suboxone and methadone when compared head to head have similar effectiveness in keeping people alive, out of prison, stopping injections -- there’s more data on methadone because it’s been around longer -- but every time Suboxone and methadone have been compared they come out about equal. 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 19 What that means is that on nothing, on abstinence based therapy, you could say twenty percent at best are abstinent still after a year. 9, 16, 20 If you just try to do behavioral, talk therapy alone, the outcomes are approximately twenty percent a year, and some have been ten percent in the studies. 9, 10, 12, 13, 15, 16, 19, 20 Sometimes it’s five percent. 5, 18 To be fair to abstinence based treatment, twenty-five percent is the high end after a year. 8, 9, 12, 16, 20 Methadone or Suboxone changes that to seventy-five percent, eighty percent in some studies. 9, 16 You are taking a one year abstinence success rate at twenty percent and turning it into seventy percent. 9, 15, 19, 20 Still note that thirty percent of opiate addicts don’t respond to Suboxone or methadone.  This is not a one hundred percent effective treatment. 9, 16 If you do Suboxone or methadone it is not one hundred percent. 5 Seventy percent are going to respond to either methadone or Suboxone as opposed to twenty percent to behavioral treatment. 9, 15, 16 Methadone and Suboxone are comparable in those studies, but there are some differences and I’ll itemize them. 9 Methadone is a full opioid. 11 Both are very long acting and can be taken once a day and will last all day. 6, 9, 10, 19 If you stop taking them you won’t go into withdrawal for three days. 9, 10, 14, 19 In case of emergency or if something happens you have time to get to a clinic if you can’t get it today. 7, 12, 19 They both have very long half lives, and can be taken once a day and last all day, and don’t cause withdrawal for the first three days. 6, 9, 14, 19, 20 They both block other opiates.  If you try to use heroin you won’t feel the heroin. 9, 16 Therefore, it helps you extinguish your heroin habit. 13 Almost all methadone and Suboxone patients, early on, test it; they try heroin on this drug and they realize they are wasting their money. 9, 14, 16 Suboxone may be a little better at blocking heroin than methadone, but they both block heroin. 5 They are both once a day drugs that last long and block opiates. 9, 14, 19 Neither of them get you high if you are tolerant. 7, 8 If you have never touched an opiate before and you take methadone -- yeah, you’re going to get really intoxicated. 5, 6, 10, 15 Even Suboxone you can get intoxicated on if you have never used an opioid before. 9, 10, 15 But, if you are a heroin addict, you aren't going to get high on methadone if it is dosed appropriately. 5, 8 They are long acting, block other opiates, you should be wide awake, not nodding off, not intoxicated. 10 In that sense, they are identical. 17 The difference comes in in that Suboxone has a ceiling effect in approximately forty percent opiate strength. 9, 13, 19 Even if you really wanted to overdose someone on Suboxone you couldn’t because it has that ceiling effect. 12, 13, 15 Suboxone in some ways is dummy-proof. 16, 17 You aren’t going to get oversedated on Suboxone.  If you take Suboxone patients -- I was showing this to a medical student yesterday in the clinic -- if you took Suboxone patients and lined them up with patients who had never used opioids in their life and you took an expert and they had to pick who’s on Suboxone and who’s not, you can’t. 6, 9, 10, 11, 14, 15, 19 I’m very attuned to this -- the size of someone’s pupils, their eyelids, the rate of their speech. 16 I’m very attuned to opioid intoxication and I cannot pick a Suboxone patient out of a line-up. 6, 10 It’s got a lighter touch. 15 You don’t have to worry so much about dosing Suboxone. 11, 18 If you don’t nothing terrible will happen. 12, 15 Methadone does not have that ceiling effect.  Methadone is a full opioid agonist. 9, 11 Because of that, if you want to be a responsible methadone prescriber you have to work really hard to set limits. 5, 11, 13, 17 There is a dose of methadone which is enough to keep the patient out of withdrawal, addiction managed, keep the patient comfortable, block other opioids, and yet not cause oversedation or, even worse, overdose. 5, 10, 12, 14, 15, 20 There is a dose of methadone that can do that. 5 There is a sweet spot.  There is also such thing as too much methadone. 5, 18 If you are going to work with methadone you have to work really hard to set limits on your patients. 11, 17 Some of these are patients that don’t like limits. 10 Part of the job of being a methadone doctor is setting limits. 5, 17 If you can set those limits and keep them in that window where they are getting incredible therapeutic benefits without the oversedation, then methadone behaves exactly the same as Suboxone. 10, 12, 14, 17 Suboxone’s advantage is that ceiling effect and you don’t have to constantly say ‘no’ to people. 9 That is the first major difference because you can overdose and die on methadone much more easily. 5, 9, 15, 18 There’re only a few cases of people dying of buprenorphine alone.  You can mix buprenorphine with all sorts of other drugs and die, but buprenorphine alone doesn’t kill you. 7, 14, 17 Methadone alone can kill people. 7 Because it is more potentially lethal that is why it is more highly regulated. 8, 15, 19 That is why we get these clinics and people coming in six days a week. 19 Suboxone is less tightly regulated and can be done out of a primary care clinic. 7 Primary care doctors can prescribe Suboxone and not see the patient six days a week. 7, 19 AS: I’ve heard that there’s a limit on how many patients a doctor can take because of the DEA [Drug Enforcement Administration]. 6, 9, 15 Has that changed? 16 First, there were thirty patients per doctor. 9 Then, if you do that for a year you can apply for a hundred patients. 12, 14, 20 Now the DEA has raised it to 275 patients per doctor. 5 That far exceeds what any reasonable doctor needs. 13 CR: Within the last year -- less than six months ago. 8, 9, 20 That far exceeds what any doctor would need. 13 Right now that limit has been raised to almost too high of a level. 5, 8, 9, 14, 20 The truth is that the average primary care doctor has 1500 patients, let’s say. 7, 19 Of those, twenty percent at least are on opioids. 9, 10 That’s three hundred patients on opioids. 10 So the average primary care doctor has three hundred opioid patients and of those ten percent are addicted. 7 The average primary care doctor actually has thirty patients that are addicted to the opioids they are prescribed. 7, 10 The average primary care doctor has a couple dozen addicts in their midst, and they know those patients and they are desperate to do something for those patients. 7, 9, 13, 14, 15 It is incredibly burdensome to their day, to their clinic, to their nurses. 12, 19 They call in all the time, they are running out of pills; they are addicts. 7, 11 Right now those patients are fumbling through with their primary care doctor on Percocet. 7, 14 When the primary care doctor creates a manmade addiction -- iatrogenic addiction -- they created it themselves as a side effect of a prescribed medicine. 7, 16 When that iatrogenic addiction occurs it would be really handy if the primary care doctor had a tool to treat that addiction. 7, 16 It would save everyone a ton of time and heartache.  In that sense, the average care doctor only needs fifteen to thirty spots in suboxone. 7, 13, 17 If they wanted to take on community Suboxone patients they would need more than thirty. 6, 12, 13 When I’m talking to a person and they ask if they should go on Suboxone or methadone, if you are a very complicated patient: mental illness, socially sick, homeless, legal issues, and you’ve relapsed multiple times and you would benefit from very close supervision, methadone is better. 5, 10, 12, 14, 15, 18, 19 If you need a stronger agent because you have a super sky high tolerance, methadone is better. 7, 8, 9, 12, 13 If you basically have stuff together, if your life is together, you’ve got a job, you aren’t seriously mentally ill, you haven’t had multiple life-threatening overdoses and relapses, having a community Suboxone doctor for one month at a time and not get all that supervision; that may be better for you. 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 14, 15, 18 You don’t have to come into the clinic six days a week because you basically have good mental health, good social stability, good structure because you can take medicines on your own. 6, 7, 9, 11, 13, 14, 19 You just need to get out of this trap you are in in this opioid addiction. 9, 12, 13 That’s the really basic part.  The reality is what can you get in your community.  Right now you just take what you can get. 6, 9, 12, 14 AS: Right.  In the ideal world where the primary doctor knows how to deal with Suboxone, but that’s not happening right now? 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 That’s not happening right now. 12, 13, 14 There’re not enough Suboxone spots. 20 Only these major metropolitan areas have methadone clinics. 5, 18 If you are in the rural clinics you have to drive hours to a methadone clinic. 7, 11, 14 It’s not safe.  There is this weird patchwork of availability of these different drugs. 14, 16, 17 If you can get anything they just jump at it and take it. 6, 9, 12 It will save your life. 11 In the future if there is greater availability, that’s what a methadone clinic is for: people who need this high degree of supervision. 8, 11, 12, 13, 20 AS: Is there any kind of campaign to get Suboxone out more? 8, 16, 17 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 People talk about campaigns but I don’t know what that actually is or if it will actually affect change. 8, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16 AS: The only other question I was going to ask was what an ordinary day for you is and what an extraordinary day for you is. 6, 9, 15, 19 You can limit it to one of your places. 11, 17 CR: There is one other thing I want to say. 13 Another variable in all of this is the research into addiction.  There is incredible work being done right now in the NIH [National Institute of Health]. 9, 12, 14 Nora  Volkow is at the center of this but there are many great researchers involved in looking at where the addiction centers are and all the neurotransmitters involved. 7, 9, 11 There’s a lot of money involved in other pharmaceuticals and treatments. 6, 9, 16, 17 If you can treat addiction more effectively and safely it is a gold mine. 16, 20 There is a lot of interest in it, but it is complex science. 9, 17, 19 I think it’s going to take ten to twenty years. 6, 20 As that science emerges I think it’s a really exciting time.  There is a refocus on clinical science and basic science and the development of pharmaceuticals for addiction. 15, 16 It’s exciting.  That is another way to destigmatize things. 9, 16 If you can define them in analytical terms it removes a lot of stigma. 9, 14, 17 I’m hopeful that we are on the right path. 10, 14 I really am.  I’m not doing any of this science, so I’m really glad someone is out there doing it!  My boss is one of them, so I’m glad people are doing it.  A fulfilling day -- there are two versions of the same day. 19 Either a busy Suboxone clinic or like on Monday I saw twenty-three Suboxone patients. 9, 19 Greater than eighty percent are doing well.  One of them was a pregnant mom who was on pain pills and got pregnant and the doctor abruptly cut her off pain pills. 15 She went into withdrawal and she got desperate and she went and used heroin. 9, 14 She called me and I was able to get her onto Suboxone which was life saving for her and her pregnancy -- it improves her pregnancy outcome. 7, 11, 13, 19 Another one, similarly; I had two pregnant moms. 15, 18 I just had an incredible mix of patients at a crossroads in their lives. 9, 12 I had this pregnant mom who was at a crossroad in her life. 9, 11, 15 Eight years in I’m confident -- I’ve made errors, I’ve had bad outcomes -- but I’m confident I can help this mom who is snorting heroin and get a good outcome. 13, 15, 16, 19, 20 That is exciting and thrilling me to see my eighty plus patients who are living the good outcome and then have the ten to twenty percent that are trying to get there and I feel a real sense of hope and confidence that I can get these patients to cross the finish line to a good outcome. 6, 10, 13, 16, 17, 19 I want both these moms to have healthy deliveries. 13, 14, 15, 18 A similar analogy here is I’ll have methadone clinic days where I’ll just line up the methadone patients and I’ll see maybe ten in the morning talking about dose and side-effects and their life. 5, 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 19 Some of those mornings it is so fulfilling and wonderful to me even though the majority of them have some problem we are working on, either with their dose or something else. 15, 18 To see these people that were really badly wounded and suffering and sick in a lot of ways, to hear them and their stories and to meet them and understand how they are really leading a meaningful life now. 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17, 18 Whether it is Suboxone or methadone having those clinics where I can see these folks and sit down and get to know them. 13, 14, 15 Friend isn’t the right word, but I’m friends with some of them and I really appreciate their presence in my life. 11, 12, 14, 18 I had one guy give me a cup of coffee -- he’s a ceramicist -- and I drink out of it every morning. 6, 9, 14 This heroin addict made me this beautiful mug and I drink out of it every morning! 6, 14, 16 Those things are wonderful. 16 I think the worst thing for me is administrative paperwork called a prior authorization that is attached to Suboxone administration. 7, 9, 19 It is January so I am getting nailed with them because it is the beginning of the year. 20 The worst things is when red tape gets in the way of delivering care. 7, 9, 12, 16 Then I have to call my patients and be like, Sorry, there is going to be a three day delay until you can get your medicine. 7, 10, 19 They start crying and yelling. 9, 11 They are angry, scared, tearful, and they’ll relapse. 5, 7, 11, 12, 18 I’ll call them and say there is nothing you can do because your insurance requires this paperwork and they’ll blame me, the pharmacy; they’ll cry, they’ll beg, and I’ll say there is literally nothing I can do. 7, 17 It is all work put on me. 10 AS: It is red tape but also denying access to care. 6, 7, 12 There has been lawsuits settled in other states about prior authorizations for Suboxone. 9, 17, 19 The attorney general has put on notice the insurance companies in the state that she will be prosecuting. 7, 9, 10 A similar thing for prior authorizations on Suboxone. 19 She just put out a memo encouraging this to be a legislative priority. 9, 10, 12, 19 She is hoping that she won’t need to prosecute them because it will be legislative in this session. 13 There’s hope, but it is absolutely the worst thing when an administrative detail prevents the care of a patient and then I feel their pain when I tell them it is going to be days before they get their medicine. 7, 9, 10, 15, 16, 19 AS: Is the prior authorization because it is Suboxone or just red tape from the insurance company? 7, 9, 12, 19 It’s not DEA restrictions or anything? 9, 19 Insurance companies made a practical, financial decision that they used prior authorizations for anything that is costly or potentially abusable or when they think physicians aren’t educated about appropriate use for a medicine. 7, 8, 9, 10, 15, 16, 19 When you talk to the people doing the prior authorizations, like me, they catch a lot of doctors prescribing the wrong thing. 10, 17, 19 There is a benefit to it, but it hurts the well meaning. 14, 16 AS: Thank you very much. 18 I’m so appreciative.  CR: Thank you.  It was fun "
"21","Hooker_Julie","Shelley Roberts Gyllen Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer August 17, 2017 Ely, Minnesota Shelley Roberts Gyllen -SRG Amy Sullivan -AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan I'm here with Shelley and I'm going to let Shelley say her name because it's about to change. 6, 9, 16, 19 It's August 17th. 9 We're at a cabin in Ely, Minnesota and the other noise you might hear in the background is a little puppy named Logan. 5, 6, 8, 19 Shelley do you give me permission to record this? 6 SRG:  I, Shelley Roberts Johnson, soon to be Shelley Roberts Gyllen.  AS: So why don't you start by talking about your childhood, some of the first memories of your life. 9, 10, 11 SRG:  A lot of them are actually up here in Ely. 10, 17 We came here all the time as kids. 19 Labor Day, Memorial Day, a week in the summer, and then eventually two weeks in the summer, and then eventually my parents bought this place and it's great. 7, 10, 11, 15, 16 We had so much fun. 18 I think part of it was just who our parents are and part of it is the childcare that we were at, which is on a hobby farm. 7, 9, 10, 12, 16 We both just developed a love for being outside and boredom certainly entered into our lives, but the answers to it were things like go outside and build a fort or wander around a wetland and play an imagination game as opposed to watch a bunch of TV, which we did, too. 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 16 We were not no-screen kids, but we definitely had that outdoor adventure aspect.  And just so we're clear, you're younger than Spencer? 5, 9, 12, 14 SRG:  Yes, two and a half-ish years younger. 5, 14, 20 AS: So, your whole life is a memory with a big brother. 5, 8, 11 SRG:  Yes, I have flashes of memory from one time when I was in the hospital because we were at a family picnic at the daycare that we went to and there were sheets hanging up. 7, 18, 19 The older kids were all playing baseball and this sheet was their home base backdrop to catch pitches. 5, 8, 10, 14, 19, 20 I was running with my friends behind it and someone swung a bat and I got clocked in the head from the other side of a sheet, hard. 7, 11, 12, 18 This kid was swinging a baseball bat to hit a ball. 8 I have a memory of my dad and my brother visiting me. 5, 12, 13 SRG:  Maybe even younger. 5, 14, 15 I don't know how old I was when that happened. 12, 13, 14, 15, 20 I definitely remember Dad and Spence visiting in the hospital. 12, 13 I think they gave Spence a little hospital gown to visit me in. 12, 13 Who knows if that's a real memory, but it's there. 13, 14, 15 I remember a lot of Sunday nights we would get our laundry out and we would have to fold our laundry and then after folding our laundry we would put it up on the ottoman and get to build forts in our laundry baskets to watch Sunday night TV which was like Life Goes On and The Simpsons and there might have been one more. 10, 14, 17, 19, 20 Sunday night family time, it was great. 11, 18, 19 That was definitely a tradition.  Wintertime, the house was built on a hill and so in front we had a more gentle sloping hill, which was great when Dad would go and scoop it out and make this really cool run for tubing. 6, 9, 11, 16, 17 The tube would sail up the sides and we had a back more steep hill and then the wetland off of that. 8, 9, 19 We would play for hours in the winter outside. 11 My dad would do his [whistles] whistle and it would carry across the wetland and it'd be like, ""I guess we've got to go in."" 7, 8, 9, 10 In the den we had this old, old heater. 20 You'd go and you'd turn it up so that it clicked on and you'd go put your feet on it until your feet burned to try to warm up. 10, 16, 19 AS: Did your property back up to a wetland? 8, 19 SRG:  Our property backed up to a wetland. 8, 19 You can see it from 494, when you're driving north it's on your right side right before you get to 394. 14 We called it “The Island,” like a hump of land in the middle with a bunch of trees on it. 7, 8, 9 We would always just hike out to The Island, more so in the winter than in the spring or summer because it was often so deep. 8, 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 I vaguely remember being able to canoe out there one time but I was really young, I can barely remember that. 5, 14 AS: So tell me about school and your big brother. 5, 8 SRG:  When I was younger I don't remember being like, ""I have a big brother who's in this grade,"" which I'm sure I did. 5, 8, 10, 14, 15, 20 School was just like ""Ahhhhh, this is great. 9, 10, 11, 12 I can just go sit in a corner and read books and have friends."" 9, 12, 13, 18 AS: So you liked school? 8, 10, 18 SRG:  Yeah, I liked school a whole lot. 8, 10, 17, 18 I still like school. 8, 9, 10 If I could be paid to go to school instead of paying to go to school my life would be perfect. 8, 9, 11, 16 I'm a lifelong learner for sure. 11, 12, 15 I almost went on a tangent about learning. 9, 12 I remember maybe like second grade I have strong memories of playing with friends. 9, 12, 18, 20 He, obviously being older, had already established some friendships. 5, 9, 12, 18, 20 I was actually talking about this last weekend at my bridal shower with one of the other moms. 9, 10, 12, 15, 18, 19 We were trying to remember how all of the friendships got forged. 12, 16, 18 She remembers her son who was Spencer's age, also a redhead, came home from school and was like, ""Mom, there's another redhead."" 8, 10, 12, 19 They started playing together. 9, 11 She also has a daughter who's my age and so then we played together and I think were in each other’s classes, too. 5, 8, 20 Within biking distance there were two other families in the district with sons Spencer's age and daughters my age and then another family with a daughter Spencer's age, but they didn't really play, and a daughter my age. 5, 9, 18 There was a neighborhood full of kids all going to the same school. 8, 11 It was fun because then all of the sudden we'd have four families over at the house and have these romping playdates is the word they use now. 6, 9, 13, 14 We'd just go and be in the wetland. 8, 9, 12 We'd have all these adventure games. 10 In the fall we'd have the tractor out. 10 At one point we had a moped and some go-carts. 7 My cousins that were the same age as us would come over and play too. 5, 13, 19 The same thing: we'd always be running around. 7, 8, 11, 16, 17 Of course the older kids would annoy the crap out of the younger kids and vice versa. 5, 14, 20 I'm sure there was lots of, ""It's not fair,"" going on. 5, 15, 17 Just a ton of getting to learn about negotiating as a human being through play, which was really cool. 9, 12, 17 Getting to romp around in the woods and be like, ""Do you think it's a good idea that we're this close to a buck fight?"" 8, 10, 11 Just stuff like that. 9 I think I was in fourth grade and he was in sixth grade, it was the last year we were in elementary together. 9, 20 It was the first year we were home alone after school for a few hours until my parents got home. 8, 9, 10, 11, 16, 19, 20 At least I think it was the first year. 9, 20 Spence and I, he had been working on a fort with his friends out in the woods. 12, 18 We were playing in the fort and we heard a buck fight going on. 15 It was so cool. 17 At a certain point Spencer was like, ""Alright, you have to go inside."" 10, 14 Not inside the house because that was too far and you had to go past the buck fight. 6, 9 He was very much like, ""Okay, this is starting to get dangerous."" 9, 10, 11, 18 Didn't come inside the fort himself. 13, 19 The fort had a fully enclosed area and then a top. 10, 11 I did, and then I'm sitting there and I'm like, ""Wait a minute, why does he get to watch?"" 10, 13 Also, I would much rather be able to see it coming if I need to run instead of get trampled. 9, 11, 13, 18 Very cool, but definitely he was a risk-taker. 6, 17 Playing certainly involved a lot of risk and then later on being like, ""Hm, maybe we should do this thing that will keep us safe."" 9, 10, 12, 17 AS: Were you a risk-taker at all? 6 SRG:  I was less inclined to it. 6 I was a ""good kid"" to use really big quotes there, but not also a good kid. 8, 9 I knew how the system of rules worked and especially by the time I was in high school and got over my fear of getting in trouble. 6, 8, 9, 12, 20 I knew how to work the system. 6, 8, 9, 12 Definitely knew how to get around it. 6, 12 I learned how to take risks because of Spencer. 6, 12, 17 Up here there's a part of the lake that has this sheer rock cliff and it's perfect for climbing because there's lots of different handhold levels. 5, 16, 17, 20 It was like a Memorial Day or Labor Day weekend. 12, 19 He had a friend come up, but I didn't. 12, 13, 19 I played with them a lot. 8, 17 They decided they were going to go climbing this thing. 12 I was like, ""Okay, I can go, too."" 10 I followed along. 12 Then at a certain point we're out in the middle of this. 8 I'm terrible with judging distance with my eyes but it's like from here to the cars in terms of height. 7, 9, 14, 15, 16 It's not an insignificant height.  A couple hundred feet, and it's very wide and we're in the middle of it. 8, 12, 14 I remember hearing my mom or my dad on the dock being like, ""Ah!"" 10, 15 I all of a sudden realize and Spence and his friend were just like, ""Follow us, try not to look down. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 16 If you do look down just accept that that's your fate."" 9, 12 AS: Did you jump into the water? 6 Was it over the water? 6 SRG:  No, it was over the water but there was no safe way to jump. 6, 16 It was enough of a slant in that there were a ton of rocks below us. 20 It was one of the rare parts of the lake that didn't slant in super quickly. 9, 12 There was rubble and rock at the bottom.  It was a terrifying moment that was also a really good growth moment. 13, 15, 17 It was like, ""Oh, hey, you just confront the next thing ahead and you find the next handhold and the next foothold. 9, 10, 12, 13, 20 That has been an allegory in terms of the whole experience with Spencer's addiction and death.  You find the next handhold and if you look down you just think, ""This is my fate now. 9, 12, 14, 20 You hope you reach the top. 10, 13 We did that obviously.  None of us fell to a rocky death. 15 AS: With your parents watching. 10, 16 SRG:  Encouraging, but also like probably half mad.  Follow us and endanger themselves? 12 I think I remember one of them drove over in the boat and was trying to coach from below. 7, 14, 16 They can't see all the nuances of the little holes and handholds. 20 It was literally following Spence and his friend up the side of this cliff and hoping to God that it wasn't some sort of ""I'm going to get you now, little sister."" 5, 9, 12, 14, 17 He never had it out for me. 15 Not at least more than regular sibling rivalry would state. 9 AS: I keep hearing the story that he was very, very shy and you were very, very social. 9, 12 SRG:  Yeah, that is true.  AS: Is there a point where you kind of remember that or where that stands out to you? 9, 12, 16, 17 SRG:  No, because it's just how I've always been. 9, 12, 16, 17 I think more poignant is as the last year and a half has gone by and I've figured this thing called grieving your sibling out I have become less social, and that's different. 7, 9, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19, 20 I am far much more in need of my me time. 13, 18 It's one of those weird skills that you can't learn until something super shitty happens that is ultimately I think a self-care skill. 7, 12 I got a lot better at being like, ""Oh, I need to do this for me."" 10, 13, 17 For at least a week there was a whole like, ""I can't do anything else but be selfish."" 9, 10 Then a few months after that figuring out how to function in the world again. 8, 15 A few weeks after Spencer died Prince died.  Everyone cared so much and I'm like, ""How do you care so much?"" 7, 10, 11, 12, 18 Removed from the immediacy of Spencer's death I get it, I do, because people become really important culturally. 8, 13, 19 At the time it was so hard. 11 The end of the year posts because a lot of famous people died in 2016 and a lot of stupid crap happened. 9, 12, 13, 17, 20 People were just like, ""Fuck off 2016."" 9, 10, 12 I was like, ""No this is the last year my brother was alive. 5, 9, 10, 20 How could you possibly?""  Then I'm like, “Oh yeah, people are entitled to their life experiences.” 10, 11 Figuring out how to claim that space and exist in the world. 9, 15 I've always been a super empathetic person, too, which I think goes along with the outgoing in a sense that I just get people. 9, 12, 14, 16, 17 I can have empathy with the manipulative behavior of addiction. 14 AS: Did you get your brother, or did it go in and out? 5 SRG: Yeah.  I mean especially when we were kids I got him. 16, 20 I think when you have siblings that's where you do the most of your social negotiation and figuring out how to function in the world. 5, 15 It's this whole different relationship than you have with any other human being. 16, 17 You can't treat everybody the way you treat your siblings because you don't know the backstory. 5, 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 Then in terms of one of the hardest things about his addiction—and when he was around, and when we were together and confronting that—was that he would say things and I knew he was manipulating me. 6, 8, 9, 11, 12, 16 He's my brother; he's always known what to say to get under my skin. 5, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 I don't think it was until my late twenties that I finally stopped just letting it roll off my back and being like, ""No, I disagree with you. 9, 10, 12, 19, 20 You're being a jerk.""  These things that at the same time that I need to stand up for myself I'm like, “What if I say something that makes him go use again?” 9, 10, 12, 13, 16 AS: That sense that you have some control, that your behavior can somehow impact what he does or doesn't do. 10, 17 SRG:  Wouldn't that be an interesting character trait, if we could control other people? 9, 10, 17, 19 You can with manipulation.  There are these things, but that's another soapbox for another day. 16, 19 AS: Do you feel like talking about your own struggle? 9, 10, 16 Some of your own mental health struggles? 9, 14 SRG:  Yeah, I can talk about that. 10 AS: That came up in your parents’ conversations, just trying to deal with that. 9, 10, 12, 13, 16, 19 What was that like for you and how did that play out?  SRG:  I think it was ninth grade. 20 AS: We're talking about what year? 10, 20 What year were you born? 20 SRG:  I was born in 1984.  I'm thirty-three now in 2017. 14 Ninth grade would have been 1997-98 school year. 8, 20 I don't remember if it was the summer before ninth grade or the summer before tenth grade. 15, 20 I just got real lethargic and didn't care about a lot all of a sudden. 7, 9, 12, 13, 17, 19 That was weird.  I'm a happy-go-lucky, horns-of-the-bull, grab life sort of person. 11, 17 It was just all of a sudden like not having any energy. 9, 12, 13 This bizarre irrational sense that I would die in my sleep and then I had a really hard time falling asleep. 7, 11, 17 Then would have a really hard time staying awake because I was exhausted but also terrified of sleeping. 7, 9, 11, 19 Looking at it now and knowing as much now, it was some really hardcore anxiety and puberty stuff. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 18 At the time, I agree with the doctor's prognosis that it was a lot of depression. 17 I was put on antidepressants and did a lot of counseling with a wonderful woman in Plymouth. 10, 17 It was so weird to just go and talk to someone. 9, 10, 12 ""Did you feel sad this week?"" 12, 16 Yeah because I have to go and do homework and I want to go play and this boy and that person. 13, 19 I'm a teenager—of course I'm sad! 12 Then at the same time because I'm a teenager not realizing the impact on my personality that medications are having, just figuring out the nuances of side effects. 9, 10, 12, 16 Now knowing what we know now about how brains develop my brain is still developing. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16 My personal experience was a very bad one with antidepressants. 16 Ultimately, I became a part of the statistic that antidepressants make young people even more depressed and suicidal. 5, 9, 12, 14, 15, 16, 19 In high school we got a really good handle on it. 8 I was just on a maintenance level and then I went to school. 8, 9, 12, 15, 20 AS: To college? 8 SRG:  To college. 8 I went to DePauw University and had chosen it because they had an education program. 10, 13 It was far away, but not too far away. 16 A big factor was I got a really big financial aid package, too. 8, 10 I got there and they were like, ""We're disbanding our education program. 10, 15 Get a degree in whatever you want and then do a fifth year program."" 13, 20 I was like, ""Okay, because I just worked my ass off to get here."" 9, 10, 12 It didn't even occur to me that I could be like, ""Well this isn't for me then. 10, 15 Thank you.  Goodbye.""  That's another soapbox for another day. 19 I struggled. 9 It was hard. 11 I thought about coming home. 11, 12, 19 I'm also very stubborn. 9 I built these friends. 12, 18 I'm sure I saw moving schools as a failure. 8, 15 I made it through my freshman year and had signed up for an anthropology class and loved it. 13, 16, 20 I declared in my first week that I would take anthropology partially because I loved the class and partially because my first year advisor for whatever my first year seminar was not a good fit, we'll put it that way. 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 I just didn't want to have to go talk to her about my life and everything. 9, 10, 11, 12, 13 Sophomore year I moved into the sorority house that I rushed. 6, 8, 9, 20 I had decided not to rush, but they offered me a snap bid, or something, which is just enough of them knew me and thought I was great and a good fit. 6, 9, 11, 12, 14, 20 Without reconsidering, you decided not to do this for a reason, I just was like, “Oh yay I feel included. 9, 10, 12, 16 This is great!"" 11 I joined the sorority.  It was fun and sisterhood and all of those things that is again another story. 5, 9, 16 I moved into the sorority house sophomore year. 6, 8, 9, 20 One night just was at my desk and took a bottle of Excedrin. 9, 12, 14, 17, 19 A whole bottle, which will kill you as it turns out. 7, 17, 19 I was up the whole night, the overwhelming constant fear that I was going to die in my sleep, which was irrational. 7, 9, 19 AS: You still had that? 9 SRG:  It came back. 19 It came back out of nowhere. 14, 19 I've gone back and read what I was journaling that day. 19 Nothing about it is depressed sounding. 10, 12 It's a journal, so why would I mince words or anything?  I'm also a pretty open book much to my mother's chagrin for a while. 17, 18 On paper I attempted suicide but I still don't consider it that. 9 AS: Do you think it was the antidepressants?  SRG:  I do, one hundred percent.  AS: Now they know that. 13, 14, 15 SRG:  Even a year later these ads were coming out. 20 I'm like what the fuck? 10 Then I got diagnosed with bipolar.  They're like, ""Clearly blah blah blah."" 10 That's what they knew at the time. 6, 12 I can be angry about it, but it's also the truth of what they knew at the time. 6, 12 Again I can look down and see all of those rocks below me and I got to the top of that cliff eventually and I'm happy for it. 15, 17 I was on all sorts of stuff. 9, 17 AS: That was a misdiagnosis?  SRG:  Yes, that was a misdiagnosis.  I was on an anti-psychotic.  I don't remember very clearly like two years of my life. 11, 20 AS: In college? 8 SRG: Yeah.  I remember some big events but I don't have, I can't pull out. 8, 15 I went back later on when I was doing my education coursework—went back to find a paper I had written on something. 10, 15, 19 I was like, ""Oh, I have that book."" 10 I have no memory of writing this paper or reading the book. 11 I have shelves and shelves of books and plays that have my notes in them and I have no memory of reading them. 11 It's a little terrifying.  It was hard. 11 I know it was hard for Spencer. 11, 13, 14, 15 He definitely, again, would when he needed things or wanted things and was trying to manipulate me would use that as ammunition, which was really hard, too. 9, 11, 12, 13, 16 AS: He would use what? 9 SRG:  Use the attention I took away from him from my parents, with my parents supporting me so much as ammunition. 10, 15, 16, 18 He would say some terrible shit when he wanted to wound me. 12, 13, 15 He could be a really big asshole, a really big asshole. 8 AS: Let's pause this for a second. 9, 20 [Break in Recording]  AS: At what point did his addiction, at what point was that clear to you?  Did you know about what was going on with him? 13, 14, 15 SRG:  I remember in junior high him getting kicked out or suspended because he had brought booze to school and someone asking me out on a date because of it. 8, 9, 12, 13, 18, 19 The unfortunate part is that I super liked this guy and so I totally went out and dated him the way you do in seventh grade for two weeks. 10, 12, 15, 16, 17, 18, 20 AS: Because your brother was cool? 5, 17 SRG:  Yeah, and so therefore I was probably really cool. 17 Fun fact: I was a really big nerd. 8, 10 Then also in high school I got into the things that high schoolers got into. 8, 16 I didn't really drink in high school. 6, 8, 14 I wasn't really a partier.  I did get high starting in I don't know what grade. 8, 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 20 Then my sophomore year that was kind of my year of exploration. 8, 16, 17, 20 That was my first time that I went to a party and lied to my parents that her parents were home. 6, 9, 10, 16, 19 I got drunk and I got high. 8, 11, 14, 15 That spring also my best friend's little sister died from leukemia and I didn't know how to handle that. 5, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 One of my friends at the time over spring break we just went with her boyfriend and some people that he knew and got in their car and went to St. Cloud and did some drugs that I didn't know what they were with some people. 6, 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18 She went home in the middle of the night and left me there. 8, 19 She had a ride home with someone. 6, 19 I don't know why we thought any of this was a good idea. 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 I don't really remember much about Spencer's response other than I was sleeping everything off and he came in and was like, ""That was really stupid. 7, 9, 10, 18, 19 You could have died,"" which in retrospect is what it is.  We didn't really talk about it beyond that. 10 We would smoke pot together.  In college years we would take mushrooms together and would do cocaine together. 6, 7, 8, 20 One day I was like, ""Well this is all very stupid and a waste of my money and I will get into trouble."" 9, 10, 19 I just walked away. 9, 12, 16, 17 I think I called my parents and was like, ""Hey, I have to tell you something."" 7, 10, 16 It was more of a way to keep myself accountable because I get to that point where I'm just an open book. 9, 12, 16, 17 I'm like, ""Hey, I've been doing this really stupid thing. 9, 10 I'm going to change that."" 16 AS: Did you tell them Spencer was doing all that?  SRG:  I don't think so.  I don't know. 13, 14, 15 I don't remember.  This was also during college when I don't remember a large portion of things. 8, 16 I don't think I started doing coke until after I was off the anti-psychotics. 9, 11 I was also super terrified about drug interactions. 10, 12, 14 It was more the last three semesters that I was at school. 8, 9 Then again it was like, ""Well, I'm done with this."" 10 When we were in town we'd party. 6, 19 Spencer would become mad that I was becoming too close to his friends. 12, 13, 18, 19 He'd yell at me for flirting with his friends. 12, 18 I was like, ""Then why are you inviting me to hang out with your friends that you think are cool if you don't want me to become friends with them? 10, 12, 13, 17, 18, 19 Your friends are cool."" 12, 17, 18 I have a different opinion about that now. 14, 16, 17 I think a lot of them are actually all pretty cool people. 10, 17, 18 There was that time—I think for me I was able to walk away from it, so I wasn't really worried that he couldn't either. 16 He just needed to get to the point where he made that choice to walk away, too. 9, 12, 13, 16, 17 ""He just hasn't gotten here yet,"" which is a different thing. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 When he and Jamie were dating and living at the old house they were talking about getting married and stuff. 6, 9, 10, 20 Are you going to continue doing drugs and all these things? 14, 16 Jamie was like very much I don't want this lifestyle anymore. 9, 11, 13, 18 Spencer was saying that he didn't and then they got pregnant and at one point during Jamie's pregnancy Spencer was growing in a closet. 11, 17 He was growing pot. 17 I was like, ""This is the opposite of giving this up,"" but also like very much deferring to Jamie. 10, 11, 13, 18 “I want to maybe tell my parents because I bet they don't want this at their house, on their property that they own. 6, 9, 10, 13, 16 You're going to have a kid.”  It's hard because pot for a lot of people is not problematic. 11, 17 It's less problematic than alcohol.  That's just a thing that exists in the world that is a discussion I constantly have with myself and it changes every day whether I think it's a problem or not. 9, 12, 15, 16, 19 I don't know the answer still and that's okay. 9, 13, 14, 15 It's tricky because I've seen it hurt a ton of people.  There's also the influence of the DARE program and the whole marijuana is a gateway drug, which I don't really think is true. 14, 16, 20 I also don't know because that's not my field of study. 9, 13, 14, 15 From my personal experience I don't see that as a truth. 16 Anyways, that's that. 16, 17 I think for people who were kind of hardwired for addiction it can definitely be a gateway drug, but not for everyone who uses it. 9, 11, 12, 14, 16, 17 SRG:  That's the true thing about alcohol, too.  If you're wired for addiction then it doesn't matter if it's beer or scotch or wine. 12, 20 I definitely, as the years have progressed, have been like ""Am I drinking too much?"" 6, 14, 18, 20 Then I'll just quit drinking for two months just to see if I can. 6, 8, 9, 12, 14 I just don't have that and it's kind of hard to reconcile. 9, 11, 12, 16, 17 AS: It kind of haunts you? 16, 17 SRG:  Yeah, it's like, “What's up with my brain that I can just walk away?” 9, 10, 12, 16 I was just, ""Alright, I'm done,"" and then walked away. 9, 12, 14, 16, 17 The day after Spence died when we went to the sober house and hearing people talk about how that addiction is always there even when you're sober. 6, 9, 10, 15, 16, 17, 19 I smoked cigarettes a lot. 17 That's the closest I have. 9 It took me a really long time.  We'll see if it sticks this time. 9 I really like smoking. 10 There's a lot of things I really like about smoking despite knowing that it's horrible for me and could kill me. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 That's the closest I could relate to and it just felt so ingenuine to be like, ""I get what you guys are going through."" 9, 10, 12, 17 I walked away with no problem. 16, 17 Then part of it was feeling that guilt. 16 Was us doing some drugs together contributing to that? 14 Maybe and probably.  Did it contribute in such a way that it caused Spencer to die? 9, 16 No, there were a hundred factors and the main one of them being that he was severely addicted. 10 AS: And to opioids. 10 SRG:  And to opioids, which I never got. 10, 15 I remember getting injured at work one time. 12 He was like, ""When you go to the doctor tell him you can't sleep because it hurts so much and they'll give you blah blah blah."" 6, 7, 10, 18 I remember being at my grandma's, I think we were down there for her ninetieth birthday. 7, 19 He told me he'd found my grandpa's, and my grandpa had died in like 2005 and this was 2009, these pills were dated before he died. 7, 20 Spence found these pills and he just took them. 9, 12 I didn't think anything of it.  AS: He just ingested them or he took the bottle? 9, 12, 17 SRG:  I think he put them in a different bottle. 10, 16, 17 He left the pill bottle but left it empty. 17 I'm sure my ninety year old grandma didn't notice. 7, 15, 20 I don't remember if I ever told my parents about that. 10, 16, 20 It was that whole “the sibling code of secrecy” sort of thing, which was also hard. 11, 17 If I tell Mom and Dad that he did all of this cocaine then I also have to tell them that I did.  It was a silly fear because I told them. 20 I got so wrapped up in what Spence was going through.  He was super manipulative and knew how to say just the right thing to get under your skin. 6, 9, 12, 14 He would be vicious, which is just hard to say about a person that you love that is now dead. 9, 11, 12, 13, 14 There were some crappy things about him. 16 There're crappy things about me. 16 AS: Addiction can also bring out things in people that you wouldn't really consider it an inherent part of their personality. 16 SRG:  It magnifies all the worst things. 9, 16 AS: I understand what you mean. 9, 12, 16 I know that you love him. 13, 14, 15 SRG:  I totally do. 17 AS: It does bring out the worst in people. 9 When did you learn that he had a problem with pills? 12 Was it not until he came back from Montana? 19 SRG:  I knew that he kept doing them. 6, 12 Aidan was born in September.  In the months between then—and it was Oscar night I remember, late January, early February. 7, 8, 19 There were three different occasions when Jamie called me in tears like, ""We have to have an intervention."" 7, 10, 16, 17 I was like, ""Alright, I will support you. 10, 14 We'll go over to Mom and Dad's right away in the morning."" 14, 16 Then she'd call me in the next morning and be like, ""No, things are okay."" 7, 10, 16 Finally the third time this happened and I'd been talking to a really good friend of mine. 10, 12, 13, 20 I was at his house for an Oscar party and the phone rang. 6, 7, 9 He saw that it was Jamie and he's like, ""You go. 10 Do your thing.""  It was an Oscar party so we had dressed up. 6, 7, 14 I'm standing outside on the sidewalk on Colfax in Uptown in heels and a dress and my coat probably smoking a cigarette sobbing with Jamie. 9, 12, 14, 19 Just being like, ""We're going to do this in the morning."" 9, 10 Hanging up and calling my parents. 7, 10, 16 She's not going to turn this around on me again. 8, 19 I don't know that I have the strength to stand up to her. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 So much of it was like, “It's your family and I don't want to tell you.” 10, 13, 18 That's a deficit in my personality is that I have a hard time saying, ""No, this is actually really problematic."" 10, 11, 16 For as much as I'm a teacher, I don't want to be overbearing. 13, 18 AS: That put you in such a difficult situation. 10, 13, 20 SRG:  I want the best for him. 9, 13 It was a really tricky situation. 13 I called them and was just like, ""Jamie and I are coming over in the morning because we've got to talk about Spencer."" 7, 9, 10, 12 Usually when they tell this story they don't remember that part of it. 9 They always just talk about how it was Jamie. 9, 10, 12, 16, 17 I'm like, ""The fuck?"" 10 That's a small thing to be upset about so I let it go. 17, 19 I called them so many times in the middle of the night when I was dealing with my anxiety and depression and misdiagnosis. 7, 8, 13, 18, 19 That was a really solid, easy thing to remember.  I'm sure I questioned it before then though. 6, 9, 11, 15 SRG:  Yeah, or 2010 because it was January I think or February.  He went into his program.  When someone goes into a program there's a certain amount of admission both on their part and also on your part as a family. 18 Alright this is a problem and we're going to confront this. 14 Then it became really hard because you go through all of that initial, “Why didn't I do anything sooner?” 5, 11, 19 I'm so mad we even have to do this. 15 He would just always be like, ""I just don't believe it. 9, 10, 12, 16, 17 I don't understand why I'm here for pot. 9, 12, 16 There are people who are here for blah blah blah.""  Lo and behold we learn all of this later. 12, 20 I don't have a strong memory of him using meds. 9 I remember there were a couple times where he would be like, ""Oh you have this thing. 10, 18 You should tell them you can't sleep because of it and they'll give you this."" 6, 7 I remember him getting appendicitis. 12 He would come to every one of my plays. 13, 19 He was my biggest supporter. 8, 9, 11 I have parents who are super supportive. 10, 12, 16 Even the silly stuff, the stuff my parents couldn't get to he would try his best to show up to see shows. 9, 10, 16 I remember him being at a show that I directed and just being out of it and in pain. 9, 12 He had just gotten his appendix out and they were going to move to Montana soon. 9, 12, 15 Then that the following year when they had lived in Montana for six months I was doing the Reading Corps, it was Minnesota Reading Corps. 8, 12, 20 It's not Teach for America it's the literacy version of that's under AmeriCorps.  For spring break I took the train out. 18 I could kind of tell some stuff was going on just because of the way my parents couldn't give me a real reason they thought visiting Montana was maybe not the best idea. 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17 AS: So they kind of tried to hide this from you? 10, 16, 17 SRG:  They definitely did.  They definitely were trying to hide it for sure. 15, 16 I went out and things were just tense. 9, 12, 15, 16 Aidan's a year and a half at this time. 20 Things were tense. 15 They weren't outright fighting, Spencer and Jamie. 14 They'd squabble and skirmish more than normal.  Spence was, he just seemed constantly high. 8, 9, 12, 19 I don't remember that he was necessarily smoking pot.  It was just kind of like, it wasn't awful to be around him, but I didn't really want to hang out. 9, 10, 12, 13, 16, 17 This isn't cool. 17 I just played with Aidan a whole lot. 8, 9, 12, 17 He went into the hospital with pain.  Jamie and I went out with Aidan one day. 19 It was becoming apparent that something was going on. 10, 16 I ultimately at the end of that trip when I was getting on the train, Aidan came home with me. 12, 19 My parents bought Aidan a ticket. 7, 10, 13, 16 Aidan and I took the train back and he stayed here for I don't know how long while that situation was getting figured out. 5, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 19 That was the first of the, ""Okay, there's something going on."" 9 My parents still weren't really telling me anything and Spencer was still like the pain narrative with me. 9, 10, 15, 16 Jamie was just like unless I was there in person we didn't really talk a whole lot about it unless it was stuff about Aidan. 9, 10, 12, 17 That was kind of like the beginning of the unveiling. 16, 17 I remember many conversations with my mom and dad being like, ""Why aren't you telling me these things?"" 10, 12, 15, 16 ""Well, we don't want you to be burdened."" 13 ""That's very sweet of you, but you're actually burdening me more by keeping me out. 10, 11, 12 Now I feel stupid. 9, 16 I feel uninformed. 16, 17 There are other people in the family who are asking me how Spence is and I don't know why the hell they're asking me. 13, 14, 15, 18 Everyone else knows because you talk to your brothers and sisters who talk to their kids about this."" 5, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 There was a lot of anger around that. 17 You work through it.  AS: Do you think part of them wanting to protect you had to do with their experience with your mental health issues? 13, 14, 15 That they felt that would somehow tip you over the edge or something? 17 SRG:  Yeah, like it would trigger it or something.  I think that's why I was most angry about it.  Why don't you trust me to tell you I don't want to know this if I don’t? 9, 13, 14, 15 I definitely do and there was a lot of anger around not feeling like I was trustworthy. 8, 9, 16, 17 AS: By this point you're in your...?  SRG:  I'm in my twenties, mid to late twenties.  There was a lot of discussion with my mom because she is the opposite of me, or was at that time in terms of being an open book. 13, 15, 17 She was like, ""Don't tell people you're depressed. 10, 12 You don't have to share everything with everyone.""  I share certain things that I've given thought to. 6, 11, 12, 16 Less thought then than I do now. 11, 12, 14 It's interesting to see how she is now where she's like, ""We have to talk about these things, that's how stigma happens."" 9, 10, 12, 14, 16, 19 Fighting against that “don't tell anyone” narrative. 15 What's the point?  Then you're just sitting there suffering in silence. 9, 12, 13 Then there was a lot of anger around that as well. 17 Her worry that I would just turn around and post it on Facebook, which if you don't want me to and then say, ""Hey don't."" 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 19 Will I always listen? 9, 15, 16, 17 Not one hundred percent of the time, but I'll frame it in a certain way. 16 AS: At that point she was very afraid of people finding out.  SRG: Yeah, and the stigma around it. 9 I get it.  It's hard when one of your kids is struggling with something and your other friends have kids who are seemingly perfect. 9, 11, 12, 18, 19 That's just because nobody talks. 9, 10, 12, 14 If we change the narrative and we start talking to each other then we understand that we're all struggling and it's great. 9, 10, 11, 12, 15, 16 Then we can all celebrate when things are great and we can help each other when things suck. 11, 13, 16 It's been a rough period. 18 We've gotten to a really nice place with it. 11, 15 There was a lot of having to ask always. 16, 17 AS: Can I talk about this? 10 SRG:  Or even asking, ""Hey, is something going on?"" 13, 15 Like asking ""What's this?"" 13 Then feeling horrible because I'm the last one to know. 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 Then feeling like I can't get mad and confront them about it because they're dealing with a kid who's addicted to heroin. 13, 16 AS: So you kind of fall in the shadows a bit even under the guise of them wanting to protect you from the hardest parts of it. 9, 11, 13, 15, 16, 17 SRG:  Then at the same time being the person who just gets and has that empathy. 9, 12, 14 I get why they made that choice. 16, 17 I get it.  While I'm mad about it I also get it.  AS: You feel like you could have been more of a support to them? 16 SRG:  Yeah, and also if maybe you don't want to deal with it ask me and I will cancel my vacation and stay home and hold down the fort. 9, 10, 13, 19, 20 Give me the tools so it's not only ruining my life. 11 It can ruin all of our lives together, which feels terrible to laugh about, but it's easier to go through a shitty time when you have other people to go through a shitty time with you. 15, 16 AS: They did talk about a time when they went to go bring Aidan back and Spencer was here at home or he was in treatment and you were alone at their house and he called. 6, 7, 9, 10, 16, 19 SRG:  He called and wanted to come in. 7, 12, 13, 19 They had very strict rules about it. 9, 12 I was like, ""I'll put this sleeping bag on the porch for you."" 7, 10 He was playing us against each other.  Then I found out later in the morning that he had dug up something in the backyard. 19 I don't know if it was stuff he had stashed there to pawn later. 9, 13, 14, 15 I don't know if it was a key to the house so he could get in to grab stuff. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15 He'd stashed something but he dug it up from the yard in the middle of the night. 8, 9, 19 That was crappy.  Then there was the time when they had come up to close the cabin, this was the fall before Spence died, and I had just moved in out of a really shitty living situation. 6, 8, 9, 12, 13, 19 I was student teaching. 9 It was the Renaissance Festival and I had just met Jeff who I'm going to marry in sixteen days. 5, 9, 12, 19 Spence was also at home. 19 I heard the TV on when I went to go to the bathroom at like two in the morning. 7, 15 It was Sunday night so I had to go to work in the morning. 19 I'd been at the festival all weekend, which was hot and exhausting. 9, 12, 19 AS: You were working at the festival? 9 SRG: Yeah, I'm a street performer. 9, 17 I walk on stilts and I do puppets. 9 I hear the TV on so I look over the banister and I'm like, ""Hey Spence go to bed."" 9, 10 He got really mad at me for telling me what to do, which should have been the first sign. 9 Then he did eventually like two hours later come upstairs and go to bed. 9, 11, 13, 15, 19 At that time he was just like ""It's really hard to sleep."" 7, 9, 10, 11, 12 All the things he says. 16 We had this really deep conversation, which in hindsight I'm like, ""Oh you were coming down."" 10, 12 He was like going through that cycle of feeling, I think, guilty. 16 He was doing a lot of like, ""I just miss when we were kids. 9, 10, 12, 17 I'm really sorry."" 10 Then he's like, ""I've got to go to the bathroom."" 7, 10 He came back and he was a different person. 16, 17, 19 It was a progression but it just got weirder and weirder and he would fall over. 9, 12 I'd be like, ""Let's go to bed."" 10 He was nodding off.  Hopeful me is like, ""He's fine."" 10, 14 I should have called the police and been like, ""My brother is super high."" 5, 7, 8, 10, 12 Kicked him out two hours later anyways. 11, 16, 17 I went to the bathroom and I found a spoon on the counter and a needle. 7, 13 The side of the tub had been pulled away, which is a place that he stashed things. 9, 11, 16 It was all literally dirty, covered in dirt. 12 He was like, ""This is just really old. 9, 10, 12, 20 I found it because Jamie is making me super mad so I want to send it to her and show her what she makes me feel like doing."" 12, 13, 16 I stupidly, stupidly, stupidly let him dispose of the needle, which I'm sure he didn't do. 9, 13, 15, 19 I don't remember if I told my parents about it. 10, 16, 20 It was the beginning of when everything was going crazy. 16 AS: This was just six months before he died? 8, 9, 12 SRG: Yeah.  They had come up here to close the cabin down for the winter. 13, 19 I think a day or two before he was super sober. 6, 12, 19 Otherwise I don't think my parents would have come up here together to close the cabin. 10, 13, 16, 19 He met Jeff. 5 That's the only time that Jeff got to meet him when he was sober. 6, 13 Then every other time it was shitty.  I promise I have all these really great stories, too. 9, 11, 18 One third this, I don't know. 13, 14, 15 Then everything went back on that rollercoaster of losing hope and finding hope, having hope and everything being in a good spot. 9, 10, 19 I saw him super briefly two or three days before he died. 12, 19 He was at the house. 6, 9 I was coming and he was going or vice versa.  It was just a, ""Hey, how's it going?"" 9, 12 ""Fine.  Good to see you.""  That's the last time I saw him alive or saw him. 9 I'm glad that was a positive interaction. 10, 13, 14 He seemed pretty sober at that point, too. 6, 18, 19 AS: That's what your parents thought. 10, 11, 12, 16 Everybody thought that. 11, 12 SRG:  It seemed like he was doing so good. 19 The thing that sucks about it is it's even more awful heroin. 10, 15 All heroin is awful, but had he maybe not had this exotically strong heroin that he had shot up he wouldn't have died. 7, 9, 10, 15 Is that useful thinking? 9 I don't know. 13, 14, 15 It serves whatever purpose it serves and then you let it go. 19 It was really weird because I was in a yoga class that Sunday. 19, 20 I had a Fitbit, which I was wearing during class. 20 It was linked to my phone and it started buzzing and it was like the last couple minutes of class. 7, 9, 11, 20 It started buzzing and it was my mom calling. 7, 9, 11, 15 It was the first time since Spencer's addiction that I wasn't like, ""Oh no, he overdosed."" 9, 10, 15 I knew. 6, 12 I just knew. 6, 9, 12 I just laid in shavasana and let myself have that. 9, 12, 19 They called back. 7, 19 AS: All these other times your mother had called you, you never thought that? 7, 11, 12, 15, 18 SRG: I had.  All the times she'd call, especially if it was a weirder time of day, I was like, ""Oh is this..."" 7, 10, 18, 19, 20 This time I didn't have that thought, which is how I knew. 6, 11, 12 AS: This is the first time you weren't concerned when she called. 7, 9 How long had you been anticipating Spencer's death?  SRG:  I think for sure at Christmas I was like, ""God, I don't think he can do it."" 9, 10, 15 That Christmas was hard. 9, 11 Here I have my new boyfriend. 6, 12 Welcome to the family. 13, 18, 19 This is just our life. 9, 11, 12 Then before that I remember having a conversation with my dad where he had admitted to me the hard truth of wondering if that was coming soon. 11, 12 Then again the hard truth if it happens: is that the worst thing? 9, 11, 12 It is at the same time that it's not.  It sucks so much but it also sucks so much in both situations. 13, 18 The person he was when he died was an asshole.  He wasn't my brother, but he was also. 5 It sucks so hard. 11 AS: Is it the worst thing? 9 SRG:  It's the worst thing, but it's also a really great thing. 9, 11 There're so many great things about it. 11, 16 He's done with that struggle. 9 We're done with that struggle. 9 It's so selfish, but it's so true.  You feel crappy for saying it, but it's also like my parents got to go on vacation and they didn't have to worry. 10, 11, 16 It was so good.  They went to Ireland and they’ve been to Florida. 8 Now they have to worry about a wedding, but that's a different kind of worry. 11, 16, 17 It sucks and I would change it if given the option, but I also admit that there are things that are better. 6, 16 It is better to not live daily wondering if my mom's calling to tell me my brother died. 5, 7, 15 It is better to not see my brother in that pain and shame and guilt and struggle. 5, 9 It's better that it's over even though at the same time it sucks and I don't want it to be over. 13, 15 There's always that little voice of could I have had him back? 16, 17, 19 Could we have scaled the cliff?  Then feeling really terrible that I couldn't show him the handholds on this particular allegorical cliff. 15, 16, 18, 20 AS: That's a great analogy. 11 SRG:  It's worked out well for this situation. 13 Then going forward and knowing that addiction is a thing that can tear apart families. 9, 13, 14, 15, 20 I do what my parents have done? 10, 16 I've always wanted kids and now I've questioned wanting kids. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17 I do but it's terrifying and is it worth it?  I think one hundred percent it is.  AS: When you have a kid you give yourself over to the unknown in so many ways. 6, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 That's also how we continue to be a species.  We give ourselves over. 6 SRG:  I think it's really hard to live in that fear of making the wrong choice or having a kid and having them grow up to be an addict. 11, 17 It's not fair to let that change your mind against it. 16, 19 I don't know if it's not fair. 13, 14, 15 I would rather live my life continuing to hope. 10, 11, 13 It was really hard to continue to hope in those last months. 8, 9, 10, 11 One of the times he was sober before he died and I was telling him about the trip we were taking to Costa Rica. 6, 9, 18 He was like, ""You've got to hold a monkey and send me a picture of it."" 10, 12, 20 I didn't get to hold a monkey, but we were at Marcos Antonio Park [Manuel Antonio], that's not quite the name. 6, 20 A big nature park in Costa Rica and one of the beaches has a bunch of little monkeys on it. 8, 9 I held out one of my hands and the monkey came and held my hands. 19 Jeff got it on video and I started crying. 9, 11 This is like three weeks after Spence died.  I didn't get to send him that, but I did get to do it and have that nice memory. 12 That was the birthday trip—the trip on my birthday. 19 A little gecko wandered into our room that was the exact size of the gecko that he had given himself a tattoo of. 6, 7, 10, 12 That felt like a nice little coincidence. 17 I'm not a religious person.  I don't really believe that there is a Spencer out there that is sending me things or anything. 12, 16 I do really appreciate all the little things that exist that remind me of him. 9, 16 Then the hard part is at a certain point I'll run out of the things that I said I'd do. 11, 16 I think there's only one left.  I told him when he was sober for a year 6, 20 I'd take him skydiving. 6 He's now been sober for a year. 6, 14, 20 At some point I'm going to take his ashes with me and go skydiving. 6 I don't think my mom's very excited. 15 I don't know if I've told her. 13, 14, 15, 20 I think I probably won't tell her until after it's done.  The other times I've went she's like, ""I don't want to know. 10, 13, 14, 15, 18 AS: The other times you've gone skydiving? 18 SRG: Yeah.  It's super fun. 12 AS: Thank you.  SRG:  You're welcome. 13, 19 I don't know if any of it's useful. 9, 13, 14, 15 AS: It's all useful. 9 SRG:  It's so hard to sum up a person and talk about it. 10, 11 Thank you for writing this book. "
"22","Johnson_Chris","Star Selleck Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer June 21, 2016 Minneapolis, Minnesota Star Selleck-SS Amy Sullivan-AS SS: I’m Star Selleck.  I give Amy permission to record this. 6 AS: Thank you.  Could you start by talking a little bit about where you grew up and your younger years? 5, 9, 10, 11, 14, 20 Your education, career, and up until you became a parent? 5, 7, 10, 11, 16, 19 SS: It is hard to do this fast. 9, 11 AS: You don’t have to do it fast! 9 SS: I’ll try to give you the abbreviated version. 6, 16 My biological parents came over on a boat from Germany. 7, 10, 16, 19 My father was Russian and his family was all killed—the males were all killed in the war. 5, 7, 8, 18 He was released in a camp from Germany. 8 My mother and my brother and sister were there. 5, 9 It was his dream to come to this country. 11, 13, 14, 16, 19 He came to this country and had a hard life. 11, 16, 19 Eventually the fact that he witnessed the murder of his father caught up with him and he ended up being diagnosed with schizophrenia. 5, 10, 12 At that time my mother couldn’t take care of all three of the children so two went to an orphanage and I went to a family at church. 6, 7, 14, 18 That family at the church only ever had me as their child and I was raised at a home where I got to see my natural parents and my brother and sister over the years. 5, 9, 10, 16, 18, 19, 20 Once my father got released from the state hospital. 5, 9 AS: Was that here in Minnesota?  SS: No, that was on the East Coast in the Boston area. 9 I grew up for the most part in Rhode Island where the dad raised me, settled, and had a good job. 5, 8, 17 They lived through the Depression, so they lived life very conservatively. 11 We lived in a nice neighborhood. 8 I grew up with four other girls in the neighborhood and we all hung out and played together all the time. 8 I missed having brothers and sisters. 5, 9 The first few years up until either grade I went to a private Christian school. 8, 9, 14, 20 It was a few towns away. 16, 19 Then in ninth grade I got to transfer to public school. 7, 8, 20 I started first grade at five, so was ready to graduate when I was sixteen. 9, 11, 20 I thought, “Hey, why don’t I go one step further?” 9, 11, 12 I rode my bike to my local college and took the test to go to college. 8, 9 I came home and told my parents I got accepted. 10, 16, 19, 20 I please do second semester in college? 8, 9, 20 My high school had said it was all right. 8, 14 They acquiesced and let me go. 19 I got a 3.2 grade point average. 20 Got my high school diploma and had my first semester of college out of the way. 8, 9, 16 I had a pretty good childhood. 11, 18 We lived near the ocean.  Spent lots of time at the beach. 5, 17 Those girls in the neighborhood, we thought up the most creative games. 8, 10, 11, 12 We had free reign back in those days. 19 Our parents would let us go and as long as we came home either before dark or before dinner we didn’t get in trouble or anything. 10, 16, 19 They didn’t care where we could ride our bikes to or how we got there. 6, 7 It was just don’t go with any strangers and don’t take candy from any strangers. 6, 7, 9, 12 Other than that…we would ride our bikes to the ferry and take it over to Prudence Island and it was a tiny island and bring our lunch and ride home. 6, 8, 19 We would ride to various swimming holes. 6 We would ride our bikes lots of different places. 5, 6, 11, 16, 17 Go eat stuff, and— AS: Until you were how old did you girls hang out together? 8, 9, 20 SS: I was the oldest, so my entire life. 5, 9, 11, 20 Then even when we all left on breaks we would set up the annual Christmas party and draw names and get gifts. 6, 9, 14, 15, 17, 18 I still keep in touch with them. 9, 12, 15 AS: That is so great. 11 SS: We never lost—we don’t talk as often as we used to. 9, 10, 12, 15 I can still contact any of them. 9, 10 I still have a rough idea of what is going on in each and every one of their lives. 9, 11, 18 I had friends at church, too. 12, 18 All in all I had a pretty good childhood. 11, 18 I went to camp at this place called Summit in Colorado. 7, 8, 11 They also had a college. 8 I was going to go back to the little college that I started at, but after going to this camp and meeting all these kids that were going to go to this little, tiny school in Oklahoma, I begged my parents to let me go to school in Oklahoma. 8, 9, 10, 11, 13, 16, 19 AS: Where in Oklahoma?  SS: Tulsa.  AS: That’s where I grew up!  SS: I think we might of had this conversation. 12 What college did you go to? 8 SS: Originally  I went to a school that then had a major scandal. 8, 18 I started at American Christian College. 8, 9, 11 Major scandal.  Then I transferred to TU [University of Tulsa] and graduated from TU. 7, 8, 12, 13 AS: We did talk about this! 10 SS: Where did you live in Tulsa?  AS: Not far from TU.  I grew up at 15th and Pioria.  SS: I rented a house through our college on College Ave, which is no longer there I guess. 6, 8, 9, 10, 16 Just down the street from the Arby’s. 9 AS: College  Avenue is still there. 9 SS: Last time Priscilla said… 9 I lived on College Ave.  that ran right into campus. 7, 8, 14 She said that has been eliminated entirely.  AS: Probably.  TU, you probably wouldn’t recognize it today. 19 She said our house is all gone. 6, 9, 19 I haven’t been back there in a long, long time. 19 She went back this year, my roommate. 7, 19, 20 We are still good friends. 9, 12, 18 AS: You have everlasting friends in your life. 9, 11, 12, 18 I remember when—except my husband. 15 He only lasted for five years! 9, 20 He used to tell me when I would cry and we would leave somewhere he would say, “You never lose your friends. 6, 9, 12, 15, 18 They are always still there. 9, 16, 17 You always keep them. 12, 16, 17 You just make new ones. 6, 9, 12, 16 You will just add to the collection you won’t take any away!” 6, 9, 12, 16 I will try and look at it that way. 16 Although I will say he does stay here about a week a month. 8, 9 We still are good friends. 9, 12, 18 He has his own girlfriend but we still get along. 9, 12 AS: What did you major in in college? 8, 18 SS: Nursing.  AS: And that has been your career? 7, 11 SS: Yes.  I did pediatric nursing my whole life. 11 Now, running up and down the hospital floors has gotten harder on me now. 7, 11, 14, 15 Starting my generation with [unclear].  I take care—I am just part of a crew they have for her. 6, 7, 9, 12 I do that still for pay. 9, 16 I was MNA [Minnesota Nurses Association] so now I am semi-retired I guess. 10, 12, 14, 19 I can still do some things. 9, 16 Then I do my advocacy work, which rounds out my life. 8, 11 AS: Did you meet your husband in Tulsa? 13, 15 AS: How did you end up here? 12 SS: I went to church in Tulsa with my two good girl friends. 12, 18 One I lived with and one I had lived with.  The first time we chose to go to adult Sunday school class I met my husband. 5, 8, 9, 15, 19, 20 We got married in Tulsa and had my first child in Tulsa. 9 Built my first house in Tulsa. 6, 9 He decided he wanted a better job in Florida. 12, 13 I had to leave my beautiful house behind and all my friends and everything. 6, 9, 12, 18 It was thirteen years I had lived there. 20 It was heartbreaking for me. 18 I left and went to Florida with him.  AS: Which son was born there?  SS: It was my daughter, Jessica. 5 AS: Sorry.  Your oldest daughter. 5, 9, 20 SS: Then a year and a half later he moved me to North Carolina because the bank he worked for got bought out and we had to move to North Carolina. 7, 8, 20 I had Ian in North Carolina.  The year and a half we lived in North Carolina I had Ian there. 20 Then we moved here. 8 After we had been here a very short time I found out I was pregnant with Nick. 16 Nick, my youngest was born and bred right into this house. 6, 9, 12, 14 He was born at Fairview Southdale, but not very far away. 16 AS: Did you work the whole time during those moves?  SS: I worked what they would call ‘casual’ when we were in Florida and in North Carolina. 7 I would work roughly one or two days a week. 18, 19 AS: That is a term in nursing?  Casual schedule?  SS: Yes.  You have more control over it too. 17 If you don’t want to work one week you don’t necessarily have to. 13 I did keep my hand in it, and worked in all those places. 11, 12, 17 The first summer we moved here—we moved here in May—and I didn’t go to work until August. 8, 9 I started at Children’s in Minneapolis in August ‘91. 9, 11, 14 I had Jessica and Ian—they were four and nine months old when we moved here. 8, 20 Then Nick came. 19 They were, I don’t know, twenty months apart? 8, 13, 14, 15, 20 Not that far apart [laughter]. 20 AS: Can you talk about your mothering style? 9, 10 The way you raised your kids? 5, 16 SS: Well, since there was just me in my family of origin and I grew up in that era of not hovering and this particular neighborhood was not a highly hovering neighborhood—there were a lot of kids that came with the same era of my kids. 8, 9, 12, 17, 18, 19 They pretty much…it is kind of an isolated little place. 11, 16, 17, 18 They kind of ran the neighborhood. 7, 8, 16, 17 They were on their bikes all around and there is a little wooded area at the bottom of Oxford, which is a couple of streets over, that they thought was like really far away. 8, 9, 11, 12, 16 There was a pond at the bottom.  People have tried to float things and fallen in. 10, 16 The dogs would escape down there a few times. 10, 12, 18 They would climb trees and do things there. 16 I did, other than the little ones that I was afraid I would lose or whatever, once you could ride a bike, and they were usually with other kids in the neighborhood, they would just—all of a sudden I would have a herd here and then there would be a herd at the other house and be down at the thing. 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13 Eventually someone would come home crying. 11, 13, 19 “So and so hit me!  Someone left me in a tree!  Jessica did this!”  Sometimes it was just “I fell off this or I fell of that. 5, 9, 12, 15, 18 I wrecked my bike.”  We did have—my youngest Nick was two sitting in a diaper on the front steps cutting up the tissue paper with some safety scissors, which I didn’t care. 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: Hospital safety scissors?  SS: Little kids’ scissors!  [laughter]  I had the back door open and had the front door open. 17, 19 I could kind of see him through the front door. 16, 17 I was talking on the phone and turned my back and he was gone. 7, 10, 19 I came down the steps and out to the street because you got a pretty good view. 9, 12, 18, 19 He is gone. 19 There are other kids around, people around, I’m asking, “Did anybody see where Nick went? 8, 13 Did anyone see where Nick went?”  He was in nothing but a diaper.  No one had seen him.  I was standing in the middle of the road my heart racing thinking, “Do I go call 911?” 7, 8, 9, 12 That is my next step. 9, 12 My neighbor that lived in that house—used to be a little house like this—she was one of my best friends. 6, 9, 12, 18 We would wave at each other while we were talking on the phone. 7, 10 She pulls up in her car beside me with Nick in the car. 7 She goes, “I bet you’re wondering where he was!”  I said, “Yes!  I was ready to call 911!” 7 A few nights ago before that we could cut through the bank and walk across Vernon and there was a restaurant side and a shopping center over there. 7, 9, 19 We had taken the family to dinner and then I had let Ian buy a cap gun at the drugstore. 5, 6, 7, 9, 14, 18, 19 Nicholas decided he was going to go over there, get a cap gun. 12 He cut through the bank and went just like we had done going to the restaurant. 7, 9, 12, 19 He knew where that cap gun was. 6, 12 She said, “I found him in the Jerry’s parking lot.” 17 She said, “Nicky, does your mom know where you are?” 13, 14, 15 “To get a cap gun!”  She said, “I know this boy’s mother, I know she must be really worried about what happened to him.” 12, 13, 14, 15 She said thank goodness it was in the day. 19 She said, “My name is Barb Trainer. 6 I live across the street from her.” 9 People were still skittish about letting him go with her. 9, 19 Then she said—she was a Hershey representative, and all the kids went to her house for candy all the time. 6, 7, 9, 13 She said, “Oh, I know I should never do this,” but she said, “Nicky, if you come with me I’ll give you candy.” 6, 13, 14, 15, 19 And then someone came up and said, “Barb what are you doing?” 19 And she said since the person called her Barb the rest of the crowd kind of assumed, okay, she must be Barb. 7, 9, 16, 17, 19 She probably explained she was a Hershey representative and that she gives all the kids in the neighborhood candy, and Nick was willing to go with her for the prospect of candy because he knew she was good on her word! 6, 7, 8, 12, 13 They were always going to her house for candy. 6, 9, 16, 17 So she brought him home. 9, 18, 19 That’s not a good—I guess that is an example of my—I mean I was aware suddenly, quickly, that he was missing. 6, 9, 10, 13, 16 But they had a pretty— AS: It was a safe place. 11, 18 I said to Nicky, “Were cars honking at you when you crossed Vernon?” 7 “No, mommy, I was running across Vernon.” 7, 11, 15 AS: Oh, wow. 14 Still a good story. 9 SS: Oh, there are so many stories of kids growing up. 9, 17, 18 A lot of parents were a little more mellow about stuff. 9, 10, 16, 17 The bigger house over there in the white, she is a teacher and we’ve been friends over the years, and this would have been well after the event, she goes, “I had to crack up when I saw Ian and Carson driving that steam roller down the street!” 6, 8, 9, 12, 14, 15, 18, 20 And I’m like, “Doing what?!” 10 She goes, “Oh, you didn’t hear about that?”  She goes, “Ian and Carson got the steam roller that was parked in the alley. 9 They left the keys in it.  They decided to see if they could drive it. 7, 12, 14 So they parked it in front of a friends’ house as a joke!” 6, 9, 12, 18 She looked out the window and saw them driving by in a steam roller. 9, 14 AS: And never told you? 15, 20 [laughter]  SS: She just thought it was funny! 9, 11, 12 They parked it, they got out, they left it.  She said, “Don’t you know all those workmen who came and said ‘I swear I parked it right here!’” 13, 14, 15, 19 AS: That sounds fun. 10, 16 Sounds like a fun place to grow up. 11, 17 SS: One time I remember my husband and I, I’m not even sure, but he took the boys in the neighborhood and I took the girls in the neighborhood and we were going to take them to a movie, but we raced to see who could get to the movie theater first. 6, 8, 9, 15, 20 Not side by side.  “You take your route I’ll take my route and let’s see who gets there first!” 6, 9, 19 AS: In your cars? 7 Yes.  I loved children. 13, 14 We got the closest in time, but we didn’t do anything excessive. 9 But it was fun.  Lots of birthday parties and various events. 15, 19 Kids all played sports. 8 Played a lot of basketball around each others’ houses. 6, 8, 9, 17 AS: Tell me about your kids as they are getting into their teenage years. 20 They are kind of spread apart? 16, 17, 20 The two boys were closer in age. 8 SS: Right.  So Jessica is the first one. 9 She just gets a little moody like girls get. 8, 9, 12 She was what I would call a very self-regulated child. 7 I guess to some extent I was, too. 10, 15 Maybe I thought everybody was. 11, 12 She didn’t need a curfew. 13 She just really didn’t need a lot of boundaries. 9, 12, 13, 17 She set them tight enough for herself. 17, 20 I didn’t feel like I needed to get behind her and set more. 13, 16, 17 She always asks me why I didn’t do that. 16, 17 I said, “You didn’t need them. 13 You were never out later than concerned me. 15 You were very concerned to stay away from bad things. 9, 16 You were, you know, almost a straight A student. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15 I didn’t need to say anything about your homework. 13, 19 You had friends that I approved of.” 12, 18 Although, come to see on her side, she saw her friends were a lot wealthier than we were. 11, 12, 13, 17, 18, 19 She was too embarrassed to bring any of them to our house. 5, 6, 9 All of our kids thought we were poor, and would say that. 11, 12 I’m like, “You guys don’t even know what poor is. 10, 13, 14, 15 We might be poor for Edina, but you have a nice place to sleep, you’ve never gone hungry, you have a mom and dad that love you.” 7, 11, 13, 15 They just see get a new car on your 16th birthday, live in a mansion, have all the money in the world. 6, 7, 9, 12, 15, 19 Jessica was the one because she was really bright so she hung out with the brightest of the bright and all their parents tended to be the richest of the rich! 9, 10, 12, 14, 15, 16 She just was embarrassed to bring anybody—except for the one house over. 5, 6, 9, 12 She was best friends with that girl, and a few houses down she was best friends with that girl. 6, 9, 12, 18 So those two were in our house because they were part of the neighborhood. 6, 8, 9 She barely ever brought the school girls over. 5, 8, 9, 18 Although, in elementary years 11, 20 I had birthday parties and she had friends over in elementary years. 12, 18, 19, 20 It wasn’t until she hit middle school that she said the differences in finances. 8 No teacher ever had a problem with her.  She never intentionally did anything wrong. 15 She got a bus demerit once because she zipped a coat up over her face being silly. 9 That obstructed her view and that was a bus demerit. 9 That really troubled her, but oh well!  Was always in the honor role and graduated high in her class in Edina. 8, 16, 17, 20 Went to Emory with two or three other kids from Edina went to Emory that year. 20 She was very easy.  She didn’t drink, she didn’t do drugs in high school. 6, 8, 14 I know she experimented in college, but that’s all it was was experimenting in college. 8, 13, 14, 15 She realized she couldn’t do what she wanted to do with her education and focus on that. 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 I’m sure she drank at a few frat parties. 7, 14, 15 She was usually the sober driver so it wasn’t [unclear]. 6, 7, 10, 14 AS: It makes sense as a mom. 15, 16, 17 SS: It sounded like pretty normal college behavior. 8, 10, 18 Her grades were good. 20 When she first got to Emory she called me up and she said, “Mom, there are people here that are really smart!” 7, 9, 20 [laughter]  “From all over the world!” 15 I tried to reassure her, “Jessica, you’re smart too!” 10, 15, 20 “I know but I have to study here, and they don’t!” 9, 13, 14, 15 [laughter]  She did fine! 14 She was the one that got the TA position in the non-native speaking—to help with the non-native speakers that come to Mankato. 13, 16, 19 She taught freshman English to the non-native speakers there while she was getting her master’s. 9, 20 That was a very sought after position because it also paid and gave you free school. 8, 13 AS: What did she get her master’s in? 9, 20 SS: English as a second language. 13, 20 But her undergrad was English and South Asian studies. 8, 9 And now she’ll get an education— AS: There goes a little guy on a bike! 10, 14 Yeah they still ride around [laughter] 6, 8, 9 And I remember Jessica couldn’t master a bike until about five. 9, 20 Ian hopped on a two-wheeler at three never having had training wheels. 15 “Oh, my three-year-old can ride a two-wheeler? 6, 20 I’m in trouble now!” 14 That was my first hint right there! 9, 14 I would say fairly early age you will see, once they can ride—it kind of was a rule. 6, 12, 16, 17 If you could ride your two-wheeler without training wheels, you could— AS: Did that go for Ian then when he was three? 6 SS: I tried to keep him—well the good thing is Jessica—if he was three, Jessica was eight, and Kelsey next door was nine. 10, 12 If he would hang with the eight and nine year old, I was okay. 20 As long as they were going to stay in a clump because I knew I had reporters that would report back. 6, 9, 12, 19 I tried. 10 AS: Tell me about Ian.  SS: Ian.  Ian, Ian, Ian.  He was the antithesis of whatever I thought was going to happen in a child from the day he was born. 11, 12, 19 Jessica would nurse and fall asleep. 7 Ian would nurse and say, “Okay, I’m refreshed and energized.  What should we do now?!” 14 At just born! 9, 12 At two in the morning.  I’m like, “You just sleep like one little nap a day and you are a newborn. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 19 This is very difficult!” 20 When I was tired I would go downstairs, lay on the couch, put him in his swing beside the couch. 9, 10, 12 Got to be right there, but dozing when I could because he is five weeks and tearing at things. 14, 16 I remember asking his doctor early on, “Is he still hungry do you think? 9, 13 Should we try some cereal?” 16 Nothing worked.  AS: To try to make him tired? 12, 16 SS: Or full so he would sleep longer. 7, 11 Jessica sat quietly and played with toys. 8 I found Ian getting around at four months old and methodology and getting himelf around. 5, 8, 20 I put him in this little thing that had wheels on it out on our concrete patio in Charlotte. 10, 17 He ran that thing so fast at four and a half months old and he toppled and it was just a little lip that he would go over. 7, 8, 9, 12, 20 He just ran around and kunk! 7, 8, 9, 12 Knocked over sideways. 16, 17 He hurt himself, and I was just like I can’t believe he made that thing go so fast that he could run it over like that. 9, 11, 12, 16 Then, it was, you know, by the time he was eight, eight months old he was toddling around, holding onto the furniture. 8, 13, 14, 15, 20 It wasn’t too long after that—that’s when we made the move. 16 When we got here within a month or two he was walking. 8, 15 I know he pulled a chair up to the kitchen counter, climbed on the chair, climbed on the counter, pulled a knife out of the knife bucket and was like, “Look what I have accomplished.” 10, 12, 13, 14, 15 I’m like, “Oh no. 10 What am I going to do with this boy?”  Needless to say, out of the children he was a bit accident prone. 7, 14 As his pediatrician would say, “His brain is writing checks his body can’t cash.” 8 He would fall off of things. 16 It is a wonder…  I was afraid I was going to get looked at for child abuse. 9 I don’t think he was—no, I was pregnant with Nick.  He wasn’t two years old. 20 He took the Little Tikes car—we had a deck out here—he took the Little Tikes car and pointed it straight at the steps. 6, 7, 9, 12 He wanted to see what it was like to go down the steps. 9, 12, 13 So he went out the windshield flat and face first into the driveway. 7, 9, 14, 16 He had to go in to get his head examined, but he had two huge black eyes. 14, 16 Shortly after that—he was in the process of potty training.  Shortly after that I had Nicholas.  While he had two, big black eyes he had chicken pox. 8, 14, 16 He had big wet stains on his pants and he has his hands in his pockets and I remember his face with chicken pox and black eyes. 8, 9, 14, 16 I was still at the hospital, or maybe I took Nick home, but the two boys had to stay apart for four or five days because I couldn’t bring a new baby into the chicken pox. 5, 6, 8, 9, 19, 20 The parents that raised me were in town with their RV, so my mother watched Nick in the RV and would just let me know when he needed to eat. 5, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 And I would sleep with him out there. 7 Nick came a month early. 8, 19 I would sleep out there with him at night. 7, 19 Steve left to go back to work, so two days he would sleep out there with the other kids while I slept out there with Nick. 7, 19 Ian was very physically coordinated and verbally gifted. 7, 8 You don’t usually expect the two to come together. 10, 13, 19 He was very charming.  Made a lot of friends. 12, 17, 18 Challenged a lot of friends; not in a confrontational way, but I remember getting called to the elementary school about Ian. 7, 8, 12, 16, 17, 18 He would get in trouble for the oddest things in elementary school. 8, 9, 16 He got in trouble because he started a club on the playground that involved doing an obstacle course before you could join. 8, 9, 11 All the boys wanted to be a part of this club and one boy fell and hurt his back doing the obstacle course, therefore Ian was in trouble because he had designed something that caused someone to get hurt, and so he got in trouble for that. 8, 9, 12, 13, 15, 19 He and another boy at some point in time put a bunch of smelly lunch stuff in a milk carton in the bathroom, and there was a question about whether or not someone peed in it or not and so there was trouble involved there. 6, 7, 9, 10 One time he did a backflip off the front step of the bus into the grass and he got in trouble for that for being a bus hazard. 9, 12, 19 Then in later elementary school I remember he got in trouble because he punched another kid on the bus. 8, 9 He came in all fuming and I said, “Tell me the story.” 9, 19 He said, “He came up to me with his leather mittens and just started slapping me across the face. 9, 11, 12, 15, 19 So I kind of pushed him away with my fists.” 9, 16, 17 I said, “Who was this?”  And he told me and the father called me that night upset that he had punched his son and I said, “Well did he tell you that he was slapping him across the face with those leather gloves?” 5, 7, 13, 17, 19, 20 He said, “Let me call you back!” 7, 19 It progressed.  At some dance in middle school a girl was upset because Ian didn’t like her or something accused him of snapping her thong, so he got sent home from the dance. 7, 8, 9, 10, 17, 19 He got in trouble for punching a boy in school there. 8 I said, “Tell me the whole story.” 9 He said, “Me and Morgan,” who is a good friend, “Morgan said, ‘hit me in the shoulder as hard as you can.’” 11, 12 So Ian hauled off and hit him in the shoulder, and Ian broke his hand.  These two fingers here.  And Morgan said, “Didn’t hurt!  Didn’t hurt at all!”  But Ian was in intense agony and eventually someone sent him to the office and they said— AS: What happened? 7, 12, 13, 15 SS: They find out from people, “Well, we heard you punched Morgan.” 15 He said, “Well, he told me to.” 20 They said, “That doesn’t matter, Ian. 20 Anytime you punch anybody it is an instant one day suspension from school.” 8, 9, 19 One day they were snowboarding for the day. 5, 8, 14, 19 He calls towards the end of the day and says, “When you come pick me up from snowboarding we need to go to the hospital. 5, 7, 8, 12, 13, 14, 19 I broke my finger.”  I said, “Well, how do you do that?”  He said, “I heard it snap.” 15 I said, “What time was that?”  “Probalby about noon.”  I said, “Why didn’t you call me sooner?” 7 “I wasn’t going to waste a good day of snowboarding because I broke my finger!” 5, 8, 9, 14, 19 [laughter]  And sure enough he had broken his finger. 5, 15, 20 He was, for the most part, loved by his peers. 13 When it came to the adults they either really took a liking to him or really took a dislike to him. 10, 19 There was not much middle ground. 8, 18 He got sent to the principal’s office in middle school for writing—do you remember Survivor? 7, 8 He folded up a little piece of paper and wrote: Vote Mrs. K off the island [laughter]. 8, 20 That was a send home. 12, 19 I don’t know if— AS: He had a good sense of humor. 13, 14, 15, 17 SS: Awesome sense of humor. 17 And he wasn’t afraid of anybody.  I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 I gues she got it from me.  His dad is not like that.  I guess he got that part from me. 10 He got his dad’s athletic ability and my sense of, “They are just people.” 9, 12, 17, 19 He truly loved people, too. 13 He loved people. 13 He was very emotionally wise. 13 The first kid I had that could see right through me. 9, 14 He would say, “I know why you are saying that. 11, 13, 14, 15 And he would have my ulterior motive nailed.  I would be like, “Shoot! 10 This isn’t supposed to happen!” 6, 12 I remember he was ten, and one day he came in and he goes, “Mom! 15, 19 Guess what I figured out! 12, 13 You can’t make me do anything!” 16 SS: Shoot!  You can’t make me! 16 He recognized his own free will.  SS: He would always stand up for the underdog. 9, 10, 12, 16, 17 Always. 16, 17 That didn’t sit well with the teachers, but it probably made him friends. 12, 13, 16, 18 There was this one really smart boy. 20 He’s a smart boy. 20 He had a bottle of water and he was drinking his water. 6, 14, 17 The teacher was saying, “Maybe you shouldn’t be drinking so much water because you will end up having to go to the bathroom.” 6, 7, 11, 12, 14, 18 I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 Later on in the class the kid said he had to go to the bathroom. 7, 20 She was like, “I told you not to drink so much water. 6, 10, 14, 18, 20 You can’t go to the bathroom.” 7 “Mrs. So-and-so, I don’t think that is the way it works in life. 11, 14, 16 You know, if you told somebody that there was a well on the property and not to go near the well because you might fall in the well, but the person fell in the well, you wouldn’t say just stay in the well because you are in there because they told you not to walk near it. 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 20 You would get them out!  I don’t think you get to tell somebody they can’t go to the bathroom.” 7 I don’t remember exactly how that wound up, but I remember hearing the story from probably more than Ian! 9, 10 That boy went on to be a famous doctor.  Some teacher told that boy he was stupid, and he stood up for him too and said, “He’s like the smartest boy in school!” 8, 9, 20 He must have had issues when he was young. 14, 15 Those are just glimpses into… 9, 12 So, then Ian tried Peewee basketball, he liked that. 8, 10, 18 Gymnastics, worked his way up to the boys team, and competed in the state. 9, 16 They were trying to put him in line for Junior Olympics, and he was going to have to be in the gym twenty-four hours a week. 6, 10, 11, 16 My husband was all set that he was going to be an Olympic gymnast. 9, 15