e early years when I was seen as the leader I was the person who was there every week. 20 Now that we have a good core of people who are there week after week I rarely am the trusted servant or the speaker or the reader. 9 I try to sign up every once and awhile. 16 I signed up for three weeks from now to do something on a topic. 14 AS: Can we pause for just a second? 9, 12, 20 KSF: Yes.  [Break in Recording]  AS: We were talking about Nar-Anon and the benefits that it had on you. 10, 14 You said you started Nar-Anon in ‘97? 9, 11 KSF:  I think this is the twentieth birthday at the end of this month. 8, 12, 19 AS: So ‘97, when you started it where is Rachel and what’s going on? 9, 11 KSF: When I started it Rachel’s living in Seattle. 6, 9, 11 I can’t remember the order of things. 16 In that time, she did go into treatment. 9, 16 Didn’t stay as long as I would have wished she could. 9 I had no say and I knew that. 6, 12 She and Kent were still together. 9 I don’t know if this was because of my Al-Anon, Nar-Anon practice or what. 10, 13, 14, 15 I love this girl and her baby and I trusted her to do whatever was best. 5, 9, 13 It was her life. 11 By this time, I had been in Al-Anon or Nar-Anon for ten years, starting when she was fifteen. 9, 11, 20 This is a lot of long practice. 10, 17 Sitting here today I can’t tell you. 19 I knew she was seeing a therapist. 6, 9, 12 I knew she was trying her best. 6, 9, 12, 16 I don’t think she was going to any support group.  I don’t know a lot about what she did because it wasn’t my business. 9, 13, 14, 15, 17 I truly believe that she would do what was best for her. 9 AS: You really took that to heart because of what you had learned in a 12-Step Program? 12, 17 KSF: I think so.  AS: As a mother you were…?  KSF:  I was always worried how things were going. 16, 17 She wasn’t living in a way that I would have dreamed for her. 6, 14, 16 There was nothing wrong, it wasn’t an unhealthy way she was living but it was way difficult. 6, 14, 1