to the extent of helping with her after school care. 7, 8, 9, 11, 13, 15 That’s continued. 18 She’s not afraid to give me feedback. 6, 19 From time to time she’ll say, she always prefaces with do I want to hear this. 13, 16, 17 I’ll say yes. 14 It gives me something to think about. 6 Recently I had a little run in with Brianna. 8, 11 We were doing a decorating job in her house which I own. 6, 9 Brianna’s house. 6, 8, 9 Brianna said I was making all the decisions and just asking for her opinion to be placating. 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 16 I thought, “This is not true.” 11, 12 I sat down and wrote all the decisions we had made and ninety-nine percent of them had ended up with Brianna’s decision. 8, 12, 16 One big one where I said, “It’s fine with me. 8, 14 It’s not at all what I would have done but let’s change this to be the way you want it. 13, 16, 19 You’re living there after all.” 6 I was feeling badly about that for quite some time. 16 I mentioned to Rachel that I was having some communication problems with Brianna which was putting it lightly. 8, 10 She said something about how she could relate to that.  I said, “How so?”  She said to me, “At times when I was growing up I had that feeling too. 16, 17, 18 That you were just placating me. 9, 10, 12 You come across pretty strong. 9, 13, 18, 19 You’re a force to deal with.” 13 I have thought about that. 11, 12 That was probably a month ago that she said that. 8 I didn’t take it personally. 6, 16 I mean I do take it personally but in a constructive sort of way. 6, 9, 16, 17 I’m strong enough to be able to hear that about myself. 9, 20 I know myself well enough to know that that’s true. 13, 14, 15, 20 I’m not happy that I appear to scare people sometimes if I’m being very certain about my ideas. 5, 7, 11, 17, 18 I come across as kind of scary. 7, 13, 16, 17, 19 That is how I am and I need to pay attention the more that I do to how I say things. 13, 15, 16 How I present things so I don’t come across as scary. 7, 13, 16, 19 AS: Thank you so much. 18 Anything else you can think of?  How’s your Nar-Anon group now? 14 What’s changed in twenty years? 16, 20 KSF:  It’s got a nice size.  If it could be helpful to more people I’d be happy about that. 13, 17 It seems to be some of settled at about fifteen to twenty people max who come at any given time. 6, 13, 16, 17, 19 There are people who come back. 13, 19 There are lots of people who are new who do return. 5, 6, 17, 19 Some who’ve been with the group for a very long time.  That’s a positive I think. 13, 14 I don’t know if we were in a way bigger room I don’t know if more people would come. 7, 8, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 AS: What changes have you seen in the kinds of situations that people are faced with? 13, 16, 17 KSF:  Way more scary drugs now with fentanyl in drugs. 7, 9, 14 Five deaths, three of them in Nar-Anon in the last year. 9, 20 Two in family friends. 12, 18 That happened because of drug overdoses. 12, 13, 14, 15 AS: That wasn’t the case twenty years ago? 20 KSF:  One family in seventeen years whose son had some serious mental illness and was in the service and was under suicide watch in the service. 14, 18, 20 They didn’t pay attention enough to him. 15, 16, 20 He killed himself. 7 AS: You’re saying in the past three years then? 9, 11, 20 KSF:  In the past two years, five people in my life. 9, 11, 20 Three of them who are Nar-Anon connections.  I think that it’s hard to know over the years the majority of the people in the program have had adult children that they’ve been concerned about. 11, 13, 14, 15, 18, 20 Just recently in the last six months we’ve had more people in relationships with their partners, husbands or boyfriends or girlfriends. 8, 9, 12, 13, 15, 18 Right now at our meeting the other night out of twelve people there were four who had either boyfriends or girlfriends or husbands that they’re concerned about. 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19 AS: Whereas it had been primarily parents. 10, 16 KSF:  I’m comfortable however that takes it. 6 I sometimes thought in the olden days that it might be that there were so many people in their forties and fifties and older who were concerned about children or grandchildren. 5, 7, 11, 12, 14, 18, 19, 20 That might have discouraged some of the younger people from coming. 5, 14 I truly don’t know whether there’s anything about that. 13, 14, 15 Some of the issues are different and the option to get out of it, not that it’s easy, but the option to remove yourself from a relationship that isn’t birth related is very different. 14, 15, 16, 17 AS: Thank you Kathie.  KSF: You’re welcome. 13, 19"
"24","Kazel_Jeff","Verne Wagner Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer May 18, 2017 Duluth, Minnesota Verne Wagner -VW Amy Sullivan -AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan it is May 18.  I got it right gals. 14 May 18, 2017 I’m in Duluth, Minnesota with Verne Wagner.  Verne do you give me permission to record this interview? 6 VW: Yes, you have my permission to record this interview. 6 AS: Let’s start with your story. 9, 11 Where you grew up, when you became a parent, some of your childhood, a little background on who you are. 5, 8, 10, 11, 16, 19 VW: I grew up in the town of Proctor, just a little bit outside of Duluth. 9, 12, 19 It’s a railroad town. 9, 19 My father was a railroader; my grandfather was a railroader. 5, 7, 9 I grew up there.  Railroad men are known for drinking. 6, 9, 10, 13, 14, 15 My dad and my grandfather were no exception. 5, 7 My grandfather was a terrible alcoholic that got into recovery. 5, 7, 15 He left my dad and his mom at a very young age. 14, 15 They separated and he was gone for eight years until he finally got into AA and got very involved in AA. 19, 20 My grandfather was also an international union president which took him to Washington. 5, 7 While he was in Washington, I have some pictures of him and John Kennedy together, fell off the wagon and started drinking again. 6, 9, 11, 14, 15 He ended up retiring. 12 My grandfather, one of the local railroads asked him to be a drug and alcohol counselor for them. 5, 7, 9, 10, 14 He started a program that is used now throughout the United States. 9, 11, 14 Rather than firing people if you agreed to go into treatment they would put you in treatment and keep you working. 9, 10, 12, 16 When I was a little boy growing up I used to see these men that looked like the roughest meanest looking men sitting in my grandfather’s living room. 5, 6, 7, 9, 13, 16, 17, 18 I’d say, “Grandma who are these men?” 7 “Oh, they’re just men that need to talk to Grandpa.” 7, 9, 10, 12, 13 Those were sponsors.  He sponsored those men. 12 When Grandpa died, all these people at his funeral came up and said, “Your grandfather saved my life, that’s how I know him.” 5, 7, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 That was my introduction to the AA.  AS: But you didn’t know about AA until much later? 13, 14, 15, 18 VW: No, Grandpa gave me his big book and I knew a little bit about it. 6, 7, 8, 12 My father also was a terrible alcoholic. 5, 15 My mother came down with breast cancer in about 1965. 9, 19 On July 4, 1967 she passed away. 16 I was twelve years old at the time and my older brothers and sisters were four, five, and six years older than I am. 5, 9, 20 My father remarried six months later and moved us into a stepfamily. 5, 8, 9, 12, 18 My brothers and sisters all revolted and pretty much left. 5, 9, 18 AS: So they were all teenagers. 18 VW: Yes.  I was left in a stepfamily. 9, 12, 18 My dad was gone drinking. 6, 14, 19 My stepmother was very upset that he was gone and was very, very verbally and emotionally abusive to me. 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 17, 19 I was a teenager.  You can imagine as a teenager what that’s like with a stepmother especially. 9, 12, 14, 20 I was born very strict Catholic. 9 Not only did I go to Catholic grade school but I sang in the choir at eight o’clock mass, at ten o’clock mass I served mass, and at eleven thirty mass I usually read the epistle to the church. 8, 9, 10, 20 I had a priest that taught me public speaking skills. 7, 9, 16 This priest abused me, sexually when I was twelve. 9 He basically raped me. 7, 11 I quit the church shortly after. 16 What’d I’d do when I was supposed to go to church… 6 AS: You were still supposed to go so you didn’t tell anyone. 6, 9 VW: I went to the Proctor golf course and I’d hide up there.  I worked there as a summer job so I could hide up there.  I’d come home after church was done and I never told anyone about this. 13, 15, 19, 20 Finally, my father said to me, “You’re not going to church.” 5 I said, “How do you know?” 13, 14, 15 “I know. 13, 14, 15 “I don’t know, Dad. 13, 14, 15 Church does not appeal to me anymore. 13 I’ve learned everything I can learn. 12, 17 I don’t like church. 10 I don’t want to go.” 13 That was my way out of church. 16 I started discovering girls. 8, 9, 11 Girls started discovering me. 9, 11 I was a chunky little fellow. 15 I lost all this weight and the girls started knocking on my door which was very strange for me. 7, 8, 9, 11, 18 As a young boy it was extremely exciting. 14 As a Catholic I was never sexual with girls. 8, 15 My father always said, “Verne you don’t have sex with a girl unless you’re either married to her or you plan to marry her. 5, 16, 17 You never, never have sex with a girl.” 15 That’s how I was raised. 5 I had girlfriends who used to say, “How come you aren’t like the other boys? 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 18, 19 How come you never try anything?” 13, 15, 16, 19 I don’t know but I just knew that was not what I was supposed to do. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15 I had a secret life. 11 Going through puberty I learned about masturbation. 9, 12, 17 It was extremely shaming to me.  It was a secret.  I used to think, if my mother is watching me how shaming this was. 9 Your deceased mother.  VW: Yes.  AS: That’s so intense. 15 VW: I started doing that compulsively. 9, 11 I hurt myself.  Then I started exposing myself to young girls when I masturbated, girls my age, in Proctor. 8, 9, 11, 14 I’m thirteen, fourteen years old. 20 At fifteen I get caught.  Somebody turns me in. 19 My dad sends me to a psychiatrist. 9, 12 One of my older brothers is gay and my dad could not stand the thought of a son that was gay. 5, 9, 11, 12, 20 This was a World War II, John Wayne, butch haircut, six foot two man’s man. 12 To have a son that was gay was the worst thing in the world for him. 9, 15 Now he’s afraid that his youngest son is gay too. 9, 14 He sent me to a psychiatrist. 7, 9 It was so shaming.  Only nuts crazy people saw, back then. 16, 19 Only crazy people saw psychiatrists. 9, 16 I was a crazy person. 16 AS: What year were you born? 20 I saw this psychiatrist, he kept me from committing suicide. 9 At fourteen I actually attempted suicide. 10 US Highway 2 runs through Proctor. 11, 16 There used to be grain trucks from North Dakota that would come down to the grain elevators and it was a steady stream of big grain trucks. 8, 9, 13, 19 At fourteen I closed my eyes and walked out in front of one. 10, 14, 16, 17 That man, poor guy, slammed on his breaks and went around me. 18 When I realized he didn’t hit me he jumps out of his truck and I took off running. 7, 11, 14 That was my suicide attempt.  At fifteen I started drinking. 6, 9, 11, 14 I started using marijuana and LSD. 9, 11 I was a very out of control kid. 17 The psychiatrist I went to see, I saw him for about a year and then he got arrested for molesting his patients. 9, 19, 20 AS: Where did you see him?  VW: In Duluth.  I’d see this where he had women laying on different cots in different rooms. 7, 16, 17, 18 He’d give them a tranquilizer and then he’d molest them when they were out. 6, 7 One time he came in and he had his pants down and he had thigh high stockings on and a garter belt. 8, 9, 19 What the hell is that?  AS: What did you think of the world at this point? 15 He’s a professional and I’m the one who’s crazy. 16, 20 I was scared of anybody as an adult. 5, 7, 11, 12 I played sports in Proctor. 8 I was scared to death of the coaches. 5, 7, 11, 12 I was scared of people in… 5, 7, 11, 12 AS: Positions of authority. 13 VW: Positions of authority. 13 With my father’s drinking I got very involved in lots of things trying to become a leader in something to get his attention. 5, 6, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 Children of alcoholic type stuff. 5, 9, 14 I struggled to do that. 9 I always thought once I had sex with a woman my compulsive behavior would finish. 11, 12, 16, 17 I met my wife when she was fifteen and I was sixteen. 5 It was a dance that the Catholic Church in the western part of Duluth would put on for teenagers in the summer. 9, 10, 18 I met her, she had white blue jeans on. 5 AS: Those were the days. 19 VW: I memorized her phone numbers. 7 We dated off and on.  She was an extremely strict Catholic. 9 She has two nuns in the family. 18 I’m thinking she’s from the west part of Duluth. 9 If you’re from Proctor you’re thinking west-end girl these women are rowdy. 9, 12, 18 I have to marry one who’s thinking about becoming a nun.  We dated off and on.  We finally got engaged.  After four years at nineteen years of age we lost our virginity together. 9, 20 It was very intense. 15 I felt like I was doing something wrong. 17 “You took her virginity, you asshole.  You selfish bastard.” 9 She was like, “No, it’s okay. 10 I wanted to do this.” 12, 13 We ended up marrying. 12 We’re going on forty years now of being married. 14, 20 I always thought that would stop my behaviors and it didn’t. 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 17 I got in some trouble with the police. 7 AS: After you were married?  After I was married.  I met a psychologist in town. 5, 9, 19 I said, “My grandfather was very big into AA. 5, 7, 8 This feels like a very compulsive addiction, what I’m doing. 16 I’ve tried stopping this my whole life. 9, 10, 11 I can’t stop it.” 9, 10 I made promises to myself, I made promises to God, I made promises to my wife and I can’t stop this behavior. 9, 10, 16 I said, “I’d like to start this twelve step group based on the steps of AA.” 9, 11, 12 He said, “That’s an interesting thought.” 9, 11, 12, 19 I put it together. 10 He was part of this community group of therapists. 6, 9 He said, “Would you put a presentation on to these folks?” 7, 10 This one therapist said, “You’re talking about sexual addiction.” 6, 9, 10 I said, “What?  I’ve never heard that term.” 15 “There’s a doctor in the Twin Cities named Patrick Carnes. 5, 6 He’s written a book called Out of the Shadows. 7, 15 It’s now called Out of the Shadows. 7, 14 You should read that book.”  I went and got it.  Oh my God.  It was like this guy wrote this book about me.  I contacted him and tracked him down to the Twin Cities. 10 He said, “I just started a program in Golden Valley. 9, 11, 12, 20 Would you like to come down?” 10, 13, 19 I was patient number ninety-seven of his.  Pat Carnes is now a world famous therapist. 6, 9, 14, 15 My second son is named after him. 5, 6, 20 I went through his program.  I learned about addiction. 12, 17 I learned about core values that addicts have about themselves, low self-esteem. 9, 12, 17 If people knew what I was really like they wouldn’t like me. 6, 10, 12 For me sex was my most important aid.  I can’t depend on other people to meet my needs. 12, 13 You have very little self-worth, self-esteem, you don’t trust people so therefore you have a very secret life. 9, 11 I learned that. 12, 17 While I was there I started going to Sex Addicts Anonymous meetings in the cities. 9, 11, 13, 14 But when I came up here we didn’t have anything. 19 I started a group in Duluth, still going strong. 9, 11 I don’t go to it anymore but I went to it a year ago. 13, 20 I walked into the meeting and folks were like, “Hi how are you?” 10, 13, 17 “Good.”  “Do you know what meeting you’re at?” 13, 14, 15 “Isn’t this Sex Addicts Anonymous?”  “Yes.  How do you know about us?” 13, 14, 15 “I started this meeting in my living room in 1985.” 6, 7, 9, 11, 13 It’s still going strong. 9 After about two years in therapy I started the Minnesota Council on Sexual Addiction which was an educational organization. 9, 10, 11, 20 What that did for me though was it got me very involved in the twelve steps. 9, 11, 12 I understood the twelve steps. 9, 12 Starting that group in Duluth I can’t tell you how many hundreds of people who I had coffee with that told me their story that needed help. 9, 12, 13, 14, 20 The county jail would call me up, “Verne we have someone up here who needs to talk to you.” 7, 10, 13 I’d go down to the sex offenders program in Moose Lake and they asked me not to come back because they said, “These folks are going to be here the rest of their lives. 9, 10, 12, 13, 19 We’re not going to let them go. 19 You’re telling them that their behaviors are insane.  The second step of the program is belief in a higher power will restore us to sanity. 5, 8, 9, 12, 15, 19, 20 By doing that they’re going to claim that they’re insane and they’re going to try to get out of here. 16 We’ll never let these people out of here. 15, 19 We don’t want you to come back here.” 13, 19 “I don’t think this is the right thing to do.” 14 They wouldn’t let me come back. 13, 19 We started SAA meetings here. 9, 11, 13 I got a call and went up to Canada and did it up in Canada. 7 Long story short, that’s what got me involved in the twelve steps. 9, 12, 16 I worked the twelve steps, I know the life of an addict, I know how powerful an addiction is. 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15 The insanity of that addiction.  I’ve been married going on forty years, we have two children. 14, 20 My wife is a medical social worker. 14 She’s soon to retire.  She started a group called COSA. 7, 9, 11 COSA was the AlAnon version for co-dependence of sex addicts. 12 Both of us have this background. 8, 19 When our oldest boy called us up and said, “Mom, Dad I’ve got a problem. 5, 7, 9, 20 I’ve gotten myself addicted to meth.” 5, 15 We were like, “Oh my God. 10 We’ve been down this road.” 9 AS: Did your sons know about your addiction? 13, 14, 15 VW: I told both my boys my story. 8, 9, 20 VW: Probably when they were seventeen, eighteen years old. 15, 20 I started to be on the news media more and more. 6, 9, 11, 13 I got involved with my work with the church.  I filed a lawsuit against the church in 1992.  What I did is I went to the bishop of Duluth who I knew very well. 6, 12 I had dinner with him several times at my mother-in-law’s house. 6, 9, 18 I called him up and said, “Look, I had a priest in Proctor, Father John Nicholson. 7, 9 He molested me. 9 He raped me.  He did that to a bunch of the kids I went to school with. 8, 9 I’m not interested in suing you. 9, 11, 19 All of this is starting to come out in the media about what’s going on. 9, 11, 13, 19 Let’s do something proactive. 10 Let’s reach out to my classmates and say we heard this happened. 12, 13, 15, 20 What can we do as a church to help you heal?” 13 “Come into see me.”  He wouldn’t see me.  He’s an attorney basically, the second in command to the bishop. 7, 11, 20 AS: So the bishop invited you to talk to him but then the bishop didn’t take the meeting. 6, 10, 13 VW: So then this guy meets me. 13 He tells me who he is.  “The bishop won’t be joining us.”  I told him this guy molested me. 9, 20 I said, “I’d like to do something positive with this. 13, 14 I would like to do an outreach to my schoolmates. 8, 10, 13 I think we could heal together.  I think this could be something very positive that we do together.” 13, 14 He said, “I think that’s a great idea. 11 Let me get back to you.” 19 He never did. 15 A couple months later I called him back. 7, 8, 19 “We’re still thinking about it.” 9 He never did. 15 I’m watching Sally Jessy Rafael.  She’s got Father Tom  Doyle and another priest on the show. 9 Tom  Doyle was a lawyer and he was with the embassy, the Vatican Embassy in Washington D.C. He and the priest were charged by the American Association of Bishops to look into this. 9, 17 This was all starting to happen. 9, 11, 12 “Is it really that bad or is it just a few bad priests?” 9, 12 He came back and said, “No, this is huge. 19 We need to do to reach out to these people. 13 We need to do something about it.” 13 They buried his report and said, “If you two want to have a future as priests you’ll forget this ever happened and bury it.” 9, 12, 13 Here these guys on Sally Jessy and they said, “The only way we’re going to get the church to do something right about this is to sue them. 14, 16 Go after their pocketbook.”  I contacted Jeff Anderson from the Twin Cities. 10 They took me on.  I settled the case. 17 The laws got changed in one of the courts. 16 Jeff Anderson calls me up and says, “Verne your lawsuit is dead. 7 Until this gets appealed to a higher court, your lawsuit’s dead.” 8, 15 AS: Because of the reporting?  VW: No it was just the way the law had gotten interpreted. 9, 12, 15, 16 There’s a lot of Catholic judges. 17 He said, “Verne the church will give me enough money to get my money out of this. 6, 20 I can get you a couple thousand bucks.”  I said, “Jeff I told you when I first started this, this has nothing to do with money. 9, 11, 20 This is about keeping the church accountable. 11, 12 You get your money out of this.  I will settle this thing so you can get your money but I will not sign a clause that will keep me quiet. 9, 12, 17 I want to publicly speak about this.” 13 That allowed me then to continue my work as a volunteer.  I think Nicholson had thirty some people that he ended up molesting. 9, 12 AS: That’s the priest? 9 VW: That’s the priest. 9 Since I started that I think the diocese has about thirty or forty priests that have been identified. 9, 11 AS: What’s the name of the organization? 6 VW: SNAP, the Survivor Network of those Abused by Priests. 9 AS: That’s a powerful story. 9, 15 That interests me being raised Catholic. 5, 9, 19 We were at the point where you said you told your boys when they were seventeen and eighteen. 8, 20 VW: Matthew was born in ‘86.  Patrick was born in 1990.  AS: This isn’t until the 2000s.  But you brought this up in ‘92? 9, 18 This was a long process.  VW: Yes.  It was settled in about ‘95. 17 AS: You started speaking out more because it blew up nationally. 9, 11, 16 Your boys were teenagers and they were going to hear you. 8, 18 VW: They were going to hear me on the news. 6, 13 I told my father, “Dad you’re going to hear in the news.” 5, 6, 13, 20 He felt terrible. 15, 17 He absolutely felt terrible. 15, 17 The reason  I’m throwing this at you was this was the framework that I’ve had to be there to help my son. 13 Sometimes you kind of look about why things happen in your life, talking about higher power stuff. 5, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 15, 16, 17, 18 My son Matthew is a professional dancer, he does dance and theater. 20 He was out in New York.  He had a partner out there, they would go in New York City, it’s all about who you see and being seen. 13 Somebody said, “You ought to try meth.” 5, 16 “Okay.”  He tried it and it was like “Oh my God, this is incredible.” 10, 12 As a dancer, “I’m losing weight because I’m on this stuff. 9, 18 I don’t have to eat as much.” 18 It ended up consuming him. 12 He lost his job, he lost his relationship. 9 He lost pretty much everything. 9, 18 AS: At what point did he call you? 7 VW: He’d been using for about six months when he called me. 7, 8 He called me in the fall. 7 AS: What year is this? 20 VW: He’s been clean for five years. 20 That was seven years ago, 2010. 20 It was 2012 during our flood that I came down. 19 I had to go down to the cities and pick him up, he’d been using. 14 Probably 2010 when he first...I got him involved in a treatment center in New York. 9, 16 This was a revolving door place. 11 “Come on in.  Thirty days. 19 Goodbye.”  He started using again. 9, 11 His partner was very upset. 13, 17, 19 They were hurting for money. 12 His partner finally said, “I’m done.” 13 Matt started sleeping with all kinds of people so he put his partner at risk too. 7, 9, 10, 11, 13, 16, 17 Matt’s gay and it’s all part of that gay lifestyle of New York. 9, 11 His partner said, “I’m done.” 13 He called me up, “Verne, Matt owes me money for rent. 7, 16 Can you help me out?” 13 “Yes.”  I ended up paying his debts. 11, 12, 16 He’d been gone for two weeks on the streets of New York. 9 Nobody knew where he was, none of his friends. 6, 12, 18 I called the St. Louis County attorney who I know. 7, 13, 14, 15 I said, “Mark do you have any contacts in New York City? 10 I’ve got a son that’s using out there.  He’s using meth. 5 I get somebody to look for hi