 twenty-five. 12 The day of the storm we were scheduled to do a rule twenty-five. 9, 12, 19 The social worker from St. Louis County said, “I’ll try to get to my office.” 16 Mary said, “Great, I will be there.”  Mary took a whole bunch of detours and got there and met with the social worker. 5, 9 She did a rule twenty-five. 12 Then a couple days later I got him down to Pride Institute. 6, 9, 19 He was there for ninety days. 19 He got out, they put him in a sober house. 6, 9, 10 They should have put him in a halfway house. 6, 9, 10, 16, 20 Bought all his clothing, food, linens, all this shit. 6, 17 He was there for two days and he’s gone. 19 We’ve both been down this road. 9 Finally, we talk and he’s living at some guy’s house that’s providing a free place to stay. 6, 9, 10, 11 AS: He’s going to work the program on his own?  VW: “You’re on your own.  Good luck.”  After three weeks he calls me up and says, “Can I come home?” 7, 13, 19 I said, “I don’t know. 13, 14, 15 Here’s when you can come home. 13, 19 You go to ninety meetings in ninety days and you get an NA sponsor.” 13, 19 AS: And then you can come home? 13, 19 VW: Then you can come home. 13, 19 “You have to agree to those terms.”  He went to the Center for Drug and Alcohol and they had an outpatient day meeting. 9, 13, 19 He went there and he started going to NA at night. 9, 11, 19 He got a sponsor, a woman from Superior, Robin.  Robin is incredible. 12 She’s been clean from heroin for about twenty-five years now. 14, 20 AS: Is it Robin E?  VW: Yes, Robin E. AS: Robin’s being interviewed right now by my students. 6, 9, 14 VW: I was going to suggest to you that you interview Robin. 6, 9 AS: I found her on NA.  VW: Robin’s incredible. 12 Robin became Matt’s sponsor. 5, 19 Matt did ninety days. 19 He said, “I’m going to do another ninety.”  AS: Is he living here at this point? 6 VW: He’s at home. 19 For two years he was going to NA every day. 19, 20 Then he got on the area board. 5 Then he became the assistant regional. 5, 9, 19 He’s very involved in NA.  He sponsors a number of people.  I got a call from Douglas County, their jail. 7 I criticized them, their county attorney and their jailers. 7 “You’re talking about locking people up longer. 10 You don’t have a treatment program in Northwestern Wisconsin. 9, 16 You just got done saying if you lock people up longer it’s a better idea. 9, 11, 12 I’m not from here, I’m from Duluth, I’m not here to tell you your business. 9 You don’t provide any type of programming while they’re in jail.  If you believe it’s better to keep them in jail, then why the hell aren’t you offering NA in your jail? 12 “I don’t know why not.” 13, 14, 15 “I’ll tell you why not.  You have a policy that you have to be clean for at least two years and you also cannot have a felony on your record to be in a jail. 6, 9, 20 How many heroin addicts and meth addicts do you know that don’t have some sort of record?” 5, 6, 13, 14, 15, 17 I got a call the next day from the county jailer. 7, 19 “We’ve changed our policy. 16 Can you come over and start an NA group?” 9, 11, 13, 19 “No I’m not an addict.”  I said to my son, “Son this might be great service work for you.” 11 Nothing was more sobering for me than to hear that big steel door shut behind me and know I was not locked in. 6, 8, 9, 13, 14, 15 I said, “I would really recommend you consider that.” 12 He runs an NA group up at that county jail. 7, 11 AS: So Matt still lives here. 9 VW: Yes.  Matt lived with us for two years. 20 Two years of my life I was taking care of my dad who was quite elderly. 7, 11, 20 I was his caretaker up here and I was taking care of Matt at the same time. 6, 7 My life was extremely full. 11 After two years I said, “Son it’s time for you to go.” 20 “You think I’m ready?”  You’re working your program.  You have a higher power you’ve connected with. 8, 15, 18 It’s time for you to go.”  He started, because he’s a professional dance, one of the dance schools called him up. 7, 8, 9, 11, 20 Then he got a call from a theatrical director, “We have a small company in Duluth to not only do choreography for us but we have a couple of lead roles we’d like you to do.” 7, 14 He’s like, “God, Dad I can’t believe this.” 10 “And you thought coming back to Duluth your whole theatrical life was over.” 11, 12, 19 We talked about higher power action. 8, 10, 11, 15 How this was so much higher power that he needed to recognize. 8, 13, 15, 18 “Son when this happens you need to bank this. 12, 13 When you’re feeling very scared if you can recognize that your higher power has been there for you it’s a very comforting thought. 5, 7, 8, 11, 12, 15, 16 You can recognize you might not have the answers about what’s going to happen in life but you can trust that a higher power does.” 8, 9, 11, 12, 15 He got a call from University of Minnesota Duluth campus saying, “We’d like you to teach a class for us.” 7, 8, 11, 13, 20 This last year they called and said, “One of our teachers is going to be gone. 7, 9, 19, 20 We’d like you to be full time on our staff.” 9, 11 He just finished with that. 9, 12 Matt’s been clean for a little over five years. 20 Now he’s headed down to Milwaukee to get his master’s degree. 9, 20 The college folks have said, “Matt we’d love to have you come back.” 8, 13, 19 He says, “I love teaching college level.” 8, 13, 20 But he needs to have his MFA. 13 AS: When did you start the NarAnon group? 9, 11 VW: Three years ago this June. 20 During those first two years you said were hard, you started the NarAnon group after Matt moved out? 8, 9, 11, 20 VW: Pretty much. 18 He’d been here for a little while when we started the NarAnon group. 9, 11 AS: Tell me why you started the NarAnon group. 9, 11 VW: I wanted to start NarAnon because what we went through and what every parent goes through is the darkest shit. 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16 You just can’t get over how dark this is. 9, 12 It felt like I had something to give to people. 6, 17 It’s the old thing about turning lemons into lemonade. 19, 20 Trying to do something positive. 13, 14 Three years ago I contacted the mayor of Duluth, Don Ness, and I said, “Mayor we’ve got this opiate problem going on. 9, 10, 20 We can’t rely on the police to do this. 7 This is bigger than the police. 7, 8 We need to start some sort of community organization. 9, 11, 13, 17 Some sort of community task force. 17 I would like to offer you my services to do that.” 10, 14 I started the NarAnon by contacting the police chief and saying, “We’re going to do this NarAnon group. 7, 9, 10, 11 Would you put that on your Facebook page that we’re going to do that at Miller-Dwan Meeting Room at this date?” 10, 20 I did that with the Superior police chief too. 7 We had ten people at our very first meeting. 9, 13 The police, I’m getting calls all the time with them. 7 The mayor said, “I think we need to do more than what we’re doing.” 9, 13 He put me in touch with the police chief and he said, “There’s a group called the Opiate Advisory Response Strategy group, OARS group. 7, 10, 15 I will make it happen that you can be on that group.” 12, 16 I joined them.  I do not have a formal education. 10, 17 I’m a high school graduate. 8 In Proctor High School I was the valedictorian of my class with a 2.7 grade point average. 8, 20 Just kidding. 9 I always joke in Proctor it’s all about trains. 16, 17 I got on that.  It’s a lot of doctors, very professional people. 17, 20 We were meeting just to meet. 9, 12, 13 It was becoming a clearinghouse of information but nobody was doing anything. 6, 9, 17 I got ahold of Maggie Kazel and a couple other people. 20 We have all this talent, all this expertise in this room and we’re not doing anything with it. 7 We need to do more. 13 I started speaking more. 9, 11, 16 I started letting these people know that we have too many kids who are dying of overdoses. 9, 11, 13, 14, 15, 19 We’re doing a lot of talking but now it’s time to take this talk and go into action. 6, 10, 14, 17 We started holding public meetings. 9, 11, 13, 20 I got everybody to break off into small groups. 18 We have committees on harm reduction, on support, treatment programs. 9, 12, 16 Biggest thing we found in treatment is lack of access to treatment. 6, 9, 16 Five to seven-week window to try to get into treatment. 9, 16 I got on all those committees.  I started pushing like hell to say this is not enough. 9, 11, 20 People listened. 9, 15, 17 We just put in a one point four million dollar grant to the Department of Human Services. 7, 9, 10, 12 We’re supposed to hear something by the end of May. 6, 12 I’ve been meeting with the mayor. 9, 13 The mayor put the opioid epidemic as her first priority for the state of the city address this year. 9, 10, 14, 19, 20 She’s going to hold a summit. 20 I went down to the legislature and met with some people. 5 We’re all going to get together in one room with county commissioners, legislatures, the mayor, the police, treatment centers. 7, 9, 16 I’ve been pushing for these rapid response groups where if somebody overdoses we go in there with a rule twenty-five, we have a place for them to go, we have people from the recovery community to meet with them and say this is my story. 9, 11, 12, 13, 15 We get them into a program where they stay overnight for a week or two weeks, get them on Suboxone or medically assisted treatment as soon as we can. 7, 8, 9, 14, 16, 19 It’s a continuous thing.  The police chief just told me, “We’ve decided to adopt the Gloucester community model.” 7, 9, 12, 15, 20 That’s in Massachusetts. 9, 17 “If people come to our precinct and say 13, 19 ‘We no longer want to do this. 13 Here’s our stuff, here’s our drugs.’ 9, 14 We will not arrest them. 9, 19 We will bring them right into treatment and walk them through the steps so they are not alone.” 9, 12, 14, 16 Now they have Narcan being distributed everywhere. 9 I’m with the rescue squad.  VW: If there’s a car accident, if there’s a drowning, people are lost in the woods, if there’s an overdose, all that kind of stuff. 7, 9, 14, 15, 16, 17 A lot of the overdoses I get are people who are lost or committed suicide. 9, 15, 17 AS: Do you have Narcan in there?  VW: We do not but we are getting it.  I have Narcan in the house. 6, 9 I keep it here. 12 I let all my neighbors know I have Narcan in the house. 6, 9, 13, 14, 15, 19 That’s how I’ve gotten involved in this. 15 This is more involved than I wanted to get. 12, 13 AS: You’re still on the committee. 9 VW: The committee gave me this award not long ago.  It’s from the Public Health Department.  It’s an achievement award.  The county gave me this about two weeks ago. 7 “This is for the work that you’ve done.”  I’m a volunteer.  That’s the nice part about being a volunteer.  I can speak my mind and say what I want to say. 13 AS: You’re not at risk.  You’re not beholden to anyone. 20 You’re like the voice of the community.  VW: That’s what they’re calling me. 7 AS: That’s really powerful, especially in this current crisis that we’re in. 15, 16, 20 They stay siloed, this task force idea is great. 9, 11 You can sit around and talk but if you don’t do anything there’s no point in meeting. 8, 10, 13 VW: The folks on the range called me up and they want to do the same thing, “Will you come up and meet with us?” 7, 13, 19 I don’t have any magic bullets on this thing. 19 I’m just trying to get people… 9, 12, 16 AS: You’re saying you don’t have the answers. 11 AS: You’re coming to it from a place of humility. 11 VW: If I had an answer I’d throw it out there.  All I’m saying is I believe in the twelve step programs. 9, 11, 12 I think medically assisted treatment has to have a finite end to it. 7, 9, 12, 14, 16 We need to work addicts to a point where they go, “I’ve tapered off of it. 12, 13 Let’s stay involved in the twelve step community and let’s live a twelve step life.” 9, 11, 12, 19 Everybody kinds of cringes when I say this but I want to start a two year or a three-year treatment program where people can come to it and live there for two or three years and get stabilized. 9, 11, 13, 16, 17, 19, 20 It was two years for my son to really get back to his old mental self. 14, 19, 20 He doesn’t remember half of the stuff that went on when we talk about it. 9, 10, 20 As parents you just don’t get it. 9, 10, 12, 16 All you can think of is, “How in the world don’t you realize how bad this is for you?” 14, 15 We talk about at our twelve step meetings about expectations and fears. 9, 10, 12, 13 Don’t have expectations, recognize that the addict can’t do that.  If you have expectations you’re setting the addict up to fail, yourself up to fail. 17 All you’re doing honestly is putting more shame on the addict. 9, 10, 16 Then you’re mad, “Why are you doing this to me?  If you love me, you wouldn’t do this to me.” 13 I think that’s part of the important message that in NarAnon we get to talk about. 10 I try to share that when I do public speaking. 16 As a NarAnon person I say, “I’m a part of NarAnon but I’m not speaking tonight representing NarAnon.” 7, 16, 19 Same with this OARS group I’m a part of.  I say, “I’m a member of NarAnon but I do not represent NarAnon at this meeting. 7, 13 Please know that. 13, 14, 15 I’m a volunteer.”  AS: The anonymity thing worked in the time period that it was developed. 15, 16 There was a need for privacy and anonymity. 13, 15 For some people there is a need for privacy but the anonymous part hasn’t really helped us understand addiction as a society. 9, 12, 13, 15, 16 It’s only kept shame alive.  I think we are about to move into a new time. 6 My experience as a mother of a teenager who was going off the rails that other parents didn’t want to talk to me. 10, 13, 16 I felt ashamed. 17 I wanted to talk but parents of other troublemaker kids didn’t want to talk. 10, 12, 13, 16 They didn’t want to admit they weren’t in control or their kids were struggling too. 9, 13, 17 It was the most alienating thing.  I remember thinking “Why when they’re little babies we’ll talk about the color of their poop and when they’re teenagers we can’t talk about the social problems they’re having.” 10, 18 How can I as another parent help you? 10, 13, 16 I’m talking about long before addiction came into my life. 10, 11, 19 Just normal teenage acting out. 9, 10 We don’t support each other in things we feel shame around. 8, 16 VW: I look at how that reflects on the child.  When the child knows the family is shamed of them what does that do for the child’s self-esteem and self-worth? 9, 13, 14, 15, 18 “I’m the black sheep of the family. 18 I’m the bad one.  They don’t even want to talk about me.” 10, 13, 15 I explained that to my son.  We talked about shame, we talked about the core beliefs of the addict. 10, 11 “Drugs are my most important aid.  If people knew what I was like they wouldn’t like me. 6, 10, 12 I can’t depend on other people to meet my needs.” 12, 13 Those are some of the core beliefs that addicts have to go through.  The major one is “I am basically a bad person. 7, 11, 18 No matter how many times I have tried to stop my addiction I have not stopped. 9, 10, 18, 20 I have to be a bad person.  I have prayed about it.  I have gone to treatment about it. 9, 16 I have made promises to my mother, my father, my wife, my kids. 5, 16 I’ve responsibilities to my children, to my family. 14, 18 I have thrown them all away to take care of my addiction. 6, 7, 16 What an asshole of a person I am.”  That’s a terrible thing to live a life of that. 11, 15 That’s why it’s important that we have this public education and stop that stigma. 9, 10 Do you mind if I read this letter of this kid? 19 It kind of ties into this. 16, 17 AS: You can tell a little bit about it.  VW: A NarAnon mom just lost her son. 9, 12, 15 He took his own life because he was addicted to heroin and he couldn’t stop it. 9, 10, 11 He was ashamed of his behavior.  He felt like a failure. 17 This is an apology letter that he left his mother. 19 “Mom, Words can’t come into place for the way I’ve been feeling for a while now and I know you’re going to want to blame part of this on yourself because you gave me more money. 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 This is the most peaceful way I could have done it.” 16 He put a hose from his exhaust pipe into his truck. 9, 10 That’s how he died.  “It would have happened no matter what but this was the cleanest least sufferable. 9, 12, 13, 20 You and Dad did an amazing job with what life threw at you and not a lot of people would have been able to handle it. 11, 15, 17 I love you Mom and thank you for being the best you could possibly be. 9, 13 Ok suicide by heroin didn’t work.  I know you’re wondering why I did this and I will tell you. 13, 14, 15 Monday I went in to do one of my weekly eye scanners and ninety-nine percent of the time it says I’m clean and I most certainly am not clean. 9, 16, 19 Obviously I started using again. 9, 11 I’m pretty sure probation was going to work for me anymore. 10, 13, 15, 18 I also needed to learn how to get clean off heroin on my own. 12, 13 Probation isn’t going to hold my hand for the rest of my life. 9, 11, 19, 20 I found a way to stay off heroin though. 9, 11, 16 I’ve been smoking weed.  To probation weed isn’t legal so there’s no possible way to overlook that. 10, 16 If you need to substitute drugs it needs to be Suboxone or methadone or destruxin which are no different than heroin. 9, 13, 14, 16, 17 They all get you high. 8 They all make you totally dependent on them and they all make you sick when you don’t use them every single day. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17, 19 That’s why most addicts are in court systems in the first place. 8, 9, 11 We get sick and we do anything to use again. 9 I can stop using weed for however long I want and I’m sure as shit I don’t get the least bit sick. 9, 10, 13, 15 I don’t even nod off in public. 15 If for some reason I do need to increase my dosage the same thing happens if increased, nothing. 12, 13 I’ve tried just about everything besides this. 9, 10, 12 I know you’re thinking prison would change me but not in the way anyone would want. 13, 14, 15, 16 Most importantly how I wouldn’t want. 13 I’ve met enough of Duluth’s finest in county and I’d rather not meet anymore. 5, 7, 9, 13, 14, 20 Please don’t leave my body in the ground either. 6, 8 I don’t mind if you have an open casket funeral but please cremate me. 17 I’ve always had the belief that if your body stays in the ground then so do you but if you’re cremated then you get free.” 8, 9, 16, 17 That is tragic.  Thanks for sharing that.  VW: This epidemic is extremely powerful. 15 Those of us that it affects, it affects all of us.  It doesn’t matter if you’re a parent, it affects all of us. 10, 16, 20 AS: You can’t be in a room with more than fifteen people with someone who knows someone. 7, 13, 14, 15 VW: I think of all the children that are in foster care because their parents are in addiction. 7, 9, 10, 14, 16 I think of all the problems those kids are going to have.  This is not something we can sit on and allow people to die. 13 That’s pretty much why I’m here. 18 This is what got me involved with all this.  AS: Thank you.  It’s a really powerful story. 9, 15 VW: You’re welcome. 13, 19 I didn’t say it but with my sexual addiction I had been clean and gotten into SAA and did all the stuff I did and was able to put all that behind me. 9, 10, 15 Thank God for that.  AS: You know it can happen for addiction. 12, 13, 14, 15 VW: I know people who have eating disorders, who have so many other kinds of addictions. 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 I have been handing a gift, going through all this crap that I’ve gone through.  I have a lot of insights. 17 AS: Thank you.  [End of Interview] "
